the president of dartmouth college on monday accused the review, a conservative off-campus weekly newspaper, of ``poisoning the intellectual environment of our campus.''
what the review has done on this campus has not been decent. what it has done has been irresponsible, mean-spirited, cruel and ugly,'' president james freedman said at a faculty meeting
he called staff members of the independent newspaper ``ideological provocateurs posing as journalists.''
chris whitman, editor of the review, did not immediately return a message for comment
the review has been at the center of controversy since it was founded in 1980
it has been attacked as anti-minority, anti-women and anti-homosexual and has been championed by such conservatives as william f. buckley jr. and former white house communications chief patrick buchanan
freedman's public criticism of the review, the strongest to date by any high-ranking dartmouth official, came weeks after three review staffers were suspended and a fourth was put on probation for their role in an angry confrontation with a black professor described by the review as incompetent
the college also announced monday that dean edward shanahan had denied the students' request for reconsideration of their cases
in addtion, review staffers in 1986 were involved in a nighttime sledgehammer attack on symbolic anti-apartheid shanties on the college green
freedman, who left the university of iowa to become president of the ivy league school eight months ago, said: ``it is time for me to speak out ... because i now see that the review is dangerously affecting _ in fact, poisoning _ the intellectual environment of our campus.''
the college, freedman added, ``must not stand by silently when a newspaper maliciously engages in bullying tactics that seem virtually designed to have the effect of discouraging women and members of minority groups from joining our faculty or enrolling as students.''
the college charged that the review has referred to homosexuals as ``fairies'' and written that ``some negroes prefer being slaves.''
freedman disputed claims that the review is under attack because it is politically conservative, and he insisted that issues posed by the review have ``nothing whatsoever to do with freedom of expression.''
he said that the review represents ``a perversely provocative style of journalism that vulgarizes responsible conservative thought and is, in fact, an affront to it.'' fear</head>
a chinese immigrant was sentenced monday to a year in prison for acting as the middleman in a missile-smuggling plot involving a high-ranking member of the chinese mission to the united nations
shang-yao chi, 65, pleaded guilty dec. 10 to conspiring to illegally export 10 tow ii missiles to china
defense attorney alan zegas said chi went along with the plot out of fear that his brother, an anti-communist like chi, would be harmed while in a chinese prison
chi was arrested in a customs service sting operation and charged with being a middleman between a government informant and the u.n. diplomat, who has since left the country, prosecutors said
u.s. district judge dickinson r. debevoise could have sentenced chi to five years in prison. but he gave a the year-and-a-day sentence because of what the government called his ``exemplary'' cooperation in the investigation
the u.s. government has taken no diplomatic action against mission officials, and the chinese government has denied any involvement in the plot
chi was born in china and lived in nationalist taiwan for 30 years before joining his daughter in new york city in 1979, zegas said. chi's father was killed during the cultural revolution by chinese authorities, the lawyer said
zegas said chi's brother was imprisoned because of his anti-communist sympathies. ``if (chi) didn't go through with the plan, he felt his brother would be murdered,'' zegas said after sentencing
a federal judge monday barred the boys clubs of america from adding ``and girls'' to its name pending the outcome of a lawsuit by the girls clubs of america
the girls clubs of america filed a trademark-infringement suit last month to prevent the boys clubs organization from renaming itself the boys and girls clubs of america
the boys clubs has said that the organization has about 300,000 girls among it 1.3 million members, and their parents are demanding the name change
u.s. district judge kenneth conboy granted the girls clubs of america request to block the national organization from changing its name for now, but he refused to issue a similar order against local boys club groups
margaret gates, national executive director of the girls clubs of america, said the girls clubs' identity and fund-raising are threatened by the boys clubs' name-change
she said monday that she was pleased with conboy's ruling but that local girls clubs will be encouraged to sue if the local boys clubs in their areas change their name
ms. gatessaid the girls clubs of america serves about 250,000 girls, and about 40,000 boys participate in its activities. update with scene inside hotel; subs 12th graf, ``the other ... with 2 grafs to update with nationalities of reporters, identities of detained opposition leaders, correct spelling to pintada, sted pintana; edits thruout to tighten.</note>
soldiers firing into the air burst into the capital's leading hotel and detained opposition leaders and foreign journalists after an anti-government demonstration was smashed by authorities
the military confiscated the film of foreign television crews at the marriott hotel, which has been used for weeks as an informal headquarters by reporters and leaders of the national civic crusade
opposition spokesmen said nearly 20 of their leaders were detained. eight foreign journalists, including richard cole of the associated press, were taken away and held for about three hours
the civic crusade, a leading anti-government coalition, staged the afternoon protest march in an attempt to force the ouster of panama's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega. five leaders of the march were arrested
the violence monday coincided with the beginning of the second week of a general strike that has closed down an estimated 90 percent of panama's industry and commerce
gunmen dressed in civilian clothes but believed to be members of the defense forces's state security force, and helmeted soldiers carrying assault rifles, swept into the marriott about three hours after the demonstration was put down
directors of the civic crusade had just begun a meeting in an office on the mezzanine floor when police and soldiers charged into the lobby, firing handguns and rifles into the air
the opposition leaders dashed toward elevators and stairways. but many were caught by the raiders, who sealed off the lobby and searched the building floor by floor
the soldiers then forced their way into temporary offices of nbc, cbs, abc and cnn, among others. they ordered employees out of the suites at gunpoint and searched the rooms, confiscating film of the earlier demonstration and other equipment
a police officer on the scene who declined to identify himself said about 40 people were taken away, including local and foreign journalists
cole, a reporter from the ap's miami bureau, and the seven other foreign reporters were released unharmed
we went there (to the hotel) to neutralize the crusade's center of operations,'' maj. felipe camargo later told cole and the other detained journalists
among the crusade leaders arrested was aurelio barria, owner of an import-export firm who helped found the movement 10 months ago. also taken were raul mendez and manuel burgos, both well-known opposition figures
the other detained foreign reporters were thomas haley, a u.s. photographer for a french photo agency; j.b. diedrich, a miami-based photographer for an independent u.s. photo agency; and five mexicans, abdiel vivancos of abc, alfredo gudinno of nbc, maria cortina of radio mexicana and jose manuel pintada and eduardo herrera of spanish television
cole said the reporters were packed in police vans and taken to state security headquarters. there, he said, authorities searched and interrogated them, photocopied their documents and notes and told to line up facing a wall
later the reporters were transferred to a baseball field where about 40 other people, at least two of whom appeared to have been beaten, were being processed by army officials
the foreign reporters were then separated from the other detainees and camargo told them their arrest was a mistake. they were set free
ed rabel, an nbc correspondent, said seven panamanian employees of the network were among those taken into custody
horst sicher, the manager of the hotel, said he had no notice of the raid
frankly, i can't do anything about it,'' he said, watching with chagrin as soldiers in combat gear rushed through his establishment
minutes after the assault, phone service at the hotel was cut
earlier monday, a crowd of about 10,000 cheering, singing anti-government demonstrators marched toward the central business district, ignoring an order to disperse. they had moved about half a mile when soldiers suddenly attacked
a water cannon sped through the line of march spraying people with a choking mixture of water and chemicals
behind the truck charged police and soldiers firing birdshot and beating people with 18-inch truncheons
reporters saw several people hit by shotgun pellets and at least two people trampled in the rush to escape police and soldiers. there was no official account of injuries or arrests from the demonstration, one of the largest in months
jose faundes, secretary of the panamanian human rights commission, identified the five detained march leaders as carlos gonzalez de la lastra, alberto aleman, roberto aleman, roberto roy and frank maurice
the united states has called for noriega's ouster since he was indicted in florida in february on drug-trafficking charges. the defense forces chief has said he is innocent
the reagan administration has also imposed economic sanctions on panama and supported efforts by former president eric arturo delvalle to freeze panama's deposits in u.s. banks
the cash-short government on monday paid its lowest-paid retired public servants living in panama city and colon, those whose semi-monthly pension benefits come to $150 or less
those living in other cities and other retirees were told they would be paid later in the week. there was no official estimate of how many got paid monday
banks were closed on march 3 after a run on deposits triggered by the dismissal of delvalle by the national assembly, dominated by noriega supporters. and recast. pick up 5th graf pvs, `such as ...'</note>
passengers apparently panicked at the sight of flames on the wing of a northwest airlines jet and evacuated the plane without waiting for instructions from the crew, officials said monday
the plane did not actually catch fire sunday night, but the incident closed detroit metropolitan airport for 20 minutes, and four passengers were hurt sliding down the emergency chutes, authorities said
i think the unfortunate thing here is that the passengers in confusion initiated the escape exit without being ordered to do so by the captain,'' faa administrator t. allan mcartor said. ``and of course we'd like to see that the captain be able to call the shots in this regard.''
the plane was carrying 144 passengers and seven crew members from san diego, calif
it appears at this time that it was a spontaneous evacuation (by passengers) at the time of the flash,'' said northwest william wren
wren described the fire as a flash caused by residual fuel. it occurred in the right wing and probably lasted only a second or less, he said. the plane returned to service monday, he added
such a flareup is not unheard of, and ``it's not as dangerous as one might think if handled properly,'' said mcartor, who happened to be in detroit on monday for a speech
wren said northwest had not interviewed crew members but that the passengers, rather than the crew, apparentlty initiated the evacuation
that needs to be the call of the captain,'' mcartor said. ``we simply would like the crew to be able to initiate that sequence of events.''
naturally we would like to find out more about this,'' he said
faa spokesman mort edelstein said the pilot was alerted about the flareup and triggered an automatic device that extinguished the flash
a 64-year-old woman whose name was not released was listed in good condition monday at william beaumont hospital in royal oak, suffering from trauma and knee and elbow injuries
the other injured passengers were treated at another hospital for cuts and bruises and released
passenger mike young of toledo said he popped open an emergency exit as panic spread through the plane, and he and his wife climbed onto the wing
we thought about jumping, but when the flames died down, we thought it might be too dangerous,'' young said
other passengers said flight attendants jumped up to help with the evacuation. ``they helped calm everyone down,'' carolyn reinhardt of marlton, n.j., told the news of detroit
three prison escapees including a triple murderer were captured sunday night in a stolen car after four days of freedom in which they found a gun and allegedly committed a robbery, authorities say
no one was injured when the car in which the three were riding was surrounded by law enforcement officers outside this town, said mason county sheriff's lt. howard armsfield. he said a handgun was stuffed under the seat of the car
the three escaped wednesday night from the washington corrections center in shelton, about 15 miles northwest of olympia in western washington, authorities said
they apparently had been hiding in a shed near a home about three miles from the prison, armsfield said
armed with a gun they found in the shed, the three confronted the people who lived in the house on sunday afternoon, robbed them of a few dollars and stole their auto, he said
armsfield said he did not have additional details of the robbery. mason county sheriff bob holter said earlier he believed the residents were unharmed
the convicts first drove off in a pickup truck, and abandoned it and another stolen car before seizing the car in which they were captured, armsfield said
one of the escapees, sean stevenson, 17, was convicted of murdering his mother, stepfather and sister. he went to prison june 20 on a sentence of life without possibility of parole
with him were gary curtis van winkle, 17, convicted of attempted murder and burglary, and patrick j. rice, 23, convicted of 10 counts of second-degree burglary and one count of taking a motor vehicle without permission
the three escaped after apparently scaling a chain link fence topped with three feet of razor-sharp ``ribbon wire'' at a point close to an unoccupied prison guard tower, said corrections department spokeswoman barbara lovelace. flash, sted fire, other details; no pickup.</note>
a northwest airlines jet was evacuated sunday night when residual fuel vapors briefly ignited, causing what witnesses thought to be a fire, authorities said
four passengers were injured slightly while evacuating the boeing 727 jetliner shortly after it landed at 8:20 p.m., and the incident forced the airport to close for about 20 minutes, according to northwest and airport spokesmen
flight 288, originating in san diego, calif., with 144 passengers and seven crew members aboard, landed routinely at metropolitan airport, northwest spokesman william wren said
residual fuel in the exhaust system of the auxiliary power unit produced a flash that caused evacuation of the aircraft as the aircraft awaited clearance to taxi to the terminal,'' wren said in a prepared statement
the flash was sighted at the plane's right wing, where the residual fuel is exhausted, wren said
mort edelstein, a spokesman for the federal aviation administration in chicago, said the flash was sighted by a controller in the airport tower, passengers aboard flight 288 and by people aboard another plane taxiing behind the northwest aircraft
the pilot of flight 288 was alerted and triggered an automatic device that extinguished the flash, edelstein said. by that time, he said, the plane had been evacuated and airport firefighters were summoned
but, edelstein said, ``by the time the fire department got there, there was no visible evidence of a fire.'' an initial faa examination of the plane revealed no burned parts or other signs of an actual fire, he said
the auxiliary power unit runs the aircraft's electrical, air conditioning and other systems while it is on the ground and operates separately from the engines, wren said
the four injured passengers were treated at annapolis hospital, mainly for cuts and bruises suffered while sliding down evacuation chutes, nursing supervisor barbara morrow said
dallas'' star larry hagman says that 10 years after the television series began, double-dealing oilman j.r. ewing still has a few years of treachery and lechery left
i would have thought by now `dallas' would have petered out somewhat. but i hope we get a couple more years out of it,'' hagman said in an article in this week's people magazine
i know a lot of tv actors get trapped in a hit show,'' said hagman, who first brought j.r. to life april 2, 1978, on cbs-tv. ``maybe i'm lazy, but i'm happy doing what i'm doing
but hagman, 56, said even j.r. can't live forever
sooner or later `dallas will ride off into the sunset, just like everything else. but whatever happens, i know what i want on j.r.'s tombstone. it should say: `here lies upright citizen j.r. ewing. this is the only deal he ever lost.'''
bernice a. king, daughter of slain civil rights leader martin luther king jr., has become the first of the third generation of kings licensed to preach at ebenezer baptist church
it almost makes you believe preaching is hereditary,'' said atlanta mayor andrew young, a congregational minister who worked with her father. ``so many of her mannerisms and so much of her style is so much like her daddy, it was a very emotional occasion for me.''
miss king's grandfather, the rev. martin luther king sr., was pastor of ebenezer for 44 years until his death in 1984. her grandmother, alberta williams king, was church organist until she was shot to death at the keyboard june 30, 1974
her father was associate pastor until he was assassinated in 1968. his funeral was at ebenezer
after her sermon sunday, which used the story of zaccheus to exhort the congregation to rise above the crowd, miss king, 25, was awarded a license to preach by ebenezer pastor joseph roberts
when she completes her five-year study program at emory university and is called to a particular ministry, miss king will be ordained as a minister and may perform all the sacraments of the church
opera star beverly sills says she became involved with the march of dimes after her own children suffered from birth defects and she wondered ``why them?''
in order to make progress we had to ask, `why them?''' ms. sills, who chairs the march of dimes' 50th anniversary celebration, told a nashville newspaper
ms. sills, now general director of the new york city opera, said in the sunday edition of the tennessean that she and her husband, peter greenough, never asked ``why me?''
`why me?' is a lot of self-pity. `why them?' is a genuine desire to see that it doesn't happen to others. it helps you concentrate and move on,'' she said
the couple's daughter, meredith greenough, 28, is deaf, and son, peter greenough jr., 26, is autistic, retarded and epileptic
steven tyler, lead singer for the rock group aerosmith, says he never realized his life would reflect his 1973 song lyrics: ``you got to lose to win.''
i didn't even know what i was writing at the time,'' tyler said of the song ``dream on'' in a newspaper interview published sunday
but it's true, you have to get on the bottom to appreciate what you've got,'' tyler told the tennessean
in the 1973 hit song, tyler sang:
i know nobody knows
where it comes or where it goes
i know everybody says
you got to lose to win.''
aerosmith's 1975 album ``toys in the attic'' sold four million copies and singles including ``walk this way'' and ``sweet emotion'' were hits. but the band's success led to a downward spiral that began with drugs and led to the group's disintegration, tyler said
the five original members reunited in 1984, and this year they staged a comeback with ``dude (looks like a lady)'' and three other top 10 singles on their ``permanent vacation'' album
billy carter, the outspoken younger brother of former president jimmy carter, says he has returned to religion and hasn't had a beer since 1979
carter, 51, was diagnosed in september as having pancreatic cancer, a disease fatal to more than 95 percent of its victims. his sister ruth and his father both died of pancreatic cancer
but carter remains hopeful after a bile-duct operation at emory university in atlanta and six weeks of radiation and chemotherapy
we'll know in a couple of months,'' he told people magazine in an article published this week. ``whatever is going to come is going to come.''
in the meantime, he spends his days at his home in plains, ga., and has resolved to just ``live a normal life and do what i want to do.'' he plays scrabble with his wife and bones up on the world almanac ``so my children will think i'm smart.''
lawmakers from areas where japanese imports threaten to cut into jobs are coming down with a case of the blue-collar blues over changes they say will water down their sweeping trade bill
i don't see why we should be pulling all the teeth out of our bill out of fear of a presidential veto,'' says rep. donald j. pease, d-ohio
the concerns are surfacing as a house-senate conference committee prepares to meet tuesday to begin thrashing out what lawmakers are calling the ``cosmic issues'' still remaining in the debate, such as retaliation against foreign trade barriers
the conference committee is seeking to reach a compromise between rival house and senate versions of the 1,000-page trade bill, a massive attempt to solve a massive problem _ record u.s. trade deficits and related layoffs in some u.s. industries
president reagan's repeated veto threats are raising anxieties on capitol hill and may have prompted efforts by senate conferees to tone down the measure in hope of winning administration support
some of the most stringent provisions, such as democratic presidential hopeful richard a. gephardt's plan for retaliation if japanese trade surpluses don't fall 10 percent per year, have long been opposed by the administration
reagan says they could lead to counterattacks on american farm goods and other exports, cost more jobs than they would save and hurt consumers by narrowing the choice of goods on the shelf and raising prices
some lawmakers from the nation's hard-hit heavy industrial belt, however, say senate attempts to minimize reagan's objections could throw away the best of a three-year effort to produce ``tough trade legislation.''
the conference on the trade bill is like a diet coke when you take away the sugar and you take away the caffeine and all you have left is the bubbles,'' says rep. frank guarini, d-n.j., a house conferee
i think the president and his people are not fools,'' says pease, also a conferee. ``they know that trade deficits are very large. they know that trade is a political issue this year, so i think the president is likely to sign a trade bill that we send him this year. he may grumble but he'll sign it.''
guarini points to a plan he devised under which the government would step up monitoring to find out what foreign companies are ``dumping'' products in the u.s. market at prices slashed below those charged to consumers at home. the practice is illegal under the general agreement on tariffs and trade
both house and senate versions of the bill contained a monitoring provision, but the latest senate proposal would wipe them both out
that's a strange way to compromise,'' says guarini
pease is smarting from a senate move to strike provisions designed to expand the definition of unfair trade practices by including such issues as foreign companies' and governments' denial of collective bargaining rights to their industrial workers
pease is especially concerned that the senate proposal would wipe out some causes of retaliatory action already appearing in u.s. trade law, among them denial of market access to american companies
other house conferees grumbling over the possibility of diluting the bill include reps. marty russo, d-ill., and ed jenkins, d-ga., the latter an outspoken champion of the hard-hit textile industry
senate finance committee members who drew up the proposals are understandably impatient with these complaints
we're trying to write a bill that's in the 20th century,'' says sen. max baucus, d-mont., ``we don't want a petrified bill stuck in the past.''
itemizing every possible unfair trade practice merely runs the risk of leaving something out and then having it used against american companies, baucus says. the problem of repeat dumping offenders is taken care of by other provisions of the bill, he adds
over the last few weeks, house and senate conferees have not been meeting face to face but instead communicating through messages sent back and forth between the two wings of the capitol
the meeting tuesday will be the first in-person confrontation and because of the friction between the two sides, it almost certainly will take place behind closed doors
we're getting down to the cosmic issues,'' rep. william frenzel, r-minn., told reporters. ``we have to do that face to face.'' nominee</head>
jesse jackson's win in michigan has sent a message to the democratic party that it can no longer ignore _ at the rate he's going, jackson just might wind up as its presidential nominee this fall
political analysts say jackson's almost 2-1 victory over erstwhile front-runner michael dukakis in saturday's michigan caucuses is a clear signal that the preacher-turned-politician is a very viable contender for the nomination
jackson, treated as an also-ran in 1984, has won in eight states so far this year _ michigan, alabama, georgia, louisiana, mississippi, virginia, south carolina, alaska _ and in puerto rico's non-binding contest
the string of victories is forcing the party to re-examine the theory that a black cannot be nominated for president in 1988
the democratic voters are sending a very strong message to the party,'' said ann lewis, a democratic strategist and informal adviser to the jackson campaign. ``the quality of leadership is something they like and admire. this is a referendum on him and a referendum he's winning.''
the campaign-watchers also said the michigan win could translate into victories in other high-stakes contests, including the new york primary on april 19
i don't believe dukakis can stop him,'' said david garth, a new york media consultant who is working for tennessee sen. albert gore jr.'s campaign, ``unless something different happens.''
new york, which has 255 delegates at stake, represents a serious challenge for dukakis, who has failed in the major industrial states of illinois and michigan
the stakes could not be more critical,'' said paul maslin, pollster for illinois sen. paul simon's campaign. ``he can't just finish second to jesse jackson. he can't say i'm the leading white candidate. it's not going to work this year
dukakis has got to win big to even say `this is the guy the party wants,''' garth said
a new york daily news poll published sunday showed dukakis favored by 45 percent of the 528 democrats surveyed to 29 percent for jackson. the poll, conducted between monday, march 21 and thursday, march 24, had a margin for error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points
however, new york gov. mario cuomo has said that if two or three candidates are left in the democratic race prior to the primary, jackson has a chance of winning
a poll by the marist college institute for public opinion found that 57 percent of 459 democratic voters surveyed in new york earlier this month gave jackson a favorable rating, to 30 percent unfavorable. in a survey by the same group in january, only 44 percent had given jackson a favorable rating while 41 percent rated him unfavorably
new york is a fairly volatile state,'' garth said. he noted thatg the state has a large jewish vote, a group that has been skeptical of jackson in the past
in the most recent marist college survey, 36 percent of the jewish voters gave jackson a favorable rating, an increase from 17 percent in january. forty-three percent gave jackson an unfavorable rating compared to 62 percent in january. the results had a margin of error of 5 percentage points
the numbers suggest jackson is mending fences with jews whom he offended in 1984
there are still some in the political establishment who think 1988 is an inevitable replay of 1984,'' ms. lewis said. but, she added, ``the day after michigan a new world has dawned.''
one aspect of supreme court justice anthony m. kennedy's past that senate investigators apparently missed was his high school absenteeism
kennedy, who joined the court feb. 18, ``confessed'' while discussing his childhood in sacramento, calif., during a recent interview with the court's ``docket sheet'' publication
my dad was a lawyer, a great lawyer and i wanted to follow him,'' the justice said. ``he was a sole practitioner and he used to take me with him to hear him try his cases. he didn't think school was very important; he would take me
even in high school, he'd say, `we have to go now, we're going for two weeks for a trial.' i would just leave school because he would insist that i go with him. i probably saw 10 trials before i was ever out of high school. i loved it.''
no word in yet on kennedy's truancy as a stanford undergraduate or as a harvard law student
efforts by the television networks to provide live coverage of the ceremony in which kennedy became the 104th justice in the court's history failed
despite allowing greater access to cameras in various public portions of the court building, and granting more on-camera interviews from their chambers than in past years, the justices apparently have drawn the line at the courtroom door
the court last week cited a lack of a quorum in refusing to kill a lawsuit stemming from an armed confrontation between indians and federal agents at wounded knee, s.d
four justices, including kennedy, disqualified themselves from the case, and the remaining five justices automatically upheld a lower court ruling that clears the way for a trial in which former federal and military officials are named as defendants
three members _ chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices antonin scalia and sandra day o'connor _ had disqualified themselves when the case was granted review, before kennedy joined the court. his disqualification came as something of a surprise
his office informed reporters that as a rule, kennedy will not explain such actions
during a recent question-and-answer session with george washington university law students, justice scalia proved a popular guest despite his reluctance to give substantive replies to several queries
asked why supreme court justices seem more hesitant to talk about substantive issues than lower court judges, scalia said justices are more likely to be quoted in the news media _ thus causing controversy
the nice thing about this job is i'm not running for anything,'' scalia added. ``there's nothing anybody can give me i don't already have.''
retired justice lewis f. powell, replaced by kennedy, has high praise for his successor
in a recent interview with the cleveland plain dealer, powell noted kennedy's long career as a federal appellate judge and added: ``i think he's better qualified than i am. i had none of that experience. that helps you tremendously here.''
powell was a longtime trial lawyer in richmond, va., before he joined the court in 1972
powell, although spending considerable time in richmond these days helping out the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals, still maintains an office in the supreme court's stately building on capitol hill
so does retired chief justice warren e. burger
but a little-noticed bill introduced in december by sen. patrick moynihan, d-n.y., would change that
the proposed legislation authorizes construction of a new judiciary building at the foot of capitol hill, on land currently used as a parking lot for senate employees
the building would house the administrative office of the u.s. courts, the federal judicial center, the judicial panel on multi-district litigation, the u.s. sentencing commission and offices for ``retired u.s. supreme court justices.''
the ``attack ads'' of super tuesday have given way to a gentler spring, but experts say the most pointed jabs of the presidential primary season will be back this fall _ with a new twist
history tells us that we're likely going to see democrats being quoted against the democratic nominee and republicans quoted against the republican nominee both in advertising and in speeches,'' says kathleen hall jamieson, author of two books on political campaigns and advertising. ``it's a classic move and this year both sides are vulnerable.''
the outbreak of tough television talk started in new hampshire, when sen. paul simon questioned rep. richard gephardt's consistency and vice president george bush dubbed senate gop leader bob dole ``senator straddle.''
the negativity was contagious. by super tuesday on march 8, almost all of the candidates had been both victims and perpetrators of attack ads by their intra-party rivals _ their determination to survive the 20 contests that day stronger than any long-term concerns about the fall
when the others keep attacking you and it's going to cost votes, there's no choice but to fire back and worry about the consequences at a later date,'' says dan payne, a media adviser to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
some people are lucky. bush's offhand remark in 1980 about ronald reagan's ``voodoo economics'' didn't keep him off the ticket and didn't keep the ticket from winning
but jamieson said that was because jimmy carter didn't use the remark effectively. ``it could have been much more damaging than it was, but the democrats didn't take advantage of it,'' she said
pre-convention squabbles have played a significant role in several recent elections. lyndon johnson, richard nixon and ronald reagan won in 1964, 1972 and 1980 at least partly because they reminded voters of what had been said about their opponents in contested primaries
in 1964, jamieson said, johnson reiterated the charges that george romney, nelson rockefeller and william scranton had made against barry goldwater. in 1972, nixon's most effective ads against george mcgovern ``simply repeated the attacks hubert humphrey made against mcgovern,'' she said
and in 1980, jamieson said, one reagan campaign ad showed sen. edward kennedy chanting something to the effect of ``no more high interest rates, no more high inflation, no more jimmy carter.''
it's an attractive strategy because it minimizes any backlash against the nominee. he can quote what others have said without going on the attack himself, remaining in more of what author stephen hess calls ``the presidential mode.''
once nominated, ``they want to be perceived more as statesmen than as politicians and it's less attractive to them to be in the mudslinging business,'' said hess, a senior fellow at the brookings institution and author of a book called ``the presidential campaign.''
thus nominee bush, if he felt so inclined, could undermine dukakis by citing gephardt's attacks on him as a tax-raiser and a city guy who thinks destitute farmers can get rich growing belgian endive
the democrats, for their part, have a wealth of material against bush, much of it compliments of dole and rep. jack kemp of new york. kemp went after the vice president on taxes and social security while dole ads questioned bush's leadership ability and his judgment in the iran-contra affair
the same issues also came up in debates. the democrats will have access to scenes of bush's pugnacious rivals demanding explanations of his iran-contra role and how he has distinguished himself in the past seven years
any front-runner right now that isn't collecting tapes of the debates is foolish. they're a gold mine,'' said jamieson
the ammunition provided by primary opponents can be especially useful in drawing disaffected voters who had supported someone other than their party nominee. ``it's a powerful reminder'' of what they initially disliked about the nominee and a strong inducement to cross party lines in the general election, jamieson said
there's no guarantee these tactics will work. if both sides point to what opponents said in a primary, the effect may be a wash. if the nominees borrow too liberally from the remarks of others, voters may end up confused by the cross fire
and then there are the tests of time and relevance. by the conventions this summer, will voters remember the dukakis campaign's 1987 ``attack video'' against sen. joseph biden? will they care about the gephardt ad accusing dukakis of smearing biden?
political analysts say it's unlikely. the high-water mark of negative advertising was probably reached on super tuesday and no one, they say, has come up with anything as potentially damaging as ``voodoo economics'' or ``where's the beef?'' walter mondale's 1984 question of gary hart
if it's not worse than voodoo economics, it probably doesn't hurt,'' said democratic consultant bob squier
squier and others pointed to the developing iran-contra situation as a bigger headache for bush than anything the democrats have said about each other thus far
and while it will be nice for the democrats to be able to quote dole, squier said they won't have to be nearly as circumspect
dole had to make his attack on a sitting vice president but he had to shoot around the president,'' he said. ``we democrats won't have that problem.''
sen. paul simon said all he expected in michigan's democratic presidential caucuses was a respectable showing
he got 2 percent. but aides put the best face on even that
they said the results, while far from what simon wanted, made his strategy of expending little effort in michigan and focusing on the wisconsin primary more important than ever
simon was saying after michigan what he's been saying for weeks now _ that the democratic race is so muddled that he's got as much right as anyone to hang in there
we're clearly headed toward a wide-open convention,'' simon said
jesse jackson's victory over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in michigan increased simon's attractiveness as an alternative, said chris sautter, the illinois senator's wisconsin campaign coordinator
now, we're in a position where we can be considered a serious contender here,'' sautter said sunday. ``it underscores the whole idea of an open convention.''
simon acknowledges, though, that wisconsin's primary, a week from tuesday, is a key test
in a state like wisconsin, where politics is synonymous with the word `progressive,' we have the opportunity to communicate that the democrats don't have to settle for a weak alternative,'' campaign spokesman terry michael said. ``we need to make that case in wisconsin.''
what happens if simon loses?
we have to reassess at that point,'' michael said
even longtime supporters said simon must win in wisconsin or think seriously about abandoning his quest for the white house
the big questions are whether his campaign after wisconsin is credible and raising money,'' said rep. richard durbin, d-ill. ``if the answer to those two things is `yes,' he'll be pressing forward.''
simon's only victory so far was at home in the illinois primary
he has placed third, fourth or fifth in most other primaries and caucuses, sat out super tuesday races in 20 states and ranks fifth among five candidates in delegates to the democratic national convention in july
he's by no means out of it, and i'm sticking with him as long as he wants to stay in,'' said rep. lane evans, d-ill., voicing sentiments of aides speaking for reps. marcy kaptur, d-ohio, and stephen solarz, d-n.y
yet evans hedged when asked if he thinks simon still has a chance of becoming the democratic nominee
it's very hard to say what's going to happen,'' evans said. ``strange things happen occasionally at conventions.''
other allies, though, said they have counseled simon against hurting his chances for re-election to the senate by clinging to a hopeless cause
i think he will continue to look at it as long as he doesn't incur more debt,'' said sen. alan dixon, d-ill., one of those who urged simon to bypass the super tuesday states
`you don't want to have a big debt when you're looking at 1990,'' dixon said. ``i can't tell you what his present financial shape is. but it's hoped he can walk away from this thing pretty much as a wash.''
simon has repaid more than a half-million dollars' worth of bank loans and he expects to use 20 staff members and spend $100,000 for television advertising in the wisconsin campaign, spokesman michael said
california is in a broccoli race with other parts of the country where farmers seek crops more profitable than the traditional harvests of wheat, corn, cotton and soybeans
an agriculture department report by roberta cook of the university of california, davis, says cauliflower has joined broccoli as a favorite among the veggie expansionists
between 1978 and 1986, harvested acreage of broccoli increased by 90 percent, while the number of states producing for the fresh market grew from the traditional four (california, texas, oregon and arizona) to include new producers such as maine, north and south carolina, new york, illinois, virginia, oklahoma and colorado,'' she said
the expansion is explained by the rapidly growing popularity of fresh vegetables in the american diet and by the declining profitability of food and feed grains in the 1980s
unfortunately, the capacity of the fruit and vegetable industry to absorb the additional acreage is limited,'' ms. cook said
that is because there are more than 200 million acres in the united states used to produce grain, compared with only about 5 million acres of fruit and vegetables
consequently, while shifting 2.5 percent of grain acreage into fruits and vegetables would not solve the excess supply problem in grains, it would double fruit and vegetable acreage and devastate prices,'' she said. ``at the same time, other regions of the world, particularly mexico and the caribbean basin initiative countries are expanding vegetable exports to the united states.''
california remains the dominant broccoli producer, with its area increasing to 106,400 acres in 1986 from 64,400 in 1978. however, california's share of the total u.s. broccoli acreage declined from a high of 96 percent in 1979 to 82 percent in 1986
the california market share of broccoli production also dropped during the 1978-86 period from 96 percent to 91 percent
there has also been a rise in cauliflower production, with the harvested area rising 65 percent between 1978 and 1986, ms. cook said. fresh market cauliflower production increased even more, to more than 5.9 million hundredweight in 1986 from 1.85 million in 1978
california's market share of fresh market cauliflower increased to 79 percent of the total in 1986 from 74 percent in 1978
although california has a climatic advantage during portions of the year, the competition in other states during the summer and fall has become significant
the combined fall broccoli area in the midwest, south and east amounts to an estimated 10,000 acres, compared with 28,000 acres in california,'' ms. cook said. ``hence, this new broccoli acreage compares to 35 percent of california acreage when viewed on a seasonal basis.''
meanwhile, imports of fresh vegetables have increased sharply since 1978. despite the growth, however, she said broccoli imports still represent only about 1 percent of the total u.s. supply, while cauliflower imports make up about 2 percent of the supply
mexico is the leading source of fresh broccoli imports, and canada is the largest provider of imported cauliflower
however, both canada's and mexico's share of the import market has declined slightly while other exporting countries, including guatemala, jamaica, chile, belgium, france and israel have gained,'' ms. cook said
a four-year experiment to control houseflies with tiny parastic wasps and special traps is near an end, perhaps paving the way for use by consumers generally, says the agriculture department
richard miller of the department's agricultural research service said the traps were used last year by a laurel, md., resident, paul schwartz, whose home is next to a horse farm. flies bred in manure and straw bedding were a problem. it was impossible to eat outside because of the flies
last summer, the experimental traps reduced the flies by an estimated 90 percent, schwartz said
miller, whose work was reported recently by the agency, said houseflies can be major irritants in areas where many new houses are being built near farms. and they're a nuisance to farmers and livestock, too
the trap is painted white to attract the flies, and a sticky coating nabs them once they land. miller said that while there is interest in the pyramid traps, none is yet being produced commercially
miller said the tiny wasp, muscidifurax raptor, is a biological control alternative to chemical sprays. the wasps are found throughout the united states and are natural enemies of the flies, while being harmless to humans. the wasps lay eggs in the fly pupae, which are killed as the wasps develop
these parasites are reared by the thousands and released to maintain or augment natural (wasp) populations,'' miller said. ``in last year's test we increased the wasp populations up to tenfold.''
later, he said, traps were used to capture the surviving flies
a year-end review by the agriculture department shows 1987 production of red meat totaled 38.7 billion pounds, down 2 percent from 1986
production included: beef, 23.6 billion pounds, down 5 percent; veal, 429 million, down 18 percent; pork, 14.4 billion, up 2 percent; lamb and mutton, 316 million, down 6 percent
the national research council is out to prove the chinese proverb: ``give a man a fish and you feed him once; teach him how to fish and you feed him for life.''
the council has seized on the idea _ an oft-quoted aphorism in foreign aid circles _ and come up with a lot of ideas, from pedal-power fishing craft more efficient than rowboats to artificial mangrove branches made of aluminum wire bathed in concrete. the fake branches provide the kind of surface that baby oysters like to hang on, useful in places where cutting mangroves is illegal
the council has recently published a book-length manual of low-price fishing methods, called ``fishing technologies for developing countries.'' it's not for big commercial fleets but for traditional fishermen who account for a quarter of the world's catch, about 20 million tons a year. they provide most of the fish in africa and asia, but a much smaller proportion in latin america
an estimated 200 million people depend on them
first thing most fishermen need is a boat. the high quality hardwoods many peoples traditionally use have become dearer and harder to find. plywood is not too expensive, and plywood catamarans developed in western samoa have lasted almost a decade. plastic tubes and ferro-concrete are ugly, but cheap and durable
the japanese have found another use for six-inch plastic tubes. two of them, 30 inches long, are laid side by side with a two-inch concrete plug that bisects them: the result offers four fatal dens to unsuspecting octopi
in venezuela they make octopus pots from old rubber tires
a boat has to move. sailing has declined among third world fishermen in recent years, the council says, and instead there have been ideas for cheap fuel: alcohol made from cassava (manioc) in fiji, coconut oil for mixing with diesel fuel in the philippines. the coconut oil clogged the fuel filters, and the filipinos have been trying to use charcoal from coconut shells to make gas for fuel
several ideas, some more effective, have come from the philippines. the academy says a system for cultured mussels developed at sapian bay, on the island of panay, uses rope-webs floated from rafts instead of the more usual stakes driven into the mud. it raised mussel production to more than five times the old method
advanced technology need not be too expensive, the council points out. fish are sensitive to the temperature of the water, and move when it changes. a shift of one degree or even less can indicate a place where fish may cluster. ordinary thermometers are not sensitive enough, but a simple electronic thermometer can show differences of a tenth of a degree and cost less than $100
the federal reserve has been trying to keep the economic recovery alive following the october stock market collapse, but many economists believe it is starting to worry more about rising inflationary pressures
these analysts think the switch will mean that interest rates, including mortgage rates, will not fall further and actually will climb slightly in coming months
the central bank's top policy makers will meet behind closed doors tuesday to review monetary strategy. the decisions made by the federal open market committee will not be revealed until mid-may
while analysts are not looking for major policy changes to come out of the meeting, they said recent comments by federal reserve chairman alan greenspan indicate that the central bank has begun to worry once again about inflationary pressures
the central bank tries to balance the competing economic goals of supplying enough money to the financial system to keep the economy expanding while guarding against supplying so much money that inflation is rekindled
in congressional testimony earlier this month, greenspan said he was worried that inflationary bottlenecks could develop in u.s. industries later this year
greenspan said there were no signs of inflationary troubles at present, but that the central bank would act fast at the first sign that the economy was overheating. for the fed, fighting inflation means raising interest rates
before the oct. 19 collapse of stock prices, the fed had been tightening credit conditions out of fear that a weaker dollar would increase u.s. inflation
but following the record 508-point drop in stock prices, the central bank moved quickly to ease credit in order to keep the country out of a recession
analysts said they believed greenspan's recent comments were an indication the central bank is once again switching gears
i am not looking for any more interest rate declines. i think the fed is worried again about inflation,'' said david seiders, chief economist of the national association of home builders
mortgage rates, which hit a high of 11.58 percent immediately before the stock crash last october, dipped into single-digits earlier this year, falling to 9.84 percent in early february
but in recent weeks rates have been rising again, averaging 9.99 percent last week, according to a nationwide survey by the federal home loan mortgage corp
seiders predicted that mortgage rates could top 11 percent by the end of the year. other analysts agreed that a variety of interest rates would likely head higher in coming months, especially if economic growth rebounds
allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co., said he believed the central bank would make no outright change in policy at its march meeting but would stand ready to tighten credit conditions later in the year
if the economy picks up steam and produces inflationary pressures, i wouldn't rule out a tightening move later this spring,'' he said. ``the central bank is making people aware that if inflation does heat up, they would tighten.''
lyle gramley, chief economist for the mortgage bankers association, said he expected mortgage rates to fluctuate between 10 percent to 10.5 percent over the next two months as the fed watches for further indications of how the economy is performing
one key indicator the fed will be watching is the monthly unemployment report. the jobless rate dropped to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent in february and greenspan indicated that it was unlikely the rate could fall much farther without triggering inflationary pressures
if economic growth is too strong, the unemployment rate could drop down into a danger zone which would generate an upturn in wage increases,'' said gramley, a former member of the fed board. ``once you get that under way, it is very hard to stop and even harder to reverse. that is what you want to avoid if you can.''
some economists said that the fed would hold off making any major change in direction until late next month when the government releases its first estimate of overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national product, for the january-march quarter
roger brinner, an economist with data resources inc., said that if growth was really weak in the first quarter, the fed might be persuaded that a further dose of easing was needed, especially since this is a presidential election year
houston has suffered low oil prices, a troubled space program and the near-exodus of its pro football team. now it wants to avoid another hit: the departure of superstar superconductivity physicist paul chu
i think we need to be sure we don't drop the ball,'' says city councilman jim greenwood. ``it's probably more important to keep paul chu as it was to keep the houston oilers.''
superconductivity, the potential of some materials to carry electricity without energy loss, has become one of the hottest areas in science today. and chu, a 47-year-old university of houston physics professor, has become one of the hottest researchers in superconductivity
the research promises to spawn tremendous advances in industry, with applications in computers, transmission of electricity and transportation, although many observers feel it will be decades before any significant commercial products result
early last year, chu announced that his experiments with materials showed evidence of superconductivity at temperatures warmer than ever before achieved. the discovery brought energy-saving practical applications within closer range
the news spread quickly and made chu an overnight celebrity in scientific circles. job offers began rolling in. one university has promised him a $20 million research package if he moves there, said chu, who isn't naming the school
the rumors have prompted houston businessman tom wright to organize a letter-writing campaign asking small business owners to urge chu to stay
we should go out of our way to make sure he likes it here,'' wright said. ``wherever major discoveries are made, industry grows around it. ... in my mind, superconductivity will be bigger to this area than nasa ever was.''
chu says he has made no decision, but is considering an offer from the university of california-berkeley. on march 6, the san francisco examiner reported chu had accepted a teaching and research post there, and berkeley officials continue to claim chu has taken the job
we are expecting him to come to berkeley this fall,'' said geoffrey chew, berkeley's dean of physical sciences. ``he came here last week, and confirmed that he had accepted the offer.''
in recent weeks, chu has not responded to numerous interview requests. through his secretary, mike albert, he says he remains undecided
paul has been agonizing over this decision for about a year now,'' roy weinstein, dean of the university of houston college of natural sciences and mathematics, said last week
among the attractions of berkeley for chu are the university's prestige, the favorable california weather and the closer proximity to family members who live in california, weinstein said
since his major discovery, chu has been appointed to the newly created t.l.l. temple chair at the university of houston, funded by a $1.5 million endowment. his salary has been raised and he has been named director of the texas center of superconductivity at university of houston, a $30 million research unit to be built at the university
i think that the superconductivity center is more important to him than anything else,'' said university of houston president richard van horn. ``we have perhaps more people working in superconductivity than anywhere else.''
houston's relatively undiversified energy-based economy was hit hard by the 1986 fall of oil prices. and operations of the nation's space program, and the nearby johnson space center here, came to a virtual halt with the explosion of the space shuttle challenger
the city's confidence was further battered last year by the near departure of the houston oilers to jacksonville, fla. the team eventually signed a 10-year lease to remain in houston
weinstein says he believes chu will split his time between california and houston, but says the strain of such an arrangement may be difficult for the quiet researcher
it's a question of whether he can do it,'' weinstein said. ``he will have to confront it, test it, and see.''
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,622.71 points, up 301.99 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on monday
house speaker jim wright is pledging to work with the republican leadership to produce a humanitarian aid package for the contra rebels, saying the amount of money involved isn't ``a serious stumbling block.''
together, we'll work it out,'' the speaker said of his planned negotiations with house gop leader bob michel, r-ill
today's talks come in the wake of the preliminary cease-fire agreement last week between the contras and the sandinista government of nicaragua, which allows the rebels to remain armed and in the field while entering political talks with the government
earlier this year, house democrats beat back president reagan's request for a package of weapons and ammunition for the contras, saying it would interfere with the peace process. then, republicans sided with a few democratic opponents of any contra aid to defeat the house leadership's alternative plan for $30 million in strictly ``humanitarian'' assistance _ food, clothing and the like
as a result, u.s. aid to the rebels ended feb. 29. wright is still supporting humanitarian aid, and this time he wants to ensure gop backing for the proposal
the speaker, whose high-profile role in the central american peace process has upset some administration officials, declined in an interview sunday on nbc-tv's ``meet the press'' to specify the amount of humanitarian aid he envisions
i have one, but i'm going to be amenable enough to listen to bob michel and others. i don't think the dollar figure is a serious stumbling block,'' he said
the speaker did not express any opposition to a provision in the package guaranteeing a speedy vote on military aid if the peace process breaks down, but he said triggering such a vote should be a ``collaborative'' decision by both congress and the white house
last week, wright said the aid package should include food, clothing and medical assistance for the contras. also last week, michel said he had discussed a $48 million, one-year aid package that provided an expedited vote on further aid in june
wright, reminded of congress' refusal to send military aid to the rebels, was asked if the soviets should be required to end their support to the nicaraguan government
i think it's high time that we do sit down with the soviet union and hammer that out,'' wright said. ``i don't know any good reason why we shouldn't be doing that.''
wright was asked if he believed the nicaraguan government should be allowed to receive ``whatever foreign assistance ... it deems fit in its own interest'' in light of the regional peace accord that bars funds from foreign sources seeking to overthrow a government
i don't see anything wrong with their getting humanitarian assistance or economic assistance. god knows they need all the help they can get from every source with the state their economy is in,'' the speaker said
but i think it has to come to a point where there is a cessation of military weapons. ... and now that's up to the reagan administration to sit down and negotiate that.''
nicaraguan president daniel ortega, appearing on cbs-tv's ``face the nation,'' repeated his call for direct negotiations with the united states
we're ready to talk with the united states,'' ortega said
but assistant secretary of state elliott abrams, appearing on the same program, rejected the idea of direct talks with nicaragua
we don't need bilateral talks with the sandinistas,'' abrams said
he expressed skepticism that the nicaraguan government will hold to the agreement signed with the contras, saying, ``we've heard those promises before.''
abrams said congress had forced the agreement on the rebels, saying ``congress had just smashed them into a corner'' with the cutoff of military aid
contra leader adolfo calero, also appearing on the nbc program, said he believed he should be included in the wright-michel discussions
i feel that we should be invited by speaker wright to go to washington and participate,'' he said
