filing for personal bankruptcy was ``embarrassing,'' says famed heart surgeon dr. denton cooley, but it was the only solution for his financial troubles
the 67-year-old pioneer heart surgeon's career has been a success story. he was the first to implant an artificial heart and the first american to perform a heart transplant operation, among his 70,000 open-heart surgeries
but defeat entered cooley's life on jan. 4 when he filed under chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy law, his many real estate investments in houston victimized by a depressed oil economy
i think this is the first (professional) defeat that has come to me,'' he told the houston post in sunday's editions. ``it was embarrassing. ... there's sort of an indignity that goes with it.''
but i've always felt like i was a real competitor. i have participated in all sorts of sports and athletics in the past, and one of the things you learn on the playing field is how to take defeat as well as victory.''
cooley, founder of the texas heart institute in houston, said he's one of the few people to file a reorganization plan at the same time as a request for bankruptcy protection. that move will allow him to emerge from bankruptcy as early as april, he says
i want to carry on with my life,'' he said. were there</head>
michael dukakis was late for the final rally of his michigan caucus campaign, but his staff was still scrambling to fill a half-empty hall in the polish enclave of hamtramck
at the same time, miles away in flint, 40 people were turned away from the overflowing church where jesse jackson was speaking. so they gathered around a television station's truck to watch jackson on the monitors
campaign events are an uncertain barometer of election success, but in michigan, the developments on friday were an excellent forecaster of the results on saturday
dukakis had a difficult day _ a schedule snarled by logistical problems and a sometimes testy response from some spectators
in contrast, jackson was drawing substantial, enthusiastic crowds as he motored across the state
and on saturday, that enthusiasm turned into votes that gave jackson an overwhelming victory, crushing dukakis by nearly 2-1 in the big industrial state
i think the major factor was the level of intensity of jackson supporters and the lack of intensity of other supporters,'' michigan house speaker gary owen said
owen said he found ``an overwhelming lack of enthusiasm'' for everybody but jackson. owen supports tennessee sen. albert gore jr
as expected, jackson swept the black vote by margins of up to 15-1. but he did well in others parts of the state with small minority populations, winning 10 of the state's 18 congressional districts
jackson knows well the dubious reliability of rallies and town meetings as indicators of political success. he drew big crowds in 1984 and still finished third in the democratic presidential race that year
but in michigan this time, the indicators were right on the money
in some sense, it's a lot of poetry,'' jackson said in milwaukee late saturday. ``it's a lot of history. we also have the numbers, and it's a lot of reality.''
at the hamtramck event, the audience was no longer so small as to be embarrassing when dukakis arrived with detroit mayor coleman young, sen. don riegle and others. but at least a quarter of the crowd was made up of reporters and plainclothes policemen
earlier that day in detroit, two plainclothes policemen stopped a reporter and asked why a crowd had gathered down the street. told that jesse jackson was speaking, the two parked _ and went inside the union hall to listen
crowds generally waited patiently for jackson to appear. but in comstock park, the grumbling was evident when dukakis arrived about half an hour late due to logistical problems that wiped out many of his planned events
make them wait _ we did,'' yelled one older man as dukakis cut short his town meeting in the grand rapids suburb to hold a news conference and rush to a fund-raiser
speak english _ this is america,'' said another as dukakis spoke in greek and spanish with those in the uaw hall who addressed him in those languages
jackson worked this state hard, even delaying his departure from the state on saturday to motorcade and walk through mostly black neighborhoods, encouraging his supporters to turn out
dukakis spent less time in the state. he flew in monday night for a quick visit, held a pair of news conferences wednesday night and then muddled through the day friday
part of the difference in schedules came from dukakis' commitment to return to boston to work as governor, part from dukakis' greater attention to fund-raising and part from campaign judgments about allocating candidate's time among the various states
and when dukakis was in the state, he found himself explaining over and over again that he had not flip-flopped on the trade issue, that his backing for a trade bill by sen. don riegle of michigan was not just a political ploy. rep. richard gephardt grabbed the front pages by pounding away at dukakis on trade
it didn't help gephardt _ he finished a dismal third _ but the blows kept dukakis on the defensive
the messages from the two candidates were also substantively different. dukakis talked of competence and compassion, as his televisions ads emphasized balancing budgets and creating jobs
jackson hit over and over again at his theme of hope for those who are down, who are jobless, who are out of luck
in a state where the auto industry has put thousands out of work, jackson's more optimistic message was the stronger one _ as dukakis came close to admitting saturday night in defeat
the people of michigan have been through a very difficult time. there is great unhappiness, great concern, great uncertainty. there are laid-off workers. workers today who have jobs are worried they are going to be next,'' dukakis said. ``jesse has strong feelings about that _ as i do.''
dukakis relied on an impressive organization in michigan, as he has in other states, plus endorsements from young and riegle
jackson had a good organization himself in michigan and spent about $90,000 on paid media. but he couldn't resist a swipe at dukakis
it was the message of the soul and authenticity of jesse jackson versus money and technology _ and the people prevailed,'' jackson told supporters sunday at westchester county airport in new york
everybody won something in detroit,'' jackson said when the votes were counted. ``dukakis won mayor young's endorsement. i won the people's votes.''
michael dukakis gained and jesse jackson received a smaller boost as iowa democrats went through the latest step in their lengthy process of choosing democratic national convention delegates
richard gephardt, whose hopes had surged with a victory in last month's iowa precinct caucuses, faltered in the latest test following poor showings in other states
it confirms what's going on nationally,'' said bonnie campbell, iowa democratic chairwoman
party activists over the weekend held county caucuses where they elected delegates to congressional district conventions in may and the state convention next summer. at those meetings they will elect 52 of the state's 58 delegates to the democratic national convention in atlanta. the state has six ``super delegates,'' party leaders who automatically are delegates
with 97 of the state's 99 counties reporting results of their conventions, dukakis had 28.7 percent of the delegates to gephardt's 27.9 percent. illinois sen. paul simon was third with 26.4 percent, based on a strong showing in counties along the border of his home state
jackson pulled in 13.1 percent of the delegates, improving on his performance in last month's precinct caucuses, while 3.9 percent remained uncommitted
in last month's precinct caucuses, gephardt got 31 percent, simon 27 percent, dukakis 22 percent and jackson 9 percent
dukakis backers had been quietly lobbying supporters of other candidates to switch and unite behind a front-runner
i'm telling our people to treat everyone like you would your next date,'' said jerry crawford, a dukakis organizer. ``but for some people it isn't time to get engaged yet.''
the dukakis forces targeted backers of former arizona gov. bruce babbitt, who has dropped from the race, and succeeded in picking up support
it looks like those people who defected, dukakis picked up the lion's share,'' said ms. campbell. ``jackson picked up a few.''
party activists said gephardt was damaged by his poor performance in saturday's michigan caucuses
as word filtered out of gephardt's third-place michigan showing, some of his backers apparently decided not to make the effort to attend county conventions, many of which ran until the wee hours sunday morning
jesse jackson said he was looking at the votes, not the color of the voters, in his landslide victory over michael dukakis in the state's presidential caucuses
jackson's commanding 55 percent of the vote far outstripped the state's black population, which according to the 1980 census is 13 percent
as usual, jackson galvanized the black community, which responded with a highly organized get-out-the-vote effort for saturday's caucuses
that provided him with a solid core of support _ but he didn't stop there. campaigning in connecticut on sunday, jackson said his first concern is to ``count the votes, not the color.''
it's a campaign of growth, a campaign of hope,'' he said
mary holmes, deputy state coordinator for the jackson campaign, said, ``what feels so good is that it's a clear-cut victory. it's all ours. you want to talk about the popular vote? we won that. you want to talk about the majority of delegates? we won that too.''
holmes said the keys to the jackson victory were the campaign's plan to turn out the vote for the caucuses, and jackson himself. ``it's the effect he has on people who hear him,'' she said
her comments were echoed by michigan house speaker gary owen, who said ``the major factor was the level of intensity of jackson supporters and the lack of intensity of other supporters.''
owen, who supports tennessee sen. albert gore jr., said sunday that he had campaigned several days and found ``an overwhelming lack of enthusiasm'' for any of the candidates except jackson
i know there was excitement in seeing a presidential candidate and hearing a presidential candidate, but i never felt that degree of intensity among the crowds for those other candidates,'' he said
that intensity was reflected in the vote totals, where jackson buried dukakis with 107,689 votes or 55 percent to dukakis' 55,337 or 28 percent. missouri rep. richard gephardt came in third with 24,995 or 13 percent. illinois sen. paul simon had 4,069 or 2 percent; and gore had 3,818 or 2 percent
those totals represented 94 percent of the vote counted. the state democratic party said it would release final figures sometime today
the delegate projections from those results showed jackson with 74 of the state's 138 committed delegates, dukakis with 50, gephardt 11, and uncommitted 3
michigan also will send 12 uncommitted ``super delegates'' to the july convention in atlanta. they are gov. james blanchard and the 11 members of the democratic national committee
jackson particularly swamped dukakis in the predominantly black 1st and 13th congressional districts, which cover detroit. in the 1st, jackson had 25,416 compared with 1,809 for dukakis, while in the 13th he had 17,725 to dukakis's 1,539
however, if those figures are subtracted from the two candidates' totals, jackson still comes out ahead, 64,548 to 51,989
state rep. alma stallworth, a democrat from detroit, said she thinks those figures represent ``a lot of young people and new voters who got involved for the first time.''
stallworth said the highly organized jackson campaign also got a boost from black churches, which urged people to vote
but she pointed out that jackson also did well in mostly white districts covering the western, southern and eastern lower peninsula
state rep. ilona varga, who supports jackson, said he carried her district, which is only 26 percent black, by attracting white voters
i think it says something about our people. i think it says something about our country,'' she said
he was saying what people wanted to hear,'' said state sen. david holmes, d-detroit. ``it all boils down to bread-and-butter issues regardless of race, color or creed. he outworked, outtalked and outcampaigned the other candidates in all 18 congressional districts.''
zolton ferency, a former state democratic party chairman, said organized labor leaders liked gephardt's tough trade stand, but ``his campaign was dying. they didn't want to back a loser.''
dukakis, on the other hand, wasn't well-known in michigan and had to introduce himself to the state's democrats and then try to get them to vote for him, ferency said
dukakis, he added, wasn't ``the kind of candidate that can generate instant enthusiasm.''
maneka gandhi's goals include saving the bears, monkeys, donkeys, dogs, frogs, crocodiles and, she hopes, the country
the 31-year-old writer, former model and once and probably future candidate for parliament is the estranged sister-in-law of prime minister rajiv gandhi. she's also the daughter-in-law of the late prime minister indira gandhi and the widow of sanjay gandhi, who was groomed to become prime minister but died in a crash while stunt-flying a small plane
the political game is familiar, if not always comfortable, turf for maneka
so is a front lawn filled with 14 tail-thumping, tongue-lolling puppies and dogs, 13 of them rescued from the streets of new delhi and waiting for maneka to find homes for them. the 14th is a permanent resident, maneka's pedigreed bull mastiff sabra
in mid-march, maneka disbanded her own small political party and joined forces with the janata party, one of the largest of india's many opposition groups. she declared anew her determination to see rajiv ousted, calling him an ineffective leader and his congress party corrupt
within a week, newspapers were speculating maneka would run against her brother-in-law in the next parliamentary elections, scheduled to take place by early 1990
whether i stand for office is something that will be decided in a year or two,'' maneka says
i really think quite frankly that the time for little parties is past. we have a huge upsurge of opinion against the government, but because we are all separate, none of it has come into the mainstream opposition. it's gone to the lunatic fringe,'' she said during an interview in the one-story house where she lives with her 7-year-old son feroze
in the meantime, she is continuing her animal protection campaigns and describes her political outlook as similar to that of the environment-oriented ``greens'' parties of western europe
every time i do animal work, i lose votes. i'm in politics _ that's my main philosophy. i just don't believe you can isolate one form of service from the other,'' she said
speaking with the intensity and speed of a machine gun burst, in british-accented english that is the hallmark of economically comfortable, well-educated indians, maneka launched into precise examples:
we are killing 21 million frogs a year in india for standard experiments in our school laboratories. if i run a save-the-frogs campaign, it's not because one of them is going to turn into a prince in my hand. it's because the small farmer needs them. without frogs to eat the insects in his fields, he has to buy pesticides, which will probably give him cancer. so it's really a political decision, not an animal decision, the campaign for the saving of the frogs.''
as a young bride, maneka filled the role of adoring wife and daughter-in-law. but after sanjay was killed in 1980, maneka grew apart _ outspokenly apart _ from his iron-willed mother, prime minister indira gandhi
indira, in the meantime, had plucked sanjay's older brother rajiv out of his pilot's job with indian airlines and put him in the cockpit to succeed her in what is sometimes wryly referred to as ``the world's only democratically elected dynasty.''
in 1982, maneka was pitched out of indira's house with her son, two dogs and a heap of suitcases
she started her own party, the rashtriya sanjay manch, dedicated to perpetuating what it called the populist ideas of her dead husband
when indira gandhi was assassinated in 1984, rajiv became prime minister. two months later, he successfully defended his parliament seat in new elections, swamping a field of challengers
one of them was maneka
her party faded into the shadows, but her energetic espousal of causes didn't. much of it was channeled to the sanjay gandhi animal care center on the outskirts of the capital
the red sandstone clinic, staffed by two veterinarians and 11 helpers, is refuge for sick and injured animals brought by their owners or found in the streets
or dumped at maneka's house. in this way she has acquired, at least temporarily, hundreds of dogs, the occasional bullock, a peacock with a tumor and a white donkey with one eye sightlessly opaque and an oozing hole where the other had been
i went out to dinner and came back about 11:30 and found it tied to the gate, blinded, bloody,'' maneka said
the donkey went to the animal center. it will probably stay there indefinitely, like lakshmi, a one-eyed chestnut mare who arrived nearly seven years ago. the horse's right hind leg extends foward at an improbable but permanent angle, the result of violent dislocation
lakshmi, named for a hindu goddess, is one of maneka's favorites. ``she's my first. that's why we call her lakshmi. it means luck,'' maneka said as she led a tour of the clinic and grounds where 41 dogs were ensconced
she also serves as a free-lance consultant for wildlife sanctuaries throughout india, counseling warmer water for crocodiles penned in icy himalayan waters, trying to figure out why some monkeys at bangalore aren't breeding, and how to end the plight of the dancing bears
there are 10,000 bears in india who have been kidnapped from the himalayas,'' she said. ``they have their teeth pulled out, their nails pulled out. they're made to dance. their average lifespan is 42 years, but they die at 3.''
she has heard about a man who wants to donate land for an animal sanctuary, ``so maybe it's going to fit in with my bears. maybe we can use zoos as halfway houses, get the railroads to transport them, rehabilitate the bear handlers _ some can work in the sanctuary, line up businessmen to give the others jobs.''
in between politics and animal care, she writes a biweekly pet column for newspapers, has just completed a book on the origins of indian names and has promised two more, one of fairy tales, the other on the plants of india
the book of names, she said, was ``the kind of job i don't have any business undertaking, like most of the things i do. but if you wait for people? so i just sort of begin. every time i start something, it's always sort of off the beaten track.''
a first lady once criticized for extravagance got in a good-natured jab at her soviet counterpart's own fashionable ways when nancy reagan put on a surprise singing performance at the washington media's annual gridiron club dinner
mrs. reagan, dressed in a red formal gown, unexpectedly appeared on stage saturday night as a chorus of journalists was wrapping up its ribbing of key figures in the news, including the first family, the presidential candidates and jim and tammy bakker
the first lady received two standing ovations for her song, which included a verse about her meetings with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's wife, raisa, during the washington summit last december
to the tune of ``thanks for the memories,'' mrs. reagan sang, ``thanks for the memory, the soviet mona lisa, sometimes known as raisa, she said to me, `would you like to see my mastercard and visa?'''
president reagan, beaming at his wife's show-stopper, issued the challenge ``raisa, top that'' after mrs. reagan's song
it was all in good humor,'' mrs. reagan's press secretary elaine crispin said sunday. ``the whole gridiron is done in that spirit, and that's all that's intended.'' she said the words to mrs. reagan's song were written by former white house speech-writer landon parvin
although both mrs. reagan and mrs. gorbachev maintained that their relations during the december summit were warm, observers noticed a coolness between the two women
it was mrs. reagan's second appearance as a solo singer on the gridiron stage. in 1982, amidst criticism of her expensive tastes, she stepped out in an outlandish hawaiian print dress with polka dot sleeves and yellow galoshes and sang a self-effacing ``second hand clothes'' to the tune of ``second hand rose.''
mrs. reagan was an actress but has sung only occasionally
reagan, in his traditional gridiron response, poked fun at vice president george bush and bush's fellow republican presidential candidate pat robertson as well as rich republicans
before i refuse to take questions,'' reagan said, ``i have an opening statement. i thought nancy's performance was absolutely wonderful. raisa, top that.''
reagan later said if robertson becomes president, ``there'd be no more `hail to the chief.' it would be `when the saints go marching in.''
referring to the fact that bush was born in massachusetts, has family connections in connecticut, has been active in politics in texas, and spends time in maine, reagan said bush could win ``if he carries his own states.''
during the show, a chorus of washington journalists thanked reagan ``for the memories'' _ the memories ``of david stockman and jim watt, the iran-contra plot, of ollie and bill casey, the diversions you forgot.''
the tune lampooned former budget director david stockman, the late cia director casey, ex-interior secretary james watt and former white house aide oliver north
the 103-year-old club also presented a spoof to the tune of ``to all the girls i've loved before'' by show members playing former sen. gary hart and television evangelist jim bakker
here are the words mrs. reagan sang:
thanks for the memory, of all the times we had, the happy and the sad
looking back, don regan doesn't seem so bad
oh, it's been so swell
thanks for the memory, the soviet mona lisa, sometimes known as raisa, she said to me, `would you like to see my mastercard and visa?'
oh, it's been so swell
not all was happy, that's granted
the congress, it raved and ranted
the right wing became disenchanted
in spite of it all, we had a ball
thanks for the memory, of the whole press corps, at times i cursed and swore
you sometimes were a headache, but you never were a bore
so, thanks for the memory, it's time to say goodbye
oh, how the time does fly
ronny's loved these past eight years, and so i confess have i
thank you, bye bye.'' prices. pickup 4th graf pvs ``traders said...''</note>
the dollar fell sharply against the japanese yen in tokyo monday while stock prices rose
the dollar closed at 124.43 yen, down 1.31 yen from friday's close of 125.74 yen, after opening the day's session at 124.60
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which lost 305.99 points in saturday's half day of trading, rose 301.99 points, or 1.19 percent, and closed at 25,622.71
traders said the dollar continued to decline even after the bank of japan intervened in early trading by buying dollars to support the u.s. currency, said ken iio, a currency dealer with the bank of tokyo
the dollar's opening level was its lowest since jan. 5, when it began trading at 123.00 yen
on the stock market, dealers said the lower dollar did not affect prices because market participants were expecting the central bank to continue to prop up the u.s. currency. demonstration</head>
about 100 people threw stones and bottles that broke windows and smashed the front door of the iraqi embassy in an angry demonstration against chemical weapons attacks that killed more than 5,000 kurds last week
but local police said no one was arrested in sunday's incident
a supreme court ruling last week knocked down a rule that had kept all demonstrations, including peaceful ones, at least 500 feet away from foreign embassies. however, the court still allowed police to disperse groups congregating near embassies when they ``reasonably believe that a threat to the security or peace of the embassy is present.''
iran has said iraq used internationally banned poison gas bombs in a march 20 air raid that killed 5,000 kurdish villagers. a leader of kurdish rebels in the area of northeastern iraq occupied by iran said at least 50 other kurds were killed and scores wounded thursday when iraqi planes bombed seyo and senan villages nearby
iran's official islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, cyprus, said the iraqis used cyanide, mustard and other unidentified nerve gases in the attacks ``to prevent the people from joining iranian combatants.''
the attacks came in the latest confrontations of the 7{-year war between iran and iraq which began in september 1980. fighting has recently intensified in the kurdistan mountains for control of a strategic area east of the kirkuk oil fields, which produces more than half the oil that finances iraq's war effort
many kurds, a semi-nomadic sunni moslem people, have been fighting the baghdad government for years
a judge's decision to reunite two girls with their father three years after they watched him strangle their mother has touched off a new custody fight and public outrage against the judge
i guess the bottom line is whether or not it's ok to kill your wife in front of your children,'' says gene tranel of eldridge, iowa, brother of the 26-year-old victim, carol lutgen
tranel, who took in his nieces, tracy, 11, and dana, 10, while james lutgen served a 20-month prison term, is fighting to get them back
but lutgen's lawyer, william schirger, says the case has been blown out of proportion in this small mississippi river town
the kids are not in any danger. jim loves the girls and they love him. they asked the judge to let them live with him,'' schirger said
lutgen, 33, pleaded guilty to voluntary manslaughter for the dec. 21, 1984, death of his wife at the family home in tiny menominee, in the northwest corner of illinois
two original murder counts against lutgen were reduced after the court ruled his daughters were too young to testify as witnesses to their mother's death
the lutgens were on the verge of a breakup as the 1984 holiday season approached. ``she didn't love jim no more,'' recalled lutgen's mother, grace. ``they were separating the day after christmas. he was broken up about it.''
the couple's fatal battle was fueled by lutgen's belief that his wife was seeing another man, his mother said, although the fight was sparked by a disagreement over whether to take the girls shopping and skating
as the girls looked on, verbal attack became physical confrontation
i picked the girls up afterward and they told me ... they had seen part of the fight,'' mrs. lutgen said. ``they said they were pushing and grabbing each other around the neck.''
lutgen was released from prison in october 1986 and regained custody of his daughters last dec. 29
the jo daviess county judge who made the custody decision, eric demar of galena, has borne the brunt of the public outcry since lutgen regained his daughters
demar has been attacked by mail, over the telephone and in newspaper articles and editorials
a judge can't always make a popular decision and that certainly is the truth in this case,'' he said
the law and the facts in the case left me no choice,'' he added, noting that the u.s. supreme court has placed a high priority on parental rights in custody cases
lutgen, a cement finisher in the construction business, has not responded to requests for comment. but his mother says she believes there is no risk to the girls
i check on them several times a week. i'd never let anything happen to them. they love their dad,'' she said
lutgen has continued to have family troubles. his mother said he and the girls moved out of her house to one of his two brothers' homes after an argument with her last month
meanwhile, tranel has fought lutgen's request for custody of the girls. he filed a wrongful death lawsuit against his former brother-in-law and is appealing demar's custody decision
it seems to me to be so basically, morally wrong for the children to go back to their parent in a case like this,'' said tranel, who has visitation rights
is that person a fit and proper parent?'' tranel asked. ``how can you get your children back and go on like nothing happened?''
schirger countered that lutgen's criminal conviction did not strip him of his parental rights, and he has not been proved an unfit parent
chrysler corp. chairman lee iacocca, who continues to disavow interest in the democratic party's presidential nomination, won the plurality of write-in votes cast in the michigan presidential primary
second place went to new york gov. mario cuomo, who also says he won't seek the party's nomination
other non-candidates and notables also got backing from write-ins
new jersey sen. bill bradley, who last week endorsed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, picked up at least seven votes
candidates who left the race early, arizona gov. bruce babbitt and deleware sen. joe biden, each pulled minor support from write-ins
so did candidates who battled for the nomination 16 years ago _ edmund muskie and george mcgovern
even republican sen. robert dole of kansas, whose bid for the gop nomination is hanging by a frayed thread, received one vote in the democratic caucuses
and, how about rock star ozzie osbourne? or maybe the road runner's arch enemy wile e. coyote?
they each got one vote. the road runner got no votes
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis holds a slim lead over jesse jackson but many likely democratic voters are undecided on a candidate going into wisconsin's april 5 presidential preference primary, a new poll indicates
the milwaukee sentinel, in results being released in today's editions, said the statewide public opinion poll conducted last week showed dukakis to be the choice of 28 percent of the likely democratic voters
jackson, winner of the michigan caucus vote saturday, was the choice of 25 percent, but another 25 percent of those likely to vote for a democrat in the primary were undecided
among other democratic candidates, illinois sen. paul simon had 9 percent, missouri rep. richard gephardt 7 percent and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. 4 percent
on the republican side, vice president george bush was the choice of 62 percent of those likely to vote for a republican, while kansas sen. robert dole was the choice of 27 percent. the rev. pat robertson received 3 percent, and 7 percent were undecided
the sentinel said its telephone survey of 798 randomly-selected wisconsin adults was conducted march 17-22
among the sample of 158 people identified as likely to vote in the democratic primary, the margin of sampling error was plus or minus 7.9 percent
with the new york primary less than a month away, a recent poll shows massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush to be the clear favorites among democratic and republican voters across the state. the daily news poll, published sunday, had dukakis favored by 45 percent of the democrats surveyed. his closest rival was jesse jackson, preferred by 29 percent of the democrats
none of the three other active democratic candidates were favored by more than 6 percent of the voters who participated in the survey. missouri rep. richard gephardt was favored by 6 percent, illinois sen. paul simon by 5 percent and tennessee sen. albert gore by 5 percent
on the republican side, voters surveyed favored bush by 68 percent, kansas sen. bob dole by 23 percent and former television evangelist pat roberson by 4 percent
the poll, conducted for the daily news by chilton research services of radnor, pa., surveyed 528 democrats and 496 republicans who said they intended to vote in the primary. the poll was conducted between monday, march 21 and thursday, march 24 and has a margin for error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points
two hundred twenty-five democratic delegates and 136 gop delegates are at stake in the april 19 primary
if vice president george bush becomes the republican party's candidate for the presidency, he will have the support of pat robertson
robertson, a former television evangelist and current gop hopeful, also said over the weekend that if bush is elected, he most likely would not challenge him in 1992 if bush opted for a second term
it will all depend on what george bush does as president,'' robertson said in a news conference following a rally of his supporters. ``basically i would support the republican president. that would not be a wise thing _ to go against the president of your own party.''
but until the national convention, robertson said he is concentrating on his own campaign, a campaign he admits no longer is aimed at the white house but at the future
and if he is to survive, robertson told his supporters he must win his home state's upcoming caucuses
robertson placed third earlier this month behind bush and kansas sen. bob dole in virginia's non-binding primary. he also was third in his hometown of virginia beach
the punishment of fallen tv evangelist jimmy swaggart was left to his church's key governing body today, in an effort to settle a dispute between state and national leaders of the assemblies of god
the pentecostal denomination's 250-member general presbytery opens a two-day meeting, with a decision on swaggart's punishment expected tuesday afternoon, church spokeswoman juleen turnage said
the general presbytery will have the final say on swaggart's rehabilitation. swaggart has been linked to a prostitute, but the exact nature of his transgression has not been disclosed since he tearfully stepped down from his pulpit feb. 21
the louisiana presbytery of the assemblies of god had recommended that swaggart undergo two years of rehabilitation and be suspended from his baton rouge, la., pulpit for three months
but the executive presbytery, 13 men who serve as a national board of directors for the church, asked the state district to reconsider what some called an unprecedentedly lenient response to a minister's moral lapse
after gathering again on feb. 29 in a nine-hour session, the louisiana presbytery stood by its original decision. the general presbytery, whose members include representatives from each of the church's state districts, has been charged with resolving the conflict
reports circulated that swaggart would leave the assemblies of god if church officials suspended him from his pulpit for longer than three months. but a spokesman for swaggart's ministry said he has made no decision on how he might react to the national council's decision
mrs. turnage said she did not believe the general presbytery would be swayed by ``rumors heard through the media.''
church officials refused to comment on a newspaper report that a compromise proposal has been offered that would bar swaggart from preaching for one year, but would order him to give public testimony about his sin
the 10-page proposal, obtained sunday night by the springfield news-leader, was worked out by cliff jackson, a little rock, ark., lawyer and church member who said the plan has been endorsed by both swaggart and louisiana church leaders
swaggart, who addressed his congregation briefly in baton rouge on sunday as he has done several times since formally relinquishing the pulpit, is not expected to appear at today's meeting, mrs. turnage said
in response to reporters' shouted questions as he drove from the service, swaggart said he wasn't planning to leave the ministry, adding, ``why should i?''
the general presbytery is a court of last resort on ministerial credentials. a minister usually appeals to it after his course of rehabilitation has been set by the executive presbytery and a state council. the executive presbytery short-circuited that process when it decided march 3 to turn the swaggart case over to the larger body
the louisiana presbytery has close ties to swaggart's jimmy swaggart world ministries, a television-church-school complex based in baton rouge that broadcasts swaggart's fiery sermons to several countries. louisiana superintendent cecil janway, for example, sits on swaggart's board
jimmy swaggart world ministries took in an estimated $150 million in 1986. donations have fallen off since swaggart's confession, forcing the ministry to lay off about 100 people and suspend construction at the jimmy swaggart bible school
but swaggart seems undaunted and apparently is counting on the general presbytery to follow the louisiana district's recommendation that he be barred from the pulpit for only three months
swaggart told the congregation wednesday that he was going out of his mind but ``when i'm back in the pulpit on may 22, i'll be back in my mind.''
may 22 would be three months from the day swaggart confessed and voluntarily stepped down from his pulpit
the federal government estimates that between 1973 and 1985 more than 12.3 million cars, trucks, vans and motorcycles valued at $52 billion were stolen from americans
after recovery of about 65 percent of them, losses were estimated at $29 billion in 1985 dollars, the government said sunday
insurance payments reduced actual losses to vehicle owners to an estimated $16.1 billion, according to an analysis of the bureau of justice statistics national crime surveys for the the 13-year period
the number of thefts per 1,000 registered vehicles fell 33 percent over the surveyed period, from nine to just six, the bureau concluded in an analysis of its semiannual surveys of more than 40,000 households nationwide
in addition to the vehicle thefts during the period, there were an estimated 7 million attempted thefts, said bjs director steven schlesinger. about 64 percent of those were not reported to police, he said, and 13 percent of the actual vehicle thefts also went unreported
half of the thefts involved a loss of $2,455 or more before recoveries and insurance payments. about 10 percent involved losses of $10,000 or more
a survey of college presidents indicates women may have trouble combining marriage with a climb to the top of the academic ladder
in a survey released sunday by the american council on education, 90 percent of male college presidents but only 35 percent of the female presidents said they were married
excluding nuns, priests and other members of religious orders, it said, ``the difference ... narrows somewhat. among the lay presidents, 93 percent of men but 49 percent of women were married.''
the women presidents were more likely to be divorced _ 11 percent compared with 3 percent of the men
the council's report on its survey, called ``the american college president: a contemporary profile,'' concluded, ``the image of who shall occupy the chief executive office is clearly still a traditional one.''
the survey indicated the typical college president is white, male, married and 53 years old
western europe's top airline regulator is warning u.s. officials that there may be a sudden rise in fares in this country as a result of deregulation
frederick soerensen, head of the air transport division at the european commission, says u.s. deregulation has been in the main successful. but then he adds: ``when we see how, after the first few months of enthusiastic expansionism, the number of operational airlines is tending to shrink further and further, we may well wonder whether deregulation does not lead, in the end, to cartelization, and whether the tendency for fares to fall in the first few years may not suddenly go in reverse
what is more the united states has run into unexpected infrastructure problems and operating conditions are becoming difficult. i am thinking in particular of airport congestion at peak operating times.''
soerensen's criticism was in a paper he distributed during a visit to the united states last week
paul ridgeway's magic trick was a hit with his audience, but it was a bomb as far as police were concerned
ridgeway used the trick during his address on ``the impact of special events'' before public relations people at a downtown hotel. he had been invited by tom jardine, vice president of public relations for the carlson companies
the reason why tom gives me a nice introduction is that i have this dating book and it's really hot,'' ridgeway told the group as he opened a book and a flame magically shot out
the group laughed and ridgeway, a public relations consultant, finished his talk. but he left the book behind when he left the hotel thursday
a hotel employee called security guards when he opened the prop and saw wires and batteries. a guard took it to a basement office, checked it over and decided it was harmless
but hotel officials had second thoughts on friday and called police
there was a strange odor coming from it,'' said sgt. rick nelson of the bomb squad
nelson wrapped the book in a lead-lined blanket, drove it to the bomb squad's disposal range and blew it apart with a high-pressure water cannon
an irish firefighter says that after traveling to eight american cities named dublin on a three-week visit to the united states, he is ready to return to the dublin he knows best
seamus o'connor, station officer of the dublin, ireland, fire department and coordinator of the visit, wrapped up his tour with five other irish firefighters by shopping sunday afternoon in this columbus suburb
dublin, ohio, with a population of 14,000, has been a city since september and has planned a yearlong celebration. dublin, ireland, is marking its 1,000th birthday this year
o'connor, 44, said there are 16 cities named dublin in the united states, but ``four thousand miles is enough in one trip.''
maybe we'll visit the other dublins during our 2000th anniversary,'' he said
the firefighters have been to dublins in indiana, north carolina, maryland, pennsylvania, virginia, georgia, kentucky and ohio in an attempt to ``to share greetings of native irish with the offspring dublins,'' o'conner said
this is the biggest dublin we've been to in the united states and the most modern,'' o'connor said of the ohio city. ``but it's very irish-connected. they have many things planned around the irish, but i say `never enough.'''
jesse jackson's weekend victory in the michigan democratic presidential caucuses raised the stakes in wisconsin's april 5 primary
massachussets gov. michael s. dukakis will begin an ``aggressive campaign'' of television advertising in wisconsin tuesday and will be in the state thursday through april 5, said dukakis' wisconsin campaign manager, pat forciea
we feel this is a two-person race,'' forciea said
some of the dukakis advertising will be new, but he will not take on jackson in the commercials, forciea said
none of the ads are zapping anybody,'' he said
jackson edged dukakis in saturday's michigan caucuses for his first win in a major northern industrial state
jackson said he was confident he could follow michigan with another victory in wisconsin ``because i've stood here with the meat packers in cudahy, the auto workers in kenosha, and the paper workers in de pere.''
dukakis, who entered saturday's caucuses as the front-runner and ended in an almost 2-1 loss to jackson, refused to categorize the results as a significant setback
as i said in the beginning of this campaign, it's a marathon,'' dukakis said. ``you've asked me about inevitability. as i have said on more than one occasion, nothing is inevitable about anything in american politics
i hope when we finish up in california and new jersey, i have a lead i can take into the convention . . . and win the nomination.''
dukakis and jackson joined sen. albert gore jr., of tennesee, rep. richard gephardt, of missouri, and sen. paul simon, of illinois, at a democratic party fund-raising dinner in milwaukee saturday night
both dukakis and jackson left sunday for connecticut to lobby for last-minute support before that state's primary tuesday, while simon and gore remained in wisconsin
wisconsin democratic chairwoman suellen albrecht predicted nearly two-thirds of the wisconsin voters who go to the polls april 5 will vote for a democrat, giving the state its largest role in selecting a presidential nominee in 12 years
albrecht said wisconsin residents could expect to see ``full-blown'' campaigning efforts from all the remaining democratic candidates over the next 10 days
prior to the jefferson-jackson day dinner in milwaukee, all the candidates except jackson joined about 1,500 people in an afternoon labor rally and march to support nearly 600 marathon electric corp. shop workers represented by the international brotherhood of electrical workers local 1791 who have been involved in a four-month fight over wage cuts in wausau
dukakis, gephardt, and simon walked behind a bright orange solidarity banner with the workers and their supporters
each candidate wore orange armbands saying ``solidarity local 1791'' as they sought the vote of laborers in wisconsin
you've got a fight on your hands, and i want you to know you've got friends across the state and across the nation and we're here,'' gore told a rally at a downtown parking lot before the march
jackson sent former new mexico gov. toney anaya to show his support
while the front-runners began planning strategy to capture delegates in the remaining states, gephardt prepared to meet with family and advisers to decide whether he would pull out of the race and run for re-election to congress
gephardt has canceled his wisconsin schedule and scheduled a news conference today where it is expected he will annouce he will file as a candidate for re-election by tuesday's deadline
gephardt had said he needed to do well in michigan to sustain a candidacy that took off in iowa but stumbled in the south on super tuesday. he finished a disappointing third
dukakis said the field of candidates probably would be narrowed again after wisconsin's primary. jackson declined to comment on whether a wisconsin victory would make him the front-runner. but jackson also said he had been the front-runner for a year
the average retail price of gasoline fell again during the past two weeks, although prices were still higher than a year ago, according to an industry survey
the price drop for all grades of gasoline was 0.78 cents a gallon, bringing the average price to 94.96 cents a gallon as of march 25, according to the lundberg survey of gasoline prices from stations around the united states
the average price is just over 1{ cents a gallon more than that of march 1987, and almost a nickel less than the march 1986 price when crude oil prices were crashing, analyst trilby lundberg said sunday
the average prices for self-service pumps were: regular unleaded, 85.55 cents a gallon; premium unleaded, $1.0083 cents a gallon; and regular leaded, 82.13 cents a gallon
for full-service pumps, regular unleaded was $1.1625 cents a gallon, premium unleaded $1.2653 cents a gallon and regular unleaded was $1.1202 cents
a contra rebel freed after more than four years in prison said he will rejoin the contras, who negotiated his release under an amnesty agreement with the leftist sandinista government
roberto amador was among 100 people who walked out of the zona franca jail on the outskirts of the capital sunday as a result of the agreement, part of a government-rebel cease-fire accord signed last week in sapoa
i will continue being a major in the fdn,'' amador said, referring to the contra military arm, the national democratic force, which will still be allowed to operate in designated cease-fire zones. sandinista and contra leaders were to meet in sapoa again today to determine where those zones will be located
when he was freed, amador received a hug from his wife, melba, who returned from miami on saturday with their two sons
it's a benediction from god that this happened,'' he said of his release. amador, 43, was captured on oct. 3, 1983, when sandinista troops shot down the dc-3 supply plane he was piloting for the contra rebels
two other captured crew members, jaime lau and wilfredo gutierrez, also were released sunday. but a fourth, miguel angel lopez, was not included on the list, said amador, who also was a major in the now-disbanded national guard of president anastasio somoza who was toppled in the 1979 sandinista revolution
gonzalo ramirez, president of the nicaraguan red cross, said on sunday that contra negotiators had asked for amador's freedom during last week's talks
isidora zapata, a mother of two, also left the prison sunday
i was condemned to 30 years in jail for counterrevolutionary activities,'' said mrs. zapata, the only woman among those released
i was jailed since april 16, 1982, and since then have seen my two children very little,'' she said. ``my husband died the same year i went to jail. i don't know what he died of.''
also among those released were 12 members of the independent liberal party and 12 from the social christian party
all were activists in our party and not contras, which they were accused of being,'' said eduardo coronado, an independent liberal
relatives embraced the prisoners as they left the jail, but there was a tinge of anxiety
they say i don't have anything to fear,'' said feliz pedro chavaria gomez, 32. ``i'm happy, but i hope it (the cease-fire) doesn't fail.'' he said he was arrested in 1980 and charged with being a counterrevolutionary
the prisoner release was the first step in an amnesty the government agreed to last week when it signed an accord with the u.s.-backed contra leadership that calls for a formal 60-day cease-fire to begin april 1
the amnesty law, passed saturday by the national assembly, could affect the fate of an estimated 3,300 politial prisoners
police riding herd on tens of thousands of youths who jammed this desert resort for spring break have made 140 arrests and issued 545 citations, but report the students are behaving fairly well
authorities say there have been no repeats of the rioting that occurred in 1986, when youths went on a downtown rampage, throwing beer bottles and tearing the clothes off young women
about 99 percent of those arrested were for public drunkenness,'' said police lt. lee weigel on sunday. ``but all in all, it appears as though the students are being pretty good.''
vacationing young people began invading this desert city 120 miles east of los angeles on friday, clogging the streets as they cruised and caroused. traffic was backed up for several miles on the roads entering palm springs on sunday
instead of rioting, huge crowds have flocked to ice cream and yogurt parlors as temperatures soared to 100 degrees, said police officer karen holtz
from friday through sunday, police issued 545 citations for misdemeanor offenses and made 140 arrests, weigel said
police prepared for the onslaught. the 82-officer palm springs force is working 12-hour shifts all week and being supplemented with officers from the california highway patrol and riverside county sheriff's deputies
officials were unable to estimate how many youths were in the city of 36,000 permanent residents because many visitors stayed in hotels outside the city, weigel said. picks up pvs 5th graf bgng ``abrams, the ....''</note>
the reagan administration is sending panamanians the blunt message that their nation's crisis will end if the military turns on gen. manuel antonio noriega
ultimately, i think it's going to have to be the (national) guard itself that gets rid of him,'' assistant secretary of state elliott abrams said sunday
abrams, appearing on cbs-tv's ``face the nation'' expressed hope that the military strongman would be forced out in ``a matter of days.''
noriega has been indicted by a u.s. federal grand jury on drug trafficking charges. the reagan administration has demanded that noriega step down and go into exile
the new york times, in today's editions, says administration officials considered forcible extradition of noriega to the united states
panamanian opposition leaders in washington said they understood from the administration and from leaders in latin america that the united states had considered seeking to have noriega arrested in costa rica, the newspaper said
the times also said the panamanian strongman had tried to arrange a visit to costa rica over the weekend. according to senior latin american diplomats, the times said, noriega wanted to discuss his political future with costa rica's president oscar arias sanchez and prime minister felipe gonzalez of spain
gonzalez was in costa rica over the weekend. spain has offered noriega asylum if the united states agrees not to ask madrid for his extradition
panamanian opposition leaders said arias rejected noriega's request for a meeting and also refused to see a top deputy of the general
abrams, the state department official in charge of central and latin american policy, acknowledged that he is surprised the military leader is still in power in the face of u.s. opposition and a general strike at home
i guessed wrong. i thought he'd be gone by now,'' abrams said. ``i think he's clinging at this point by his fingertips.''
abrams made the comments as he pointed out that noriega has not been able to pay his military supporters
on saturday, bankers rejected a panamanian government demand for $70 million in their vaults. the government's attempt to secure the funds came after it was unable to meet the 15,000-member military's payroll
noriega ordered a shake-up of his forces after a failed coup on march 16. over the weekend, he sent in troops and police to reopen panama city's flour mills in an attempt to break the general strike aimed at ousting the military leader
the panamanian government has been strapped for cash because of economic sanctions taken by the united states. u.s. military aid to panama was suspended by congress last year as the political situation began to deteriorate
abrams, however, said ``it's got to be the national guard itself'' that forces noriega out of power. ``he just won't leave. ... he doesn't care about panama. he doesn't care about the defense forces. he doesn't care about the economy. he doesn't care about the people.''
asked about any possible threat to u.s. citizens in the country, abrams said the united states intends to protect the 50,000 military people and civilians there
if there is a threat from gen. noriega, it won't last long,'' he said
abrams, speaking with reporters following his television appearance, was asked whether the united states would use its military to protect its interests in panama
we have an obligation to protect americans in panama, the bases, and a treaty right and obligation to protect the (panama) canal and we will do it,'' he responded
abrams repeated administration assertions that an offer from the dominican republic to give asylum to noriega is not good enough, and that it would be better if the military leader accepted a similar offer from spain
the way to end this crisis is to get him out of the country,'' abrams said
nicaraguan exiles and supporters prayed for peace in a special outdoors mass, but many worried that contra leaders had been too eager to sign a cease-fire agreement with the sandinistas
more than 300 people, palm fronds in hand, gathered in this nicaraguan enclave to pray in a special outdoors palm sunday mass
all the deaths were for nothing if they signed a treaty in just four hours,'' said segundo marenco, a member of the exile group that organized the mass. ``they haven't asked for the retirement of cuban troops from nicaragua. it's just another way to buy time for the sandinistas.''
we are looking for peace _ peace with freedom. the resistance is going to continue to resist until their rights are respected,'' said retired army gen. john singlaub, who has waged a public and private battle to keep the contras fighting
the gathering came a day after a handful of demonstrators _ one who punched contra official enrique sanchez in the mouth _ protested the cease-fire agreement outside a miami hotel where rebel leaders were holding closed-door meetings
the general feeling is confusion _ what will happen now in nicaragua,'' roberto serrano, an engineer who has worked as a wine importer since leaving his homeland, said at the mass. ``we have to wait and see.''
we want peace in nicaragua, but we don't believe we have enough guarantees to go back, for we believe the sandinistas don't like to be at peace inside nicaragua,'' exile eduardo salgado said
under the pact, which declares a cease-fire until june 1, the contras agreed not to accept any more u.s. military aid. in return, the sandinistas promised a gradual amnesty for contras and unrestricted freedom of expression that would allow them a role in nicaragua's political process
share prices dropped on the london stock exchange today morning as investors reacted to friday's plunge on wall street
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index fell 16.8 points, or 1 percent, to 1,751.1 by 11 a.m
shares prices fell despite a recovery in tokyo share prices earlier today
however, dealers said the london market didn't have much direction of its own, with little trading taking place ahead of the extended easter holiday weekend that will begin friday
major shares were down across the board, with some composite insurance stocks showing the only rise
the early trend followed the sharp fall in new york friday, where the dow jones industrial average fell 44.92 to 1,978.95, and gains in tokyo overnight, where the nikkei index rose 301.99 to 25,622.71
an off-duty police officer pleaded with his colleagues to kill him after he apparently fatally shot his 24-year-old wife, a sheriff's recruit, during a struggle over a gun, neighbors said
pablo j. agrio, 29, a four-year veteran of the san diego police department, was being held today without bail in the death of alma catalina, police said
he was booked for investigation of homicide, and the district attorney's office will decide today what charges to file, said police officer pete westrick. however, investigators believe the shooting was accidental, he said
april montera, a neighbor of agrio, said he greeted police in tears after they responded saturday night to an emergency call at the paradise hills condominium
he was waving his arms and telling the cops to shoot him,'' said mrs. montera
agrio told investigators that he and his wife exchanged blows during an argument, and then his wife seized the gun and pointed it at him, said sgt. anne o'dell, a police spokeswoman
during the struggle over the handgun, the weapon discharged and struck mrs. agrio in the head, killing her instantly,'' the sergeant said
the weapon may have been the officer's firearm, o'dell said
the couple's son, 18-month-old pablolita, apparently slept through the altercation, neighbors said
alma catalina, a recruit correctional officer at the san diego county sheriff's academy, was scheduled to graduate this spring
a moderate offshore earthquake rattled the hawaiian islands but caused no damage or injuries, authorities said
the temblor, measuring 5.5 on the richter scale of ground motion, struck at 5:33 p.m. sunday about 35 miles west of hawaii island. fifteen minutes later, an aftershock of 4.1 was recorded
a 5.2 earthquake hit in the same area two days earlier
the strength of sunday's quake was not great enough to generate a tsunami, or tidal wave, said richard sillcox of the pacific tsunami warning center
the temblor was unrelated to kilauea, the world's most active volcano, which has been in eruption on hawaii island since jan. 3, 1983, said tom wright, scientist in charge of the u.s. geological survey's hawaiian volcano observatory
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. thus a reading of 5.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 4.5
an earthquake of 5 can cause considerable damage in a populated area, while a 6 can cause severe damage. the san francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the richter scale
let us not make a mistake. let us not confuse ourselves. they have only signed a cease-fire.'' _ roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo of nicaragua, commenting on the truce between the contras and the sandinistas
the democratic voters are sending a very strong message to the party. the quality of leadership is something they like and admire. this is a referendum on him and a referendum he's winning.'' _ ann lewis, a democratic strategist and informal adviser to the jesse jackson campaign, on jackson's michigan primary victory
i guess the bottom line is whether or not it's ok to kill your wife in front of your children.'' _ gene tranel of eldridge, iowa, brother of a 26-year-old woman killed by her husband, who has regained custody of his children
the chinese government today announced a major overhaul of its bureaucracy to streamline operations, eliminate 10,000 jobs and reduce its role in the direct management of the economy
song ping, state councillor and head of the communist party organization department, outlined proposals under which 14 ministries under the state council will be abolished, one redefined and 10 new ones set up
it will mean a net reduction of five state council organs from the current 45, song told a session of the national people's congress, china's parliament. the 10,000 staffers dropped from the payroll will be transferred to other jobs
the new bodies should be set up within three months after being approved during the current congressional session, but the process of making the state council more efficient and reducing overlapping will take time, song said
the functions of government offices and work methods cannot be changed all at once and a new work order cannot be established at once either,'' he said
song said the reorganization was transitional and will lay the groundwork for further restructuring of the state council, equivalent to china's cabinet
the reorganization will address such problems as too rigid micro-management and insufficient macro-control, overlapping functions, overstaffing, low working efficiency and lack of clarity about duties, the state councillor said
the reforms will reduce the staff directly under the state council from 50,000 to 40,000, he said
the government, as part of reforms to separate the functions of government and business, will no longer manage enterprises directly, as it has under soviet-style central planning, song said. instead, government organs will be responsible for general planning, finances, supervision and regulation
the current annual session of the congress, which convened last week, is also to pass a law guaranteeing the rights of factory managers to run their plants without undue interference from the government
the 10 new bodies to be created are the ministries of personnel, labor, materials, transportation, energy, construction, aeronautics and astronautics industry, water resources, machine building and electronics industry and the state planning commission
that commission, merging the current planning and economic commissions, is to be a powerful body in charge of formulating china's development strategies
song said the new commission will no longer engage in direct management of trade and industrial operations, as the two existing commissions do. the commission is expected to be headed by veteran economic expert and vice premier yao yilin, who heads the current state planning commission
the labor and personnel ministry will be split into two ministries, with the new labor ministry responsible for overseeing reforms in china's labor structure and the personnel ministry in charge of introducing a state civil servant system
the new transportation ministry will combine the ministries of railways and communications and the state air transport control administration
china's antiquated and overtaxed transportation system has come under strong criticism as a result of one air crash and four fatal train crashes this year, killing 277 people
song outlined the proposed energy ministry as encompassing the work of the ministries of coal industry, petroleum industry and nuclear industry
the official xinhua news agency will become a separate institution under the state council. previously it was an administrative organ listed as one of the 45 state council units, he said
he said the 10,000 people to be pared from state council payrolls will be transferred to units handling taxation, finance, prices, auditing, supervision, statistics and law enforcement. many will join companies and institutions engaged in information, consultancy and research, he said
transferring workers to companies will raise efficiency, eliminate bureaucracy and promote the introduction of a civil service system, song said
a six-week-old sedition trial in which white supremacists are accused of plotting to overthrow the government by force could go to the all-white jury this week if the defense completes its case
prosecutors contend the 13 defendants conspired to replace the federal government with an aryan nation. the defendants say the government is trying to silence its critics
the defense started presenting its case last week in the sixth week of the trial and several defendants plan to take the stand
prosecutors predicted when the trial began feb. 16 that they would spend two months and call 200 witnesses, but they rested monday after five weeks and 106 witnesses
u.s. district judge morris arnold has repeatedly reminded the jury, ``mere disagreement with the government is not seditious conspiracy.''
seditious conspiracy, he said, requires two or more persons to plot to bring down the government by actions that produce, or are likely to produce, imminent lawless action
the government contends the sedition defendants robbed, counterfeited, bombed and murdered, and witnesses have testified how money to do so was distributed
a key government witness, unindicted co-conspirator james ellison, led an arkansas white supremacist group _ the covenant, the sword and the arm of the lord _ until his arrest in 1985. he is serving 20 years in prison
ellison said defendant louis ray beam jr. called for war against the government, and that co-defendant robert edward miles provided him with a 30-gallon barrel of cyanide that could be used to poison the water of a large city like washington, d.c., or new york city
beam testified that the real issue in the trial was whether there would be liberty or tyranny. ``in america today, dissidents in some ways are treated as bad as dissidents in the soviet union,'' he said
miles says the government wants to silence him because he's a gadfly. ``sometimes the government gets out its flyswatter,'' miles said
of the 14 defendants originally charged, 10 were accused of seditious conspiracy; one was acquitted for lack of evidence. five defendants, including one of the sedition defendants, are accused of plotting to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent. two sedition defendants are accused of the interstate transportation of stolen money
two men stole a locomotive and took it on a three-mile joyride at speeds up to 50 mph before it derailed, chicago &amp; north western railroad officials said
no injuries were reported in the derailment late saturday on the city's north side, railroad spokesman fred bloedorn said
the unidentified men boarded the 1,500-horsepower, 112-ton freight locomotive at a rail yard and fled after a rail tower operator switched it to another rail yard and it jumped the tracks because of its speed, he said
the 25-year-old locomotive, valued at $100,000 to $150,000, was badly dented when it fell on its side, but crews were not immediately able to determine how much repairs will cost, he said
three prison escapees, including a triple murderer, were back in custody today after allegedly stealing three vehicles, robbing a family and stealing a handgun, authorities said
no injuries were reported in the crime spree sunday
sheriff's officers who had been on the lookout for the inmates since they escaped wednesday spotted them on u.s. 101 near shelton when their southbound car abruptly turned and headed north, said lt. howard armfield of the mason county sheriff's department
with officers in pursuit, the car veered off the highway and onto washington 3, where it was surrounded by five sheriff's vehicles just outside of shelton, about 15 miles northwest of olympia
the prisoners left the car peacefully with their hands behind their heads, leaving the stolen weapon stuffed under a car seat, armfield said
they didn't have anywhere to go and they knew it,'' he said. ``they apparently weren't out to hurt anybody. all they were out for was a ride.''
the inmates were taken to the county jail before being transferred back to the washington corrections center
it was real apparent they didn't have any outside help and they didn't have a plan,'' sheriff bob holter said. ``we didn't know they were still here.''
the men escaped wednesday night after apparently scaling a chain link fence topped with three feet of razor-sharp ``ribbon wire'' near an unoccupied guard tower, prison spokeswoman barbara lovelace said
the inmates hid in a shed near a family's home, armfield said. armed with a gun they found in the shed, they confronted the family, robbed them and stole their truck, he said. they later stole two other cars
the inmates likely will face first-degree escape charges, three counts each of grand theft and three counts each of armed robbery, armfield said
sean stevenson, 17, was convicted of two counts of first-degree murder and one count of aggravated first-degree murder in the deaths of his mother, stepfather and sister. he was serving a life term without possibility of parole
with him were gary curtis van winkle, 17, of seattle, convicted of attempted murder and burglary in king county and patrick j. rice, 23, of north bend, convicted of second-degree burglary and one count of taking a motor vehicle without permission.   
the motion picture industry has presented its scientific and technical academy awards to people who developed new devices or methods that helped improve filmmaking
the scientific and technical oscars were given to 15 recipients during a ceremony sunday night at the beverly hilton hotel. the 60th annual academy awards ceremony is april 11
the awards were given ``for devices, methods, formulas, discoveries or inventions of special and outstanding value to the arts and sciences of motion pictures and employed in the motion picture industry during the awards year,'' according to the academy of motion picture arts and science's board of governors
the selections were based on recommendations made by the academy's scientific or technical awards committee. winners received a statuette, plaque or certificate, depending on the award. previous awards can be upgraded, as three were this year, based on the impact the device has had on the industry since being introduced
the academy award of merit, which earns a statuette for achievements that have influenced and advanced filmmaking, was awarded this year to bernard kuhl and werner block, and to the osram gmbh research and development department
it was given for the invention and continuing improvement of the osram hmi light source for motion picture photography, which has become the standard for daylight illumination photography throughout the world. the recipients previously received a certificate, then a plaque, for the device
the scientific &amp; engineering award is a plaque given for achievements of high levels of engineering of importance to the progress of the industry. it was given this year to:
_willi burth and kinotone corp. for the invention and development of the non-rewind platter system
_montage group for the development, and ronald barker and chester schuler for the invention of the montage picture processor electronic film editing system
_colin mossman and rank film laboratories' development group for an automated handling system for improving the productivity of high-speed film processing
_two to eastman kodak co. for the development of high-speed daylight film, and for the development of high-speed film for traveling matte photography
_fritz gabriel bauer for the invention and development of the improved features of the moviecam camera system
_zoran perisic of courier films ltd. received an upgrading from a 1979 certificate for the zoptic dual-zoom front projection system
_carl zeiss co. also was upgraded from a prior certificate for the design and development of a series of super-speed lenses
the winners of the technical achievement awards receive a certificate for accomplishments that contribute to the progress of the industry. they were awarded to:
_ioan allen of dolby laboratories inc. for the cat.43 playback-only noise reduction unit
_john eppolito, wally gentleman, william mesa, les robley and geoff williamson for refinements to a dual-screen, front-projection image compositing system
_jan jacobsen for the application of a dual-screen, front projection system
_thaine morris and david pier for the development of the dsc spark devices for motion picture special effects
_tadeuz krzanowski of industrial light &amp; magic inc. for the development of the wire rig model support mechanism used to control the movements of miniatures in special effects
_dan norris and tim cook of norris film products for the development of a single-frame exposure system
the rev. jerry falwell has launched a petition drive to press for a presidential pardon for oliver north, saying the government is using the fired national security council aide as a scapegoat in the iran-contra affair
falwell announced the petition drive sunday to his congregation at thomas road baptist church
falwell said north, who was indicted earlier this month for his role in the iran-contra affair, was only following orders and trying to do what a ``spineless congress'' wouldn't do in central america
i decided we didn't have any hope with the independent counsel and the 250 staff members, who are being paid with millions of our tax dollars to hang this man, to imprison this man. we can't win there,'' falwell said, referring to special prosecutor lawrence e. walsh
we can't win in the congress,'' he said. ``we've long since abrogated a congress that has enough statesmen in it to make a difference. the majority of them are more committed to the next election than the next generation
but, we can appeal to the court of public opinion,'' falwell said. ``and i've decided to put together a national pardon petition to the president of the united states, and see if i could find 2 or 3 million people who would sign with me.''
falwell's petition says north, who just retired as a marine corps lieutenant colonel, fought communism in central america and in the process became the object of terrorist death threats
the least our country can do is to free him from the cloud of persecution that hangs over his head and that of his family,'' it says
falwell said he would deliver the signed list personally to reagan
in an interview following the church service, falwell said he expects critics to accuse him of once again using his position to influence governmental matters. he said, however, he is not acting in his capacity as the leader of the church or or the moral majority
i'm doing this only as a citizen who appreciates what this man has done for me and my children,'' he said. territory</head> iraqi jets, iranian rebels claim attack. updates with more details on ship attacks, kurd protests. pickup 16th graf pvs ``iran's prime...''; edits to trim.</note>
iran said today its revolutionary guards killed or wounded 300 iraqis in a battle in northeast iraq and now hold more than 500 square miles of the strategic kurdistan region
also today, iran attacked two supertankers in the persian gulf, setting them ablaze, and iraqi-backed rebels claimed several thousand of their fighters attacked iranian troops in southwest iran
iraq has admitted losing some territory in kurdistan. if the iranian claim is confirmed, it would mark iraq's biggest military setback in the 7{-year-old war since the iranians battled to within six miles of basra 13 months ago
iran said its troops in kurdistan were within three miles of a hydroelectric dam supplying most of the power for the region as well as electricity for baghdad, the iraqi capital. the fighting also was reportedly within 70 miles of oilfields producing more than half of iraq's total output, vital to the country's war effort
the official islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, said the iranians _ who have thrust into the kurdistan mountains in a 13-day-old offensive _ ``fiercely repelled'' a counter-attack by iraq's 5th army corps around lake darbandikhan during the night
amid another wave of iraqi air raids on towns in western iran, the iranians said their fighter planes shot down two iraqi warplanes in the kurdistan battle zone today
the iraqi-backed iranian rebels said their national liberation army launched a major offensive on a 14-mile front in iran's khuzestan province near the town of shush
the rebels claimed in a communique issued in baghdad that 15 brigades pushed across the border to drive iranian forces out of positions and were threatening a highway southwest of the garrison city of dezful
the communique reported heavy iranian casualties with ``a large number of tanks captured.'' there was no independent confirmation
the iranian rebels said the assault involved several thousand fighters and was the biggest it mounted since it launched a campaign against the iranian regime a year ago
in the gulf, iranian gunboats today attacked the 337,733-ton danish supertanker karama maersk off the southern emirate of sharjah, setting it on fire, gulf-based shipping executives reported
lloyd's shipping intelligence unit reported there were no casualties on the vessel
three hours later, the gunboats attacked the 219,287-ton norwegian-operated tanker golar kansai in the same area and set it ablaze, said the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity
it was not immediately known if there were any casualties aboard the norwegian tanker. salvage tugs went to aid the stricken vessels
also today, iran's official islamic republic news agency said two u.n. officials, dr. manuel carmona and james holger, arrived in tehran to probe iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons against three kurdish towns in iraq
the iranians claimed 5,000 iraqi kurds were killed and 5,000 injured two weeks ago when iraqi warplanes dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on the towns after they had been captured in the iranian offensive
the reported chemical attacks sparked protests in the west. in washington about 100 people stoned the iraqi embassy and about 50 kurds protested outside an iraqi mission in vienna on sunday
in london today, about 200 kurds ended a peaceful candelight vigil outside the u.s. embassy but refused to hand over a petition demanding u.s. action after embassy officials declined to meet with them
iranian prime minister hussein musavi was quoted today by irna as saying iran's offensive in iraq ``has brought the possibility of an iranian military victory and punishment of the aggressor closer.''
the agency quoted revolutionary guards minister mohsen rafiq-doust as saying in tehran after a cabinet meeting sunday that the iranians have overrun 540 square miles of iraqi territory
the iranians have pushed about 15 miles into the lake darbandikhan area, iranian communiques said. they claim to have killed or wounded nearly 13,500 iraqis, captured more than 5,000 and destroyed 225 tanks and armored vehicles in fighting since march 16
the iranians said they have seized the eastern and southern shores of lake darbandikhan, cutting off large number of iraqis
iran reported its troops were within three miles of the hydroelectric dam on the southern end of the 10-mile-long lake after capturing the shaakh shamshir heights overlooking the dam
iran said the front line lies 70 miles east of the kirkuk oilfields, which produce 1.5 million barrels of oil a day
twenty-six journalists were killed last year while covering the news, a jump of 11 over 1986, according to a report by a journalists' group. eleven of the deaths occurred in the philippines
the report released sunday by the committee to protect journalists also listed 59 assaults on journalists and more than 185 arrests or kidnappings of journalists
eleven journalists were forced to leave their own countries under threats, and 32 foreign journalists were expelled from the countries where they were working, the committee also said
these figures are a grim reminder that even in the midst of a worldwide communications revolution, some still feel the temptation to kill the messenger,'' said committee chairman josh friedman
in 1986, the committee documented the killings of 15 journalists, 56 assaults and more than 190 arrests or kidnappings. another 37 journalists were expelled, and eight left countries under threat
in the philippines, the committee said, most attacks against journalists ``took place within a series of retaliatory actions perpetrated by guerillas on one side, and military and paramilitary (or vigilante) personnel on the other.''
five of the 11 killed in the philippines, more than any other country, were killed aug. 27 by armed men who broke into a radio station. the victims reportedly had ties with an anti-communist radio commentator
the committee to protect journalists is a non-profit, non-partisan organization founded in 1981 by a group of american reporters and editors
an uneasy truce reigned between surfers and fishermen after the two sides fought over the right to use the waters around a popular jetty
the two groups hurled obscenities, bottles, lead sinkers and fists at each other friday after surfers accused fishermen of deliberately casting their hooks and lines too close to them
the brevard county sheriff's office broke up the fight and posted a deputy on the disputed jetty at sebastian inlet state recreational park, which lies about 80 miles southeast of orlando. there were no arrests
deputy jeff ludwig said fishermen often cast off the jetty's north railing while surfers frequently come within 10 years of the jetty. but ludwig reported no problems over the weekend as surfers stayed 40 yards north of the jetty while fishermen cast their lines mostly from the south side
it's probably because i'm standing here,'' ludwig said
tom cross, 32, a surfer from nearby melbourne beach, agreed
i think with that sheriff's deputy out there on the jetty, people are going to be a little more careful how they cast,'' cross said
fishermen claim the jetty is the best fishing spot around and say surfers can ride the waves elsewhere
people should show a little consideration for one another,'' said gary hoover, who admitted he intentionally hooked a surfer once for entering his fishing spot
it's ridiculous,'' said hoover, 27, of nearby satellite beach. ``you've only got how many miles of beach in florida and only a couple of spots where fishermen like to fish. i don't think they should be surfing this close to the jetty.'' `while pflug ...,' to correct that bullet was not removed from brain.</note>
jackie pflug suffered permanent brain damage when she was shot in the head and left for dead by arab terrorists during a 1985 airplane hijacking in malta. today, she's able to say she's glad it happened
it's ``not a hijacking story. it's a story of survival, of learning about yourself,'' said pflug, 32, whose brain injury impaired her ability to read, wiped out her short-term memory and caused epileptic seizures
in the 2{ years since the hijacking, pflug says she has learned to accept the fact that she lived while 59 other people, including four of the five hijackers, died. and she has learned to love her new self
now she is taking a year's leave of absence from her job teaching learning-disabled children and first-graders in nearby wayzata to tell her story on the lecture circuit
pflug, a teacher at the american school in cairo, where her husband, scott, also taught, was returning to cairo from athens when the egyptair jetliner was hijacked on nov. 24, 1985, just 15 minutes into the flight
the worst moment, pflug said, was the very first one
the man stood up with the gun and the grenades. he was grimacing and pulling at the grenades with his mouth and i had the realization that this was a hijacking and i thought, `we're going to blow up in the air,''' she said
after the plane landed, pflug was among two israelis and three americans who were tied and taken to the front of the plane one by one. they were each shot, and their bodies pushed out the door onto the pavement
pflug, one of two americans who survived the shootings, was hit in the back ot the head but the bullet failed to penetrate her skull. she lay still on the pavement for five hours before maltese workers were allowed to remove the bodies to the morgue, where workers turned her over and found she was alive
they started screaming, `she's alive.' i said, `are you the good guys or the bad guys?''' pflug recalled
while pflug underwent surgery in malta to have the bullet removed from her skull and bits of bone from her brain, egyptian commandos stormed the plane as hijackers tossed grenades at the passengers and the pilot killed the terrorist leader with a fire ax. when it was over, 59 people were dead
pflug was later transferred to a hospital in west germany, then came to minnesota, where her husband's parents live, for more treatment at university of minnesota hospital
i'm classified as severely disabled. it's a hidden handicap because i look so normal that people can't tell there's anything wrong with me. it appears as if i'm not listening,'' pflug told the star tribune of minneapolis
her epileptic seizures are controlled by medication and pflug is able to teach again, but her husband grades the papers because her reading ability is impaired
the psychological problems caused by the hijacking have been difficult to overcome, pflug said, but therapy has helped
pflug said not a day has gone by that she hasn't thought about the hijacking
i see a man who looks like one of the hijackers. or i hear a voice like one of the children on the plane. or i see a gun,'' said pflug. but those thoughts have been changing lately, partly the result of therapy, she said
i think about it, but it doesn't get under my skin in the same way. it doesn't control me. i control it,'' she said
now pflug wants to share her experiences with others in hopes that she can help them. ``i'd like to motivate people to take charge of their lives because life is just so wonderful. i know that now,'' she said
so yes, i am glad it happened. i know, that's a pretty bold thing to say. but you have to go through the bad part to get to the good.''
gunmen seriously wounded the mayor of a manila suburb and killed seven of his bodyguards today in the bloodiest attack in the capital blamed on communist rebels. gunmen also shot dead a businessman
police said mayor prospero oreta of suburban malabon suffered three gunshot wounds in the mouth, chest and arm but was out of danger after surgery. seven of his bodyguards died in the attack and another was in serious condition
the ambush occurred as military units in various parts of the country were on full alert in anticipation of stepped up rebel attacks marking tuesday's 19th founding anniversary of the now 24,000-member communist new people's army
seven hours after the ambush, three men in a car shot a businessman while he was driving in suburban quezon city, just north of manila, police said. the victim, who died at a hospital, was identified as francisco castro
police said they had no idea who his attackers were or what their motive was. but the victim's brother, jose castro, vice president of the manila chapter of the leftist people's party, told reporters he believed he was the real target
radio and newspaper reports said police manila had received a call from the alex boncayao brigade, the communist guerrilla unit operating in the manila area, claiming responsibility for the ambush on oreta. police declined to confirm the reports
armed forces spokesman col. oscar florendo confirmed such a call had been received, but added the army could not yet say if the guerrilla unit was behind the attack
the alex boncayao brigade has been blamed for the killings of more than 150 policemen and soldiers in daylight ambushes on manila's streets since last year. before today, the attacks have killed one or two people. the rebels had announced they would soon kill officials as well as police and soldiers
president corazon aquino said she was ``shocked and saddened by these acts of violence.''
i have always asked our people to resort to the ways of peace,'' she said in a statement. ``my hope is that as democracy in our country gains a strong foothold, violence and terror will gradually rescind.''
investigators said oreta and his party were riding in a van and a car to a flag-raising ceremony at the malabon town hall when six men waiting at an intersection opened fire with automatic weapons
cpl. mario odulio said the killers were armed with ak-47 and m-16 automatic assault rifles as well as 9-mm and .45-caliber pistols. police recovered more than 40 spent shells at the scene, odulio said. he said the killers escaped aboard a van and a jeep
police said they believed the killers belonged to the sparrow unit, an assassination squad of the new people's army, but were also looking into the possibility local politics was involved
malabon, a fishing community in manila's northern suburbs, was among the places where last january's local elections were hotly contested
oreta is a brother-in-law of rep. tessie oreta, younger sister of mrs. aquino's assassinated husband, former sen. benigno s. aquino jr
a man on trial for attempted capital murder and aggravated robbery fired his attorney because she wasn't making enough courtroom mistakes and took up his own defense, the lawyer said
jerome anthony johnson, 23, who studied criminal justice in college, fired yung-sung choe because she ``wasn't making enough `reversible errors''' that would help him get a new trial in an appeals court, ms. choe said friday
he said he planned it even before he was arrested,'' she said. ``he told people, `if they catch me, this is what i'm going to do.'''
johnson was sentenced friday to 47 years in prison, half what he could have received
it came out good then,'' johnson told ms. choe after state district judge frances maloney read the jury's verdict
johnson was charged with robbing a 53-year-old woman and her 80-year-old mother in november. neither woman was injured, but prosecutors said johnson accidentally shot an accomplice as he fired at one of the women
about noon wednesday, johnson interrupted ms. choe's cross-examination of a witness and asked maloney to allow him to represent himself
dressed in a suit, johnson questioned several witnesses and objected to actions by the prosecution before explaining to ms. choe what he planned
i couldn't let him commit fraud upon the court,'' ms. choe said. so she told the judge
maloney sent the jury out of the room and told johnson he couldn't make intentional mistakes to build grounds for an appeal
i explained to him that normally a person could not deliberately make an error and then profit by that error,'' maloney said. ``after explaining all that, i said, `do you understand?' and he wouldn't answer me.''
for the next day and a half, johnson stayed silent and allowed the prosecution to proceed with no interuptions. when the verdict came in, johnson was happy and the court reporter congratulated him
weird things happen,'' maloney said. ``that's why there are courts, i guess.'' cq in 9th graf.</note>
in a pittsburgh boardinghouse in 1911, the children and grandchildren of slavery grapple with a world that won't let them forget the past and denies them the future
it is the setting for ``joe turner's come and gone,'' august wilson's heartfelt and haunting tale of a church deacon's obsessive search for his missing wife as well as for his identity as a black man
the play, which opened sunday at broadway's ethel barrymore theater, is wilson's third work to arrive in new york since 1984. following ``ma rainey's black bottom'' and ``fences,'' it reaffirms and enlarges his reputation as a major american playwright
joe turner'' is wilson's most ambitious play. in it, he blends african mysticism with compelling, naturalistic drama. the production, beautifully directed by lloyd richards, is rich in poetry, humor and an almost visionary sense of time, place and character
the story unfolds slowly. wilson weaves his spell gradually. it's his steady accumulation of detail that fascinates and finally mesmerizes
some memorable figures live in this homey boardinghouse, run by seth holly, an ambitious entrepreneur, and his hard-working, good-natured wife, bertha. the audience gets to know them all. in this play, more so than in ``ma rainey'' or ``fences,'' even the minor characters have lives of their own
chief among the boardinghouse inhabitants is bynum walker, a self-styled ``conjurin' man'' who believes in incantations, the beneficial effects of roots and herbs, blood sacrifice and voodoo. he is a link to a black man's african past, although his magic has been americanized. bynum sacrifices the neighbor's pigeons and uses weeds from seth's garden as healing herbs
also living in the house is jeremy furlow, a hot-headed young man, recently arrived from the south and not yet aware that things won't be much different up north. he takes up with mattie campbell, a frail woman who visits the voodoo man for help in finding her lost mate and decides to stay instead. she stands in contrast to another resident, molly cunningham, a resolutely realistic woman who knows she can't expect much out of life
into the lives of these transients comes a strange, menacing man wearing a long black coat and traveling with his young daughter. herald loomis is looking for his wife, martha. the couple was separated years earlier when loomis was forced into a chain gang by the infamous, real-life bounty hunter, joe turner
loomis believes his wife is in the pittsburgh area. with the help of bynum and a white traveling salesman named rutherford selig, he intends to find her
the deacon, described aptly by bynum as ``a man in search of his own song,'' is the play's most disturbing character. it's his story that brings each of the play's two acts to dramatic conclusions. at the end of act 1, the stage erupts in a joyous religious dance called a ``juba.'' during this mystical and spiritual frenzy, loomis has visions of the not-so-distant past, a time of slavery and ``bones walking on water.''
it's not until the second act that loomis finally confronts his wife and then slashes himself with a knife to exorcise the ghosts of long ago. it's not a sacrifice but rather a cleansing, enabling loomis to face the future. whether he and his wife will be able to pick up the pieces of their severed marriage is unclear but at least they will be able to try
richards, who also directed ``fences'' and ``ma rainey,'' gets some fine ensemble work out of his large cast. particularly impressive are delroy lindo as the tormented deacon, ed hall as the homespun magic man and mel winkler as the exasperated boardinghouse owner. wilson has also written a tender, funny scene for two children, and richards has coaxed two beautiful performances from richard parnell habersham and jamila perry
the warm, solid boardinghouse setting by scott bradley is capped by a splendid rooftop view of pittsburgh and a bridge spanning the entire stage. it's an evocative reminder that most of the people in this home are travelers, displaced from the south and still not comfortable in the north
joe turner's come and gone'' is one more piece in the mosaic wilson is creating about black life in 20th century america, one play for each decade. ``fences'' is set in the 1950s, while ``ma rainey'' takes place in the 1920s. ``joe turner'' may be set even further in the past, but it is a play that resonates with such feeling that it leaps across the years to speak powerfully and movingly to today
among other critics, frank rich of the new york times said that wilson ``has once again shown us how in another man's freedom we find our own.'' the play is wilson's ``most profound and theatrically adventurous telling of his story to date,'' rich wrote
here is a lovely, moving play that carries you with it like a matchbox on a flood,'' wrote clive barnes of the new york post
linda winer of new york newsday was equally impressed. ``joe turner'' is august wilson's ``best play yet _ which means it's a stunner,'' she wrote. the play has ``a breadth that connects the dots of neglected history into a picture we will never forget again.''
but howard kissel of the daily news said while there are ``scenes of great power,'' ``you feel that in his eagerness to envision a place where reconcilations abound, wilson has minimized the conflict the characters and the period require.'' charges ^eds: corrects dateline to baton rouge, where arrested occurred.</head>
howard rollins jr., co-star of the nbc series ``heat of the night,'' was arrested on drug and traffic charges after being stopped for going more than 100 mph on an interstate, authorities said
a state trooper who stopped the actor early sunday said he found two bags of a rock-like substance suspected of being cocaine in rollins' coat pockets. rollins' blood alcohol level also was above the legal limit for intoxication, according to a breath test, he said
the actor was charged with possessing cocaine, first-offense drunken driving and speeding, and was released on $5,000 bond
there was no answer to a telephone call to rollins' room at the hammond holiday inn
rollins, who co-starred as chief of detectives virgil tibbs in the two-hour television remake of ``heat of the night'' and in a six-part series of the same name, had a commission as a sheriff's deputy, said senior trooper allen coburn, who arrested the actor
he had a badge holder with a livingston parish sheriff's office badge and a full commission from the sheriff,'' coburn said. ``he didn't say anything about it, but he made sure i saw it while he was getting his driver's license.''
rollins, 37, of baltimore, told police he was in hammond to make a movie. ``heat of the night'' was filmed in hammond
coburn said he spotted rollins' car traveling east on interstate 12 at a little over 100 mph. rollins pulled his car to the side of the interstate and offered no resistance, coburn said
he took his coat off while doing the sobriety test. after the test, i picked up the coat, checked the pockets for weapons and found two bags of suspected cocaine,'' coburn said. each bag appeared to hold about one-eighth of an ounce of a rock-like substance, he said
coburn said a breath test indicated that rollins' blood alcohol level was 0.15 percent. the law sets intoxication as 0.10 percent or more
rollins' court date probably will be set in six to eight weeks
in addition to ``heat of the night,'' in which carroll o'connor co-stars, rollins' films include ``ragtime'' in 1981, in which he was nominated for an academy award for best supporting actor, and ``a soldier's story'' in 1984
in 1985, rollins starred as a ruthless cocaine dealer in the television movie ``the children of times square.''
