it is the first in a new ``america the beautiful'' series of postal cards being issued by the postal service. the design of bison with mountains in the background was adapted from a painting by bart forbes of dallas. to delete superfluous word.</note>
when he was down and out, on the heels of the donna rice scandal, gary hart quit the democratic campaign and, in practically the same breath, made the case for something called ``national service.''
i would say to the young people of this country, the torch of idealism burns bright in your hearts,'' said hart. ``it should lead you to public service and national service. it should lead you to want to make this country better.''
that was may 1987. on feb. 29, 1988, hart was back in the race but as evidenced at the polls, no one was really listening
and so the call for ``national service'' was hardly a burning issue when sen. sam nunn addressed the democratic leadership council in williamsburg, va. _ and urged the setting up of a ``citizens corps'' to perform voluntary national service
the plan could well emerge as a cornerstone of the democratic presidential campaign, the 1988 version of john kennedy's 1960 call to create a peace corps to perform good work overseas
it's a ``something for something'' approach to government
young people would commit themselves to public service _ be it military service or civilian social service _ in return for living expenses plus a $10,000-a-year voucher. ``like the g.i. bill,'' nunn said, the benefits could be used to cover school costs, vocational training or a home-ownership subsidy
the proposal is not new to the presidential campaign. not only was it one of hart's cornerstone ``new ideas,'' but paul simon and bruce babbitt also embraced the concept in their campaigns, and on the republican side, alexander haig jr. proposed such a program before he dropped out
hart, babbitt, simon, nunn and haig. all well and good. but the proposal won't go anywhere unless one of the nominees adopts it as his own and the democratic leadership council has laid considerable groundwork
the dlc is the group of moderate democrats who helped dream up the southern regional primaries and hoped the 1988 process would swing the democratic party into the political center
i am convinced that national service can revitalize the spirit of civic responsibility and enterprise that built this nation and remains its greatest strength,'' nunn said
among the goals of the dlc program, nunn said, are:
_to increase the number of military volunteers and help remedy ``some of our most urgent social problems, like widespread illiteracy and inadequate child care and health care.''
_``offer a decentralized and non-bureaucratic way to deliver human services to needy citizens.''
_``the dlc plan would link federal student aid to national service,'' he said, contending the program thus would be a ``road to opportunity and upward mobility for our young people.''
anticipating the first question about such a plan, nunn added, ``such a program, of course, won't be free. nothing worthwhile ever is
i believe, however, that a large portion of the costs of this program (estimated in some quarters at $6 billion a year) can be financed by shifting federal funds already being expended on student aid.'' in the long run, he said, ``the program, like the g.i. bill, will return huge revenues to the treasury because every additional college graduate in america will earn $640,000 more over their working life as compared to someone who doesn't go to college.''
nunn's concept and the idealistic appeal from hart recall kennedy's peace corps, an enduring element of his legacy even 25 years after his death
editor's note: jonathan wolman is the ap's assistant bureau chief in washington. case.</note>
police in west germany and switzerland have arrested 11 people suspected of spying for the soviet union, authorities said today
german federal prosecutor kurt rebmann said 10 people were taken into custody in west germany last week. in switzerland, the swiss federal prosecutor's office said today a foreigner had been arrested last wednesday
rebmann said six of the 10 suspects captured in west germany remained in jail today, including two teachers, three engineers and a businessman
swiss prosecutors said they had launched a criminal probe into activities of the arrested foreigner, an engineer living in zurich. the suspect was arrested on a tip from west germany, prosecutors said, declining to disclose his name or nationality
rebmann called the arrests ``a heavy blow against the kgb,'' the kremlin's main intelligence agency
speaking at a news conference, he said the west german arrests occurred wednesday and thursday in police raids on 33 different locations. a total of 169 police carried out the raids, rebmann said
two of the suspects _ identified only as doctors _ were freed shortly after police took them into custody, he said. two other suspects were freed in the following days, but the investigation against the four was continuing, he said
rebmann said three of the jailed suspects were soviet emigres, but none were soviet citizens
he said the arrests marked ``an important penetration of the kgb spy network in west germany.''
rebmann also said a government secretary arrested march 18 on suspicion of spying had been working for the kgb. it was the first time the woman, elke falk, was linked to the soviets
ms. falk worked in federal ministries for several years and had access to secret information
gerhard boeden, president of the federal ministry for the protection of the constitution _ the west german counter-intelligence agency _ said west german intelligence officials had developed new ways to uncover east bloc spies. he refused to elaborate
west german authorities identified 15 communist agents between august and december 1985. some were arrested, others escaped
rebmann identified the six jailed suspects as 44-year-old businessman helmut stefan kolasch; a colombian engineer identified by rebmann only as ``amaya;'' peter friesen, a 33-year-old engineer; george bender, 37, also an engineer; shimon or, a 48-year-old teacher; and another teacher, edmund neufert, 37
friesen, bender and neufert are soviet emigres, rebmann said. all six suspects had been living in west germany, he said
kolasch allegedly gave the kgb technological secrets about nato's tornado and jaeger warplanes while working for firms dealing with the aircraft, rebmann said
kolasch has been working for the kgb since 1971, rebmann said
rebmann said amaya also handed over unidentified technical documents, friesen spied on west german political parties, bender reported to the kgb about an electronics concern he worked for and neufert spied on students while teaching russian at the foreign ministry's language-training office
rebmann said or ``reported (to the kgb) on his own life and work,'' but he did not provide details
the suspects apparently were operating individually, rebmann said
demonstrators angered by reported iraqi chemical weapons attacks on kurds forced their way into the iraqi embassy in vienna today, smashing windows and pushing around embassy workers. police said 64 protesters were arrested
six shots were fired, but police said no injuries were reported
as many as 70 people took part in the demonstration, which began at 10:20 a.m., police and demonstrators said. the arrests ended the protest two hours later
a demonstrator told austrian radio a delegation wanted to speak to iraqi officials to protest the use of chemical weapons in the iran-iraq war
iran said last week that the iraqi air force dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three kurdish towns in iraq, killing 5,000 kurds and injuring 5,000 other people. the attacks on the towns, which had been captured in an iranian offensive, occurred march 16 and 17
police said some demonstrators forced their way into the building and ``shoved'' embassy personnel, but embassy security guards forced the protesters out of the building
the demonstrator, who was not identified, told austrian radio that a man with a machine gun, apparently an embassy security guard, fired shots into the streets from inside the embassy building
police said at least six shots had been fired inside the building
demonstrators smashed windows at the embassy, police and demonstrators said
the iraqi embassy refused to comment on the incident
in london, meanwhile, hundreds of kurds protesting iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons held a vigil outside the u.s. embassy but left today without delivering their petition. the chemical attacks also sparked protests in washington on sunday in which about 100 people stoned the iraqi embassy
two u.n. officials reportedly arrived in tehran today to investigate the attacks on the kurdish towns
about 220 of the 500 kurds who marched through central london late sunday spent the night outside the grosvenor square embassy, scotland yard reported. both the march and the candlelight vigil were peaceful
an iraqi embassy press officer in london said the kurds refused to give their petition to an official who met them this morning
the demonstrators wanted to engage in a dialogue with somebody rather than just have somebody passively received a petition,'' the press officer said, speaking on the condition of anonymity
he said there was no one available at the embassy to speak with the kurds ``so they refused to hand in their petition.''
scotland yard reported the demonstrators arrived at the embassy about 2:30 a.m. after a three-hour march and rally. the embassy said they left about 11 a.m
the demonstrators said many of them had lost relatives in chemical weapons attacks. forces</head> up 4th graf, `police and soldiers ...' edits to tighten. march scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. est.</note>
the mayors of panama city and its largest suburb today threatened to crack down on a mass demonstration aimed at ousting gen. manuel antonio noriega and ending the worst crisis in the nation's history
in a communique published in this morning's state-run newspapers, the mayors said they had instructed ``competent authorities'' to enforce a ban on public demonstrations
those authorities are the police and soldiers commanded by noriega
but opposition leaders said they would proceed with plans for the afternoon protest march and called the ban illegal
the protest march comes at the start of the second week of a general strike that has shut down an estimated 90 percent of the nation's industry and commerce, further aggravating a critical cash shortage
on palm sunday, roman catholic church leaders said government authorities ``fear this explosion of sentiments'' and appealed to both sides to show restraint. the church leaders said in a statement they would send observers to today's march in panama city to try to keep the peace
police and soldiers, under noriega who heads the 15,000-member defense forces, have suppressed recent demonstrations with tear gas and shotguns
also sunday, the social security institute said it will pay its 55,000 retirees up to $150 of their semi-monthly pension benefits this week. they had threatened to join today's march if they didn't receive their payments
last week, the government was without money to pay the members of the defense forces and faces another $33 million payroll for its 130,000 civilian employees this week, raising the possibility of intensified protests
in washington, elliott abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, predicted on sunday that many of the marchers will be ``members of the families of the defense forces.''
the government on sunday expelled a reporter for the french news agency agence france press because his visa had been issued a panamanian consular official in washington loyal to deposed president eric arturo delvalle
opposition figures crticized the government for its planned crackdown on the demonstration
peaceful protest is a right written in the constitution,'' opposition leader jose faundes said sunday. ``it is above any decree, any law.''
we hope they realize they cannot repress the will of the people,'' said aurelio barria, a leader of the national civic crusade, a coalition of more than 200 business, professional, labor and student groups. ``this will be a physical expression of protest against noriega.''
the crusade said the march would begin in front of the church of don bosco near the center of panama city and proceed to a park about half a mile away
the latest government crisis began last month when the noriega controlled leislative assembly deposed delvalle after he tried to fire noriega
noriega had recently been indicted in florida on drug trafficking charges
the united states responded to delvalle's ouster by freezing panamanian assets in the united states and reiterating its support for delvalle as the chief executive. president reagan has also called on noriega to resign
there were violent demonstrations 12 days ago after the goverment was unable to meet payrolls and a small group of disenchanted defense forces officers staged an unsuccessful coup against noriega
in its toughest action, soldiers loyal to noriega seized two major flour mills saturday, including a plant owned by the general mills corp., and confiscated 1.3 million pounds of ground wheat and corn valued at $227,500
owners of the mills had responded to a government announcement of its plan to confiscate their plants by saying they would instead donate their entire stocks of flour to the catholic church's food program for the poor
the church quickly thanked the mills ``for such a humanitarian gesture,'' but soldiers seized the plants and moved the flour to government warehouses before it could be delivered to caritas, the church's welfare agency
also saturday, soldiers reopened panama city's balboa port, where workers had built barricades during their strike that began march 13. the port is at the pacific entrance of the panama canal, which continues to operate normally
a rain storm whipped through central argentina, killing at least 21 people and forcing 59,000 to leave their homes, civil defense officials said today
at least 11 children drowned as floodwaters in some low-lying areas near buenos aires reached up to six feet. several other people were electrocuted while crossing flooded streets where live electrical wires had fallen, authorities said
authorities said the storm, which lasted for four days, ended today
among the hardest hit areas were quilmes, avellaneda and lomas de zamora south of buenos aires. horse-drawn carts, makeshift rafts and boats were used to evacuate residents. some people took refuge on the roofs of their homes, officials said
evacuees were taken to emergency shelters in churches, schools, sports clubs and office buildings. health authorities have warned of a possible outbreak of hepatitis following the storm
gov. buddy roemer says the unprecedented authority given him by the legislature to repair the state's finances will be tempered by compassion and his awareness that lawmakers are looking over his shoulder
budget officials worked through the weekend to come up with a list of proposed cuts to present to roemer today after the legislature wound up a special session by approving the emergency bills. the governor was expected to sign the package today
the budgetary authority is aimed at meeting a fiscal crisis which threatens to bankrupt the state
in addition to giving roemer power to cut entire state programs and close institutions through june 30, the end of the fiscal year, lawmakers granted the administration the right to raise fees for state services without public hearings or legislative oversight
after lawmakers finished work saturday, roemer said the temporary budget authority will be tempered ``by my compassion and good sense that they (legislators) will be coming back in three and a half weeks to look over my shoulder.''
the governor said he was aiming for $50 million in spending cuts for the remaining quarter of the fiscal year and $22 million in fee increases
the rest of the $200 million deficit expected this fiscal year will be met by issuing short-term bonds or delaying payments for services rendered to the state, roemer said. he also said layoffs of an undetermined number of state employees would be needed
over a full year, the spending cuts would total about $200 million if the legislature did not change them during its regular session beginning in april, while the fee hikes would bring in about $88 million, he said
those are the targets. i don't know if i will be able to reach either,'' he said
commissioner of administration brian kendrick said budget officials worked through the weekend to come up with the list of proposed cuts
kendrick also said work would begin on the new louisiana recovery corp., created by the legislature to govern a statewide taxing district that could impose up to a 1 percent sales tax. the tax would finance the issuance of bonds that would pay off the state's $1.3 billion long-term debt
the administration-dominated commission cannot issue bonds or impose the levy until the legislature drops the same amount from the current 4-cent state sales tax
the administration will ask the louisiana supreme court to rule on the consitutionality of the commission. if it does not pass legal muster, the state will use short-term bonds to finance the debt, kendrick said
those are the only two ways out,'' he said
the supreme court today refused to hear an appeal by former new york city political boss meade esposito, who sought to prevent public disclosure of certain court documents
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling challenged by esposito, the former brooklyn democratic boss convicted of giving illegal gratuities to rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y
esposito sought to conceal information contained in pretrial requests he and biaggi made to suppress wiretap evidence obtained by federal law enforcement officials
the new york times, the new york daily news and the associated press asked that the information be made public
the 2nd u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled in favor of the news organizations in january
the appeals court said revealing the information, with some deletions made by a federal judge, would not violate esposito's privacy rights
esposito was convicted last sept. 22 of giving, and biaggi of accepting, illegally gratuities in the form of free vacations
in a separate prosecution, biaggi is on trial in new york city with six others accused of turning the wedtech corporation into a racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to get government contracts
in the appeal acted on today, esposito said allowing public disclosure of the documents from the biaggi-esposito case would have an unconstitutional chilling effect on all defendants
it could prevent defendants from making pretrial motions to suppress evidence for fear that information contained in the motions would be made public, esposito said
the case is esposito vs. new york times, 87-1319
the supreme court today refused to revive a $300 million copyright-infringement lawsuit against the creators and marketers of trivial pursuit, a popular board game
the court, without comment, rejected arguments by the author of several encyclopedias on trivia that many of the questions contained in the board game infringed on his copyright works
trivial pursuit, a game utilizing question-and-answer cards, was conceived in 1979 by chris haney and scott abbot, who along with john haney developed the concept
in 1981, the three joined with ed werner in forming a canadian corporation, horn abbott ltd., to market the game. abbot and chris haney assigned their rights to the corporation, and horn abbot lt. obtained a canadian copyright in the game
in late 1982, horn abbot contracted with selchow &amp; righter co. to distribute the game in the united states, and by the end of 1984 sales had reached $256 million
fred worth, a california resident who had authored two volumes of ``the complete unabridged super trivia encyclopedia,'' sued the two corporations and the four canadians behind horn abbot in late 1984
his lawsuit alleged that the genus, silver screen and baby boomer editions of trivial pursuit _ each containing 6,000 questions and answers _ were guilty of copyright infringement
for example, worth contended that 1,675 of the genus edition's 6,000 questions were taken from his first encyclopedia volume
the trivial pursuit creators did not deny consulting worth's books in developing the board game, but they said his books were among numerous reference sources used
a federal trial judge in los angeles, upheld by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals last september, threw out the suit
the appeals court ruled that there was no ``substantial similarity'' between worth's books and the trivial pursuit question-and-answer cards
the case is worth vs. selchow &amp; righter co., 87-1268
floodwaters burst through dikes on the danube river and the rhine river was rising fast today as hundred of people were evacuated from their homes
emergency workers were working to strengthen the earthen dikes along the danube. the rhine was rising about an inch an hour in some locations today, threatening homes and businesses in cologne, bonn and other communities
major rivers across west germany have been flooding for about two weeks but heavy rains over the weekend worsened the situation
the rising rhine forced authorites to close parts of a highway between mainz and koblenz and disrupted trains in the area
officials said about 1,400 people were evacuated sunday night and early today after the danube burst through several dikes near regensburg, about 45 miles north of munich
hundreds of cows, pigs and other farm animals were also taken to higher ground to escape rising waters, authorities added
hans voggenreiter, spokesman for the rescue operation, said it was the worst flooding in the area since 1920
people were evacuated with rowboats and powerboats,'' said voggenreiter. ``most of them were taken in by relatives and friends. the rest are being cared for in schools and public auditoriums.''
floodwaters had also entered parts of regensburg itself, as well as sections of passau, 80 miles to the east
officials said flooding along the neckar and mosel rivers was receding, but the rhine continued to climb
riverside sidewalks and some streets in bonn, the federal capital, had disappeared beneath the water
residents of large villas that line the rhine in the bonn district of bad godesberg, home to many embassies and ambassadors' residents, were using pumps to dry out their flooded cellars
groundwater is coming through (cellar) seams all over the city,'' said an emergency official who asked not to be identified. ``but we're keeping our cool.'' ...,' with hatcher a candidate in forsyth county, not robeson.</note>
community leaders appealed for calm after the slaying of an activist who had sought to become the first indian judge in racially tense robeson county, but two other candidates reported receiving death threats
julian pierce, 42, was killed in his home early saturday by three shotgun blasts fired at point-blank range, in what authorities called the first assassination of a candidate for political office in the state. no arrests have been made
since the killing, pierce's opponent in the judgeship race and a friend of pierce running for office in forsyth county have reported receiving death threats, the charlotte observer said today
the rev. joy johnson of the first baptist church said sunday he hoped the crime could be solved ``before the heat rises and before there is a war.''
we've had a calm night and day, but it will take at least a few more days until the tension is out of the air,'' said johnson, who along with other community leaders appealed to residents on sunday to avoid violence. ``anything could spark something. i hope that doesn't happen.''
pierce, a lawyer, was running for a superior court judgeship in robeson county, where few indians hold office or work in law enforcement, despite a population that is 37 percent indian
he was alone saturday morning in his brick ranch house, which is flanked by farmland and another small house, authorities said
the best we can establish, he got home shortly after midnight, he undressed and went to bed,'' said robeson county sheriff hubert stone. ``then someone came to the back door, knocking. pierce slipped on a pair of jeans and went to the door. when he got to the door, the person either shot through the window or stuck the gun through the window and shot pierce in the chest
as pierce turned, he was then shot in the lower left side. pierce fell to the floor,'' the sheriff said
it just looked like he was actually assassinated,'' he said
earl moore, who said he had known pierce for 15 years, said the candidate ``knew that something could happen'' to him. moore said he knew of a threat against pierce, but said he would talk only to federal officials in washington, not to county, state or federal officials in north carolina
jim hatcher, a friend of pierce who is running for a seat on the board of county commissioners in forsyth county, across the state around winston-salem, told the observer that he received an anonymous telephone call late sunday in which someone said ``get out of town.''
i plan to talk to gov. martin,'' he said. ``the people are wanting to talk, but they're scared. either martin's going to do something, or else.''
hatcher is the uncle of eddie hatcher, who, with timothy jacobs, took over the robesonian newspaper in lumberton on feb. 1 to protest alleged government corruption in robeson county
lumberton police said they began guarding district attorney joe freeman britt's home sunday after he reported receiving threats. britt, who was running against pierce, and his family were in seclusion under police protection
pierce grew up in neighboring hoke county and worked in a virginia shipyard after graduating from college. he returned to north carolina and attended north carolina central university law school, then worked for the u.s. securities and exchange commission from 1976 to 1978
he moved to robeson county to serve as the first director of lumbee river legal services, representing those too poor to afford lawyers and practicing public interest law
he was an easygoing guy. he never had no problem with anyone that i heard tell of. people liked him,'' stone said
pierce's supporters said they might try to field another candidate in the upcoming primary
the question is whether or not that will be allowed, under the general statutes,'' said sam kerns of pembroke. ``we'll be meeting again ... but i really don't think that it may be possible, according to the law.''
pierce's campaign manager, harvey goodwin, said supporters are considering a request for a special session of the state legislature to consider postponing the judicial race
britt, a white, has been district attorney in the county for 14 years. but pierce was considered the leader in the race because of a controversial vote by indians earlier this month to consolidate the county's five school systems, which are divided largely along racial lines
the election was to be decided may 3, the date of the democratic primary, since no republicans were in the race
the judgeship pierce had sought was created to help ensure that minorities would have an opportunity to elect a judge. the legislature gave the county its own judicial district, separating it from adjoining scotland county
indian leaders met sunday but would not allow reporters to attend. a meeting saturday resulted in a request to state officials to appoint a special prosecutor to investigate pierce's death
robeson county, which borders on south carolina, is also 37 percent white and 26 percent black. it is one of the state's poorest counties, and has long been torn by racial animosity
activism, particularly by lumbees, has thrived since november 1986, when a sheriff's deputy fatally shot an unarmed lumbee
anger at what the indians call corrupt local government and entrenched racism boiled over feb. 1, in the hostage-taking at the robesonian newspaper
pierce's killing ``makes me think there's no hope for the indians,'' said one lumbee, janice locklear. ``i'm so mad i could fight.'' statements by south african military. no pickup.</note>
the south african army today raided a house on the outskirts of the capital, killing four residents who were burned beyond recognition after an hour-long gunbattle
south africa, which claims that neighboring botswana harbors guerrillas hostile to pretoria, called the victims terrorists. it said it was responsible for the attack in a statement issued by its defense force in pretoria
the office of president quett masire of botswana said four people died _ a south african man, two batswana women, and a third unidentified woman. the botswana press association quoted deputy police commissioner norman moleboge as saying residents reported all the occupants of the house were batswana
the president's statement said all were sleeping when the south africans attacked in the township of phiring, known locally as tsholofelo. the community lies two miles from the center of the capital of gaborone, a border city
the office of the president strongly condemns this dastardly attack and murder of innocent people in botswana by the south african army,'' said botswana's statement. ``the office of the president once again reiterates botswana's belief that south africa's problems cannot be resolved by attacking neighboring countries such as botswana and strongly urges the south african government to engage in meaningful negotiations with the genuine leadership of the oppressed majority in that country.''
south africa's government and economy are controlled by 5 million whites. the country's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs under a system of racial segregation known as apartheid
pretoria has issued several threats against botswana in recent months, accusing it of harboring african national congress guerrillas bent on ending white domination in south africa
the botswana government says it supports the group's goals and allows its representatives in the country. but botswana says it does not let the group launch attacks into south africa from botswana
the south african military statement said today's raid was a follow-up to a shootout near the south africa-botswana border friday. in that attack, the military said soldiers killed three suspected terrorists in a running battle near a farm and captured rifles, machine pistols and hand grenades
the operation had not previously been reported
in today's shootout, neighbors said they heard sporadic automatic gunfire, and possibly grenades, for an hour. two witnesses reported that the attackers left in a helicopter
moleboge was quoted as saying four people were shot, then set afire by the attackers, and that gasoline containers were found at the scene. the botswana press association said it was believed an explosion may have been caused by a gas cylinder in the house, which was destroyed
the south africans gave no details on how the occupants of the house died
col. moammar gadhafi said today he is withdrawing libyan troops from the egyptian border and promised libya would not use force to undermine the egyptian state
if carried out, the libyan leader's decision would represent an unprecedented conciliatory move. gadhafi began feuding with egypt about 15 years ago
gadhafi's announcement followed a series of smaller-scale reciprocal goodwill gestures between the two countries in recent weeks
gadhafi made the announcement in a speech at a former british base at the mediterranean city of tobruk near the egyptian border. the speech, broadcast live by libyan television and monitored in london, was delivered at a ceremony marking the 18th anniversary of britain's evacuation of military bases in libya
in another departure from long-standing hostile policy toward cairo, gadhafi said libya would not use force to overthrow president hosni mubarak's government or get it to renounce its 1979 peace treaty with israel. the treaty was among numerous sore spots in egyptian-libyan friction
the speech contained one anti-egyptian barb, however, with gadhafi charging that egypt ``abandoned'' the arab world when it signed the american-mediated camp david agreements with israel
i hereby declare the withdrawal of all military troops from along the libyan-egyptian artificial borders,'' gadhafi said
i want to emphasize to the egyptian people and army that the libyan eastern military zone (along the border) will finally be abolished.''
gadhafi did not say how many troops libya has along the border. neither did he specify a time frame for the pullback
the egyptian-libyan feud began in 1972 when cairo rejected gadhafi's bid for immediate merger of the two countries
egypt blamed gadhafi for a series of bombings in cairo and other cities in 1975 and 1976, and the two countries fought a five-day border war in july 1977. the political tension deepened when egypt since the peace treaty with israel and moved closer to the united states
gadhafi, who overthrew the libyan monarchy in a military coup in 1969, offered to let egypt verify the troop withdrawal
if egypt wants to ascertain this, it will be able to observe, and we accept any verification commission or any observer or monitor who would be satisfied that this region is completely evacuated by military forces,'' he said
the libyan leader said his forces will be withdrawn ``without us asking for anything in return from the egyptian side.''
the supreme court today agreed to hear the appeal of a convicted killer who said his rights were violated when he was denied an opportunity to talk to his lawyer during a trial recess
the court said it will review a ruling that denied a new trial to the south carolina man
the defendant, donald ray perry, was convicted of murder, kidnapping and criminal sexual assault in the killing of mary heimberger, whose body was found on march 7, 1981, in a wooded area in richland county, s.c. he was sentenced to life in prison
perry confessed to police that he had shot the victim, but said it was an accident
ms. heimberger had been raped, shot in both kneecaps and fatally shot in the chest
during a 15-minute trial recess while perry was testifying, his lawyer sought to speak to him to advise him about his rights on cross-examination. but the judge refused to allow them to talk
perry filed a federal court appeal in 1985 and a judge ruled that his rights were violated. the judge said denying perry the right to talk to his laywer during a recess, no matter how brief, is grounds for throwing out the conviction
but the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals reinstated the conviction in november
not every limitation of the relationship between a defendant and his attorney violates the defendant's right to counsel,'' the appeals court said
the appeals court said barring a defendant from meeting with his lawyer during a brief trial recess is not automatic grounds for declaring a new trial. there must be evidence that the denial prejudiced the case against the defendant, the appeals court said
the appeals court relied in part on two supreme court rulings in 1984 that reinstated criminal convictions of two defendants who said they were denied effective legal assistance at their trials
the high court said a claim of ineffective representation must be examined in the context of whether the trial produced a just result
the appeals court said that standard also should apply to perry's claim
it would make little sense to maintain a per se (automatic) rule of reversal for a brief restriction on consultation, but to inquire into prejudice if perry had been represented incompetently throughout,'' the appeals court said
to reverse automatically a conviction because of an absence of consultation during one brief, fortuitous recess in a trial which spanned nearly two weeks would be to confer a benefit upon a criminal defendant who may not deserve it,'' the appeals court added
it also said, ``the evidence against perry was overwhelming,'' and there was no indication that denying him the chance to confer with his lawyer prior to cross-examination altered his testimony significantly
it would be wrong to exalt technical perfection at the expense of our society's legitimate and weighty interest in punishing offenders,'' the appeals court said
the case is perry vs. leeke, 87-6325, nagorno-karabakh. picks up 3rd graf, `pravda said ...' edits to tighten.</note>
a general strike today slowed transportation and closed most factories in the largest city in a region that armenians want to unite with their republic, a witness said
the director of the only hotel in stepanakert said all but essential services were shut down today because of a strike
the bread factory and the milk factory are working. the others are not working. everyone is sitting at home,'' the director of the karabakh hotel said in a telephone interview. he said he was an ethnic armenian but refused to give his name
about 30 percent of stepanakert's public transport was shut down, he said. communist party representatives in the city called workers to meetings at factories today and urged them to return to work tuesday, he said
stepanakert is the largest city in nagorno-karabakh, a mainly armenian region in the republic of azerbaijan which activists are seeking to unite with armenia. at least 32 people have died in ethnic violence between armenians and azeris since protests began in february
armenian activists have said a general strike began wednesday in parts of nagorno-karabakh
pravda, the communist party daily, reported today the strikes and unrest in azerbaijan have disrupted the economy and cost the region millions of dollars in lost revenues
the communist party daily said action by armenianis has ``aggravated the economic situation not only in the autonomous region but also, partly, in the entire republic.''

pravda said the auto and trucking industries alone lost about $6.5 million in january and february. the railway industry lost about $360,000
the article gave little indication about how the money was lost but quoted a railway official in azerbaijan as saying freight cars had not been unloaded
the official, garik sarkisyan, was quoted by pravda as saying the situation was ``bad'' and ``loss of time and money has become the usual thing.''
pravda said yerevan, the capital of the armenian republic, was ``relatively calm'' with no incidents over the weekend ``connected with national relations.''
moscow dissidents, in telephone contact during the weekend with armenian sources, described yerevan as ``a dead city,'' with people staying off the streets to protest a government crackdown on public demonstrations
the official press acknowledged that most businesses were closed in stepanakert, the main city of nagorno-karabakh, over the weekend, but gave no information on the situation this morning
according to various reports from dissident and official sources over the weekend, the general strike appeared to have taken place in stepanakert, but in other areas most businesses were open
an administrator of the yerevan hotel, who spoke on condition of anonymnity, said the city's businesses were open today. other calls to yerevan did not go through
western reporters have been barred from the region, and telephone service has been largely cut off
the presidium of the supreme soviet, including soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and other members of the top leadership, called last week for improvement of social and economic conditions in the contested area, but it did not deal directly with the annexation issue
activists interpreted that as a rejection of their demands and called for a general strike
tass said today the communist party central committee and government's council of ministers approved plans for construction of more schools _ including armenian schools _ in nagorno-karabakh and other regions of azerbaijain where ethnic armenians live
a prostitute who says she posed naked for evangelist jimmy swaggart will show those poses in the july issue of penthouse magazine, a spokeswoman for the publication said today
from what i understand, the photographs will recreate the precise poses and actions that jimmy swaggart paid for during the long affair,'' said leslie jay, vice president and director of public relations for the magazine
i also understand that the interview will review every episode in the relationship that ruined this most powerful tv preacher in the world,'' she said in a telephone interview from her new york office
jay said she had not seen the interview or the pictures
swaggart stepped down from the pulpit feb. 21 after tearfully confessing to an unspecified sin against his wife, family and church
church leaders have said he was photographed with a reputed prostitute outside a seedy new orleans motel. debra murphree says she is the woman in those photographs
jay said she did not know how much murphree was paid or about the editorial deliberations behind penthouse's decision to use the photographs and interview
the national enquirer decided last month not to use an interview with murphree after she failed a lie detector test. she told new orleans television station wvue she failed the test because she had taken drugs the day before
paul levy, the enquirer's senior editor, said murphree's companion, john martinez, 28, offered her story to the enquirer for $100,000. martinez has said he also tried to peddle the story to people magazine and abc-tv's nightline
murphree, also known as debra arleen hedge, has three children living with her parents in indiana and an arrest record in florida, tennessee and louisiana, mainly involving prostitution charges
real estate magnate donald trump, the new owner of the plaza hotel, says he plans to make the fifth avenue landmark even posher in an effort to make it the second five-star hotel in manhattan
he vowed that the plaza, already the city's most famous hotel, would become the most luxurious hotel in the world under the supervision of his wife, ivana. the hotel is a four-star establishment
the only manhattan hotel with the distinction of having five stars is the carlyle hotel, at madison avenue and 76th street
built in 1907 in the style of a french chateau, the plaza has been cited by the city's landmarks preservation commission as a ``superb example of the elegance and opulence that characterized the period just before world war i.''
the hotel, with its famed public spaces and its commanding site overlooking central park, has become one of new york's most recognizable buildings through its frequent movie appearances, including a starring role in ``plaza suite.'' more recently, the plaza provided an upscale encampment for ``crocodile dundee.''
but it has lost some of its luster under a succession of owners in recent years and is in the midst of a major renovation
its latest owners were texas financier robert bass and the japanese-based aoki corp., which bought it last october from westin hotels
trump, when he announced announced saturday that he had purchased the plaza hotel for $390 million, said he would not change its name. ``it's got the most important name in the world, and it's going to remain that way,'' he said
trump lives just two blocks from the plaza at his trump tower high-rise apartment building. he won out in a bidding contest against two other manhattan developers, philip pilevsky and arthur cohen, who wanted to convert part of the hotel into cooperative apartments
room rates at the plaza start at $195 a night. trump said he hoped to lure some year-round guests to the hotel at rental rates of $400,000 to $500,000 a year
a 24-hour general strike today shut factories, airports and banks across portugal as hundreds of thousands of workers staged the biggest industrial action in the country's history to protest government labor reforms
the communist and socialist labor federations, united for the first time, claimed the strike was a victory for the unions over the center-right government of prime minister anibal cavaco silva
cavaco silva, whose social democrats hold a solid parliamentary majority, said the strike would not cause him to alter a single line of a government bill that would make it easier for businesses to fire workers. he said the legislation is crucial to attracting investment in portugal and modernizing the economy
labor leaders said 85 percent of union members supported the strike
the government cannot act as if were deaf, dumb and blind in the face of this massive protest,'' said manuel carvalho da silva, a leader of the communist-dominated general confederation of portuguese workers
but the government said in a statement ``the country is working normally apart from the transport sector where there have been some clear cases of sabotage.'' the labor ministry said unions were exaggerating the extent of support for the strike
twenty-two in-coming flights and 29 departures were cancelled at lisbon airport and many other international flights were diverted, officials said
most flights of the state-owned airline tap-air portugal were cancelled at oporto airport in the north and faro in the south
state-owned public transport companies were hit hardest by the strike. train services were paralyzed across the country. bus, trams, subway and ferry services were reduced to skeleton services required under strike law
police said two shots were fired at a private bus in the northern city of porto. no one was injured. traffic was not heavily congested in most cities as many workers stayed home, police said
the government says existing labor legislation, passed in the wake of a leftist military coup that returned portugal to democracy in 1975, is so protective that it is almost impossible for companies to dismiss workers
cavaco silva says this deters investors and is prejudicial to workers because it encourages companies to hire them on short-term contracts, use child labor and keep wages low
the government says the new legislation will still provide greater protection than workers enjoy in any other west european country or the united states
unions and the leading socialist opposition party say the legislation will give managers the power to fire workers ``whenever and `whyever' they like.''
the supreme court today turned away an unusual copyright dispute that pitted the easter seal society against playboy enterprises
the justices, over one dissenting vote, rejected arguments that playboy illegally used materials intended for an easter seal telethon in a pornographic movie
justice byron r. white voted to hear arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such review
new orleans musician and entertainer ronnie kole, acting on behalf of the easter seal society, contracted with public television station wyes in 1982 to make a videotape of a staged mardi gras-style parade and dixieland jam session
the videotape was edited into a 16-minute version for the society's national telethon for crippled children, and was broadcast march 28, 1982
a year later, wyes broadcasting director julius cain received a telephone call from john thompson, a canadian television producer who requested videotape of a mardi gras parade
cain, unaware of thompson's exact intentions, provided an unedited copy of the easter seal tape. portions of the tape were incorporated into a movie entitled ``candy, the stripper,'' a sexually explicit film carried on cable television's playboy channel
some viewers in the new orleans area who had taken part in the staged mardis gras parade, upon seeing themselves in the pornographic movie, complained that their privacy rights were invaded
the easter seal society then sued playboy enterprises, wyes, a canadian film producer and others _ accusing them of copyright violations
the society said it, and not wyes, owns the copyright on the videotape
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled against the society last april. the appeals court said congress in 1976 narrowed the copyright protection for those who hire others to produce original works
because wyes was an independent contractor, the easter seal society was not the sole ``author'' of the mardi gras videotape, the appeals court said
wyes did not simply set up one camera on a tripod, turn it on and sit down to watch'' the staged parade and dixieland performance, the appeals court continued. ``instead, it worked cooperatively and dynamically with the performers to create the tape.''
reagan administration lawyers, asked by the high court last november for their views, said the 5th circuit court's interpretation of copyright law's work-made-for-hire provisions differs from those of other appeals courts. but they said ``the present case is not an appropriate vehicle for resolving the conflict in the circuits.''
in another copyright case, the court refused to revive a $300 million copyright-infringement lawsuit against the creators and marketers of trivial pursuit, a popular board game
the court, without comment, rejected arguments by the author of several encyclopedias on trivia that many of the questions contained in the board game infringed on his copyright works
in other action, the court:
_ agreed to hear the appeal of a convicted killer who said his rights were violated when he was denied an opportunity to talk to his lawyer during a trial recess
the court said it will review a ruling that denied a new trial to the south carolina man
_ refused to hear an appeal by former new york city political boss meade esposito, who sought to prevent public disclosure of certain court documents
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling challenged by esposito, the former brooklyn democratic boss convicted of giving illegal gratuities to rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y
the copyright dispute case is easter seal society vs. playboy enterprises, 87-482. picking up 9th graf pvs, `in court ....' deletes last two grafs to tighten.</note>
baby m is happy and secure with her father and his wife and shows no more attachment to the surrogate mother who refused to surrender her than she does to her babysitter, the toddler's father testified today
william stern, testifying at a court hearing over visitation rights for surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould, said he believes his daughter should not be allowed to see mrs. whitehead-gould for several years
mrs. whitehead-gould, who agreed to bear the child under a $10,000 contract with stern, currently is allowed to see the child once a week for two hours under supervision
the visitation fight is the final legal phase of the court battle involving baby m, now melissa stern, who turned 2 sunday. the court hearing was ordered in a landmark ruling by the new jersey supreme court overturning surrogacy for pay
both sides in the dispute strongly disagree over what would be in the best interest of the girl, with the key issue centering on whether continued contact with mrs. whitehead-gould would be harmful or healthy
the child, conceived by artificial insemination using stern's sperm, lives with stern and his wife, elizabeth, in their tenafly home
stern likened melissa to a young sapling that has to put down its roots
if anything is done to interrupt her putting down those roots, i'm afraid melissa does not have much of a future,'' he said during a half-hour of testimony
melissa calls him ``dada,'' and his wife, ``mama,'' he noted
stern acknowledged under cross-examination by mrs. whitehead-gould's attorney, joel siegal, that melissa appeared to be suffering no ill effects from her visits with mrs. whitehead-gould, and he said he would be willing to try to work out a visitation arrangement if the court ordered one
the critical thing is that these adults can get on with their lives, put the conflicts of the past behind them and support one another,'' said dr. david brodzinsky, who acted as a court-appointed psychologist in the widely publicized 1986 trial that marked the first court ruling on a surrogacy contract
the judge in that trial barred mrs. whitehead-gould from seeing melissa, but on feb. 3 the state supreme court declared surrogacy for pay illegal and restored mrs. whitehead-gould's parental rights, while granting custody to the sterns
the supreme court, in ordering today's visitation hearing, made no specific recommendations on visitation and gave the lower court the ``broadest powers'' to resolve the issue
mental health experts who have examined melissa say she appears to be unaffected by the legal storm around her. she was described as friendly with adults, while being more attached to stern than to her mother
in court papers filed last week, mrs. whitehead-gould says she wants liberal, unsupervised visitation. the sterns are seeking a halt to visitation for several years
the session before superior court judge birger m. sween is expected to last about three days. the high court ruled that the issue of visitation must be resolved by early may
in court papers, mrs. whitehead-gould says she wants visitation immediately expanded to eight hours twice a week, unsupervised at her home in east brunswick. she says she wants the visits eventually to include half the summer and some holidays
mrs. whitehead-gould has fashioned an excellent relationship with melissa and is devoted to promoting an even more flourishing and productive relationship,'' according to papers filed by her attorney, harold cassidy
but the sterns' attorney, gary skoloff, argues in court papers that no contact would be better for the child because mrs. whitehead-gould does not offer a healthy environment for her, particularly in the last year since the mother became pregnant out of wedlock, divorced her former husband and married wall street accountant dean gould
skoloff did not spell out in the court papers how long contact should be discontinued. in an interview, he said ``as long as possible,'' and mrs. whitehead-gould's attorneys say the sterns are seeking a six-year moratorium on visits
mrs. whitehead-gould's attorneys see her divorce and remarriage in a positive light, arguing that she has a more stable relationship and financially secure lifestyle. one passenger admitted to hospital.</note>
a northwest airlines jet was evacuated when fuel vapors briefly ignited, sparking what passengers thought was a fire and closing the airport for 20 minutes, authorities said. four people were slightly injured
flight 288, originating in san diego with 144 passengers and seven crew members aboard, landed safely at 8:20 p.m. sunday at metropolitan airport in romulus, about 20 miles west of detroit
as the boeing 727 waited for clearance to taxi to its gate, residual fuel in the exhaust system of the auxiliary power unit sparked a ``flash'' on the plane's right wing, northwest spokesman william wren said
it was immediately extinguished without damage to the plane, wren said
the flash was seen by a controller in the airport tower, passengers aboard flight 288 and by people aboard another plane taxiing behind it, said mort edelstein, a spokesman for the federal aviation administration in chicago
i saw a flash and i looked down and i felt heat on my face, and i looked out and there's a big flame on my window and all i could see was red,'' northwest passenger mike soderling of san diego told radio station wcxi
this lady next to me was screaming `fire, fire,''' soderling said. ``my first reaction was to get my luggage, but then i threw it down and ran to the door.''
the pilot triggered an automatic device that extinguished the flash, but by that time, the plane had been evacuated and airport firefighters were summoned, edelstein said
an initial faa examination of the plane revealed no burned parts or other signs of an actual fire, he said. northwest officials stressed that no fire had occurred
three of the injured passengers suffered minor cuts and bruises while sliding down evacuation chutes, annapolis hospital nursing supervisor mary smith said. none was admitted. the fourth passenger, a 64-year-old woman, was in good condition today at william beaumont hospital in royal oak, suffering from trauma and knee and elbow injuries, said hospital spokeswoman carol jonson
the auxiliary power unit runs the aircraft's electrical, air conditioning and other systems while it is on the ground and operates separately from the engines, wren said
edelstein said the plane will remain grounded while faa investigators examine it further
the city of chicago has agreed to pay more than $9 million in back-pay awards to settle a discrimination case involving 729 women, blacks and hispanics on the chicago police force, the justice department announced today
the proposed consent decree, filed in u.s. district court in chicago, would require the city to establish an interest-bearing back-pay fund of $9.2 million for reimbursements of awards to discrimination victims. the city also would adjust seniority dates for those victims
the decree would resolve an employment-discrimination suit filed in 1973 alleging a pattern and practice of discrimination by chicago in police department hiring and promotion. a federal judge in january 1976 found the city in violation of title vii of the civil rights act of 1964
the consent decree covers:
_233 women on the 1972 policewoman eligibility list who were subsequently hired or reclassified as police officers and who successfully completed their probationary period; and women who were employed before march 24, 1972, as policewomen or matrons and subsequently were reclassified as police officers
_455 black and hispanic men who applied for the 1968 or 1971 patrolman eligibility lists and were hired from march 24, 1972, to dec. 31, 1978, as patrolmen or police officers from those lists, and who successfully completed their probationary period
_the first three women promoted to sergeant after march 24, 1972, who served as policewomen or matrons in 1968 or before that time
_the first 38 black and hispanic men who applied for promotion to sergeant in 1968 and who were promoted to that rank from march 24, 1972, to dec, 31, 1973
the proposed decree was filed in court friday
a man demanding the return of his adopted daughter fired into a group of people getting out of a church school van, hitting the girl's biological mother and seriously wounding her cousin
the fort worth police department issued a warrant for the arrest of ollie thomas, 74, on two counts of attempted murder, spokesman tom wayne said sunday. police said he remained at large today
bridgett shirley, 14, was in serious condition today in an intensive care unit after undergoing 3{ hours of surgery for a gunshot wound to the lower back, hospital spokesmen said
the shooting took place at 9 a.m. sunday outside samaritan church of god in christ, police said
van passengers told police a man with a gun stopped the van during its pick-up route and told them he was looking for his 16-year-old adopted daughter, carmel shirley, who had left home a few weeks ago
when the van arrived at the church, the same gunman was waiting
he was just hollering `i want my baby,''' said earnestine shirley, 33, who is carmel's mother and bridgett's aunt. ``he was talking about killing up the whole family.''
the crowd of about 15 to 20 scattered as the man started shooting, witnesses said
one bullet pierced earnestine shirley's elbow and another struck bridgett. the gunman fired several times at laura shirley, bridgett's mother, but never wounded her
carmel shirley had planned to arrive at the church later and wasn't with the other members of her family
earnestine shirley was treated for the elbow wound and released from hospital. laura shirley was treated for knee scrapes and released
according to the fort worth star-telegram, earnestine shirley said she became pregnant at 14 and six years later asked an older couple to temporarily take care of her child. later she learned the couple adopted the girl, she said
but three weeks ago, she said carmel, now 16, returned to her alleging that thomas, her adoptive father, had mistreated her since she was 8
the supreme court today refused to disqualify a bankruptcy judge from presiding over a georgia case in which he ordered the winning side to ghostwrite opinions he then signed
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the judge's actions, while ill-advised, did not violate the losing side's rights
the case involves bankruptcy proceedings begun in 1975 in which colony square co., a developer, was ordered to surrender ownership of a $200 million real estate development in atlanta to the prudential insurance co. of america
the insurance company was the developer's chief creditor
bankruptcy court judge hugh robinson, after a hearing in the dispute on june 22, 1984, telephoned prudential lawyer francis m. bird jr. later that day and told him he intended to rule in favor of the insurance firm
robinson outlined what he intended to say in his ruling and asked bird to prepare the order
after some minor typographical corrections, the judge signed the order drafted by bird
lawyers for colony square were not told of the conversation between robinson and bird, or that the judge's order was written by prudential's attorney
robinson's orders were ghostwritten on two subsequent occasions when he denied a requem and thereby leads to stronger, sounder judicial rulings.''
but the appeals court said colony square's due-process rights were not violated because robinson already had decided the case before asking for bird's help, and because colony square had ample opportunity to argue its side before robinson and before the federal judge that reviewed the case
robinson's ``actions in preparing these orders have little to recommend them,'' the appeals court said. but the process ``did not prejudice (colony square) and was not fundamentally unfair.''
the supreme court is reviewing a related issue in a louisiana dispute over ownership of a hospital corporation. in that case, the justices have agreed to decide whether federal judges may be disqualified from presiding in cases when they are unaware they have a connection to the case that presents a possible conflict of interest. a decision is expected by july
the case acted on today is colony square vs. prudential insurance co., 87-1299
independent counsel lawrence walsh has reached agreement with israel after year-long negotiations for its cooperation in his investigation of the iran-contra affair, both sides announced today
under the accord, israel has given walsh the historical and financial chronologies covering its role in the shipment of u.s. weapons to iran in 1985 and 1986, said an israeli official
he (walsh) will get what he wants without us having to give up what we wanted,'' said the official, speaking on condition he not be named
israel had sought immunity from prosecution for the four key israeli players in the arms sales, profits from which were diverted to the contra rebels in nicaragua
two former white house aides and two u.s. businessmen have been indicted in the united states for conspiracy to defraud the government in the funds' diversion
israel also gave walsh written answers to questions posed by the congressional investigators who received the israeli chronologies last summer, said the official
the government of the state of israel and the office of the independent counsel have signed an agreement covering the cooperation of the government of israel in the iran-contra investigation,'' walsh's office said in a prepared statement
walsh's spokesman, jim wieghart, and israeli embassy spokesman yossi gal said the terms of the agreement are confidential
israel had turned over the chronologies to the congressional iran-contra committees but refused to give them to walsh pending his promise to refrain from prosecuting the four israelis involved in the affair
negotiations with walsh were further complicated when he subpoenaed the four israelis: former foreign ministry director david kimche, former counter-terrorism adviser amiram nir, businessman yaakov nimrodi and his u.s.-born associate, al schwimmer
in asking for immunity, israel contended that the four acted at the request of the israeli government and therefore were not accountable as individuals
two senior israeli officials held talks with walsh's office 10 days ago to wind up the negotiations, which have been going on since early 1987. the israeli government approved the accord, said the israeli official
the negotiations were difficult,'' said wieghart. ``israel is a sovereign state with certain national security interests, which they have to defend. we recognized that, but on the other hand, we had our needs in this investigation,'' he said
