about 800 american soldiers deployed in honduras in a show of force against nicaragua left today aboard seven c-141 cargo planes bound for the united states
the soldiers from the 82nd airborne division were whistling and shouting as they boarded the planes, the first of the american contingent to leave honduras
this is nice, it's beautiful,'' said sgt. elliott cook, 22, of miami, when he saw the planes to carry him and his fellow soldiers home. ``i am happy to go home because nothing happened.''
outside the palmerola air base, about 200 hondurans demonstrated their support for the americans
they carried signs saying, ``thanks for having helped us maintain our liberty'' and ``unity makes for democracy, thanks for being here.''
the paratroopers were scheduled for an airdrop into their home base of fort bragg, n.c
they are part of a force rushed to honduras for 11 days of training exercises to flex u.s. military muscles after a reported incursion by about 2,000 nicaraguan troops chasing u.s.-supported contra rebels
i'm sure they'll be home for a late dinner at least,'' maj. gary hovatter, the u.s. military public affairs officer at this base 40 miles northwest of the honduran capital of tegucigalpa, said sunday. he said the soldiers would probably parachute into fort bragg at about 5 p.m. est today
it's great to be going home,'' said sgt. dale taylor, 22, of red springs, n.c. ``it's going to be a sis-boom-bah occasion. they're going to have a band and our families will be there.''
president reagan ordered 3,200 paratroopers and light infantry to honduras on march 17 and 18. honduran president jose azcona hoyo asked for a show of force against after the reported incursion
nicaragua denied the report and claimed the united states was preparing to invade or using the deployment as a cover for providing equipment to the contras. u.s. officials have said the troops are taking back all the equipment they brought with them, including tanks and aircraft
first they'll have to go through a complete inventory of property to make sure they can account for all the equipment they brought,'' hovatter said
in addition to the 82nd airborne, the reinforcements include soldiers from the 7th light infantry in fort ord, calif. all are expected home by wednesday
the presence of the reinforcements, which raised u.s. strength in honduras to more than 6,000, alarmed the region and raised the already high level of tension. tensions eased when the contras and the sandinistas signed a broad cease-fire accord last week after three days of talks in sapoa, nicaragua
the u.s. troops never saw action, but the honduran president said all along he expected them to back him up if the sandinistas didn't withdraw
by late last week, honduran officials said the nicaraguan troops were back on their own side of the border
capt. steve walker, 30, of new milford, n.j., said he thinks the strong u.s. presence helped bring about the cease-fire
the nicaraguans did cease action and they did withdraw and they did sit down and start negotiation with the contras without any shots being fired,'' he said. ``it was an effective display of resolve.'' party</head>
port-au-prince, haiti (ap) _ an opposition party leader was arrested and two americans were under house detention today in connection with an explosion at a bridge in port-au-prince, party officials said
joseph douze, second in command of the centrist christian democratic party, was arrested saturday and charged in connection with last week's blast under the croix des bouquets bridge. the explosion tuesday caused no damage or injuries, party leader sylvio claude confirmed
claude said douze, a medical doctor with dual haitian and american citizenship, had been planted in the party by the government. douze, who had served as the party's provisional vice president, was expelled, claude said
douze was filmed by the state television station saturday night during a search of his home by soldiers
the americans, nancy horn, of wells tannley, pa., and james gunnels, of macon, ga., told the associated press in a telephone interview that they were friends of douze's and were staying at his home in thomassin, outside port-au-prince, at the time of his arrest
horn identified herself as an associate of douze and said she had been in haiti since 1967. gunnels said he was a businessman visiting the country
the officer in charge of the search of douze's home said on state television sunday the two americans ``have a certain responsibility in the affair.'' the officer did not elaborate
u.s. embassy spokesman jeffrey lite said u.s. consular officials had been in contact with horn and gunnels and that he did not know if they would be formally arrested although they had been barred from leaving the house
horn and gunnels said they did not know anything about the bombing
i know nothing about this affair,'' gunnels said. ``i was just a guest in his home for a few days.''
the two said they had been treated well by the army
horn said douze was in his mid-40s and of haitian origin and had lived several years in the united states during the duvalier dictatorship, which lasted from 1957 to 1986
claude accused the government of president leslie manigat of planting members in his party to try to discredit and destroy it. claude, a protestant pastor, was one of the four most popular presidential candidates in the nov. 29 elections suspended because of widespread violence
the state-run television nationale reported sunday that douze was arrested for possession of detonators, wiring for explosives, a remote control detonating device, ammunition and clips for automatic assault rifles
on wednesday the christian democratic party's head of security, jocelin brochard, a former army corporal, and two women were arrested in connection with the bombing of the bridge. several sticks of dynamite, two assault rifles and a large bag of marijuana were found stashed on the roof of the women's home in the port-au-prince slum of bel-air
brochard said on state televison last week that douze supplied the weapons
claude denied knowing that brochard or douze were involved in the bombing, but said some members of the party who have advocated violence have been expelled in the past
it wasn't quite gold at the end of the rainbow, but one amateur sleuth didn't complain about his jackpot
dale mcrae struck silver _ or, more accurately, a laminated card declaring him the winner of a treasure hunt _ at the base of a telephone pole guy wire at katherine drive and monroe avenue on friday
i reached down at the base of the guy wire, and there it was,'' mcrae said. ``i didn't even look. i just knew that was it.''
joe cramer, who owns a car care shop in this grand rapids suburb, each year offers a prize of silver to the first person to solve a complicated riddle. cramer issued a 77-word riddle on nov. 20 to start the latest hunt and gave short clues on the 20th of each following month
the original riddle mentioned a large woman singer _ maybe kate smith? and monroe came from the mention ``first'' (mono) and ``caviar'' (roe)
mcrae recognized in the final clue a mathematical formula for calculating the sides of a triangle, and the riddle suggested looking for a ``little support.'' he spied the triangular shape of the wire and the pole, and the prize was his
mcrae's wife, kathy, said their home is too small to properly display the silver serving tray, engraved cup and silver coins they won, but she added, ``someday we'll have a big house, and then we'll really be able to enjoy it.''
beach-goers seeking to escape the city found something unexpected: a quarter-mile-long swath of sand imprinted with a cityscape of los angeles by a 14-ton concrete roller
i like it, but i think it is a bit crazy,'' said sandra soderberg, 20, a tourist from sweden who witnessed the progression sunday of the ``santa monica art tool.''
with a $60,000 commission from the seaside city, the national endowment for the arts and another non-profit arts group, artist carl cheng crafted his unusual device to bring art to the masses
designs carved into the surface of the roller left _ for the moment at least _ two-inch-tall sand replicas of such city scenes as the memorial coliseum and a traffic-choked freeway
i like going to the general public and making a project interesting to them, not just the art collectors, said cheng, 46, of los angeles
initial reviews were favorable
it's wonderful,'' said paul schneider, 47, of los angeles. ``i like the fact that the city is putting its money into art that can be appreciated by thousands of people. it's art that is also an event.''
cheng's work is the second commissioned for santa monica beaches as part of a 10-piece ``natural elements sculpture park.''
the roller will go on permanent display near the santa monica pier. clarifying that a sexual encounter that turned rough was part of chambers' story before his plea.</note>
jurors in the robert chambers murder trial said today that the jury, though bogged down in circumstantial evidence, could have reached a verdict
i feel very firmly that we could have reached a verdict,'' said juror cole wallace, interviewed on abc's ``good morning america'' program
we never reached a dead end,'' said juror mike ognibene, interviewed on the same program. ``we were judging with a circumstantial case and there was a great deal of discretion involved in reaching the decision.''
chambers agreed to plead guilty last friday to first-degree manslaughter and an unrelated burglary charge to end his trial on murder charges in the death of jennifer dawn levin during a central park tryst. the agreement followed nine days of deliberations and both the prosecution and defense feared a hung jury
as part of the plea bargain, chambers, who had maintained since his arrest that he killed miss levin accidentally during a sexual encounter that turned rough, acknowledged he intended to hurt the 18-year-old woman the night of her death
chambers entered the rikers island jail saturday to await sentencing april 15. he faces a five-to-15-year prison term for killing miss levin under the bargain
we were shocked that that's how it ended,'' juror ginny hoesl said of the plea bargain in an interview on ``cbs this morning.'' she said chambers would have been convicted, but it was impossible to say on what charge
betsy shankin, a friend of jennifer levin's, said on the same program that she would have preferred a jury verdict, but was satisfied that chambers had to admit his guilt as part of his plea. she wished for a longer sentence, however, saying, ``i don't think it will ever be enough for him.''
on sunday, monsignor thomas leonard, who helped counsel chambers after his arrest, said chambers would issue a statement soon about the killing
i think that ... he will make some sort of statement of how sorry he is for the trouble this has caused the levin family and for his own family,'' he said
in a separate development, chambers' lawyer, jack litman, ridiculed allegations by assistant district attorney linda fairstein that his client forged $7,000 worth of stolen checks in october and used some of it to buy drugs
the scandalous claims by the prosecutors are made in an obvious attempt to save face for having allowed robert chambers to receive a sentence in the range of reckless manslaughter when they proclaimed from the rooftop that robert chambers intentionally murdered jennifer levin,'' he said saturday
fairstein said she didn't want to provoke a mistrial by making the allegation public earlier
as part of the plea bargain, chambers is immune from prosecution from any other past crimes
prosecutors had said that the burglary to which chambers pleaded guilty was committed to support his cocaine habit, for which he was institutionalized twice
here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken monday by the supreme court

easter seal-playboy

the court turned away an unusual copyright dispute that pitted the easter seal society against playboy enterprises
the justices, over one dissenting vote, rejected arguments that playboy illegally used materials intended for an easter seal telethon in a pornographic movie
the case is easter seal society vs. playboy enterprises, 87-482

trivial pursuit

the court refused to revive a $300 million copyright-infringement lawsuit against the creators and marketers of trivial pursuit, a popular board game
the court, without comment, rejected arguments by the author of several encyclopedias on trivia that many of the questions contained in the board game infringed on his copyright works
the case is worth vs. selchow &amp; righter co., 87-1268

recess

the court agreed to hear the appeal of a convicted killer who said his rights were violated when he was denied an opportunity to talk to his lawyer during a trial recess
the court said it will review a ruling that denied a new trial to the south carolina man
the case is perry vs. leeke, 87-6325

meade esposito

the court refused to hear an appeal by former new york city political boss meade esposito, who sought to prevent public disclosure of certain court documents
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling challenged by esposito, the former brooklyn democratic boss convicted of giving illegal gratuities to rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y
the case is esposito vs. new york times, 87-1319

ghostwriting

the court refused to disqualify a bankruptcy judge from presiding over a georgia case in which he ordered the winning side to ghostwrite opinions he then signed
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the judge's actions, while ill-advised, did not violate the losing side's rights
the case is colony square vs. prudential insurance co., 87-1299
senate democrats failed again today to end debate on a bill that would require the government to notify 100,000 to 300,000 workers a year that they risk cancer and other disabling diseases from exposure to toxic substances on the job
senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., said a fourth attempt at ending what some proponents of the legislation have branded as a republican filibuster will be made tuesday. two attempts last week failed
byrd indicated, however, that tomorrow's move could be the last effort to force a final senate vote on the house-passed bill if its sponsors cannot muster the 60 votes necessary to limit further debate to 30 hours
unlike ending a filibuster, passage of a bill requires only a simple majority _ 51 votes if all 100 senators are present
the 41-44 vote today to cut off debate indicated that sens. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, and edward m. kennedy, d-mass., the chief authors of the bill, had picked up only slight support by exempting farm workers and companies with less than 100 full-time employees
metzenbaum and hatch mustered 33 votes last week for ending a threat by sens. orrin hatch, r-utah, and dan quayle, r-ind., to prolong the debate indefinitely and prevent the senate from moving on to other measures
a few southern democrats and liberal republicans who had voted with hatch and quayle last week voted with metzenbaum and kennedy today
the bill would establish a panel of experts to identify the most hazardous substances in workplaces and the groups of employees most susceptible to disabling diseases because of exposure to them
the national institute of occupational safety and health would be required to notify 100,000 to 300,000 of those workers every year at an annual cost of $25 million
employers then would be required to finance medical monitoring program for them at a cost of up to $250 each annually
if, as a result of the monitoring, a physician recommends transferring an employee to less hazardous work, employers would have to pay the same level of wages and benefits to the worker in the new job. in the event no other job is available, the employee would be entitled to full wages and benefits for up to a year after leaving a job
a court sentenced a south african to prison for 50 years after he was convicted of spying for the pretoria government
isiah moyo, 32, of johannesburg, was found guilty of gathering classified information on zambian strategic installations and the guerrilla-backed african national congress headquarters in lusaka
moyo, who is black, is a former soldier in the south african military
he had pleaded innocent to the charges. but the high court commissioner rejected his defense that police and the anc had framed him
the anc says its goals, which can only be achieved by the overthrow of the white government in south africa, are for one-man, one-vote in a unitary state
voters in two southern mississippi congressional districts will select nominees tuesday for seats that trent lott and wayne dowdy gave up to run for the u.s. senate
the runoff elections in the 4th and 5th districts are necessary because no candidate received a majority in the primaries on super tuesday
in the 4th district that has been represented by dowdy, a democrat, since 1981, the democratic runoff pits brad pigott, a 33-year-old jackson attorney, against political newcomer mike parker, 38, of brookhaven. thomas collins iii, the executive director of the mississippi veterans home purchase board, faces 30-year-old jackson attorney andy taggart on the gop side
polls show both races very close
in the 5th district, state sen. gene taylor of bay st. louis tests glenn white of hattiesburg, while 43-year-old sheriff larkin smith of gulfport and hattiesburg businessman george robert hall, 57, face off in the republican runoff
a recent poll showed smith with a decided edge, while the democatic race was rated a toss-up
