the israeli army will close off the entire west bank and gaza strip for three days in expectation of major demonstrations called by the plo to mark a palestinian anniversary, the army announced today
in the occupied gaza strip, palestinian residents will be confined to their homes for three day, the army said. in the west bank, palestinian residents will be restricted to their cities and villages
arabs will be prevented from entering the area from israel but the 65,000 jewish settlers living in the territories will be allowed to travel freely, the army spokesman said
maj. gen. ephraim lapid said the army also would bar palestinians from leaving the west bank via the two bridges across the jordan river. incoming traffic from jordan would be permitted, he said
u.n. figures say 119 arabs have been killed since unrest began in the occupied territories dec. 8. one israeli soldier has been killed
lapid said only pool press coverage will be allowed during the three-day period. reporters will be accompanied by a military spokesman, the official said
the purpose is to keep the territories quiet. it is not directed specifically against the press, but we don't want to give the people of the areas any reason for causing disturbances,'' said a senior defense official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the measures were to take effect at 1 a.m. tuesday on the west bank and 10 p.m. tonight in the gaza strip. five-hour nightly curfews are already in effect in gaza
israel's 24-member cabinet authorized the measures in its weekly session sunday, israeli officials said
the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the move was calculated to lessen tensions wednesday, when palestinians will mark land day, the 12th anniversary of a 1976 clash between israeli soldiers and arabs over the confiscation of arab land. six arabs were killed
underground leaflets signed by the plo have called for major demonstrations throughout israel and the occupied territories to mark the occasion, a traditional time of unrest in recent years
israeli officials have maintained press coverage, especially the presence of television cameras, has incited palestinians to stage violent protests that might otherwise not have taken place
robert slater, head of the foreign press association in israel, sharply protested the action and said the group was considering legal action
we reject this as we have for the last four months,'' slater told the associated press. ``the foreign press stands united in its determination to cover this story in person and wherever the story takes us.''
also today, prime minister yitzhak shamir sharply protested a meeting between u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz and two arab-americans tied to the plo
a 19-year-old palestinian, meanwhile, died of wounds he suffered during a clash sunday in the west bank village of salfit. hussein kamel odeh died of a gunshot wound to the heart, israel radio and the arab-owned palestine press service said
the army said villagers attacked troops who came to rescue a tour bus that mistakenly entered the village
but 10 american and european academics on the bus denied the army report and said troops used their presence as a pretext to raid the village. another 14-year-old arab boy also died in the clash
also today, plo chief yasser arafat's chief spokesman was quoted as saying shultz will have more meetings with plo-affiliated officials, possibly when the secretary of state visits the middle east beginning april 3
shultz met in washington on saturday with edward said and ibrahim abu lughod, both american citizens and members of the palestine national council, the parliament-in-exile of the palestine liberation organization
israel has always refused to negotiate with the plo and israeli officials contend the shultz meeting violated a longstanding u.s. commitment not to deal with the plo
shamir's criticism of shultz's meeting speech came a day after ministers of the center-left labor party told a stormy cabinet meeting visit that israel must adopt a u.s. peace plan if it hopes to end violence in the occupied lands
before his visit to the united states last week, shamir had blocked any debate on the peace plan which involves israel giving land to the palestinians in exchange for peace
the state department, which has restricted american travel to the west bank and gaza, today said it regretted israel's decision to seal off the territories for three days in expectation of major demonstrations called by the palestine liberation organization
spokesman charles e. redman said the israeli move would have an impact on commerce, visits between family members and the press
both israelis and arabs will be prevented from entering the two areas. the only exception will be the 65,000 jewish settlers who live in the territories
a total of 119 palestinian arabs and an israeli soldier have died since violent protests broke out dec. 9. the state department, citing ``continuing disturbances,'' last friday advised u.s. citizens to avoid travel to the areas until further notice
the warning also could have an impact on tourism and business, especially during holy week
redman reaffirmed, meanwhile, that u.s. policy prohibits dealing with the plo as well as negotiating or recognizing the group until it accepts israel's right to exist and disavows terrorism
the spokesman said secretary of state george p. shultz's meeting here saturday with two american members of the palestine national council did not conflict with the 13-year-old policy
the council considers itself the legislative arm of the palestinian nationalist movement. one of the two palestinians, edward said, said he informed plo chairman yasser arafat before he and ibrahim abu-lughod met with shultz
redman said that the plo and the council were not ``synonymous'' and that ``our restrictions on dealing with the plo remain as always.''
shultz will go to the middle east on sunday for five days of talks with arab and israeli leaders on his proposal to open negotiations by may 1
he will make stops in israel, jordan, syria, egypt and saudi arabia
shultz presented his proposal to arab and israeli leaders four weeks ago
and asked for a reply by mid-march. so far, only egypt has endorsed his plan
trumpeter al hirt was released from the hospital monday after a four-day stay for treatment of a hand and arm ailment, officials said
he had been treated by dr. michael debakey for an acute infection of the right hand and arm, which is his playing hand,'' said methodist hospital spokeswoman brenda blake. ``the outlook is excellent.''
hirt, 65, flew to houston on thursday from his home in new orleans so he could be treated by debakey, a friend
hirt said his doctors believed the problem may be related to his trumpet playing and a growth that developed on a finger of his right hand after 59 years of playing
hirt canceled an appearance thursday in new orleans and a weekend gig in fairfield, conn., so he could be treated
president reagan and his wife, nancy, have signed a three-year lease on a $2.5 million estate in the bel air section of los angeles to live in after they leave the white house next january, the white hose said today
elaine crispen, mrs. reagan's press secretary, said the reagans signed the lease and mailed it within the last 10 days. the lease gives them an option to purchase the house and its 1\ acres of grounds
the amount of the lease payments was not disclosed
a group of about 20 friends of the reagans set up a firm called wall management services and purchased the estate on aug. 21, 1986, saying they did so with the understanding they would be reimbursed by the reagans
the estate includes a secluded house with 6,500 feet of living space and a pool. it was purchased from a 90-year-old woman who at the time of the purchase still lived in the house
at the time of the purchase, mrs. crispen said the reagans had not yet chosen a home and might decide to purchase a different one
she said today the investors had purchased the home as an option for the reagans and ``it is one they have decided on.''
the house on monday approved a bill that would make it easier for a parent to recover a child who is abducted and taken to a foreign country, often by the other parent
the measure, passed by voice vote and sent to the senate, would enable the u.s. government to implement an international treaty intended to overcome complex, time-consuming legal issues blocking the prompt return of abducted children from a foreign country
the united states signed the treaty in 1981. although it was approved by the senate in october 1986, the united states has not ratified the pact because the state department said implementing legislation was needed first
the treaty provides for the prompt return of children abducted from their country or wrongfully kept in a foreign country, and provides for visitation rights across international borders
the bill provides for accelerated procedures by the courts of nine foreign countries that have ratified the treaty for returning abducted children to their u.s. parents
the bill would direct state courts, when petitioned by foreign parents, to order children returned to their habitual residence abroad, even if there is no legal order establishing custody
washington _ the supreme court on monday refused to rule that playboy enterprises violated federal copyright law when it used material intended for an easter seal telethon in a pornographic movie
the justices, over one dissenting vote, rejected an attempt by the easter seal society to collect damages from playboy
in other matters, the court:
_agreed to hear the appeal of a convicted south carolina killer who says his rights were violated when he was forbidden to talk to his lawyer during a trial recess
_agreed to study a challenge to the way webster county, w.va., assesses real estate for property tax purposes. the county's policy of reassessing recently sold property at half the sale price means some land is assessed 6,500 percent higher than similar property
_refused to revive a $300 million copyright-infringement lawsuit against the creators and marketers of trivial pursuit, a popular board game. the justices rejected arguments by the author of several encyclopedias on triva that many of the questions contained in the game infringed on his copyright works
_refused to hear an appeal by former new york city political boss meade esposito, convicted of giving illegal gratuties to rep. mario biaggi, r-n.y., that sought to prevent public disclosure of certain court documents in the case
the easter seal society vs. playboy case dates back to 1982, when new orleans musician and entertainer ronnie kole, acting on behalf of the society, contracted with public television station wyes to make a videotape of a staged mardi gras-style parade and dixieland jam session
the videotape was edited into a 16-minute version for the society's national telethon for crippled children, and was broadcast march 28, 1982
a year later, wyes provided an unedited copy of the easter seal tape to a television producer. portions of the tape were incorporated into a movie entitled ``candy, the stripper,'' a sexually explicit film carried on cable television's playboy channel
some viewers in the new orleans area who had taken part in the staged mardis gras parade, seeing themselves in the pornographic movie, complained. the society then sued playboy enterprises, wyes, and others _ accusing them of copyright violations
the society said it, and not wyes, owns the copyright on the videotape
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled against the society last april. the appeals court said congress in 1976 limited the copyright protection for those who hire others to produce original works
only justice byron r. white voted monday to hear arguments in the case. four votes were needed to grant review to the society's appeal. prosecutor, picking up 5th graf pvs, `today, the ....'</note>
gov. evan mecham today lashed out at the prosecutor at his impeachment trial for comparing his use of a protocol fund to a bank official's embezzling money
i resent so highly the word embezzlement in my presence,'' the first-term republican governor told prosecutor william french as french and presiding officer frank gordon jr. tried to silence him
i'm insulted by it,'' mecham said. ``i have seen no other witness who has been insulted as i have been.''
however, gordon admonished mecham against making his statement without being asked a question, saying, ``i hope, sir, that you believe that the rules are for you as well as everybody else.''
mecham, testifying as the impeachment trial entered its second month, said he never tried to hide an $80,000 loan from the governor's protocol fund to his auto dealership from the public or from other business creditors
the arizona senate is hearing evidence on three charges to determine whether the first-term republican should be removed from office
mecham argued that the loan was legitimate, saying, ``a loan is one thing and an expenditure is much, much different.'' he contended he also could have legally borrowed the money to buy himself a car, and he also could have loaned the money to his wife as long as she paid it back
french asked mecham whether a bank officer could avoid embezzlement charges if he borrowed bank funds, as long as he paid it back. that question led to the governor's outburst
the governor also testified today that he thought somebody must have been monitoring his telephone calls for the prosecutor to learn that he phoned a witness
but french said that the witness told a member of the prosecution staff about the call
mecham's former chief of staff, jim colter, initially testified about the matter tuesday. when he returned to the stand the next morning, he testified under questioning from french that he had gotten a call on his answering machine from the governor saying ``that i had done a good job or something to that effect.''
today, the governor said, ``there was no intention to contact jim,'' adding that he was ``shocked'' that french found out about the call
the governor said he had made the call to inquire about colter's health and to say he looked well
somebody had to be monitoring my phone calls to ever know that. ... i couldn't figure out any other reason, mr. french, that you would'' know about the call, said mecham, who once said he feared laser beams were being used to eavesdrop on his office
that's just an assumption on my part,'' the governor added
french then asked the governor if he would be surprised if colter had told a member of french's staff about the call
yes, that would surprise me, but if you tell me that i'll accept it,'' the governor said
the senate already has heard testimony on a charge that mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
the third impeachment charge accuses him of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan. the governor also faces an april 21 criminal trial on six felony counts related to the loan
the senate could decide this week to vote on the first two allegations without hearing the third. a conviction would automatically remove mecham from office, although the trial could continue on the third charge to decide if the governor should be barred from holding future public office
the senate last week dropped a proposal to allow a vote after the first count, and some senators predicted the same would happen this week
i imagine there will be more votes for it, but i doubt there will be enough,'' majority leader bob usdane said sunday. he added there is a chance the trial might not end before a may 17 recall election as some senators want
fellow republican sen. greg lunn said senators should hear all the evidence before voting whether to convict mecham
however, minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, said sunday there was a danger that hearing testimony in the senate on the $350,000 loan charge might make it impossible to empanel an impartial jury in criminal court. in that case, he said, ``we look pretty bad.''
a two-thirds senate margin would be required to change the rules and allow an early vote
on friday, mecham testified that he was told by fund-raiser bill long he could spend the protocol fund ```for any damn thing you want' _ those are his words _ `except you can't spend it for politics or for personal living expenses.'''
long submitted an affidavit friday contending that he never intended to turn the inaugural proceeds into state funds and that he believed they were being turned over to mecham for his personal use
the prosecution contends the protocol fund, created with proceeds from inaugural fund-raising events, became public money when it was turned over to the governor's office. mecham pontiac needed the $80,000 loan to meet its july payroll, according to prosecution testimony
however, the defense contends mecham pontiac was in good shape and that the protocol fund was private money that mecham could use as he saw fit, except for personal living expenses or to retire his campaign debt
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham, who is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades
a bus carrying 62 people fell into a ravine monday, killing 25 and injuring 37, according to a news report
the accident involving the state government-owned bus occured at 2:40 a.m. in western maharashtra state about 19 miles northeast of bombay, the united news of india said
the bus was bound from nasik to virar, a northern bombay suburb, the news agency said. picking up 3rd graf pvs, `the powell ....'</note>
they groan and squeak, lurch forward and rock backward, but as the quaint little cable cars on powell street turned 100 today they're being celebrated by thousands of adoring fans
costumed characters, including one portraying cable car inventor andrew s. hallidie, rode 14 cars decorated like floats as perennial bell-ringing champion carl payne rang out dixieland melodies and a navy jazz band led the way
it's great to be part of this celebration. it's really special,'' payne said, adding optimistically, ``i'm hoping to be here at the 200-year mark.''
a $40-a-plate luncheon to raise money for the homeless was scheduled after the parade, along with the release of 15,000 balloons and the serving of a giant birthday cake cut into 1,000 pieces
the powell street line, though younger than its sister line on california street, whose centennial 15 years ago set off a wild two-week bash, is longer and more picturesque, earning a special place in the hearts of san franciscans and millions of tourists
folks sometimes help push the trolleys at the turnaround on powell and market, getting a hands-on sense of history on a moving national landmark as the cars climb past union square and chinatown to fisherman's wharf, with a view of alcatraz as a bonus
presidents and movie stars have rumbled up and down powell during the past century, enjoying breathtaking vistas on some of the city's steepest slopes
there were spectacular accidents and annoying breakdowns, but most of the time the trolleys kept rolling, clickety clack at 9{ mph, on millions of trips through fog and earthquakes in a constantly changing city
today the two powell street lines carry about 41,000 passengers a day on 3{-mile rides that take about 25 minutes each
you could have seen a lot of change from these cars over the past 100 years,'' says gripman phillip shaw, who's plied powell for 26 years. ``only the hills stay the same.''
if you close your eyelids halfway and tune out most of the noise except for the bell and the wheels, you can almost imagine yourself riding along in the 1800s,'' says jeffery fleischmann, a visitor from dallas
powell street is where perennial bell-ringing champ carl payne, another 26-year veteran, chimes through town, delighting riders with his melodies and stories
at night, when fog creeps over the city, there isn't a more soulful sound than the muffled peals of a cable car bell
being on a cable car, you're back in history and it shows you how good people had it back then,'' payne says
south african soldiers raided a house on the outskirts of this border capital early monday, killing a man and three women during an hour-long gun battle
the south african defense force claimed responsibility in a statement issued in pretoria 10 hours after the attack ended about 2 a.m
it described the victims as ``terrorists'' of the african national congress, the main guerrilla group fighting white domination in south africa
both the united states and javier perez de cuellar, the u.n. secretary-general, condemned the raid. state department spokesman charles redman said: ``it appears the south african authorities made no attempt to seek the cooperation of the botswana authorities in dealing with the alleged security threat.''
in gaborone, president quett masire's office said the man was south african, two women were botswanans and the third woman had not been identified
according to the statement, all were sleeping when the south africans attacked at 1 a.m. in an area of the phiring suburb called tsholofelo
the office of the president strongly condemns this dastardly attack and murder of innocent people in botswana by the south african army,'' it said. ``south africa's problems cannot be resolved by attacking neighboring countries such as botswana.''
botswana ``strongly urges the south african government to engage in meaningful negotiations with the genuine leadership of the oppressed majority in that country,'' the statement said
south africa's 5 million whites control the government and economy, and the 26 million blacks have no voice in national affairs
the statement from the south african military called the raid a follow-up to a shootout near the border with botswana on friday, which had not been reported previously. in that attack soldiers killed ``three suspected terrorists'' in a running battle near a farm, capturing rifles, machine pistols and hand grenades, the statement said
following up on intelligence gathered during friday's operation, an element of the defense force killed four more terrorists ... on the northern outskirts of gaborone early today,'' it said
monday's raid provides ``further evidence that anc terrorists, originating from zambia and zimbabwe, use botswana as a transit route to infiltrate into south africa,'' it said
defense minister magnas malan said the ``pre-emptive'' raid ``resulted in the prevention of killings and maimings of innocent people at a later stage.''
a dispatch from the botswana press association quoted norman moleboge, the deputy police commissioner, as saying the four victims were shot and set afire, and gasoline containers were found at the scene. it said an explosion may have been caused by a gas cylinder in the house
neighbors said they heard sporadic fire from automatic weapons, and possibly grenade explosions. they reported seeing people flee in a vehicle and others run into the bush. two said the raiders left in a helicopter
one witness said a woman ran from the house and sought shelter in his home
south africa has issued several threats to botswana in the past few months, accusing it of harboring african national congress guerrillas
masire's government supports anc goals and allows its representatives in the country, but says it does not permit guerrillas to attack south africa from botswana's territory
the south african military has raided alleged guerrilla hideouts in botswana several times in recent years. one person was killed in an attack in may 1986 and a raid in june 1985 left 15 dead
singer dennis day is out of the intensive care unit at the hospital where he was admitted earlier this month with a head injury, but remains in serious condition, a spokesman said monday
day's ``vital signs are stable and he is showing some response to visitors and members of his family. he is not speaking, but he is improved,'' said armen markarian, spokesman for st. john's hospital
day, 71, was hospitalized march 9 after falling at his bel-air home. he underwent immediate surgery to relieve pressure on his brain; a second operation for the same problem was performed march 19
day was diagnosed last july as suffering from amyotropic lateral sclerosis. the progressive nerve disorder, also known as lou gehrig's disease, causes a loss of muscle control
day, who was born eugene denis mcnulty in new york city, began his career with comedian jack benny in 1939. an accomplished tenor, day played the innocent foil to benny's character on television and radio, breaking into song to counter benny's anger or tricking him into letting him sing
three cabinet officers unveiled a guide to workplace literacy monday that includes tips for businesses to learn just how well or poorly their workers read
the three officials _ labor secretary ann mclaughlin, education secretary william j. bennett and commerce secretary c. william verity _ all agreed that bolstering the basic skills of workers is essentially to maintaining a strong economy
the education and labor departments published the 50-page guidebook, ``the bottom line, basic skills in the workplace.''
it was verity who provided the most gripping example of problems which companies face with illiteracy in the workforce
basic workplace literacy is an absolute necessity if we are to increase our productivity, remain competitive in the global marketplace and continue to be a world leader,'' verity said
he said he had learned of one company that wanted to hire 100 people for two shifts at a new, state-of-the-art plant, but had trouble finding workers capable of performing fifth-grade math and seventh-grade in english
verity, who declined to identify the company, said, ``a test was given to 480 people who applied, and only 49 of them passed.'' the company offered to send those who flunked to an eight-week remedial course at a community college, and 50 of the 100 people who took the course passed the company's test on a second try
verity said the real problem is that schools should be improved so that all high school graduates ``at least have the equivalent of a seventh-grade education in english and a fifth-grade education in math, which is sort of the norm for getting a job in industry. hopefully, as time goes on, those levels will rise and we'll have a much better workforce coming out of the school system.''
the bottom line'' guidebook outlines how to identify employees' basic skills and how to improve them. it spells out how to conduct a ``literacy audit'' to determine what skills a worker needs to carry out a given task, and offers suggestions of actual programs that have proven successful
mclaughlin said 75 percent of the u.s. workforce for the year 2000 are already out of school. ``many of these workers are ill-prepared to deal with rapidly changing technology because they lack adequate basic skills,'' she said. ``clearly, business must take a lead role in remedying the basic skills gap for these workers.''
she cited estimates that up to 23 million american adults lack the basic skills needed to hold a job
bennett said, ``unfortunately, there are still too many people who graduate from our high schools with a diploma, but without the necessary skills.''
our job doesn't stop with the schools. and that's where this book comes in,'' said bennett
mclaughlin said it was ``an interesting liaison'' between the three cabinet officers. but noting that it was their first joint appearance, she said, ``maybe we're not quite getting the act together.''
bennett quipped, ``it's our first, but not our last. peter, paul and mary, look out.''
single copies of ``the bottom line'' are available free by writing:
the bottom line, division of adult education, department of education, 400 maryland ave. s.w., reporters bldg., room 522, washington, d.c., 20202. or by writing: employment and training administration, department of labor, 200 constitution ave. n.w., room s2307, washington, d.c. 20210
jesse jackson says he can win wisconsin's pivotal democratic primary ``because i've stood here with the meat packers in cudahy, the auto workers in kenosha and the paper workers in de pere.''
from iowa's bankrupt farmers to laid-off appliance workers in illinois, jackson has stood side-by-side with the nation's displaced and disaffected and in the process forged a winning coalition
jackson's campaign for ``economic justice'' has touched a chord and it may be enough to deliver another victory over michael dukakis in wisconsin next tuesday, aides to both candidates said monday
support from blue-collar workers is crucial to jackson's chances in wisconsin since jackson's core black constituency makes up only 3 percent of the state's population. jackson consistently carries about 10 percent of the white vote, but has moved beyond that in some states, notably in heavily-white vermont earlier this month and on saturday in michigan, where he won some predominantly white areas on top of black detroit wards
tony tsakakis, a national campaign aide to massachusetts gov. dukakis, said wisconsin is a two-man race. even though he feels dukakis will win, tsakakis said he could not rule out a jackson victory
it's going to be the reverand and us through the convention,'' said tsakakis
bob burns, a member of jackson's national staff working in wisconsin, said jackson would rely heavily on labor support in a push to win wisconsin
in every race where we have competed, we felt we would come in no. 1 or no. 2 and wisconsin is no different,'' burns said
both men referred to a milwaukee sentinel poll released monday that showed dukakis leading jackson 28 percent to 25 percent among likely democratic voters
the poll was conducted march 17-22, before jackson's weekend win in michigan
it is not a measure of our new-found momentum as our rock-bottom strength,'' burns said
even republican gov. tommy thompson, a supporter of vice president george bush, said monday if he were a democrat, he would vote for jackson
under wisconsin's open primary, thompson legally could take a democratic ballot, but does not plan to do so
just because he is a democrat doesn't mean i can't like him,'' said thompson, who joined jackson earlier this month in kenosha to protest plans by chrysler corp. to close an auto plant there, a move that will throw 5,500 people out of work
it is those auto workers in kenosha, strikers at the patrick cudahy meat packing plant in cudahy and striking paper workers in de pere that jackson is depending on to help him carry wisconsin, as he has done in other states
the day after super tuesday, jackson was in the chicago suburbs of cicero where workers were worried about the planned closing of a general electric plant thtat makes hotpoint refrigerators. jackson was met under dreary, damp skies by a rally of about 200 people, organized by the sheet metal workers union. they carried signs that said, ``jesse, help us save our jobs,'' and ``unemployment, made by ge.''
workers said they believed jackson would make a difference for them
nothing has changed here. i've been working here 23 years. i believe jackson would make a change,'' said mack fundes
phil haney, a kenosha auto worker who came to milwaukee on saturday to see jackson, said he felt the same way
he's been on the picket lines,'' haney said
haney said if jackson were president, he would expect him to push for legislation to promote more business investment at home and help for workers displaced by plant closings and new technologies. search resuming today. corrects spelling of last name from trenkel to trenkle throughout.</note>
a father who gave up his life preserver to save his son's life after their boat overturned and filled with water in the swift sandy river was still missing today and presumed drowned
george earl trenkle, 40, of blackfoot, idaho, tossed a seat cushion to his son, george edward trenkle, 18, after they and a third man hit a log and were thrown from their boat into the frigid water saturday, multnomah county sheriff's deputy bob boertien said
the younger trenkle said sunday that he tried to throw the cushion to his father after reaching safety, but he didn't have the strength
i threw the thing to him, but i was so tired, it really didn't go that far,'' trenkle said
i could just see his head as he went around a bend,'' he added. ``i yelled, `dad!' a couple of times, and he said he would be ok.''
the third man in the boat, roland parkhurst, 40, of nearby gresham, was a paraplegic and was wearing a life jacket. witnesses pulled the younger trenkle and parkhurst from the river
the pair were taken to a hospital in gresham, where they were treated and released. the boat was found overturned and washed ashore about a half-mile downstream from where it hit a submerged log that almost destroyed its bow
a search for the elder trenkle resumed late this morning
we were floating down river; my dad was rowing. we just got started, and he was having trouble rowing. he was kind of new at it,'' trenkle said sunday in a telephone interview with the oregonian newspaper from his uncle's house in salem
after the boat overturned, trenkle said he managed to climb on top of it at one point. his father had hold of the boat, and parkhurst held his foot as they tried to make it to shore
then we hit the rapids, and we all separated from the boat,'' trenkle said
i was under water for quite a while.'' then, he said, his father pulled him up to the surface and gave him a seat cushion that he had found
trenkle, a high school senior, said his father worked as a fire boss for the u.s. bureau of land management, and was in portland for a business meeting. he said his father and parkhurst had known each other since high school
police in west germany and switzerland seized 11 people suspected of spying for the soviet union in a crackdown that was termed a major blow to the kgb, authorities said monday
interior minister friedrich zimmermann said the arrests showed that soviet bloc spy networks were redoubling undercover work in the west, despite improved superpower relations
west germany's counterintelligence agents ``have dealt a serious blow to eastern espionage agencies,'' zimmermann said in a statement
the large number of arrests confirms that instead of refraining from activating agents in a time of political detente (between east and west), the east bloc is intensifying the illegal activities of its operatives,'' he added
security sources said the arrests were made during a series of police raids last week. federal prosecutor kurt rebmann said they marked ``an important penetration of the kgb spy network'' in west germany
an foreign engineer living in zurich was arrested wednesday on a tip from west germany, swiss prosecutors said. they did not disclose his name or nationality but said they had launched a criminal investigation into his activities
spy scandals and arrests are frequent in west germany, a front-line nato ally and one of western europe's most technologically advanced nations
in the last major espionage scandal, 15 communist agents were arrested or disappeared between august and december 1985
rebmann said 10 people were taken into custody wednesday and thursday as part of a nationwide crackdown against espionage targets. the raids were carried out by 169 police officers in 33 locations, according to rebmann
he said six of the 10 taken into custody remained in jail on monday, and that investigations were continuing against the four who were released
in addition, inquiries were under way against 14 other espionage suspects, for a total of 24 separate investigations, the prosecutor said. he declined to say how many of the cases were likely to result in charges
he said those in custody included two teachers, three engineers and a businessman, all of whom are suspected of working for the kgb. three were soviet emigres living in west germany
one suspect, businessman helmut stefan kolasch, is believed to have worked for the kgb since 1971, rebmann said. kolasch, 44, allegedly gave the kgb technological secrets about nato's tornado and jaeger warplanes while working for firms dealing with the aircraft, he said
rebmann identified the other jailed suspects as peter friesen, 33, an engineer; george bender, 37, also an engineer; shimon or, 48, a teacher; edmund neufert, 37, another teacher. another suspect, a colombian engineer, was identified by rebmann only as ``amaya.''
the prosecutor said all six were living in west germany
rebmann said amaya also handed over unidentified technical documents to the kgb; friesen spied on west german political parties, bender reported to the kgb about a ``large electronics concern'' he worked for, and neufert spied on students while teaching russian at the foreign ministry's language-training office
rebmann said or ``reported (to the kgb) on his own life and work,'' but he did not provide details
none of the suspected spies apparently knew one another and were operating individually, the prosecutor told reporters
the police raids followed the march 18 arrest of a government secretary who was also suspected of having worked for the kgb. elke falk worked in several government ministries in the past decade and had access to classified information
one of amedeo modigliani's last paintings sold for a record $9 million monday at an auction of impressionist and modern art
the oil painting, which set a record for the italian artist, portrayed greek composer marios vavoglis and was completed in january 1920, days before modigliana died in paris at age 36
an anonymous buyer purchased the simple painting, called ``portrait of mario,'' which had been put on the auction block by an anonymous owner, christie's said
it had been estimated to sell for $3.7 million to $4.65 million. the previous record price for a modigliani was $7.62 million, set in november for a portrait called ``the beautiful roman.''
works by pierre auguste renoir, camille pissaro, alfred sisley, wassily kandinsky, paul klee, salvador dali, marc chagall and joan miro, among others, were also for sale at the christie's auction
producer lee guber, who helped bring broadway entertainment to theaters and concert halls throughout the country, has died of brain cancer. he was 67
guber, who died at his manhattan home sunday, produced nearly a dozen shows on broadway, including productions of ``the king and i,'' ``fiddler on the roof,'' ``gypsy,'' ``i do! i do!'' and ``how to succeed in business without really trying.''
he also headed a suburban entertainment chain that included the westbury music fair on long island, the valley forge music fair outside philadelphia, the shady grove music theater outside washington and the painters mill music fair in the suburbs of baltimore
guber and his partner, shelly gross, booked such entertainers as judy garland, jack benny, sammy davis jr., liberace and stevie wonder. they also brought productions of broadway musicals to suburban theaters
guber's last production, however, was one of several flops in his career. ``rags,'' a $5 million musical about immigrants, ran on broadway for only four performances before closing in august 1986
guber was born in philadelphia and met gross at central high school there. with a third partner, frank ford, they began their theatrical career in 1955 with productions at the valley forge theater in devon, pa
married three times, guber divorced his second wife, broadcaster barbara walters, in 1976 after a 13-year marriage
he is survived by his third wife, lois wyse, whom he married in 1982, as well as by three children from his prior marriages, two stepchildren, a sister, a brother and eight grandchildren
funeral services are planned wednesday at temple emanu-el in manhattan
thousands of armenians in a disputed region of the caucasus stayed away from factories and schools monday to protest the kremlin's refusal to make the area part of the armenian republic
groups of young men blocked pedestrians and busloads of workers from reporting to their jobs in stepanakert, the main city of the nagorno-karabakh region, the government newspaper izvestia reported. it said authorities used mobile loudspeakers and leaflets to urge an end to the strike
the state-controlled media said the ethnic unrest was damaging the region's economy
about three-quarters of the 157,000 residents of nagorno-karabakh, which has been part of neighboring azerbaijan since 1923, are ethnic armenians
the official radio in baku, capital of azerbaijan, said ``extremely fanatical elements'' incited disturbances saturday evening in nagorno-karabakh
it did not describe the disturbances or say exactly where they occurred in the disputed territory. the british broadcasting corp. monitored the broadcast in london
sporadic strikes and protests have been reported in nagorno-karabakh since feb. 13. the latest labor trouble is said to have begun wednesday after moscow refused armenian demands to annex the region, about the size of delaware
in a telephone conversation, the manager of stepanakert's only hotel, the karabakh, said all but essential services were halted
the bread and milk plants are working. the others are not. everyone is sitting at home,'' he said
about 30 percent of public transport was shut down in stepanakert, a city of about 33,000, the manager reported. he described himself as an ethnic armenian but would not give his name
an izvestia dispatch from stepanakert said workers stayed away from factories producing silk, shoes and electronic goods, students boycotted the teachers' college and mothers kept their children home from kindergarten
azeris, the dominant ethnic group in azerbaijan, also were caught up in the trouble, it said
ethnic azeri workers arrived at the entrances to their businesses but ... announced: unless the armenians come, we will not work,'' izvestia reported
communist party officials in stepanakert called workers to weekend meetings and urged them to resume their jobs, the government paper said. appeals distributed by leaflets and broadcasts monday said the city owed the government seven million rubles ($11.2 million) in lost revenue
the hotel manager said party meetings continued monday. he predicted the strike would end tuesday but sergei grigoryants, a moscow human rights activist who is half armenian, said it was scheduled to run through friday
pravda, the national party daily, said monday the ``difficult state of affairs'' in nagorno-karabakh had damaged the economy of azerbaijan as a whole
losses to the automotive and transport industries were the equivalent of about $2.4 million in february and march, and the railway industry lost about $120,000, the paper said
it revealed little about how the money was lost but quoted a railway official in azerbaijan as saying freight cars had not been unloaded. the official, garik sarkisyan, said the situation was ``thoroughly bad'' and ``loss of time and money has become the usual thing.''
there were no strikes or protests monday in yerevan, capital of armenia, according to an armenian interior ministry official, a hotel executive and armenian nationalist hovik vassilian, all interviewed by telephone
izvestia said, however, that at least one yerevan factory was having trouble getting supplies from sumgait, a city in azerbaijan on the caspian sea north of baku where at least 32 people were killed in ethnic riots feb. 28
a van-assembly plant in yerevan sent trucks to sumgait for side windows but were not allowed into the city. izvestia said. it did not make clear who barred the truck or why
moscow dissidents in touch with armenian sources over the weekend described yerevan as ``a dead city.'' people stayed home to protest a crackdown on demonstrations that had been planned for saturday, they said
on wednesday, the government announced a plan for improving social and economic conditions in nagorno-karabakh, but it does not include annexation to armenia
on monday, pravda said the improvements hinge on whether the strike ends
any most realistic and well-considered program cannot be implemented if people do not come to feel a high personal responsibility for the destiny and development of the area and do not get down to work,'' it said. ``the machine tools should not stay idle, railway cars should continue to be unloaded and field work should go on.''
the state department criticized israel on monday for sealing off the west bank and gaza for three days in expectation of major demonstrations called by the palestine liberation organization
we regret the decision because of the impact it will have on commerce, on visits with family members and the press,'' spokesman charles e. redman said
last friday, the department advised u.s. citizens to avoid travel to the areas because of continuing disturbances. this also was likely to affect local business because tourists are attracted to the west bank during holy week
israel's decision will keep israelis and arabs from entering the territories. the only exceptions will be the 65,000 jewish settlers who live there among 1.5 million palestinian arabs
a total of 119 palestinians and an israeli soldier have died since violent protests broke out in the west bank and gaza on dec. 9. secretary of state george p. shultz will launch a new drive in jerusalem on sunday to hold negotiations for palestinian self-rule beginning may 1
he plans two stops in israel and in jordan, the two key countries, and also stops in syria, saudi arabia and egypt. spokesman redman said shultz would like to meet with palestinians while he is in the region
on tuesday, he is scheduled to meet here with representatives of the arab league, which is a group of the 21 arab countries and the plo
shultz will leave washington on thursday and spend more than two days in rome meeting with italian officials and attending religious services
redman reaffirmed, meanwhile, that u.s. policy prohibits ``dealing'' with the plo as well as negotiating or recognizing the group until it accepts israel's right to exist and disavows terrorism
the spokesman said shultz's meeting here saturday with two american members of the palestine national council did not conflict with the 13-year-old policy, which also was written into law in 1984
the council considers itself the legislative arm of the palestinian nationalist movement. one of the two palestinian-americans, edward said, said he informed plo chairman yasser arafat before he and ibrahim abu-lughod met with shultz, and arafat approved
israel protested the meeting
redman said the plo and the council were not ``synonymous'' and that ``our restrictions on dealing with the plo remain as always.''
the spokesman said shultz's meeting with said and abu-lughod, who are university professors, was ``not a negotiating format.''
shultz presented his proposal for negotiations to arab and israeli leaders four weeks ago and asked for a reply by mid-march. so far, only egypt has endorsed his plan
still, redman said the proposal was ``under serious and active consideration by the parties.'' he said shultz would emphasize the plan was a fair and balanced approach to the 40-year arab-israeli dispute
nobody has said no,'' redman said. ``we are going to continue to work on this proposal to see if we can't get something going.''
asked about a report that shultz would take with him an invitation to a united nations conference on the middle east to begin april 15, the spokesman said: ``it sounds pretty flaky.''
the pentagon, breaking its normal silence about ship movements, said monday the helicopter carrier uss okinawa would begin a transit of the panama canal on tuesday
the defense department described the movement in a statement as ``routine'' and something ``which has been planned for several months.''
the pentagon said the statement was issued in hopes of avoiding rumors and speculation in panama about the carrier's presence in the waterway
the reagan administration has been applying economic pressure in hopes of ousting strongman gen. manuel a. noriega, but has made clear it is not taking any military moves against the general
the okinawa is steaming through the canal on the last leg of an around-the-world journey that saw it deploy in the persian gulf to support mine-sweeping operations. the carrier dropped off its mine-sweeping helicopters earlier this month in norfolk, va., and is now destined for its home port in san diego
president reagan and his wife have decided on a los angeles home to live in after the president leaves office in january but will lease, rather than buy, the $2.5 million estate, the white house said monday
elaine crispen, press secretary to first lady nancy reagan, said the reagans signed a lease and mailed it within the last 10 days. the estate in the luxurious bel air district is owned by wall management services, a group of about 20 friends of the reagans who bought it with them in mind
the three-year agreement gives the reagans the option to renew the lease or purchase the property. the estate includes 1\ acres of grounds and a secluded house with 6,500 feet of living space and a pool
wall management bought the estate on aug. 21, 1986, from a 90-year-old woman who the investors said would lease it back from them until the reagans were ready for it
mrs. crispen said the previous owner has since died
the spokeswoman said she did not know the amount of the lease payments. she said the lease agreement was worked out by the reagans' lawyers, the white house counsel's office and the office of government ethics
the reagans' money is in a blind trust
the reagans lived in pacific palisades, in the western part of los angeles, before his election as president. that house has since been sold
they own a century-old, spanish-style adobe house of five rooms and 1,500 square feet at rancho del cielo, their ranch on a 2,250-foot-high mountaintop 30 miles northwest of santa barbara
the soviet union has stepped up its aerial reconnaissance patrols along the entire asian coastline and is becoming more aggressive in sending up fighters to meet american patrol planes, the head of the u.s. pacific fleet said monday
while it is difficult to know for sure, the increased activity may reflect the aftermath of the mathias rust affair, in which a west german teen-ager managed to fly a small plane past soviet air defenses to moscow's red square, said adm. david e. jeremiah
rust's success prompted a shake-up of the soviet military hierarchy
the four-star admiral, who took command of the pacific fleet last october, also confirmed previous reports that the united states would conduct naval exercises off the korean peninsula during this summer's olympic games
he also argued that congress, in debating whether some older navy carriers should be retired soon, should not disturb the current practice of basing a carrier in japan. and he declared the most important concern of military commanders in the pacific to be the situation in the philippines and continued access to u.s. bases there
the 54-year-old jeremiah met for more than 45 minutes with pentagon reporters monday to discuss developments within a military theater that is by far the navy's largest _ stretching from the west coast to africa
jeremiah said the soviets had become much more aggressive in recent months in meeting u.s. aircraft over the pacific, particularly in scrambling mig-23 jet fighters out of a base in cam rahn bay, vietnam, and from soviet bases above the sea of japan
i think you're seeing a pattern that reflects the rust incident,'' jeremiah continued
that's what the reaction is. the soviets (military) obviously got jacked around pretty hard after that penetration of their air space. the soviet aviation forces ... have been much more aggressive in reconnaissance flights around the sea of japan and offshore off japan, some of them over north korea and down to cam rahn bay and into the south china sea
the activity rate is higher than it was in times past,'' he said
addressing the large russian naval base at cam rahn bay, jeremiah said the soviets did not appear to be engaged in any major construction projects at the moment. but he added the base is now substantially larger than when it was used by the united states during the vietnam war
the admiral refused to offer many details on u.s. plans for naval exercises during the summer olympics, beyond saying the aircraft carrier midway and a battle group would maintain ``a fairly continuous presence through the period.''
pentagon sources disclosed last month the exercises would be staged to let north korea know ``that we're watching them'' and nothing should be done to disrupt the olympic games in south korea
jeremiah described the midway, the only u.s. aircraft carrier based outside the united states, as an essential part of america's forward defenses in that part of the world
while the midway itself has become the object of proposed budget cuts, it would ``absolutely'' have to be replaced with another carrier, he said
if anything is done to change the composition of the carrier force, then this country should be careful to do it in a prudent way that allows us to get all of the pieces put together in sequence so that we don't disturb relationships with our host nations,'' jeremiah added. in 4th graf pvs, on the; note 5th graf pvs, bush's one-time, embargoed for release at 4 p.m. est</note>
rep. richard gephardt quit the democratic presidential race today, a victim of mounting losses in the seven weeks since he won the lead-off iowa caucuses. rival jesse jackson, on the rise with a victory in michigan, said he expects the party to embrace him as its nominee if he wins the most pre-convention delegates
gephardt, who declared his candidacy in february 1987 and actually began campaigning more than a year earlier, said at a capitol hill news conference, ``it's time to end a presidential campaign.''
he said he would file for re-election to his house seat on tuesday ``to continue my fight for the people whose concerns have been at the heart of this campaign.''
the missouri congressman noted that it is often said that an opera isn't over ``until the fat lady sings.'' referring to his distant third-place finish in the michigan caucuses, he said, ``last saturday in michigan, i think i heard her walking to the microphone.''
he ranked fourth among the democratic contenders in delegates to the national convention
on the eve of tuesday's connecticut primary, vice president george bush, who grew up in that state and is heavily favored to win, set off today on a three-day wisconsin campaign swing

bush's one-time foe, jack kemp, endorsed the vice president, saying ``george bush is going to be the nominee of the republican party and he has earned that nomination.'' kemp said the gop must rally around bush to avoid a democratic win in november, which he said would lead to a decline ``every bit as steep and severe as under jimmy carter.''

bush, the overwhelming gop front-runner, wasn't likely to run into either of his remaining rivals in wisconsin, which holds its primary a week from tuesday. bob dole, who has all but conceded the nomination, was in washington today, giving a speech on the future of the republican party. and pat robertson was taking a week-long vacation
jackson, on abc-tv's ``good morning america,'' said today, ``if at the end of california, we have the most popular votes and the most delegate votes, becoming the nominee is logical and proper.''
he questioned the idea that party leaders might ignore his delegate strength at the convention and give the nomination to another democratic candidate
they would not have given me the nomination; i would have earned it from the people,'' jackson said. ``there is no small group. no electoral college that can give. ... if so, why even have a primary? why not just let the small group choose candidates in the first place?
i don't believe in collecting a group of favorite sons, and then selecting one, the people elect what's left,'' he said
jackson said if he wins the nomination through the democratic process, ``i expect the party to embrace me and to embrace those principles.''
rival michael dukakis was seeking to come back with a win on his new england home turf. jackson was campaigning in connecticut again today. but dukakis, the governor of neighboring massachusetts, has won every state in new england so far and was expected to do well in the state
with returns from 94 percent of the voting sites in michigan, jackson had 55 percent to 28 percent for dukakis. gephardt had 13 percent; sen. paul simon had 2 percent, as did sen. albert gore jr. the remaining returns were expected later today
the michigan victory put jackson within striking distance of dukakis in the national delegate count, although the massachusetts governor still clung to a narrow lead. the latest ap delegate count put dukakis at 603.55 to jackson's 597.55. tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 362.8, sen. paul simon 171.5, gephardt 167 and uncommitted 362.6
some of the democratic candidates were gathering for a forum in new york tonight. but dukakis was not expected, and gephardt might not be a candidate by then
dukakis, who before michigan had been seeking to position himself as the inevitable democratic nominee, was talking instead about a long fight to the finish
this race is only half over,'' he said sunday at a greek festival in new haven. ``anyone that thinks that this race is over or even that it's narrowed down to a two-person or a three-person race doesn't understand the unpredictability of american politics. ... there are no front-runners.''
that was fine by gore and simon. the tennessee senator was in connecticut on sunday, suggesting dukakis' disappointing finish kept the race ``wide open'' _ to his benefit
we're building momentum steadily. ... we're gaining speed,'' gore said after a speech at an italian-american club in the industrial city of derby. ``this race has a long way to go. it is wide open, even more so after the results in michigan.''
simon also suggested _ as he has for some time _ that the race was still fluid, and no nominee would emerge before the democratic national convention in july. the illinois senator, who came away with only 2 percent of the vote in michigan, has said he needs a strong showing in wisconsin to carry on
a statewide poll in today's milwaukee sentinel suggested jackson and dukakis were in a dead heat in the state
another poll suggested dukakis was the clear favorite in new york, which holds its primary on april 19
the weekend wasn't a complete loss for dukakis. he won precinct caucuses in north dakota, and he edged out gephardt in iowa's county conventions, the latest step in that state's complicated delegate-selection process
police arrested 60 people monday during a demonstration in which protesters tried to force their way into the iraqi embassy and hurled stones through the windows
the crowd was protesting iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons in kurdish regions in its 7{-year-old war with iran
interior minister karl blecha met with the iraqi ambassador, wahbi a. razak al-qaraguli, and expressed the government's regrets, said karl newole, spokesman for the minister
protesters and police said shots were fired when some in the crowd tried to force their way into the embassy. police spokesman martin muellgassner said no one was injured
muellgassner said it was not clear who fired or what kind of weapon was used. he reported four to six shots, fired inside the building
on austrian radio, a protester who was not identified said an embassy employee fired into the street with an automatic weapon
a statement from a group of kurdish groups, carried by the austria press agency, protested the shooting. it said a delegation of demonstrators had wanted to enter the embassy to protest ``the massacre of kurds in iraq.''
iran accused iran last week of dropping cyanide and mustard gas bombs march 16 and 17 on three kurdish towns in iraq that killed 5,000 people and wounded 5,000. the towns had been captured in an iranian offensive
one of monday's demonstrators told austrian radio a delegation of three or four people had wanted to present a protest to embassy officials. the kurdish statement said the shots were fired as the delegation tried to enter the building
people gathered outside the embassy at 10:20 a.m. in a heavy rain. some carried posters saying, ``stop the massacre,'' or ``freedom for kurds.''
muellgassner said the crowd surged toward the embassy and five to 10 people pushed through the door, but embassy personnel managed to force them back. the four policemen regularly posted at the embassy were outside, he said
newole said the iraqi ambassador asked blecha for increased protection and blecha said an investigation would be conducted to determine whether it was necessary
according to police, protesters threw stones through the windows after the shots were fired. a demonstrator interviewed by austrian radio said the crowd began the protest ``with peaceful intentions.''
demonstrators said about 70 people took part, but some fled when shots were fired
some of the kurds allegedly wounded in the iraqi attacks were expected in vienna on tuesday for medical treatment. they originially were to have arrived monday and there was no explanation for the delay
richard gephardt, who fell short of the ``michigan miracle'' he needed to revive his candidacy, quit the race for the democratic nomination today but said ``our effort was not in vain.''
departing at an announcement on capitol hill, gephardt continued the populist, anti-establishment flavor that he used on the stump
i believe that our effort was not in vain _ that we challenged the democratic party and and called it back to its central role as an agent of fundamental change,'' he said
gephardt also updated the line that became the populist slogan of his campaign, ``it's your fight too.''
whether the issue is trade or social security, contra aid or the environment, tax justice or corporate responsibility, your fight will always be my fight too,'' gephardt said
gephardt's candidacy limped out of the south on super tuesday three weeks ago, having never received the beneficial momentum he had expected from iowa
gephardt had looked to michigan's caucuses last saturday, figuring that auto-industry state would provide a most receptive ear for his call for trade retaliation against countries that don't open markets to u.s. products
he asked for a ``michigan miracle.'' instead he got a distant third place finish behind jesse jackson and michael dukakis
it's been said the opera isn't over until the fat lady sings,'' gephardt said. ``last saturday in michigan i think i heard her walking to the microphone.''
gephardt's campaign blossomed in the lead-off delegate event, iowa's caucuses, where his tough talk on trade caught on with the state's democrats. he won again in south dakota, but on super tuesday he failed to win anywhere other than his home state of missouri
gephardt said he would file for re-election to his house seat from missouri. ``i hope to carry their cause as a member of congress, and tomorrow i'm filing for re-election,'' he said
aides said gephardt did not intend to try to preserve the delegates he had already won as a bloc by continuing his campaign in a suspended state
he spent sunday at home in seclusion at his suburban virginia with family and advisers. aides were silent about what went on, but as early as last week they had said privately that he would drop out if he didn't make a strong showing in michigan's democratic caucuses. he finished a distant third in saturday's contest
going into michigan, gephardt indicated it was a do-or-die state for him, but said he believed his prospects were good. michigan is an industrial and union state that offered as receptive an audience for his tough talk on trade as gephardt was likely to find anywhere
gephardt's last campaign speech was in milwaukee, before wisconsin democrats who vote next tuesday. he delivered it as the size of his michigan defeat was becoming clear
all things considered, i'd rather be back in des moines,'' said gephardt, who won iowa's lead-off caucuses but was unable to convert that into victories in other states aside from his own missouri and in south dakota
even in iowa, gephardt's candidacy was slipping away
at county conventions there over the weekend, follow-ups to the precinct caucuses in february, gephardt lost supporters to dukakis, and jesse jackson gained ground as well
i think people see that gephardt is pretty much out of it,'' said tom mann, a state senator from des moines who backed jackson
gephardt had won 167 delegates through 31 contests, falling behind even sen. paul simon, who was not a factor on super tuesday and only stayed in the race because he won his home state of illinois
his delegates, where people have actually been selected to fill those slots, would become free to do as they wished if gephardt pulled out of the race. in states where no people had been selected yet to fill delegate slots won by gephardt, his delegate share would be reallocated among the other candidates depending on state rules
gephardt surged to the top of the democratic field in iowa with savvy television ads and a tough, pointed campaign message blaming unfair trade practices for much of the nation's economic difficulty
but his win in the iowa caucuses feb. 8 didn't provide the ``bounce'' that he hoped for in the states that followed
gephardt got very little momentum out of iowa,'' said democratic party professional elaine kamarck. pat robertson's surprise second-place finish over george bush on the republican side dominated the news
gephardt lost everywhere on super tuesday except for a homes-state win in missouri. he was pounded across the south in a withering crossfire of negative television ads by both dukakis and sen. albert gore jr
gephardt delivered strongly stated populist, anti-establishment themes. but his message had a fundamental negativism to it _ at every speech he declared that america was ``in decline.''
his depiction of himself as battling the establishment also brought an undercutting skepticism from those who knew him as the consummate washington insider. some critics called his message ``pseudo-populism.''
when he tried to resuscitate his campaign in the northern industrial states, organized labor did not provide backing. a day before michigan's caucuses, he asked uaw members at a rally in flint to deliver a ``michigan miracle.''
but the uaw in michigan was splintered, with many of the rank-and-file members backing jackson. when uaw president owen bieber appeared with gephardt two days before that state's caucuses, his unwillingness to offer an endorsement underscored gephardt's problem
gephardt formally declared his candidacy on feb. 23, 1987, but he had begun campaigning more than a year earlier
state and local governments increasingly are considering whether men and women should be paid the same for jobs that are different but of similar value to an employer, according to a private study released monday
the survey by the national committee on pay equity said more than 1,500 local governments, school districts and community colleges have taken steps to identify or eliminate race or sex bias in the wages of civil service employees
cities, counties and school districts in 24 states and the district of columbia have taken some action to address the issue of pay equity, the report said
americans are rejecting compensation systems that unfairly penalize women and people of color,'' eileen m. stein, chairwoman of the washington-based coalition of women's, labor and civil rights groups, said in a statement accompanying the report
it is indisputable that pay equity is taking hold at the local and state levels,'' she said. ``employer by employer, jurisdiction by jurisdiction, race and sex discrimination will be removed as wage determinants.''
pay equity, also known as comparable worth, is the concept of paying men and women similar wages for different jobs judged to be of equal value to an employer. supporters of the concept say action is needed to offset historical discrimination that has depressed wages in job fields dominated by women, such as teaching, nursing and clerical work
opponents say it is impossible to compare jobs as disparate as, say, nursing and truck driving
stein pointed to recent victories for pay equity proponents, such as the $35 million decision by the city of san francisco last march to give 12,000 city and school employees raises of $750 to $2,000 a year over two years
the city acted after its civil service commission found that female and minority municipal workers were paid an average of 42 percent less than their male counterparts in similar jobs
the year before, washington state adjusted the wages of about 35,000 state workers in a program that could cost about $482 million through 1992
stein also said los angeles, chicago, seattle, colorado springs, colo.; west hartford, conn.; ann arbor, mich.; spokane, wash.; sioux city, iowa; palo alto, calif.; long beach, calif.; green bay, wis.; virginia beach, va.; and burlington, vt., have made pay equity adjustments
pay equity proponents in congress have been unsuccesful so far in attempts to pass legislation requiring the government to study its wage and job classification systems for possible discrimination
to date, no federal appeals court has ruled that employers must pay similar salaries to workers in jobs of comparable worth although some employers are undertaking such salary revisions on their own
graffiti will remain on the walls of a synagogue through passover as a reminder that anti-jewish attitudes remain widespread, a rabbi said
some of the red scrawling at temple beth-el was partially erased sunday, but some will remain through the holiday, which begins friday and marks jewish deliverance from slavery, said rabbi alan cohen
meanwhile, police have assigned an investigator to the vandalism at temple beth-el and temple beth david in palm beach gardens, but there were no leads and no arrests, sgt. michael fulk said monday. the temples were defaced over the weekend
acts of vandalism against jews, their institutions and property rose nationally in 1987 but declined in florida and palm beach county, according to the anti-defamation league, which monitors racist incidents. sixteen anti-semitic acts were reported in palm beach county last year, down from 17 the year before
more than a million workers halted public transport and closed many businesses monday in a 24-hour general strike against a government labor proposal
the walkout also disrupted international flights, closed banks and brought factories to a standstill. union leaders said the strike, aimed at a bill which they say would give employers too much power to fire workers, was the country's biggest ever
jose torres couto, head of the socialist-led general workers' union, said between 1.75 million and 2 million workers went on strike. his union called the walkout
the labor ministry said the figures were exaggerated
prime minister anibal cavaco silva said most of the country went to work as normal with the exception of the state-owned public transport sector, where union militancy is high
the general workers' union is dominant among white-collar workers. the communist cgtp, stongest among blue-collar workers, supported the strike, the first time it has backed industrial action by the socialist union
opposition parties do not have the strength to defeat the government's labor bill in parliament. but union leaders have expressed the hope that president mario soares will veto it
soares, whose election two years ago was strongly supported by the unions, could use his veto to delay the legislation but could not overturn it altogether. he has not said what he will do
however, the prime minister said monday his social democrat center-right government won't change a word of the bill. threat</head>
supporters of a bill to warn as many as 300,000 workers a year that they risk cancer or other diseases from job exposure to toxic chemicals failed monday on a third attempt to stop a republican filibuster
sens. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, and edward m. kennedy, d-mass., the chief sponsors of the union-sought legislation, mustered only 41 of the 60 votes needed to end debate and force a vote on the measure itself
the bill is aimed at addressing what the national institute of occupational safety and health estimates is one in every four americans who has been exposed to carcinogens at work, most of them unaware of it
this bill is about people getting cancer in the workplace and learning about it too late to do anything about it,'' metzenbaum said. ``the american cancer society estimates we can save 250,000 lives in the next 10 years by implementing it.''
a fourth and possibly final attempt at ending the filibuster is scheduled tuesday. supporters of the bill believe if they get another 14 or 15 votes then, they can prevent senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., from giving up on the effort to win its passage this year
a virtually identical measure was passed by the house on a 225-186 vote last november. administration officials have said they would urge president reagan to veto if it reaches his desk
although the filibuster primarily is the work of republican sens. orrin hatch of utah and dan quayle of indiana, a small group of southern democrats who want to avoid a showdown vote are helping keep it alive
metzenbaum and kennedy were able to get just 33 votes last week for ending the filibuster. at least one southern democrat and a few liberal republicans who had voted with hatch and quayle last week voted with metzenbaum and kennedy on monday
the bill would establish a panel of seven scientific experts to identify the most hazardous substances in workplaces and the groups of employees most susceptible to disabling diseases because of exposure to them
the national institute of occupational safety and health would be required to notify between 100,000 and 300,000 of those workers every year at an annual cost of $25 million. employers then would be required to finance medical monitoring programs for them at a cost of up to $250 each annually
if a physician recommends transferring a monitored employee to less hazardous work, he or she would have to be paid the same level of wages and benefits to them in the new job. if no other job is available, the employee is entitled to full wages for up to a year after leaving work
in addition to unions, the bill is supported by public health groups, the chemical and electronic industries and several major companies, most of which have instituted such notification programs on their own
however, it is opposed by small businesses and large trade associations such as the national association of manufacturers and the u.s. chamber of commerce, which claim the bill would expose companies to liability suits from current and former employees
if this bill passes, there is going to be a liability crisis in this country like we've never seen before,'' hatch said. ``you're going to have billions and billions of dollars in lawsuits.''
sinhalese extremists threw three bombs into a city council building in the southern town of matara on monday, injuring nine councilors, police said
a police statement issued in colombo said the attack was launched by youths riding motor cycles in matara, about 88 miles south of the capital
nine council men were wounded, including four of them seriously, the statement said. the victims belonged to different political parties, including the governing united national party
the attack was carried out by six members of the outlawed peoples' liberation front, an ultra-nationalist sinhalese group, the statement said. the group has vowed to kill anyone who supports an indian-sponsored peace accord signed in july. the accord aimed at ending the tamil ethnic conflict
sinhalese extremists claim the accord gives too many concessions to the tamils
the peoples' front has killed more than 220 people in the past five months, according to official statements made last week. many of the victims have been members of the majority sinhalese community, who have supported the accord or not expressed opposition to it
meanwhile, residents in the eastern town of batticaloa said in telephone interviews that tension was increasing in the east after tamil youth looted and burned 25 moslem-owned shops on saturday in kalmunai. most of the moslem shops closed down after the arson attacks
a roman catholic priest, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: ``the whole area is very tense after the attack. large contingents of indian troops backed by helicopters are all over the place.''
more than 50,000 indian peacekeeing troops are in the eastern and northern sri lanka to disarm tamil militants who oppose the peace pact. they have been battling the rebels since last october
moslem leaders, including moslem religious affairs minister mohamed haniffa mohamed, have claimed that indian troops were responsible for the attack on the shops on saturday
sources in the government said that mohamed and three other moslem lawmakers told the high-level national security meeting that indian peacekeeping troops were involved
the attack took place after the troops had cordoned off the area and imposed a curfew, the lawmakers told the meeting, according to the sources
tamils make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people, most of whom are sinhalese. tamils say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese, who control the government and the military
tamil militants are fighting for a separate homeland in the northern and eastern provinces where most of the tamils live
foreign visitors attracted by the weak dollar and the slick ``miami vice'' image are producing double-digit increases at southern florida tourist attractions for the first time in years
it's like a language school outside my office,'' said michael finley, superintendent of everglades national park. ``i'm hearing french, german, japanese everywhere.''
a total of 306,202 visitors came to the park in january and february, an increase of 43 percent from the 213,384 who came in the same months last year
lion country safari, the palm beach county big-game preserve and amusement park, shows a 25 percent boost over last year
we were so busy over the washington birthday weekend, i stood out all afternoon directing traffic,'' said lion country marketing director brian osborne. ``we had a 4-mile-long line of traffic in the park.''
ocean world, where fort lauderdale visitors can pet dolphins and watch sharks feed, reports 18 percent more visitors this season
south florida tourist officials are unable to estimate the total number of foreign tourists, but international traffic at miami international airport was 786,951 passengers in january, up 9 percent over january 1987's total
we're something different than they've got back home in europe and japan,'' said jerome scherr, president of miami's parrot jungle, where attendance was up 16 percent from january to january. ``we're subtropical _ palm trees and glamour.''
nigel and rosy collins visited miami's seaquarium from london
everything is so warm, so clean, so new, so cheap,'' collins said, as his wife chimed in, ``and you've got don johnson.''
they expected their weeklong trip to south florida and orlando to cost barely half of what they would have paid two years ago because of the dollar's decline against foreign currencies
`you have a truly unique place,'' said klaus mueller, a german who was bird watching at everglades national park. ``everybody in the world knows about the everglades.''
businesses that thrive on tourism expect the boom to continue as long as the dollar is low
the english should be here big in april,'' scherr said. south americans will then travel north to avoid winter, and europeans will keep coming
finley expects europeans to generate 80 percent of the business at flamingo lodge at the southern tip of the park in the mosquito-swarming months of july and august
meanwhile, the traditional spring break market that put fort lauderdale on the map is in decline. broward county tourism officials had been expecting 200,000 vacationing collegians but said sunday they now expect only 110,000 to 180,000 _ the smallest crowd this decade
prime minister margaret thatcher said monday she sees no signs that president reagan is becoming a lame duck
the british leader told the british broadcasting corp. in a radio interview that the president is ``cantering up to a very strong finish.''
i mean, there's no sign of slowing down at all. if anything, it's a very, very strong finish,'' she said
asked whether she will consider herself leader of the western world while a new u.s. president settles in, mrs. thatcher said there ``can be no substitute for american leadership _ there just can't.''
they're strong, they're enterprising, they somehow keep that country going through difficulties with elections,'' she said
jesse jackson poked fun at his better-financed democratic presidential rivals on monday and urged voters to catch the ``fever of hope'' and join his own rising white house campaign
jackson, who scored a landslide victory over michael dukakis in the michigan caucuses on saturday, is far behind in the polls in advance of tuesday's contest in connecticut
but he is in a neck-and-neck race with dukakis in the associated press national delegate count, and has received more votes in the primary contests to date than any of his rivals
he said his campaign lacks the financial ``big boulders'' that some of his opponents can claim
i have little rocks,'' he said. ``but i throw them straight.''
we have the most gold and silver medals'' in the primaries and caucuses so far, jackson proclaimed. ``we can win.''
he said his campaign has a ``small budget, a strong message and a clear vision.''
jackson began his day by making it clear that he expects the party to nominate him if he winds up the primary season with the most delegates and the most votes
becoming the nominee is logical and proper'' if he achieves those goals, he said in an interview on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
he questioned the idea that party leaders _ many of whom view him as a sure loser in a general election campaign _ might turn to another contender
they would not have given me the nomination. i would have earned it from the people,'' he said
i don't believe in collecting a group of favorite sons, and then selecting one, the people elect what's left,'' he added
jackson did not address the issue of democratic party acceptance as he closed out his low-budget, high-energy connecticut campaign
but in stops in middletown, at a crime and drug-ridden area of waterbury and a well-attended outdoor rally in hartford, he managed to ridicule better-financed opponents
we don't have no rolls royces and no big stretch limousines on the road to the white house. we're walking but we know the road better,'' he said
in another jab, he said, ``we're not getting endorsements from the top down. we're getting votes from the bottom up.''
jackson stressed his message that the powerless can gain power if they have hope
he said people in wheelchairs, the homeless and others who come to hear him ``have the fever of hope.''
there's nothing more powerful in the world than the people whose hope has been raised.''
in his stop in the mt. olive church of god and christ in waterbury, jackson drew his loudest cheers when he condemned drug use. ``we the people must say down with dope and up with hope,'' he said
the nation's commercial nuclear power plants reported 2,810 accidents in 1987, about the same number as for a slightly smaller number of plants the previous year, a group critical of the industry said monday
the corresponding figure for 1986 was 2,836. at the end of last year, there were 105 nuclear plants in commercial operation against 99 at the same point a year earlier
the report was issued by the critical mass energy project of public citizen, a group founded with the help of ralph nader. the project publishes a compilation of nuclear regulatory commission reports annually, this year on the ninth anniversary of the accident at the three mile island plant in pennsylvania
the findings of this study suggest that the lesson of three mile island has been forgotten by the nuclear industry and its friendly watchdog,'' the nrc, said kenneth boley, one of the authors of the report
the report said 1987 figures could rise slightly as additional reports come in from the plants
the commission imposed fines against utilities in 46 instances, compared with 50 in 1986
the report said notable events of 1987 included:
_the closure of the peach bottom plant of philadelphia electric co. for regular sleeping on duty by plant operators in a management culture that the institute of nuclear power operations, an industry group, called ``an embarrassment to the utility and the nation.''
_the nrc's proposal of an $80,000 fine for a supervisor's instruction to tie two valves open in violation of regulations at the oyster creek plant of jersey central power &amp; light co
_the firing of five employees by detroit edison co. for their involvement in an incident in which a trainee operator failed to notify his supervisor for two hours when reactor water temperature reached a certain point
scott peters of the u.s. council for energy awareness, a pro-nuclear trade group, said he had not seen this year's report but, ``if it's anything like past years it just distorts numbers to make the situation seem worse than it really is.''
peters said industry performance improved by several measures
he said reactors were available to generate power 61.8 percent of the time last year, compared with 60.3 percent in 1986; unplanned automatic shutdowns fell from 3.9 per reactor to 2.7; unplanned activation of other safety systems fell from 1.2 per reactor to 0.9; and average radiation exposure per employee fell from 622 millirems at boiling water reactors to 521 and from 397 millirems at pressurized water reactors to 368
a chest x-ray may be as much as 25 millirems and typical background exposure in the united states is about 100 millrems per year. the nrc permits civilian reactor employees to be exposed to 5,000 millirems per year
nrc spokesman frank ingraham declined comment because he said the criticam mass report had not reached the commission
mayor carroll thomas said monday he will try to resolve squabbling between two groups of rescuers by appointing a citizens' committee to review proposals for a television movie about jessica mcclure's rescue from an abandoned well
the rescuers formed two associations, one of mostly municipal workers and another of volunteers, to negotiate rights to the dramatic story of the toddler's rescue after 58 hours in the well last fall
the other two committees have indicated that they will yield to (the citizens' committee's) decision,'' thomas said. ``both groups have been saying they want what's best for the community.''
thomas said he hoped to established the five-member committee in the next few days
one group, of more than 30 volunteers, is committed to a movie deal with los angeles producer larry spivey, president of highland communications group inc. kragg robinson, that association's president, said members have signed a contract for an initial $200,000 plus future payments to be divided among the members
the competing 11-member group has not made a deal with a producer, but says it doesn't want to work with spivey
spivey said monday he would talk to the citizens' panel about his contract with the volunteers, but added that the group was not released from its commitment
thomas said the citizens' committee would not give spivey's plans preference over other proposals
jessica turned 2 years old on saturday
her family's attorney, darrell smith, said the family won't stand in the way of a movie being made, but the girl's parents have not taken sides in the dispute
israel has handed over classified documents to independent counsel lawrence walsh for his iran-contra investigation under a cooperation agreement reached after year-long negotiations, an israeli official said monday
in return, walsh apparently agreed to revoke the subpoenas he issued to four israelis who arranged the 1985 and 1986 shipment of u.s.-made anti-tank and anti-aircraft missiles to iran, the official and a u.s. lawyer indicated
he will get what he wants without us having to give up what we wanted,'' said the israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity
melvin rishe, a lawyer representing the israeli government, said ``we have reached terms of how we would proceed, making litigation unnecessary.''
israel's government wanted the subpoenas dropped, contending that all four israelis were acting under its orders and thus were immune from prosecution and questioning by u.s. officials
the agreement with walsh is ``on a government-to-government'' basis, according to israeli embassy spokesman yossi gal, which means any questions for the four must be channeled through official israeli representatives
walsh and the israeli embassy issued brief statements announcing the cooperation agreement, but said the contents will remain classified
the government of the state of israel and the office of the independent counsel have signed an agreement covering the cooperation of the government of israel in the iran-contra investigation,'' walsh said in a prepared statement
independent counsel walsh expressed satisfaction with the agreement and said his office looks forward to continued cooperation with the state of israel,'' the statement said. the israeli statement was almost identical
the documents handed over to walsh include detailed financial and historical chronologies prepared by israel for the congressional iran-contra committees last summer, said the israeli official
when israel gave the chronologies to congress, it stipulated that walsh be denied access to the documents because of his refusal to grant immunity to the four israelis
along with the documents, walsh has also been given written answers to the questions posed last year by the congressional investigators with regard to the chronologies, the official said
the documents are expected to help walsh answer some of his questions about israel's swiss bank account, which handled the funds for the shipments to iran
walsh wanted the information to help him corroborate his case against former white house aides oliver north and john poindexter, as well as businessmen richard secord and his partner albert hakim. all four have been indicted on charges of defrauding the u.s. government through the arms sales and the diversion of profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
last year, walsh subpoenaed israeli businessmen yaakov nimrodi and al schwimmer, as well as former foreign ministry director david kimche and government counter-terrorism adviser amiram nir. nir resigned from his post last week
the agreement was finalized 10 days ago by two senior government representatives who held talks in washington with walsh and his staff. the israeli government approved the accord, the israeli official said
the negotiations were difficult,'' said walsh spokesman jim wieghart. ``israel is a sovereign state with certain national security interests, which they have to defend. we recognized that, but on the other hand, we had our needs in this investigation,'' he said
biddy mason, a former slave who became a wealthy landowner and co-founder of the city's first black church, won recognition from civic officials 97 years after her death
she is an example of the courage of black women in the early days of this city,'' mayor tom bradley said during a palm sunday service at mrs. mason's gravesite. ``our young people need to know about her.''
the philanthropist, who helped found the first african methodist episcopal church and the city's first elementary school for black children, was buried in an unmarked grave and nearly forgotten after her death in 1891
bradley and about 3,000 members of the church unveiled a tombstone hailing mrs. mason as a humanitarian
mrs. mason was born a slave in mississippi in 1818 and, with her three daughters, became the property of a mormon family that moved to utah. she and her family later walked to california, where she won her freedom in 1856
a midwife by trade, mrs. mason accumulated vast amounts of land, often as payment from clients
when i was going through school, we never talked about biddy,'' said linda cox, a mason descendant. but her 9-year-old daughter, cheryl, came home from school one day recently and said: ``mommy, part of our family is in the history books,'' mrs. cox said
interest rates on short-term treasury securities were mixed in monday's auction, with the rates on three-month bills declining while rates on six-month bills increased
the treasury department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.69 percent, down from 5.76 percent last week. another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.0 percent, up from 5.96 percent last week
the rates on three-month bills were the lowest since they averaged 5.65 percent on march 14. the six-month rate was the highest since these bills averaged 6.03 percent on feb. 16
the new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 5.85 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,856.20 and 6.27 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,696.70
in a separate report, the federal reserve said the average yield for one-year treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 6.77 percent last week from 6.63 percent the previous week
jury selection began monday in the political extortion trial of sam steiger, an ex-congressman and former aide to gov. evan mecham
steiger, 59, was charged last fall with one count of theft by extortion, accused of trying to influence the vote of a member of the state board of pardons and paroles
judge ronald s. reinstein of maricopa county superior court told prospective jurors that the trial probably would last until mid-april
steiger is accused of having told parole board member ronald d. johnson in an oct. 1 telephone conversation that unless he voted against a motion that day seeking the resignation of parole board executive director patricia costello, he would lose his position on the parole board or as a part-time justice of the peace
johnson voted with three other board members to oust ms. costello, who had steiger's and mecham's backing, and she stepped down that day
the next day, steiger allegedly sent johnson a letter saying johnson's permission to serve as a part-time justice of the peace was revoked and also that he could be fired from the parole board if he defied the order
a key to the prosecution's case will be three tape recordings of telephone converstations with steiger. reinstein ruled last week that prosecutor michael cudahy, an assistant state attorney general, could use the tapes
defense attorney thomas karas had argued against their admissibility, saying that they were secretly taped in calls to steiger at his home in prescott and therefore violated his privacy
steiger, who was paid more than $77,000 a year as a special assistant to mecham until his resignation nov. 9, faces two to five years in prison if convicted of the class four felony
until he resigned about a month after his october indictment, he served as one of several top aides to mecham, who took office in january 1987. editing throughout to shorten.</note>
an angry and bitter william stern testified monday that baby m should be kept from her biological mother for several years to protect the child from emotional harm and exploitation
stern, testifying in what is expected to be the final legal chapter of the 2-year-old dispute, characterized surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould as untrustworthy and capable of undermining his relationship with the child, legally known as melissa stern
mary beth will do anything and say anything to get her way,'' stern said in 2{ hours of emotional testimony that ended with him crying
the hearing, expected to last several days, was ordered by the new jersey supreme court in its landmark feb. 3 decision that declared surrogacy-for-pay illegal and restored mrs. whitehead-gould's parental rights, but left intact a judge's order awarding custody of the child to the sterns
stern and his wife, elizabeth, of tenafly, decided to have a child through a surrogate mother because they feared mrs. stern, 42, who suffers from a mild form of multiple sclerosis, would suffer complications during pregnancy
mrs. stern testified the possibility of both sides cooperating in the future was remote
we don't share common values with mary beth, we don't think about things in the same way and we don't react to situations in the same way,'' mrs. stern testified. ``we are poles apart.''
the sterns are seeking to cut off contact between melissa and mrs. whitehead-gould, perhaps until the child's 10th birthday. mrs. whitehead-gould now visits the child once a week for two hours under supervision at a children's social services center
mrs. whitehead-gould is seeking two, eight-hour weekly visits at her home, later expanded to include weekends, half the summer and some holidays. she was accompanied to court by her second husband, wall street accountant dean gould, with whom she is expecting a child
the sterns agreed to pay $10,000 to mrs. whitehead-gould to bear them a child and mrs. whitehead-gould was artificially inseminated with stern's sperm
after the baby was born _ she turned 2 on sunday _ mrs. whitehead-gould changed her mind and refused to surrender the child
in testimony monday, stern said melissa should be protected, likening her to a sapling that needs to secure its roots
if anything is done to interrupt those roots, i'm afraid melissa does not have much of a future,'' said stern, a biochemist
he said that immediate contact with mrs. whitehead-gould could ``force melissa into the situation where she would have to choose between us.''
stern said he and his wife have formed a warm, loving relationship with melissa. and his wife testified, `to precious little melissa, i know i'm her mother.''
under two hours of cross-examination by mrs. whitehead-gould's attorney, joel siegal, stern said he feared she would exploit the child by writing a book that could lead to a photo of melissa on the book jacket, a film, a videocassette and even a promotional tour for the book
but stern acknowledged that melissa does not seem to have been harmed so far by her contact with mrs. whitehead-gould
his testimony ended with questions from the judge on what religion the child would be exposed to. stern, who is jewish and whose relatives other than his parents all died in the holocaust, broke into tears. he drank a cup of water and composed himself, saying he expected to expose the child to a unitarian church. mrs. stern is not jewish
the drug enforcement administration on monday tested 75 headquarters employees for drugs, marking the start of random drug testing procedures covering all 5,000 of the agency's workers
the dea has been testing agent trainees for drugs since june 1986
the agency has 2,800 agents and 2,200 support personnel
agents found to be using drugs illegally will be dismissed. non-agents in less sensitive positions may face suspension or reprimands for first-time offenses, said dea deputy administrator thomas c. kelly
the agency's office of professional responsibility will conduct inquiries when test results suggest show drug use
all 650 tests administered to the agency's trainees since mid-1986 have failed to turn up any evidence of illegal drug use. color, include gephardt withdrawal, comment, local gop appearance. picks up 13th graf pvs, bgng: reagan's visit</note>
president reagan said monday the american public won't accept trade restrictions and retaliation against foreign manufacturers
reagan, promoting his free-trade stance even in the face of mounting u.s. trade imbalances, warned that a trade bill under consideration in congress could weaken international trading systems and ``require the president to start trade wars.''
i'll veto if i must,'' reagan told reynolds metals co. workers on the eve of a crucial house-senate conference committee meeting on the bill
reagan long has advocated a policy of free trade and fair trade. at the same time, he has resisted protectionist legislation, even as the merchandise trade deficit climbed to a record $171.22 billion in 1987
but in his remarks monday, reagan said the legislation pending in congress would destroy progress that u.s. companies like reynolds have made
the reality is that manufacturing exports are surging and manufacturing productivity is at an all-time high, and rising rapidly,'' reagan said
they've got a trade bill before congress that could squelch productivity, destroy american competitiveness and make all their doomsday myths a reality,'' he said, noting that his critics have been ``predicting economic disaster,'' although the economy is in the 64th month of recovery from the recession of 1981-82
i think the american people have decided that one great depression is enough, and they aren't going to give the trade demagogues a second chance,'' reagan said
protectionism isn't just bad economics _ it's bad politics,'' the president said
he pointed to the march 8 super tuesday presidential delegate selection contests and said ``those who had predicted that protectionism would be embraced in the south were proven wrong.''
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., who did poorly in the march 8 delegate selection contests throughout the south, had made the nation's trade woes an important part of his campaign. gephardt announced monday he was ending his bid for the democratic presidential nomination
a half-dozen demonstrators protesting u.s. policy in central america greeted reagan outside the reynolds plant. when he arrived in the plant's parking lot, he was cheered by several hundred employees and family members, many of whom waved small american flags
during his tour of the facility, the president walked past huge rolls of aluminum, bound up in spools like thread. at one point, he put on safety glasses and sat down at a console that operated an aluminum processing machine by remote control
reynolds is the world's leading producer of aluminum foil and foil packaging. the company, which operates 55 plants in this country and has operations in 18 others, also has experimented in new products, such as a resealable can that retains carbonation
reagan told a group of workers: ``you're performing miracles. you make me proud.''
during a forum that reagan attended, william o. bourke, reynolds' president and chief executive officer, told the president, ``the time has come for the united states to announce to everyone: ladies and gentlemen, we are back in the export business.''
the president also attended a $2,500-a-couple gop fund-raiser at a surburban hotel. michael salster, a party spokesman, said the president's appearance would add more than $50,000 for the party's coffers
reagan's visit took place as a house-senate conference committee prepared to meet tuesday to work out compromises in their widely varying versions of a 1,000-page trade bill
reagan objects to many provisions in the trade bill, including an amendment named for gephardt that would require the president to reduce ``excess and unwarranted'' surpluses run up by japan and a few other countries in trade with the united states. if negotiations failed, the president would be required to use import curbs to lower the surpluses at a 10 percent annual rate
the president could waive such action if he found it contrary to the national economic interest or if the offending country were wrestling with serious debt. but critics say the plan is a long step toward protectionism and invites retaliation against u.s. industries
in his speech, reagan said the bill's mandatory retaliation provisions could ``require me and future presidents to take actions that would be in direct violation'' of the general agreement on tariffs and trades
you may have been reading lately that the trade bill is making good progress _ that a lot of protectionist provisions have been jettisoned,'' he said. ``and there is some truth to that. but there's a long way to go before the legislation does more good than harm to the u.s. economy.''
only wholesale elimination of the objectionable provisions will produce a bill i can sign,'' the president said. ``i won't let them destroy the american growth economy. but i'd rather work with congress to bring about not just an `acceptable' bill, but one that genuinely improves our current law.''
reagan made no mention of the united states' status as the world's largest debtor nation _ it was the world's largest creditor when he took office _ and instead pointed to figures showing last year's gross national product growth as being 4 percent
the u.s. merchandise trade deficit in 1987 totaled $171.22 billion, a record. the trade deficit was $12.44 billion in january
the january report represented a slight setback after two consecutive monthly improvements and reclaimed some of the gains won from surging exports at the end of 1987. ^police break up anti-noriega protest</head>
police and soldiers using shotguns, rubber truncheons and tear gas broke up a march monday by thousands of opponents of panama's strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega
meanwhile, a general strike that has closed down an estimated 90 percent of panama's industry and commerce entered its second week
ignoring an order to disperse, a crowd of more than 10,000 cheering people began walking toward the capital's central business district monday afternoon
minutes later, a tanker truck equipped with a turret over the cab sped through the line of march, spraying hundreds of people with a choking mixture of water and chemicals that sent them fleeing into side streets
behind the truck charged police and soldiers firing birdshot and beating people with 18-inch-long rubber truncheons
as people fled the scene in panic, they left central avenue littered with their shoes. reporters saw at least two people trampled in the rush, including a woman who suffered a compound leg fracture
before the march began, lt. col. virgilio mirones of the panama defense forces urged the protesters to disperse
we don't want to fight with the panamanian people,'' the officer said through a megaphone. ``we want to fight the united states.''
but the swelling crowd jeered at him, shouting, ``join us, join us'' and ``noriega must go.''
the united states has called for noriega's ouster since he was indicted in florida in february on drug-trafficking charges. the defense forces chief has said he is innocent
the reagan administration has also imposed a number of economic sanctions on panama and supported efforts by former president eric arturo delvalle to freeze panama's deposits in u.s. banks
monday's demonstration was one of the largest in months. like others, it was smashed with drill-like precision. an hour after it ended, squads of soldiers had occupied every major intersection and most streets in the city
the mayors of panama city and one of its largest, poorer suburbs had warned protesters not to violate a ban on demonstrations that ``subvert public order.''
in a communique published in state-run newspapers on monday, the mayors said the ban imposed oct. 19, 1987 was still in effect
the papers also carried a statement from the principal pro-government political party calling for a protest rally in front of the u.s. embassy later monday
the rule seems to apply to one (protest) but not the other,'' said jose faundes, the secretary of the panamanian human rights commission
since the last major demonstration on march 16, soldiers in full combat gear have patrolled the streets
the cash-short government issued checks monday to its lowest-paid retired public servants living in panama city and colon, those whose semi-monthly pension benefits come to $150 or less
those living in other cities and retirees whose benefits total more than $150 every two weeks were told they would be paid later in the week
many, however, were skeptical, noting that government offices normally closed during the end of holy week. even some who got paid were less than happy
things in panama are not good,'' said mariela sanchez, a former government secretary who received her full $36 pension check. ``we have some money today, but what about next time?''
an estimated 55,000 people normally receive government pensions, but there was no official estimate of how many got paid monday
the 15,000 members of panama's defense forces did not receive their wages last week and the government apparently doesn't have the cash to meet a $33 million payroll for some 130,000 civilian workers later this week
the government earlier had indicated it would make at least partial payments to all of its retirees, but that plan apparently was put aside
banks were closed on march 3 after a run on deposits triggered by the dismissal of delvalle by the national assembly, dominated by noriega supporters
attorneys for delvalle, who still is recognized by the reagan administration as panama's president, managed to freeze millions of dollars in government funds on deposit in u.s. banks
the civilian chief of state hand-picked by noriega, manuel solis palma, told delegates at a ``solidarity with panama'' conference monday that washington's actions constituted a ``total, brutal and shameless aggression.''
this treacherous attack is not only an attack on our country, but on all the small and humble countries of the world,'' solis palma told the representatives of populist or leftist political parties from about 20 nations
wyatt earp is causing a ruckus in his hometown six decades after his death, as politicians and descendants of the legendary lawman quarrel over where he was born
small-town politics is fueling the dispute, with both sides lining up support from elderly cousins of earp, a survivor of the 1881 gunfight at the o.k. corral
this is a political vendetta against me,'' said robert matson, a former city council member whose successor has contested the pedigree of a house matson and his wife, melba, own and operate as the wyatt earp birthplace and museum in this town of 10,700
shortly after george morris, 45, took over matson's council seat earlier this year, he spearheaded a move to change the site's billing
the sign that proclaimed the house earp's birthplace was ordered changed to simply say, ``wyatt earp museum.''
i think it's a super idea to promote a wyatt earp museum,'' morris said. ``but i don't want to see history passed down that's wrong. i consider myself a historian and i've researched it along with some other people and we can shoot too many holes in the matsons' theory.''
matson, a 61-year-old school teacher, contends the move to discredit the building's history was prompted by less-than-pure motives
george morris is a former sixth-grade student of mine. he's got a house on the national historic register and maybe he doesn't want us to get ours on it. why he's led such an active opposition to us is mysterious to me.''
morris dismisses the accusation, saying he has ``no reason to have any grudges against the matsons.''
neither side has positive proof
there are no county records, photos or deeds to pinpoint the spot where virginia earp gave birth to her fourth child, wyatt, on march 19, 1848
the matsons have lined up several earp cousins to defend their claim that earp was born in the small, two-story frame house they bought for $4,000 in 1986 in this wind-blown prairie town, 16 miles east of the mississippi river and about 190 miles north of st. louis
morris has countered with earps of his own, as well as a monmouth college professor and a local newspaperman. his side contends the matsons' house didn't exist at the time of earp's birth, and that he was born either in the family homestead nearly a mile away or in a different house a couple blocks away
effie earp cramer, 81, one of the matsons' supporters, blames the controversy on a reporter who was preparing a story on the matson house as the earp birthplace in 1956. when he got scooped by a rival, she says, he wrote a story saying the birthplace was two blocks away
but weldon earp, 76, said he's ``seen research that shows the house where wyatt was born was moved from its original location two or three times.''
earp was a peace officer in the wild west. in 1879, he went to the booming silver camp in tombstone, ariz., and became a deputy sheriff of pima county. later, he served as a deputy u.s. marshal and rode stagecoaches to guard express shipments
in 1881, he and two of his brothers took part in the famous battle of the o.k. corral against the clanton gang
thousands of meter readers, cashiers and other utility employees are looking out for the welfare of many of illinois' 1.8 million senior citizens by volunteering in a program called ``gatekeeper.''
many are isolated and there's no support system around to notice if they are having problems. gatekeepers can link them into the aging network,'' said jeanne blackman, consumer advocate at the department of aging, which runs the community-service program
the backbone of the system is utility-company workers _ cashiers, customer service representatives, maintenance crews and meter readers
we teach them how to recognize signs that an older person needs help and give them the telephone numbers to make anonymous calls to local agencies or the state department of aging,'' said department spokeswoman jan costello
the result?
when an illinois power co. worker noticed rags were being used to plug holes in the windows of a madison county home, he alerted social workers
the residents were provided with a heater and blankets, with follow-up under a weatherization program
bill mcpherrin of galesburg, a 22-year ip veteran, became an active gatekeeper the first day he learned of the program
i thought there was a terrific need for it. we're in people's homes and we see all types of living conditions,'' mcpherrin said
illinois power, northern illlinois gas co., central illinois public service co. and several rural electric cooperatives participate in the program, and more than 6,000 utility workers have been trained to notice signs of trouble
we feel it has worked exceptionally well,'' ms. costello said. ``it's an easy program to operate and very cost-effective.''
state officials have asked illinois bell and springfield's municipally owned utility to participate and are awaiting responses
officials want to work any kinks out of the program before extending it to commonwealth edison co., the state's largest electrical utility, which serves 3 million northern illinois customers, ms. blackman said
all 2,600 cips employees are being trained as gatekeepers, said spokesman ed mcdowell, adding the utility views the program as a way to promote good will
it's a win-win situation from our company's perspective,'' he said. ``we see it as an opportunity to help cips customers and get information (about government sevices) that is useful in our own lives
we are the eyes and ears for government agencies.''
gatekeepers have been operating since last fall in some areas of illinois. similar programs are in place in more than half of the other states, said don kent, a washington spokesman for the u.s. administration on aging
the first female member of the friars club of beverly hills filed a sex discrimination complaint monday because she is being denied use of its health club
obviously, such second-class citizenship within the club could deter many women from joining,'' said attorney gloria allred, noting she pays the same dues as male club members
the fight for women's equality will not end until women are permitted both in the board rooms and the steam rooms,'' she said
the state board of equalization can disallow business tax expenses at private clubs that discriminate under a rule that took effect jan. 1. equalization board member conway collis said he wanted to inspect the friars club facilities this week
when allred became the friars' first female dues-paying member in its 32-year history in may, she was greeted warmly by comedian and friars president milton berle. frank sinatra and dean martin are also members, and president reagan is a past president
the friars club is primarily a theatrical social club
in january, allred asked friars officials about arrangements for women wishing to use the sauna, steam room and whirlpool. there are four women in the club, but allred is the only one who wants to use the health club
there is no legal requirement on the part of the club to afford you the use of the health club facilities,'' friars club legal chairman william sarnoff said in a letter of reply
there was no immediate comment from the friars club on monday, and a message was left for sarnoff at club
china announced monday a major reorganization of its top bureaucracy to cut the state's role in direct management of the economy, eliminate 10,000 jobs and modernize operations
state councillor song ping, head of the communist party organization department, said 14 ministries under the state council will be abolished, one will be reorganized, and 10 new ministries will be set up
the state council is equivalent to china's cabinet
song told a meeting of the national people's congress, china's legislature, that the reorganization will mean a net reduction of five organs under the state council, and is to be accomplished within three months of approval by the present session of the congress
the reorganization will lay the groundwork for further restructuring of the state council, song said
he said the government will no longer manage enterprises directly, as it has under soviet-style central planning. government departments instead will be responsible for general planning, finances, supervision and regulation
the changes, according to song, will be aimed at overcoming such problems as inefficiency, overstaffing, overlapping functions, overly rigid low-level management, insufficient overall control and lack of clarity about duties
he said the the staff directly under the state council will be reduced from 50,000 to 40,000
the 10,000 people to be pared from state council payrolls will be transferred to units handling taxation, finance, prices, auditing, supervision, statistics and law enforcement. many will join companies and institutions engaged in information, consultancy and research, he said
the national people's congress, which convened last week, is also to pass a law guaranteeing the rights of factory managers to run their plants without undue interference from the government
the 10 new units to be created are the ministries of personnel, labor, materials, transportation, energy, construction, aeronautics and astronautics industry, water resources, machine building and electronics and the state planning commission
the planning commission will be comprised of the present planning and economic commissions. song said the commission will be in charge of formulating china's economic and social development strategies and will no longer be involved in direct management of trade and industrial operations
economic expert yao yilin, vice premier and head of the present state planning commission, is expected to head the new, more powerful commission
the labor and personnel ministry will be split into two ministries, with the new personnel ministry in charge of introducing a civil servant system
the new transportation ministry will combine the ministries of railways and communications and the state air transport control administration
the proposed energy ministry was described by song as a superbody encompassing the work of the ministries of the coal industry, petroleum industry and nuclear industry
xinhua news agency, the state news agency, will become a separate institution under the state council. bodyguards</head>
suspected communist rebels on monday attacked a mayor who is related to president corazon aquino, killing seven of his bodyguards and wounding him, police said
it was the bloodiest attack in the capital area since guerrillas took up arms against the government 19 years ago
mayor prospero oreta of suburban malabon suffered three gunshot wounds in the mouth, chest and arm, police said. he was reported to be out of danger after surgery
oreta, 45, is a brother-in-law of rep. tessie oreta, sister of mrs. aquino's assassinated husband, former sen. benigno s. aquino jr
hours after the attack on oreta, assassins shot dead the brother of a prominent leftist politician. the leader said he may have been the intended target
also monday, communist rebels killed a bus driver and wounded his wife in suburban pasay city, authorities said
the killings occurred as military units around the country were on full alert in anticipation of stepped-up rebel attacks marking tuesday's 19th anniversary of the 24,000-member new people's army. the group is the military wing of the communist party of the philippines
communist rebels have been blamed for killing more than 150 policemen and soldiers in the manila area since last year. the rebels recently announced plans to intensify the killings, which in the past have been limited to one or two victims at a time
mrs. aquino, in a statement, said she was dismayed by monday's violence
i have always asked our people to resort to the ways of peace,'' she said. ``my hope is that as democracy in our country gains a strong foothold, violence and terror will gradually rescind.''
oreta and his bodyguards were attacked as they traveled in two cars bound for a flag-raising ceremony at malabon town hall two miles away. police cpl. mario odulio said oreta's ambushers used ak-47 and m-16 automatic assault rifles as well as 9mm and .45-caliber pistols. they escaped in a van and a jeep
local news reports said that shortly after the ambush, a man called manila police to claim responsibility on behalf of the alex boncayao brigade, the leftist rebel unit operating in the capital. but armed forces spokesman col. oscar florendo said police had not established the call's authenticity
florendo said the military was investigating whether the ambush on oreta was in retaliation for the slaying of leftist youth leader lean alejandro in september. he lost to mrs. oreta in a hotly contested congressional race last year, and leftist groups had linked the oreta family to his murder. the oretas had denied any connection
seven hours after the oreta ambush, three men in a car shot and killed the brother of jose castro, vice president of the manila chapter of the leftist people's party. he said he may have been the intended victim, and he added he had received death threats since alejandro's death
thousands of cable car fans cheered monday as a parade of the cars, decorated like floats with balloons, daffodils and streamers, proudly lurched along powell street in celebration of the line's 100th birthday
costumed characters portraying cable car inventor andrew s. hallidie and other historical figures rode the 14 cars in the parade under arches of balloons strung across powell
west german tourist manfred himpil climbed aboard a cable car for the first time
they're wonderful, really wonderful, just marvelous,'' he said. ``when the streets end in the heavens, then comes another view.''
mayor art agnos proclaimed the day ``freidel klussmann day'' in honor of the late neighborhood activist who helped save the cable cars from bus advocates in the 1940s
they're out of doors and they're open-air seating, and i love the history behind them,'' said san franciscan gail hansell, 26, watching the parade atop a hill with a dramatic view of downtown san francisco and the bay on a warm, windy morning
they're romantic as well because they are old and they are a tradition. they are a beautiful way to see the city,'' said hansell
police chief frank jordan estimated the crowd at the parade at nearly 3,000
the powell street line, which began service in 1888, carries about 41,000 passengers a day on 3{-mile panoramic rides over hills with views of alcatraz, fisherman's wharf, chinatown, union square and market street
powell street also is the line where operator carl payne has delighted visitors for 26 years with his cable car bell-ringing, livening the foggy evenings with cheery melodies
it's great to be part of this celebration. it's really special,'' payne said, adding jokingly, ``i'm hoping to be here at the 200-year mark.''
the powell street line, which like all cable cars is owned by the san francisco municipal railway, was built by the ferries &amp; cliff house railroad co. and became part of the city's united railways system in 1902
most of the tracks were destroyed in the great earthquake and fire on april 18, 1906, but since electric streetcars could not climb powell street, the united railways restored enough of the track to use 27 of the powell cars unharmed in the fire
a navy jazz band led the procession, while gripman payne, the nine-time champion bell ringer, clanged dixieland melodies in the lead car
in their heyday, cable cars operated along eight lines. the only survivors today are the the century-old powell street line, a newer powell line that branches onto another street, and their sister california street line, whose 100th anniversary 15 years ago set off a two-week party
the rattle-trap cars, propelled by a cable under the street, rumble along at 9{ mph and lack the comfortable seats and space of modern buses. but they were saved in the 1940s after a campaign by klussmann, and a court once declared illegal a 1956 attempt to radically modernize the cars. in 1964, they were named the united states' first moving national historical landmark. party</head>
port-au-prince, haiti (ap) _ an opposition leader was arrested in connection with an explosion at a bridge and two americans staying with him are under house arrest, according to party and other reports monday
joseph douze, second in command of the centrist christian democratic party, was arrested saturday and charged in the explosion march 22 under the croix des bouquets bridge, party leader sylvio claude said. the blast caused no damage or injuries
claude said douze, a physician with dual haitian and american citizenship, had been planted in the party by the government and he had been expelled
douze, provisional vice president of the party, was shown on government television saturday night during an army search of his home
nancy horn of wells tannery, pa., and james gunnels of macon, ga., told the associated press by telephone they were friends of douze's staying at his home in thomassin, outside port-au-prince
ms. horn said she was an associate of douze and had been in haiti since 1967. gunnels said he was a visiting businessman
the officer who directed the search of douze's home said on television sunday the americans ``have a certain responsibility in the affair,'' but did not elaborate
u.s. embassy spokesman jeffrey lite said consular officials had been in contact with the americans. lite said they were forbidden to leave the house, but he did not know whether they would be formally arrested
anaise chavenet, spokeswoman for the information ministry, told the ap the americans were under surveillance, not house arrest, while the army investigates whether they were involved in the bombing
both americans denied knowledge of the explosion
i know nothing about this affair,'' gunnels said. ``i was just a guest in his home for a few days.''
according to ms. horn, douze is in his mid-40s and spent several years in the united states during the duvalier family dictatorship, which lasted from 1957 to february 1986
claude accused president leslie manigat's government of planting people in his party with instructions to discredit and destroy it. claude, a protestant clergymen, was one of the four most popular presidential candidates in nov. 29 elections that were suspended because of violence
in its report sunday, television nationale said douze was arrested for possession of detonators, wiring for explosives, a remote control detonating device and automatic rifles
jocelin brochard, a former army corporal and the christian democrats head of security, and two women were arrested last wednesday in connection with the bridge explosion
several sticks of dynamite, two assault rifles and a large bag of marijuana were found on the roof of the women's home in bel-air, a port-au-prince slum, police said
brochard said on state televison that douze supplied the weapons
claude denied knowing brochard or douze were involved in the bombing, and said some party members who advocated violence had been expelled in the past
a kansas firm has been licensed to market a genetically engineered vaccine to control pseudorabies in swine, a contagious disease that can be deadly to newborn pigs, the agriculture department said monday
the vaccine will be marketed by syntrovet inc., lenexa, kan., said james w. glosser, administrator of the department's animal and plant health inspection service. he said the new vaccine is the third live genetically engineered product licensed by the department for pseudorabies vaccination
we have concluded the new vaccine is both safe and effective,'' glosser said. ``our scientists have reviewed and analyzed the procedures used to develop the vaccine, its biological and safety characteristics, and the safety and effectiveness data gathered during field trials in three states.''
further, he said, an environmental assessment concluded that use of the vaccine would have ``no significant impact on the human environment.''
during field trials, the new vaccine was administered to more than 400 swine, including baby pigs, weaned pigs and sows,'' glosser said. ``no adverse reactions were noted.''
pseudorabies, also known as aujesky's disease or mad itch, does not affect humans. although the disease caused an estimated $22 million in losses to the swine industry last year, it is not a public health problem, he said
a suspect in the slayings of five people in a supermarket last year turned himself in to federal marshals monday, authorities said
donnie blankenship entered the u.s. marshal's office in the federal courthouse at midday and said he wanted to have his bond lifted, assistant u.s. attorney frederick buckles said
blankenship was jailed a short time later, buckles said
police began searching for blankenship on friday after a grand jury indicted him and another man on five counts of murder each in the slayings at a national supermarket on the city's north side sept. 4
one suspect, marvin jennings, 27, of overland, was arrested friday. blankenship, 26, of hanley hills, had last been seen friday night in north st. louis
investigators believe two men entered the supermarket after it closed, possibly by posing as a cleaning crew. a security guard was taken by surprise and killed. six other employees were ordered to lie on the floor and were shot in the back of the head. two people survived
until about two weeks ago, blankenship had been jailed since november on a charge of felony possession of a firearm, a .38-caliber revolver believed to be the one taken from the security guard during the robbery, buckles said. buckles said blankenship had previously been convicted of assaulting a postal service employee
blankenship was in custody on the weapons charges until about two weeks ago, when he used his aunt's house to make a $10,000 bond and was released, police said
blankenship was arrested after police found the revolver in the trunk of a car that had been stopped for speeding. the driver of the vehicle said he had bought the gun from blankenship, his nephew, in late september, police said
house speaker jim wright said monday he was unaware that his friend and adviser, richard pena, had tried to sell weapons to the contras through former white house aide lt. col. oliver l. north's secret contra aid operation
i don't know a thing in the world about that,'' wright, d-texas, said when asked by reporters about an arms-sale offer made by pena in august 1986, three months before disclosure of the iran-contra weapons and money affair shut down the north network
wright said if pena was involved in such activity, it was ``at a time when he wasn't directly working with me.''
the speaker has a record of opposition to u.s. military aid to the contra rebels tyring to overthrow the nicaraguan government. he also has been active in working toward a negotiated peace in nicaragua
in an aug. 15, 1986, letter, pena wrote to a front company set up by north's associate, richard miller, offering to procure grenades, bombs, mines and boots from two south american companies
the letter went to world affairs counselors, a cayman islands front company formed by miller and his partner, frank gomez, to handle their contra transactions for north
wright said he first learned of the matter when contacted last week by the associated press, which obtained a copy of pena's letter
he said he knew of no activity by pena that was ``unethical or illegal or at all dishonest.''
he said pena was a friend and ``very knowledgeable person'' whose spanish speaking ability has helped wright pick up conversational details the speaker sometimes misses regarding central american issues
pena has been one of wright's advisers on central america over the past several years and as recently as january was the texas democrat's paid emissary to the region as the warring factions wrangled over starting cease-fire talks, wright aide marshall lynam said. he said pena was on the speaker's payroll for a few days on each of three occasions
pena now works for a lobbying firm, cassidy and associates. his office said he was on vacation and had not checked in for messages as of monday
pena was deposed by the congressional committees investigating the secret sale of u.s. weapons to iran and the diversion of funds to the contras. pena told investigators he contacted miller in hopes of making a deal for part of the $70 million in renewed contra military aid that congress approved in the fall of 1986, according to a capitol hill source who read pena's deposition
the source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the deposition contained no mention of wright or north. pena said he knew miller was involved with the contras
pena indicated to investigators that he thought he could offer the contras a better deal than they would get through other u.s. purchasing routes, the source said
it was unclear why pena would have gone to miller, a non-government businessman, and the cayman company to arrange the deal rather than through u.s. government channels
pena worked as a house foreign affairs committee staff consultant from august 1982 to november 1985, a job for which wright recommended him
one former staff member for the congressional iran-contra investigating committees said the committee staff decided not to pursue the pena matter because it appeared to be an isolated incident, rather than an integral part of the north network
miller pleaded guilty in the iran-contra case, along with conservative fund-raiser carl ``spitz'' channell, to conspiring with north to defraud the government by raising money through a tax-exempt foundation to purchase weapons for the contras
miller worked with north, then a national security council aide, raising private money to help the contras during the congressional ban on u.s. aid
miller's company, international business communications, routed nearly $3 million through the caymans, which was disbursed at north's direction to the rebel effort, the iran-contra committees' report said
north has been charged along with president reagan's former national security adviser, rear adm. john m. poindexter, and two other men with conspiring to defraud the united states of $17 million in iran arms sale proceeds and for operating a secret contra assistance program during the aid ban
the chairman of the alabama democratic party said monday he is exploring the possibility of forming a southern group of uncommitted delegates to endorse an ``electable'' presidential candidate
we've got to keep one eye, if not two eyes, on the november general election,'' said john baker of montgomery. ``i'm tired of the democratic party having a ticket that can't carry but one or two states. i'm embarrassed by losing four out of the last five elections.''
the party chairman hopes to find 50 to 100 southern ``super delegates'' who are interested in making a joint endorsement. unlike delegates elected in the super tuesday primary, the party officials and others dubbed super delegates are not committed to a particular candidate
baker sent letters to alabama's 12 super delegates and to 13 southern party chairman to see if they were interested in trying to make a joint endorsement
it's possible this group could make a commitment at the same time. that would be a tremendous boost to someone,'' baker said. but it's too early at this point to say which of the democratic candidates might be electable in november, he added
the lead-off presidential caucuses received twice as much television coverage as all 20 super tuesday contests this year on network evening newscasts, a media analyst says
robert lichter, co-director of the center for media and public affairs, said the super tuesday primaries and caucuses also got short shrift compared to the new hampshire primary on feb. 16
iowans chose 89 gop and democratic delegates in their feb. 8 caucuses, which were the subject of 105 stories, lichter said. in new hampshire only 40 delegates were chosen, and more than 80 stories were aired
super tuesday, by contrast, had 2,056 delegates at stake but the three major networks ran only 53 stories, lichter said
lichter labeled super tuesday a failure because it failed to shift the focus of attention to the south. ``the media shined a 1,000-watt spotlight on the early primaries and a one-watt flashlight on super tuesday,'' he said
one of the costliest crop pests of farmers and home gardeners may one day be curbed by a natural enemy, a microscopic killer worm that searches the soil for the corn rootworm, the agriculture department said monday
the tiny worm, or nematode, is called steinernema feltiae. after infecting the rootworm, the nematode releases a bacterium that kills the pest. then, said usda entomologist jan j. jackson, the nematode uses the larva's body as a place to reproduce while it feasts on bacteria and larva tissue
about 10 days later, hundreds of new nematodes emerge and start searching for more rootworms
that gives you an advantage over chemical controls,'' he said in a report by the department's agricultural research service. ``a chemical just sits there and waits for the rootworm to come to it. the nematode doesn't wait.''
but jackson found that the nematodes don't persist in the ground long enough to eliminate a rootworm infestation. in one field trial where he works at the department's northern grain insects research laboratory in brookings, s.d., jackson applied 100,000 nematodes to the base of each of several corn plants, reducing rootworm damage by 11 percent
jackson said that is not an acceptable level of control, but he expects further research could lead to protection as good as from chemical insecticides. a separate test with a chemical reduced root damage by 44 percent
rootworm larvae destroy corn roots, and adults feed on the leaves, tassels and ears. jackson said u.s. corn producers spend nearly $350 million a year to fight the rootworms. nematodes probably could be produced at about the same cost, without the risk of chemical injury to farmers and the environment. up 7th pvs `in washington'</note>
the israeli army on monday imposed its broadest restrictions yet on the 1.5 million palestinians in the occupied territories, sealing the regions for three days to combat a plo day of protest
army spokesmen said journalists were being barred from the territories, where 119 palestinians and an israeli soldier have been killed in nearly four months of violence
it is the first such ban since israel captured the west bank and gaza strip from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
under the orders, the 650,000 palestinians in gaza cannot leave their homes and the 850,000 in the west bank will be confined to their villages and towns, the army said
the 65,000 jewish settlers who in the occupied lands will be permitted to move freely
an army statement said the three-day shutdown began at 10 p.m. monday in the gaza strip and 1 a.m. tuesday in the west bank
a military source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said telephone links to the gaza strip also were cut for the three days
another rule bars palestinians from crossing the two bridges over the jordan river, the army said, but incoming traffic from jordan will be permitted. about 110,000 arabs who work in israel will not be able to leave the territories
in washington, the state department criticized israel for sealing off the territories
we regret the decision because of the impact it wll have on commerce, on visits with family members and the press,'' spokesman charles e. redman said
on friday, the department advised u.s. citizens to avoid travel to the areas because of continuing disturbances
the closure followed a mass arrest campaign aimed at preventing violence wednesday, when palestinians mark land day, the 12th anniversary of a 1976 clash between soldiers and arabs over the confiscation of arab land. six palestinians were killed
the palestine liberation organization has ordered widespread protests against israeli troops and jewish settlers
israel's ability to deal with expected unrest on land day is viewed as a major test of the military's muscle to quell the uprising that began dec. 8
the closure ``stems first from our desire to tell the arabs `you decided on land day, so let's have a confrontation. we'll see who wins,''' defense minister yitzhak rabin said on israel radio. ``remember, we have not exhausted every means of control at our disposal.''
rabin said the measures also were taken to prevent arabs from the occupied territories from inciting violence among arabs who live in israel
robert slater, president of the foreign press association, condemned the restrictions and said the group was considering legal action. he said the association had rejected an army offer to allow a media pool into the territories accompanied by a military spokesman
pools are meant for when there is no room for huge numbers of people and there is obviously plenty of room for everybody in the territories,'' said slater, of time magazine
israel's 24-member cabinet authorized the measures during its weekly session sunday, israeli officials said
the purpose is to keep the territories quiet. it is not directed specifically against the press, but we don't want to give the people of the areas any reason for causing disturbances,'' said a senior defense ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
in addition to the new measures, troops have arrested about 550 arabs since saturday, including at least 75 overnight monday in the dheishe refugee camp near bethlehem and the jabaliya camp in gaza, the arab-owned palestine press service said
police spokeswoman ruth lessinger said security was also increased in arab areas of israel, with traffic police summoned for riot duty, all police vacations canceled and 12-hour work days ordered for officers
she said 4,000 extra police would be ready for mobilization wednesday and could be taken by helicopter to trouble spots
left-wing legislator gadi yatziv of mapam said the restrictions were ``the first significant victory of the uprising.''
the arabs have managed to force us to take undemocratic measures and the message we will convey on land day will be more negative than anything else,'' yatziv said on the radio
on the political front, prime minister yitzhak shamir sharply protested a meeting between secretary of state george p. shultz and two arab-americans linked to the plo
we see as very grave the attempts of the americans to initiate contacts with plo members,'' shamir said in an address to israel's 120-member parliament
shultz met saturday with edward said and ibrahim abu lughod, who are u.s. citizens and members of the palestine national council, the plo's parliament-in-exile
a 19-year-old palestinian, meanwhile, died of a gunshot wound to the heart suffered during a clash sunday in the west bank village of salfit, israel radio and the palestine press service said
the senate on monday approved a resolution authorizing the reagan administration to implement the proposed compact of free association between the united states and the pacific trust territory of palau
the voice-vote action sent the measure to the house, where similar legislation has been stalled by an investigation by the interior committee into allegations of governmental corruption in palau
the senate resolution would permit the compact, which would end 40 years of u.s. trusteeship over palau, to be implemented so long as there is no pending legal challenge to a plebescite last summer in the islands
palauan dissidents have talked of filing a court suit challenging the legality of the plebescite in which a majority of voters approved amending their constitution to drop its prohibition against nuclear weapons in palau
leaders of the interior committee have sent congressional investigators to palau to probe allegations that senior palau officials may be involved with the smuggling of southeast asia heroin into the united states
the investigators also are looking into reports that palau officials have have received unjustified payments from a british company that built a power plant for the palau government
the administration, which sees palau as a militarily strategic area, has been pressing congress to allow it to implement the compact so it can get the united nations to cancel the trusteeship imposed after world war ii
under the proposed compact, the united states would handle military and diplomatic affairs for palau, whose ailing economy would get some $428 million in u.s. aid in the first 15 years of the 50-year pact
a federal judge refused monday to stop next sunday's hike in postal rates, ruling he lacked jurisdiction to order the postal service to delay the increase for two months
u.s. district judge charles r. richey ruled that he did not have jurisdiction to rule on a request by trade groups representing mail-order and direct-mail firms for an injunction delaying the imposition of the new postal rates until june 4
but richey said the trade groups could take their complaint to the u.s. circuit court of appeals here
the plaintiffs, including the mail order association of america, the third class mail association and the magazine publishers association, contended that any increase before june 4 was illegal
the suit charged that the postal rate commission calculated the rate hike to take effect on that date and that the postal service lacked authority to charge higher rates before then
the postal service will raise an extra $700 million by raising rates in april instead of june, the lawsuit said
on sunday, the cost of first-class stamps will increase from 22 cents to 25 cents with corresponding hikes for second, third and fourth-class mail. official'. deletes last graf pvs to conform.</note>
the u.s. navy confiscated film from a member of a pentagon news pool in the persian gulf for security reasons, but the pentagon said monday afternoon it was being returned
thomas salyer, a photographer for united press international, said intelligence officers refused to return 36 of 61 negatives he took of an abandoned iranian gunboat seized thursday by the guided missile frigate reuben james in the strait of hormuz
it was the first known confiscation of material from a pool member
u.s. officials had directed earlier that some portions of tape taken by an nbc cameraman in the pool be blocked out. the team later was allowed to dub a version of its own tape with those portions excluded
in washington, the pentagon released a statement monday from the u.s. central command saying salyer's film was being returned
three rolls of film were developed and half of the exposures were withheld from the upi photographer by navy officials after a determination was made at the scene that the information revealed in the film was classified,'' it said
in retrospect, the decision to classify the film was overly cautious. officers at the u.s. central command reviewed the list of materials found on the boat, and have have found no sensitive materials to warrant continued withholding of the film.''
the official concern in both cases was over showing certain artillery shells found in the boat, the serial numbers on its gun _ a 25mm anti-aircraft weapon _ and a large box that was sealed but believed to contain ammunition
the wooden box was not opened aboard the reuben james, and u.s. officers refused to speculate on what it contained
standing rules governing the pentagon news pools provide that all written, audio and pictorial material must be cleared for security by u.s. officials at the department of defense before it can be released and distributed generally to media being served by the pool
this material is scrutinized at the operational level, such as aboard ships, but is not censored. if there is a question concerning security, it is referred to the department of defense
although the system has been in effect for several years, the persian gulf is the first place it has been used for coverage of real military operations rather than maneuvers and exercises
since the news pools were instituted for the gulf in july, there have been several cases in which pool escort officers alerted defense department officials to a potental security problem in written news copy, but in all cases it was cleared by the pentagon as written
the pentagon also has not objected to any audio, video or photo reports obtained by the pool journalists
salyer said he was asked to submit his film for examination by intelligence experts aboard the uss coronado, command ship of the joint task force middle east and its gulf-based component, the middle east force
he said that after three officers had spent several hours examining it, he was told some of the film would be kept because when blown up to larger size it revealed the serial numbers of the gun, or disclosed other valuable intelligence data
salyer, noting that he had earlier been allowed to ship some other film of the boat and the nighttime operation to recover it, said he thought the officers ``overreacted'' in confiscating the second batch of pictures
he said the navy also seemed to be imposing a ``double standard'' on him that didn't apply to others
we were all told in advance that the boat material would be subjected to security review,'' salyer said. ``after looking at the film, they said i could have only a part of it back and i could appeal through the freedom of information act for the rest of it.''
experienced pool participants could recall no previous occasion when any news material was confiscated
maj. barry willey, a public affairs officer assigned to the pool from the u.s. central command headquarters in tampa, fla., said he also did not recall a precedent
willey said the decision to withhold the film was made here because there was no way to get it to the pentagon for review ``in a timely manner.''
ten american and european academics on monday disputed the army account of an incident involving the visitors' tour bus that led to a clash in which israeli soldiers fatally shot two palestinians
the version released by the army spokesman is, to put it mildly, a gross distortion,'' said zachary lockman, who teaches middle east history at harvard university
we're quite concerned about our trip being used as a pretext for what followed,'' he told a news conference about the incident sunday
an army spokesman said sunday that soldiers went to the rescue of an israeli tour bus under attack in the arab town of salfit, 20 miles north of jerusalem
he said the bus driver mistakenly entered salfit, and palestinans stoned the vehicle and then attacked soldiers sent to the scene. the soldiers responded with gunfire that killed two palestinians, he said
on monday, an army spokeswoman said soldiers entered the town becaue of reports of a hijacked bus
they quickly discovered there was nothing wrong and began to withdraw, when the soldiers were attacked by a large group of hundreds of arabs throwing bottles, pieces of metal and concrete blocks,'' said the spokeswoman, who was not identified in line with military regulations
lockman, joined by other other professors at the news conference, said the vehicle was clearly marked as a bus from bir zeit university, an arab institution. he said their group had gone to salfit to talk with palestinians
he said villagers greeted them warmly and the town was peaceful throughout the 30- to 45-minute stay
lockman, who speaks hebrew, said he overheard an army officer at a checkpoint tell his commanding officer by radio ``that we (the tour group) had not been under any threat whatsoever.'' he said an army helicopter flew over salfit during the group's visit
he added that as the bus left the area it went by a force of soldiers heading toward the town
jack taft, a lecturer in peace and conflict studies at the university of california at berkeley, noted that the army frequently bars reporters from scenes of conflict
i think that's the central point,'' he said. ``the army as the sole source of information can fabricate any story it likes.''
u.n.-sponsored afghanistan talks resumed monday, after a weekend recess and word that moscow remains unyielding in the dispute over foreign arms supplies to parties in the conflict
pakistan's chief negotiator said the question of ``symmetry'' _ simultaneous cessation of soviet military aid to the kabul government and u.s. aid to the moslem guerrillas fighting it _ was the final unresolved issue
acting foreign minister zain noorani said that, for ``the united states and pakistan (it) is of major concern.''
it is outside the formal scope of the indirect geneva talks between islamabad and kabul, but the superpowers are the designated guarantors of any peace settlement. the united states has said it will accept that role only if there is a ``balance of obligations.''
speaking to reporters before a formal session with u.n. mediator diego cordovez, noorani said the moment moscow agrees on a symmetrical cutoff of arms aid, ``my pen is with me and i will sign.''
over the weekend, noorani met with special soviet envoy nikolay kozyrev, who has been following the talks from the wings since the latest round began march 2
sources close to the pakistani delegation said kozyrev made clear that moscow remains firm on the arms cutoff. secretary of state george p. shultz, meeting last week with soviet foreign minister a. eduard shevardnadze in washington, indicated flexibility in the u.s. stand
shultz suggested the superpowers agree at least on a temporary freeze or ``something close to it.'' but shevardnadze ruled out symmetry. the soviets reject the u.s. symmetry demand as amounting to interference with relations between two states, noting that moscow and kabul are bound by international treaties
kozyrev reportedly suggested pakistan go ahead and sign the three main accords without waiting for u.s. and soviet agreement on the fourth, spelling out the superpower guarantees
shevardnadze struck that note last week at a washington news conference when he said the ``afghan question can be resolved without u.s. guarantees.''
the text of the peace package, said to comprise about 25 typewritten pages, has been translated and scrutinized by legal experts. noorani says he considers the documents complete. afghanistan was reported still opposed to having the text refer to ``international boundaries'' because of what it considers a border dispute dating to pakistan's independence
sources close to the talks, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they were confident that question could be settled
government, business and labor have agreed to hold the line on wages and prices and extend an inflation-fighting program through may
the so-called economic solidarity pact has been in effect since december and president miguel de la madrid said it seems to be stemming inflation, which hit a record annual rate 159.2 percent last year
de la madrid and representatives of business and labor signed the extension in a ceremony at the presidential palace sunday. he said mexico may soon be able to get inflation down to about 2 percent a month, according to a statement from the presidential office
at the signing ceremony, the president said more must be done to solve mexico's economic problems. besides inflation, those include high unemployment and the second-highest foreign debt in the developing world, $105 billion
there should be satisfaction with what has been achieved so far, but at the same time there should be a recognition that the work ahead will be difficult and complex,'' he said
under the extended agreement, the value of the peso _ 2,280 to the dollar _ and the minimum daily wage of 8,000 pesos, or about $3.50, will remain steady through may
de la madrid's government agreed not to raise the price of goods and services it provides or controls through through that period, and business leaders said they would keep prices steady
the bank of mexico, the nation's central bank, said it would lower interest rates on several financial instruments
last week, the president said a ``minority'' in the private sector had violated the pact. on sunday, he urged violators to follow the example of the vast majority of businesses in honoring the anti-inflation program
gunmen believed to be sikh radicals killed at least 18 people in attacks within a 20-mile radius of amritsar, the sikh holy city, police said monday
they said victims sunday included four members of a hindu family killed in their home and a sikh policeman visiting a village for his sister's wedding
the constable's uncle also was killed
attacks by militants have taken 550 lives so far this year. at least 1,000 people were killed in 1987 by sikhs fighting for an independent homeland in punjab, the only province of india where members of the sect form a majority
most victims have been hindus and moderate sikhs who oppose the militants
police said men with automatic rifles killed four members of a hindu family in manowal, a village 20 miles west of amritsar. a neighbor who came when he heard gunfire also was killed
others slain included seven employees of a brick kiln _ four hindus and three sikhs _ and two sikh members of the marxist communist party
bodies of two other men killed were not identified
officials said they did not know the motives for the killings
sikhs account for 2 percent of india's 800 million people, the vast majority of whom are hindus
amritsar is home to the sect's main shrine, the golden temple, and the center of the militant movement for a separate sikh nation in the northern province, india's most productive agricultural region. sunday</head>
a cold front raced across the rockies and plains states monday, bringing cold and snow to an area that had basked in springlike weather over the weekend. a blizzard hit parts of montana
the temperature early monday afternoon plunged to 33 degrees in pueblo, colo., where a day earlier it had reached 85 degrees. similar bone-chilling drops were reported across a wide region
a blizzard raged across parts of montana during the morning hours. strong winds produced subzero wind-chill readings and poor visibility
before moving out by midday, the storm system also covered roads with ice and left 2 inches of wind-whipped snow in much of utah. a rash of accidents, including a fatal car-train collision, was blamed on the storm there
snow and gusty winds were also reported as far east as the central plains. a high wind warning was posted in the mountains of new mexico, and wind advisories were posted in some texas mountain passes and the mountains of southern california
an advisory for snow was posted for the northern and central mountains and the northeastern plains of colorado, and a winter storm watch was been posted through tuesday morning for northwestern kansas
farther south, the front created some fears of severe thunderstorms and possible tornadoes in parts of southeastern kansas, oklahoma and west-central texas
in northern and central minnesota, the precipitation took the form of a mixture of rain, freezing drizzle and snow, while showers and thunderstorms were numerous across southern wisconsin, northern and central illinois, and northeastern missouri, and from southwestern iowa to north-central texas
heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. est included 0.89 inch at rockford, ill.; 0.85 inch at peoria, ill.; 0.56 inch at madison, wis.; 0.48 inch at dubuque, iowa, and moline, ill., and 0.47 inch at cedar rapids, iowa
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 18 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 92 degrees at mcallen, texas. the early morning low for the nation was zero at yellowstone park
the forecast for tuesday called for showers and thunderstorms in the southern and central plains and the mississippi valley to the great lakes, with snow in parts of northern minnesota and upper michigan. rain showers, with snow in the higher elevations, also were forecast across the pacific northwest into the northern rockies
temperatures in the 30s and 40s were forecast from the northern and central rockies through the northern and central plains to upper michigan, and across northern new england; in the 70s in southern california and southern arizona, and from the rio grande valley of texas to the southern and mid-atlantic coast states; in the 80s in south-central texas and across the florida peninsula, and in the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of the nation. with u.n. activity. picks up 18th graf pvs, in the ... with minor editing to trim</note>
iran said monday its revolutionary guards repulsed an iraqi counterattack in their drive into kurdistan and now hold more than 540 square miles of the strategic region in northeast iraq
iranian gunboats attacked two supertankers in the persian gulf, setting them ablaze. and iraqi-backed opponents of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini claimed several thousand of their fighters overran iranian positions in southwest iran
iraq, which has admitted it has lost ground in the mountainous northeast, vowed to ``destroy the iranian aggressors with all available means.''
baghdad's official news agency said the iraqis fired three long-range missiles into the holy city of qom, 100 miles south of tehran, while warplanes bombed four iranian towns to avenge ``iranian attacks on our cities and border.''
qom is the seat of iran's religious hierarchy and crucible of khomeini's 1979 islamic revolution
tehran radio said 11 civilians were killed in the missile attacks and the air raids on dezful, ilam, borujerd and kuhdasht
iran said its artillery hammered ``military and industrial targets'' in the southern city of basra, shelled daily for more than a month, and five other border towns
if the iranian claim of a major advance into kurdistan is true, it would mark iraq's worst military setback since the iranians fought to within six miles of basra a year ago. iran still occupies land east of the battered city
the iraqi army's al-qadessiyah daily, heightening the belief that the iranians have made gains, exhorted soldiers to ``pour your rage and fire on the heads of the persians who have gone too far.''
the official islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, said the iranians ``fiercely repelled'' a counterattack by iraq's 5th army corps around lake darbandikhan before dawn monday
it gave no indication of further iranian advances in the 13-day-old val-fajr-10 offensive
but it quoted revolutionary guards minister mohsen rafiq-doust as saying in tehran on sunday night that his men have overrun 540 square miles of kurdistan
irna also reported that iranian jet fighters shot down two iraqi warplanes in the battle zone monday
iraqi-backed iranian rebels said their national liberation army launched a major offensive on a 14-mile front in iran's oil-rich southwestern khuzestan province near the town of shush
the rebels claimed in a communique that 15 brigades of its fighters pushed into khuzestan to drive iranians out of positions and threaten a key highway southwest of the garrison city of dezful
it reported heavy iranian casualties with ``a large number of tanks captured.''
irna said iraqi soldiers and ``counterrevolutionaries,'' a usual reference by the iranian media to the rebels, launched a ``futile infiltration attempt'' that was repulsed by the iranian forces. it said 1,000 attackers were killed or wounded
at the united nations on monday, iraq condemned the world body's sending a team to look into iranian charges of chemical warfare and asked it to instead investigate what it said was iranian torture of iraqi pows
in a letter to u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar, foreign minister tariq aziz of iraq said the united nations was ignoring iran's own use of chemical arms and letting iran drag its feet in implementing a cease-fire
in the persian gulf, the u.s. navy completed its 18th escort mission of the year. two kuwaiti tankers reached international waters off kuwait after steaming northbound from the strait of hormuz, the pentagon announced in washington
the united states placed 11 kuwaiti tankers last year under the u.s. flag to protect them against iranian attack
iran attacks neutral shipping in the gulf to retaliate for iraqi raids on its oil intallations
iranian gunboats monday attacked the 337,733-ton danish supertanker karama maersk off the southern emirate of sharjah, setting it on fire, shipping executives reported
three hours later, gunboats attacked the 219,287-ton norwegian-operated tanker golar kansai in the same area and set it ablaze, the officials reported
no casualties were reported on either ship
tehran communiques said the iranians have pushed about 15 miles into northeast iraq and seized the eastern and southern shores of lake darbabdikhan
they were reported to be within 3 miles of an important hydroelectric dam on the southern end of the 10-mile-long lake
the facility supplies most of the power for the region and baghdad, 120 miles to the southwest
richard gephardt quit the democratic presidential race monday, saying ``we lost, no question about that,'' but declaring his party can win the white house in the fall only by picking up his populist economic themes
gephardt, whose campaign faltered after his initial win in iowa's caucuses on feb. 8, said he would file for re-election to his house seat from missouri
i believe that our effort was not in vain _ that we challenged the democratic party and called it back to its central role as an agent of fundamental change,'' gephardt said at an emotional capitol hill news conference packed with journalists and supporters, including many of his house colleagues
gephardt had appealed to workers, farmers and the downtrodden with his theme of ``it's your fight, too.'' he said his drive had brought other candidates closer to his positions on trade and farm policy and would result in a nominee committed to fight for economic justice
that was our message and that is our victory. now that message belongs to all the democratic party. i am convinced that it is ... the only way for us to win in 1988 and beyond,'' gephardt said as his wife clasped her hands and fought back tears
the missouri congressman, also accompanied by his three children, quipped, ``i haven't seen a crowd this large in a long, long time,'' after entering the ornate caucus room and giving a thumbs-up sign to his supporters
gephardt predicted a democratic nominee would be chosen from among those now running but refused to throw his support to anyone. he said he might make an endorsement at a later time
gephardt's withdrawal left jesse jackson just ahead of dukakis in the ap delegate count
most of gephardt's delegates were shifted into the uncommitted category with his withdrawal. but missouri party rules mandate that the at-large and public official delegates are redivided among the active candidates when a contender drops out. that gave jackson at least six more delegates
jackson now has 606.55, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis 605.55, tennessee sen. albert gore jr. 362.8, sen. paul simon 168.5 and uncommitted 515.6, according to the ap count
asked to comment on jackson's candidacy, gephardt replied, ``i believe jesse jackson can be nominated and i think he can be elected.'' he turned down a chance to give advice to the party's other front-runner, dukakis, with whom he had engaged in sharp exchanges of negative tv ads
michael dukakis has sure done a lot better than i did,'' gephardt said. ``i don't think it's my place to tell him what to do.''
gephardt attributed his failed candidacy to a lack of money and said that when he was able to get his ideas across, ``we did connect.'' but he added, ``i have no alibis. we lost, no question about that.''
gephardt's wins in iowa, south dakota and his home state were buried by disappointing showings in more than two dozen other states _ including michigan, where he had said he needed a ``michigan miracle'' last saturday to revive his campaign
with his tough trade stance, the six-term congressman might have been expected to do well in a state heavy with unions and automakers. but he failed to win labor backing and finished a distant third in the michigan caucuses, behind jackson and dukakis
gephardt, a consensus builder in the house, found a niche in the presidential race as an anti-establishment populist. he had a well-honed message and an aggressive television campaign
but gephardt, 47, was hampered by a chronic shortage of cash and by continuing skepticism about his populist challenge to ``the apostles of the status quo.''
as chairman of the house democratic caucus, gephardt was hardly a stranger to the establishment he so bitterly attacked during his campaign. he was also vulnerable because of switches over the years on issues ranging from abortion to reaganomics
the well-heeled dukakis ran pointed television ads, one showing a man flip-flopping through the air and the other a list of gephardt's corporate contributors. sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee not only attacked gephardt on his changes of heart, but adopted his same populist theme
after michigan, gephardt had only 167 delegates _ less than one-third the totals amassed by dukakis and jackson and fewer than even sen. paul simon of illinois, who didn't compete on super tuesday
last year, gephardt's poll showings in iowa had been in the single digits until after christmas, when he began running tv ads. among them was his famous ``hyundai'' spot alleging that a $10,000 chrysler k-car would cost $48,000 in korea because of trade tariffs
trade experts challenged the accuracy of the ad, but that didn't dilute its impact in iowa. the tv drive, combined with the grass-roots network gephardt had doggedly built over two years, propelled him to victory in the feb. 8 caucuses
later that month, gephardt won the south dakota primary largely on the strength of an ad charging that dukakis was ``one of the biggest tax-raisers in massachusetts history and saying dukakis' idea of helping farmers was telling them to grow belgian endive
gephardt formally declared his candidacy on feb. 23, 1987, but he had begun campaigning more than a year earlier. his last campaign speech was in milwaukee, before wisconsin democrats whose primary is tuesday. ``all things considered,'' he told them, ``i'd rather be back in des moines.''
gov. buddy roemer on monday signed legislation giving him unprecedented authority to cut spending and raise fees to lift louisiana out of a fiscal crisis blamed on the sagging oil and gas industry
roemer, who took office march 15, said his first round of spending reductions would include layoffs. administration spokeswoman sidney coffee said the cuts would not be announced before tuesday
the legislation was adopted in a special five-day session completed saturday
after lawmakers finished their work, roemer said the temporary authority will be tempered ``by my compassion and good sense that they (legislators) will be coming back in three and a half weeks to look over my shoulder.''
in addition to power to cut entire programs and close institutions through june 30, the administration also won the right to raise fees without public hearings or legislative oversight
the governor said he was aiming for $50 million in spending cuts for the remaining quarter of the fiscal year and $22 million in fee increases
commissioner of administration brian kendrick said budget officials worked through the weekend to come up with a list of proposed cuts to present to roemer late monday. ``we're moving as fast as we can,'' he said
kendrick also said work would begin on the new louisiana recovery district, a commission created by the legislature to impose up to a 1 percent sales tax to finance bonds that would pay off the state's $1.3 billion long-term debt
the commission cannot issue bonds or impose the 1 percent levy until the legislature drops the same amount from the current four-cent state sales tax
the commission was set up to get around a provision in the louisiana constitution barring use of an existing source of revenue to pay off a deficit. it also enables the governor to get around a requirement that tax increases receive the two-thirds approval of the legislature
the administration will ask the louisiana supreme court to rule on the constitutionality of the plan. if it does not pass legal muster, the state will use short-term bonds to finance the debt, kendrick said
kendrick also said the short-term notes would be used to help overcome the $200 million cash shortfall remaining for the rest of the fiscal year ending june 30
col. moammar gadhafi said monday he is withdrawing libyan forces from the border with egypt but he did not specify a time frame for the pullback
such a move would represent a conciliatory gesture unprecedented since gadhafi's feud with egypt began 16 years ago
the libyan leader's announcement in this mediterranean city 75 miles west of the egyptian border followed a series of goodwill gestures made by both countries in recent weeks
gadhafi did not say how many troops libya has along the border
i want to emphasize to the egyptian people and army that the libyan eastern military zone (beside the border) will finally be abolished,'' gadhafi told a crowd of 2,500 gathered in tobruk, once a key british base
the ceremony marked the 18th anniversary of britain's evacuation of its military bases in libya
gadhafi said the border forces would be withdrawn ``without us asking for anything in return from the egyptian side,'' and he offered to let egypt verify the withdrawal
gadhafi, who wore a bright red jumpsuit, paused repeatedly during his 1{-hour speech as the crowd chanted ``long live the revolution!'' and anti-american slogans
gadhafi also said libya would not use force to undermine egyptian president hosni mubarak's government or to pressure it to renounce the 1979 peace treaty with israel. egypt is the only arab country to have diplomatic relations with the jewish state
but gadhafi did say monday that egypt had ``abandoned'' the arab world when the late president anwar sadat signed the u.s.-mediated camp david peace pact with israel
western and african diplomatic observers in libya called gadhafi's overtures an enormous change, but said they had been expected
they said monday's announcement reflected gadhafi's confidence in his position at home
in his speech, gadhafi also discussed civil rights in libya. he said arrests should only be made through court order. critics say that under the current system, some libyans are arbitrarily arrested by revolutionary committees
in the past month, gadhafi has made several moves to increase human rights, including releasing inmates at a political prison and calling for the abolition of the death penalty
the egyptian-libyan feud began in 1972 when cairo rejected gadhafi's bid to merge the two countries
egypt blamed gadhafi for a series of terrorist bombings in cairo and other cities in 1975 and 1976, and the two countries fought a five-day border war in july 1977. both have maintained large military forces beside the frontier
gadhafi has ruled libya since a military coup in 1969 overthrew the monarchy
the government said monday it has asked the united states about a missing scientist said to have gone to america with documents about a taiwanese program for developing nuclear weapons
the foreign ministry statement was the first public acknowledgment that taiwan was in touch with washington about the case of col. chang hsien-yi, 45, deputy director of the nuclear energy research center at the military-run chungshan institute of science and technology. he disappeared in january
because many people believe col. chang is in the united states this ministry has contacted the american institute in taiwan several times on this event,'' the statement said
it said american agency told the ministry it had no information on chang's whereabouts but was investigating. the institute oversees u.s. interests in taiwan since diplomatic ties were cut in 1979, when the united states recognized the mainland chinese government in beijing
taiwan newspapers, citing sources they did not identify, claimed chang worked for the cia and fled to the united states with secret information about plans to develop nuclear weapons on taiwan
in recent weeks, officials have repeated taiwan's position that it has not developed nuclear weapons. they say they do not know chang's whereabouts and are investigating his disappearance. update with bush comments</note>
george bush on monday picked up the endorsement of rep. jack kemp, who said of the vice president: ``he's earned it.''
the new york congressman, who withdrew from the race earlier this month after disappointing showings in gop contests, said his endorsement of bush was ``unequivocal'' and that he would vigorously campaign for him
bush said the endorsement ``means a lot to me'' and called his former rival ``a rising star in the republican party nationally.''
kemp, appearing with bush at a news conference as the vice president began a three-day campaign sweep through wisconsin, told reporters that the subject of a possible vice presidential bid did not come up in his talks with bush
bush, asked whether he had considered extending an invitation to kemp to join him on a national ticket, said such speculation was premature
it's too early to get into the vice presidency question,'' bush said. commenting on his recent wins in republican primary races, bush said ``the numbers are strong.''
however, turning to the subject of sen. bob dole's campaign, the vice president said he did not want to say anything that might be construed as an effort to pressure dole to formally withdraw
i'm just going to keep on campaigning. each person has to make that decision on his own,'' bush said
however, kemp said that recent remarks by dole, including a speech earlier monday in washington, during which he thanked his supporters, appeared tantamount to a withdrawal from the race
he talked in such a way to acknowledge his campaign has come to a close,'' kemp said. dole had said last friday that bush's nomination now seemed a ``foregone conclusion.''
later, bush told an invitation-only rally in a high school in cedarburg, wis., that ``i don't put too much stock in the polls, but they do look good.''
still, he told his audience, ``i will not project an arrogance, i will not project overconfidence.''
he said kemp's endorsement was ``good, because what we want to do is to have this party unified, together, so we can whip the democrats.''
one of the best things that happened to me was getting my brains kicked out in iowa,'' bush added. ``everybody had me dead and buried. we were resurrected right there in new hampshire. so people say now things are going pretty well for you, and they are.''
kemp said that at the time he entered the gop race, ``i believed i was the best candidate for republican conservatives. the voters believed otherwise.''
turning to the democratic race, bush expressed admiration for the growing strength of jesse jackson
the man's racking up delegates, and that's how you get elected,'' bush said. ``what he has done is very admirable. he hung in there. he's doing very well by taking his case out to the people.''
bush said that despite the numbers on the republican side, he wasn't taking anything for granted
i don't want to project that it's all over,'' he said
kemp told the news conference: ``the time has come for all republicans to unite behind this man who has been a fine and loyal vice president.''
as one involved in the friendly competition, he's earned it,'' kemp said. then, turning to bush, kemp said: ``you can count on jack kemp in '88.'' suggesting senate call the trial without hearing third charge, senate leaders' response. no pickup.</note>
an angry gov. evan mecham took offense during his impeachment trial monday at a prosecutor's comparing his actions to embezzlement
i resent so highly the word embezzlement in my presence. i'm insulted by it,'' mecham declared, ignoring orders by arizona chief justice frank gordon to refrain from commenting beyond answering questions
gordon, who already had ruled the question irrelevant, admonished mecham again, telling him, ``i hope you believe the rules are for you, sir, as well as everybody else.''
mecham responded hotly, ``i have seen no witness who has been insulted as i have been.''
the outburst came after house prosecutor william french tried to compare mecham's loan of $80,000 to mecham's auto dealership from a protocol fund to a bank officer ``borrowing'' money from a bank vault and later replacing it
that doesn't make the bank official any less guilty of embezzlement, does it?'' said french, citing mecham's repeated references to the fact that his dealership paid back the loan with interest
defense attorney jerris leonard objected, and gordon sustained the objection
mecham, who began his second round of testimony friday and completed it monday, is charged with misusing state funds by loaning the $80,000 to mecham pontiac. the charge is the second of three against him
as he left the stand, he suggested the senate drop the third count _ that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan _ and judge him right away on the first two
in response to a question from a senator on how he thought they should proceed, mecham said he wouldn't mind if they decided to ``call this game at the end of six innings'' and forget the last charge
he cited the effect of the hearing on his april 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the campaign loan
outside the senate chamber, majority leader robert usdane, who like mecham is a republican, said the chances of dropping the third count were ``about as good as me going out and jumping off the highest building i can find.''
he called the loan concealment charge ``one of the most serious allegations that was made by the house.''
mecham also asked that the senate at least postpone hearing the third count until after his trial. but minority leader alan stephens said that's as likely as ``as jimmy carter being elected president of the united states again.''
in his testimony monday, mecham maintained the loan was secure with his company and a good investment for the money, which originally raised by his inaugural committee
french, in a series of hypothetical questions, suggested mecham felt the money belonged to him, not the state
could you have used the $80,000 to put a swimming pool and tennis court in the back yard of your house?'' he asked mecham
i probably could have done it if i'd invited all of the legislators and cabinet officers to swim once a month,'' mecham said with a smile. he then added, ``i shouldn't jest with you on these ridiculous questions.''
however, he conceded that under his theory he could have loaned the money to his wife for whatever she wanted to spend it on as long as it was paid back with interest
mecham also testified he could not recall whether his then-chief of staff, jim colter, or anyone else advised that the loan was politically unwise
we're all good monday morning quarterbacks,'' said mecham, ``and everybody decided it was a stupid thing to do after the fact.''
the protocol fund was set up after a state law barred use of the funds to pay off mecham's campaign debts. the prosecution claims the money became a public fund for state promotion. mecham claims it remained private for use at his discretion
the 63-year-old mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, in previous testimony denied a charge that he tried to thwart investigation of an alleged death threat on a grand jury witness
besides the impeachment and criminal trials, mecham also faces a recall election may 17
in other developments monday, jury selection began in the political extortion trial of sam steiger, an ex-congressman and former mecham aide. he resigned after being charged with trying to influence the vote of a member of the state board of pardons and paroles. day</note>
progress toward solving the dispute over participation of u.s. contractors in japanese construction projects was reported monday night as the two governments scheduled a third day of negotiations
u.s. deputy trade representative michael b. smith and ichiro ozawa, deputy chief secretary of prime minister noboru takeshita's cabinet, agreed to meet again tuesday after sessions last friday night and most of monday
there has been significant progress but we do not yet have an agreement,'' said smith's spokeswoman, kelly winkler. both smith and ozawa planned to consult their governments before tuesday's talk, she said. the japanese embassy said the talks were marked by both progress and continung problems
ozawa arrived last week and started formal negotiations friday in hope of averting further u.s. reprisals for exclusion of american builders from the multibillion-dollar japanese public works boom
congress late last year barred japanese firms from u.s. federally-funded public works because of lack of reciprocal access for american companies. during his white house visit in january, takeshita promised to seek a solution but negotiations on both sides of the pacific failed to produce it. the united states was reported on the verge of initiating a formal unfair trade action
ms. winkler said monday's progress came both in defining the japanese public works projects to which u.s. bids would be admitted and in clarifying the bidding procedure
a brother of former president chun doo-hwan has been summoned for questioning tuesday about a multimillion-dollar scandal in a semiofficial development agency he once headed, prosecutors reported
kang won-il, the prosecutor in charge of the case, and his assistants said monday that chun kyung-hwan, 46, and three of his aides were to be questioned about the alleged embezzlement of up to $14 million from the seemaul (new community) development program
kang said investigators have uncovered evidence linking chun kyung-hwan, a younger brother of the ex-president, with $9.3 million of the funds
opposition leaders have called for investigations of other members of the chun family
saemaul was founded in 1971 to promote urban and rural development. chun kyung-hwan, appointed by his brother, headed the agency from 1981 to 1987
he has been accused of using his position to obtain donations, sell influence and divert government funds to invest in profit-oriented projects
prosecutors said that last week investigators found about a dozen secret bank accounts the younger chun used under false names
scores of government officials have been questioned in the case, but prosecutors said most would face minor reprimands and not criminal prosecution
opposition leader kim young-sam demanded monday that the investigation be expanded to cover all allegations of corruption involving the administration of ex-president chun. he was in office from 1980 until last month when roh tae-woo was inaugurated after winning the presidential election in december
the administration should not be allowed to terminate the investigation of chun kyung-hwan's scandals,'' kim said in announcing his candidacy for next month's national assembly elections
protests about the saemaul case intensified after chun kyung-hwan, using a false name, flew to osaka, japan, on march 18. he returned to korea two days later for questioning
the government probe of the scandal is seen by some political observers as part of an effort by roh to discredit the former president and his supporters, who allegedly were attempting to maintain power within the government
roh, a former general who helped put chun in power with military backing, promised during the presidential election campaign to root out official corruption. brother</head> accounts of resignation. pick up 5th graf pvs: caracol had said...</note>
attorney general alfredo gutierrez marquez resigned after it was reported cocaine traffickers used an airfield at his brother's ranch, a source at the president's office said monday
the source, speaking with the condition he not be identified, said president virgilio barco accepted the resignation
radio stations rcn, caracol and todelar had earlier reported the attorney general's resignation
both the president's press office and attorney general's office had declined comment when asked about a report sunday night by the intervision television news program. the report said a 5,000-foot runway used by drug traffickers was owned by libardo gutierrez marquez, the attorney general's brother
the source in the president's office told the associated press late monday that in his letter of resignation, the attorney general said his brother did own a farm that news reports said had a runway used by drug smugglers
caracol had said earlier the attorney general resigned shortly after a confiscated drug plane was stolen march 1 from a military air base and landed at the runway, but the later radio reports said he quit on monday
the government of colombia has been at virtual war with drug traffickers, who have killed a justice minister, an attorney general, several judges, two newspaper editors and scores of policemen and soldiers
intervision said the runway in question was used by planes belonging to pablo escobar, branded as a leader of the medellin cartel
the cartel smuggles most of the cocaine reaching the united states, according to the u.s. drug enforcement administration
the united states asked for extradition of escobar and four other men named as members of the medellin cartel. medellin, a city in northwest colombia, is where most of colombia's purported drug traffickers live
the runway is on a farm near medellin next to property belonging to escobar, intervision said
the army last year seized a twin-engine propeller plane, an aerocommander, used for drug trafficking. the plane was stolen from an air force base on march 1 and landed at the runway owned by the attorney general's brother, intervision said
it said the air force tracked the plane by radar and strafed it, other aircraft and hangars. two days later, army bulldozers destroyed the runway
news media have said the attorney general suggested that the government try to reach a truce with drug traffickers
last month, at a dinner with foreign correspondents, gutierrez was asked if he thought the government should try to reach a truce with the drug traffickers
gutierrez said that would be up to the president and that his job is to follow the president's orders
the president says the government will not surrender in its war on drug trafficking
in a raid last week on a country estate owned by escobar, the army said it found tape recordings linking drug dealers with someone close to the attorney general's office. the army gave no details
the escobar home was one of five homes belonging to drug trafficking suspects where the army in the last two months found arsenals that include u.s. military assault rifles, submachine guns, shotguns, pistols, ammunition, hand grenades, stolen license plates and army and police uniforms
two of the homes were raided sunday, the army said in a news release
a group calling itself the organization of arab guerrilla cells claimed responsibility monday for a gun and grenade attack which badly injured an italian pilot at bombay airport in india last week
we claim responsibility for the attack launched against a group of zionist pilots working at the italian airline (alitalia) at bombay airport,'' said a typewritten statement from the previously unknown group, dated march 26
the arabic-language statement was received monday by reuters news agency through a courier service in mostly moslem west beirut
last friday, an arabic-speaking man who gave his name as abbas mohammed ali shahadi shot and seriously wounded an alitalia pilot aboard an airport bus
bombay police said the gun jammed after three or four shots and shahadi jumped off the bus and tossed two grenades at two off-duty policemen. the grenades failed to explode and the two officers chased shahadi and caught him
the italian embassy in new delhi said police had not determined the gunman's nationality or motive. police said he gave them only his hame and no identity papers were found on him
the attack was in retaliation for the frantic campaign waged by the zionists and imperialists against the arab nation,'' the statement said
the breakaway palestinian faction, fatah-revolutionary council, hinted last month it would retaliate for a life sentence passed by an italian court on its leader, the notorious abu nidal, in absentia
abu nidal, whose real name is sabri al-banna, and a top aide were convicted of a 1985 terrorist massacre at a rome airport. the lone survivor of the four-man attack, the only defendant in custody, was jailed for 30 years
a judge made creative use of the state's victims compensation law monday and ordered a heroin dealer with extensive real estate holdings to pay $2 million in restitution toward drug rehabilitation programs
supreme court justice lewis douglass said he reached the figure by multiplying the cost of drug rehabilitation by the number of addicts agapito lopez could have supplied with the six ounces of heroin seized when he was arrested
douglass said in a telephone interview he believed it was the first time a state law allowing restitution for crime victims was used in a drug case
defense attorney frank ortiz said he would appeal the order. he argued that when legislators approved the restitution law, they were thinking of crimes in which there is a specific victim, like robbery or rape
he also argued that the law requires a hearing to be held for any payment more than $10,000
lopez, 44, was convicted in 1987 of drug sale and possession. he is serving a 25-year-to-life sentence imposed by douglass last year
according to the judge's calculations, if the six ounces that were seized when lopez was arrested in 1985 had made it to the street, and each addict bought 20 bags of heroin, the six ounces would have gone to about 900 addicts
douglass said he contacted drug rehabilitation agencies to find what the cost of the least expensive treatment would be and was told it was $2,400 annually for outpatient care
he said he will ask mayor edward i. koch to designate a drug rehabilitation agency to receive the money
lopez sold 2,200 bags of heroin to an undercover officer for $26,000 and was arrested after the officer arranged for another sale, according to nancy young, a spokesman for brooklyn district attorney elizabeth holtzman
at that time, officers confiscated the six ounces of heroin and seized $440,000 in cash from his apartment
young said lopez owned at least three houses in two boroughs of new york city and a car dealership and other real estate in puerto rico
he also had bank accounts with $60,000. the district attorney's office will seize the assets needed to meet the restitution, young said
jesse jackson said monday he expects democratic leaders to embrace him as the nominee if he wins the most pre-convention delegates because ``i would have earned it from the people.'' democrat richard gephardt ended his candidacy, and republican ex-candidate jack kemp climbed on george bush's bandwagon
as democratic leaders wrestled with the implications of jackson's overwhelming weekend victory in michigan, gephardt left the race for the democratic presidential nomination at a capitol hill news conference
it's been said the opera isn't over until the fat lady sings,'' gephardt said. ``last saturday in michigan i think i heard her walking to the microphone.''
abc news, meanwhile, reported that republican bob dole was set to drop out tuesday. the report cited campaign sources, and could not be immediately confirmed. dole has acknowledged bush is the almost certain nominee, and had been expected to withdraw soon
one consequence of gephardt's withdrawal was to edge jackson ahead of massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the ap delegate count by one slim vote
most of gephardt's delegates were shifted into the uncommitted category with his withdrawal. but missouri party rules mandate that the at-large and public official delegates are redivided among the active candidates when a contender drops out. that gave jackson at least six more delegates
jackson now has 606.55, dukakis 605.55, tennessee sen. albert gore jr. 362.8, sen. paul simon 168.5 and uncommitted 515.6, according to the ap count
gephardt was pushed to withdraw by a third-place finish in michigan's caucuses, far short of the ``michigan miracle'' he sought to revive a candidacy that blossomed in iowa's lead-off caucuses but was trampled in the south
jackson and dukakis both campaigned in connecticut on the eve of its primary. gore campaigned in new york and was joining jackson and simon at a debate monday night
dukakis, the governor of massachusetts, was hoping his neighbor state would provide a victory sufficient to ease the pain of his loss to jackson in michigan _ a loss that raised questions about his candidacy and his abilities as a campaigner
at a junior high school in east hartford, a black student asked dukakis why she should vote for him over jackson
i am not running against him and he is not running against me; we are running for the presidency,'' dukakis responded, his answer running so long that he concluded by apologizing
i'm sorry i'm making a speech instead of answering your question,'' he said. ``i hope i've persuaded you. i don't know.''
dukakis borrowed a favorite jackson subject, urging the students to reject drugs. his wife kitty told of her secret 26-year amphetamine addiction
the governor was peppered with questions about jackson but declined to outline any differences between himself and jackson ``because i've never done that.''
i don't think the american people are particularly interested in what i think of the other candidates and what they think of me,'' dukakis said
gop front-runner bush, confident of winning in connecticut, the state he grew up in, began a three-day campaign swing through wisconsin, the next battleground with primaries next week. polls in both states put bush decisively ahead
one of the best things that happened to me was getting my brains kicked out in iowa,'' bush said. ``everybody had me dead and buried ... so people say now things are going pretty well for you, and they are.''
kemp, the new york congressman who abandoned his conservative candidacy two weeks ago, joined bush in milwaukee to offer an endorsement
george bush is going to be the nominee of the republican party and has earned that nomination,'' kemp said. ``the time has come for all republicans to unite behind this man who has been a fine and loyal vice president, and to help him be the next president of the united states.''
bush's remaining two rivals behaved as though their races were over, even though they kept their candidacies alive
dole, all but conceding the nomination to bush, spoke to campaign workers in washington in what sounded like a last hurrah _ though aides said he wasn't ready to withdraw
he said the republcan party ``must cast off the restrictions of privilege and class. we must offer help to those who need it. we must support and defend civil rights.''
former television evangelist pat robertson, with only 17 delegates to show for a campaign that has spent $25 million, took the week off
gore, the tennessee democrat, spoke at a congressional hearing in new york city on homelessness and met privately with mayor ed koch. later he criticized secretary of state george shultz for meeting with ``surrogates'' of the palestine liberation organization
gore said in a letter to shultz he had ``damaged the essential bond of confidence between america and the people of israel.''
jackson campaigned in connecticut and considered the possibility other democrats were confronting _ that he could be the candidate with the most delegate votes and popular votes by the end of the primary season in june
if by the end of california we have the most popular votes, the most delegate votes, becoming the nominee is logical and proper,'' jackson said on abc-tv. ``if i win the nomination from the people, i expect the party to embrace me, and to embrace those principles.''
he questioned the notion that party leaders, believing he cannot win in the general election, might ignore his strength at the convention and give the nomination to another democrat
they would not have given me the nomination, i would have earned it from the people,'' he said. ``there is no small group, no electoral college that can give or take your nomination. if so, why even have a primary. ... let the people speak.''
democratic chairman paul kirk said, ``i wouldn't be a party'' to a stop-jackson movement
i can't imagine that if he runs through the process and comes out on top, they could take it away from him,'' kirk said. ``i would refuse to be part of that.'''
democratic house speaker jim wright credited jackson with demonstrating ``remarkable support and surprising appeal. he is saying things people thirst to hear.''
democratic gov. dick bryan announced his candidacy for the u.s. senate on monday with a swipe at republican incumbent chic hecht
if he was the kind of senator nevada deserves, i would not have made that decision'' to run, said bryan, who is in the middle of his second four-year term
the 50-year-old former attorney general has won praise for his opposition to the government's proposed high-level nuclear dump at yucca mountain and has held a wide margin over hecht in polls taken over the past year
hecht, an upset victor over democratic sen. howard cannon six years ago, accused bryan of spouting empty rhetoric and added the governor was trying to take credit for the economic benefits to nevada of the ``reagan revolution.''
bryan urged hecht to consider a lid of about $2.5 million on spending, calling high-budget campaigns ``perhaps one of the great scandals in america today'' and acknowledging he couldn't match the $5 million to $6 million hecht has said he could raise
bryan plans to release a financial report next week that will show he has raised $1.1 million so far
bryan upset republican gov. robert list in 1982 and was re-elected in 1986 in a landslide over patty cafferata. at the time, detractors said he would be merely a ``caretaker'' governor while he prepared to run for the senate
he was born in las vegas, graduated from the university of nevada-reno and earned a law degree from the university of california hastings college of law
bryan served terms in the assembly and state senate before becoming attorney general in 1978
greece said monday it rejected american protests over a construction freeze at the four u.s. military bases here while talks proceed on the future of the installations
government spokesman yiannis roubatis said greece stood behind a september 1987 decision to ban new building and repair work for the duration of the negotiations
roubatis said u.s. ambassador robert v. keeley this month renewed a request that projects involving security and living quarters improvements go ahead. he said keeley cited a 1983 greek-american operating agreement, arguing such projects didn't require greek authorization
roubatis on sunday confirmed greek newspaper reports that state department officials in washington had protested the freeze
greek and u.s. officials are negotiating a new bases agreement that will replace the 1983 accord after it expires at the end of the year
socialist premier andreas papandreou has said a new agreement must be approved in a greek referendum before it is signed
the bases, two near athens and two on crete, have been operating since the early 1950s
iraq on monday condemned the united nations' sending a team to look into iranian charges of chemical warfare and asked the world body to instead investigate what it said was iranian torture of iraqi pows
in an angry, 15-page letter to u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar, foreign minister tariq aziz of iraq said the united nations was ignoring iran's own use of chemical weapons and letting iran drag its feet in implementing a cease-fire
the letter, delivered monday by iraqi ambassador ismat kittani, indicated a hardening of positions on both sides in the 7{-year-old war
iran will send an envoy to new york for talks with perez de cuellar this wednesday and thursday on implementing a july 20 security council cease-fire resolution. iraq will send a representative next week. the envoys have not been named
the resolution demands an immediate truce and return of prisoners of war. the united states has urged the council to call for a worldwide arms embargo to force iran to comply with the cease-fire
we ask you urgently and immediately to send a team to investigate the situation of iraqi prisoners of war in iran,'' said the letter
it said 10,000 iraqi pows are being tortured, brainwashed and forced to fight against their country
it said an additional 20,000 iraqis were missing in action and 7,000 more prisoners were registered with the international red cross but were not accounted for
the letter criticized perez de cuellar and some security council members for responding first to the tehran government's complaints about chemical warfare
it branded as ``biased and unbalanced'' the u.n. chief's statement friday condemning use of chemical weapons by iraq
iraq has been condemned by the united nations four other times since 1984 for using chemical weapons. western military analysis say iraq has the biggest chemical weapons armory in the region
the u.s. state department said recently that there was evidence iran may have fired chemical artillery shells into iraq
perez de cuellar sent a team to tehran to visit hospitals and investigate iran's charges that iraq used chemical weapons
the iraqi letter did not confirm or deny use of chemical weapons, but said iraq had the right to defend itself
when each time iran sends hundreds of thousands of people to attack and kill us, can you expect iraq to stand by with folded hands when barbarians try to invade?'' it said
the letter said since the war began in september 1980, iran's use of chemical weapons has been documented _ ``but here there is no question or quick response by the secretary-general to investigate this or any aggression by iran.''
aziz protested that last friday that the united nations only deplored the ``war of the cities'' when iraq fired missiles at tehran in retaliation for iran's attacks on basra and baghdad
he said that iraq has accepted the u.n. resolution for a cease-fire, while iran has not explicity endorsed it
bob dole, stopping short of quitting the presidential race in what looked and sounded like a last hurrah for his campaign workers, said monday that the republican party should ``cast off the restrictions of privilege and class.''
the kansas senator made no mention of vice president george bush, the front-runner for the republican nomination, and left the ballroom of a downtown hotel without talking to reporters. he posed for individual souvenir pictures with some of his supporters
abc news, citing sources in the dole campaign, said monday night that dole would drop out tuesday. the report could not immediately be confirmed, however
i have stated repeatedly ... if my campaign did nothing else, it would make clear that our party would never practice the politics of exclusion,'' dole told 450 campaign workers and volunteers
for the republican party to retain the white house, ``we have to convince more women, more young people, americans of every color and ethnic background, the disadvantaged, the disabled, independents and democrats not only to vote republican ... but to become committed party members,'' he said
the democratic party ``has lost its sense of purpose and its sense of direction ... in a mire of special interests,'' but still only 32 percent of americans identify themselves as republicans, he added
to become a majority party, the gop must open its doors ``to new legions of hispanic voters, blacks, asian-americans and other ethnic groups,'' as well as blue-collar workers, evangelicals and other conservatives who voted for ronald reagan, he said
we must cast off the restrictions of privilege and class. we must offer help to those who need it. we must support and defend civil rights,'' said dole. ``our leaders should not be timid about discussing issues that affect the homeless and the hungry.''
dole, joined by his wife, elizabeth, and daughter, robin, said the purpose of the gathering was to thank his campaign workers and to outline his vision for the future of the gop
he joked at the outset that he ``stepped on my own story'' on friday when he acknowledged to reporters that his race against bush appears lost. dole had told the u.s. chamber of commerce, ``it's probably a foregone conclusion what's happening on the republican side.''
mari maseng, a dole spokeswoman, said monday's speech was the last of three dole planned to make to stress key issues in his campaign: foreign policy, deficit reduction and the future of the gop
they're the three issues that have been most important to him in the campaign and why he got into the race in the first place. they're issues that he cares about,'' she said
asked if dole planned to withdraw, she said: ``he'll tell us when he makes that decision.''
dole said that ``i think despite the prospect of tough competition in the next few months, i believe a republican will win in november, but we must keep in mind that we've got a lot of work to do.''
no doubt about it, we've got miles to go before we rest and before we become a majority party,'' he said
two railroad buffs were charged monday with taking a locomotive on a three-mile joyride at speeds of up to 50 mph before it derailed and tipped over, police said
james schroedl, 20, and eric hoyem, 17, were charged with burglary and criminal damage to property, said detective richard obermaier. police located them through a pair of eyeglasses found at the scene, he said
we visited optical stores until we found one that remembered selling them to schroedl,'' obermaier said. ``they were a unique presciption. the kid's almost blind.''
they are railroad buffs. all their lives they've talked to railroad guys and they learned enough to start the engine and get it rolling,'' he said
joyriders boarded the 1,500-horsepower freight locomotive at a chicago and northwestern railroad yard late saturday, said railroad spokesman fred bloedorn
the 25-year-old locomotive, valued at $100,000 to $150,000, fell on its side, and the pair got out and ran off, bloedorn said. obermaier estimated damage to the engine and tracks at $320,000
police found schroedl in a hospital with a leg injury suffered in the derailment. he directed detectives to hoyem, a high school student, said obermaier
obermaier said the joyriders also apparently smashed windows, broke into the yard office and damaged computer equipment as they searched for a key to the locomotive
king fahd said monday saudi arabia would pursue plans to bolster its defenses, dismissing veiled israeli threats to the kingdom after it bought intermediate-range missiles capable of hitting any mideast capital
information minister ali al-shaer quoted fahd as telling his cabinet at a regularly scheduled meeting, ``saudi arabia will go ahead with its ratified defense programs and will pursue its islamic mission and arab duties.''
shaer said the cabinet reviewed ``solidarity'' with the kingdom expressed by most arab governments after ``repeated israeli threats to strike at the missiles that the kingdom has bought to defend its soil and sacred shrines.''
saudi arabia confirmed last week it bought css-2 missiles, with a range of 2,200 miles, from china, but said it would not put nuclear warheads on them
it said it wanted to diversify its arsenal
the kingdom's shipping lanes have been menaced by spillovers from the iraq-iran war. iran accuses saudi arabia of aiding iraq and has made threats against the kingdom
the washington post said last week israel might carry out a pre-emptive strike against the missiles
yossi ben aharon, a top aide to prime minister yitzhak shamir of israel, warned that israel had the reputation of ``not waiting till potential dangers become a reality.''
he was apparently referring to israel's 1981 pre-emptive strike against a nuclear reactor under construction in iraq
saudi arabia, like most arab countries, is technically at war with israel. support received by saudi arabia after the israeli threats included a message from egyptian president hosni mubarak, whose country is the only arab nation to make peace with israel
the state-run newspaper al-ittihad in abu dhabi, capital of the united arab emirates, reported monday that fahd would visit egypt on april 4 to discuss the israeli statements with mubarak. it quoted diplomatic sources in cairo
there was no official confirmation from cairo or riyadh. pick up 10th graf pvs: others in ... and edits to trim</note>
sandinista government and rebel negotiators met for two hours in this border outpost monday to work out details for a 60-day cease-fire outlined in the peace accord they signed unexpectedly last week
they are considering the areas where the rebels, known as contras, will gather during the truce, which is to begin april 1 under the accord signed wednesday night
after about two hours of discussions, the talks were recessed until tuesday, and rebel leaders said there remained obstacles
high-level talks aimed at reaching a more permanent truce are scheduled for april 6 in managua, the capital
the talks were delayed by the late arrival of the contra negotiators, who entered sapoa in midafternoon
representatives from the leftist sandinista government were led by maj. gen. joaquin cuadra, deputy defense minister and army chief of staff
we come with the same spirit, will and decision of the first meeting,'' he told reporters
leading the u.s.-backed contras was aristides sanchez, a director of the umbrella nicaraguan resistance alliance. he told reporters the rebels presented their plan to the government and discussions would resume tuesday
among the rebel representatives were walter calderon, a former national guardsman now known as commander tono; luis moreno payan, who uses the name commander mike lima and is chief of contra military intelligence; luis fley, or commander johnson, chief of rebel operations in northern nicaragua, and diogenes hernandez (commander fernando) whose units operate in central nicaragua
hernandez told a news conference after the meeting, ``i want to tell the nicaraguan people and the world that the (rebel) combatants are not going to put down their arms until nicaragua is a democracy.''
he said defense minister humberto ortega proposed last week that a marxist democracy be established, but hernandez said the contras want ``a real democracy like costa rica.''
cuadra declined to respond to hernandez' remarks and said monday's talks dealt with the ``mechanics of the meeting.'' he said the rebels made no proposals to define the zones where the contras would gather under a truce
we are hoping for an agreement before april 1,'' he added
a temporary cease-fire has been effect since march 21
cuadra said there had been ``violations of the truce of a minor character, but we understand that they are due to the communications problem.''
sanchez said that in a few days the rebels will free the sandinistas they are holding captive. he did not give details
others in the sandinista delegation were deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco and military intelligence chief maj. ricardo wheelock roman
on sunday, the leftist sandinista government fulfilled the first part of the cease-fire accord by freeing 100 political prisoners under an amnesty program. most of them were accused of activities linked to the contras
afterward, interior minister tomas borge called the amnesty ``possibly the beginning of the end of the (6-year-old) war.''
after celebrating palm sunday mass, roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo called the prisoner release ``very positive.''
during his homily, the managua archbishop said the cease-fire agreeement did not mean ``we have already reached peace.''
let us not make a mistake. let us not confuse ourselves. they have only signed a cease-fire,'' he said
under the sapoa agreement, rebel forces are to gather without interference from sandinista forces in specified zones inside nicaragua during the first two weeks of april. monday's talks between special commissions of the two sides could be extended and were to define ``the location, size and modus operandi'' of those zones, according to the text of the sapoa accord
nothing is said in the sapoa agreement about the contras laying down their arms. in past talks, the rebels insisted on keeping their weapons until all provisions of an accord were carried out
once rebel fighters have moved into the truce zones, the contra leadership can send up to eight delegates to participate in national reconciliation talks on april 6
last week's pact provides a gradual amnesty for nicaragua's 3,300 political prisoners; guarantees freedom of expression, and permits all exiles to return home and participate in the political process
if the peace plan is carried out, nicaragua could become the first central american nation other than costa rica to comply fully with the regional peace plan signed by on aug. 7. news digest: managua, nicaragua _ pm-nicaragua, a0439; undated _ pm-political rdp, a0429; washington _ pm-gephardt, a0425; jerusalem _ pm-israel, a0418; panama city, panama _ pm-panama, a0466; hackensack, n.j. _ pm-surrogate mom, a0417; east dubuque, ill. _ pm-killer custody, a0463; los angeles _ pm-another look: aging la, a0406; new delhi, india _ pm-maneka gandhi, a0446
