house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said he expected quick agreement on an aid package that will conform to the requirements of a truce reached last week between the rebels and the managua government
for this (peace) effort to work, there's got to be this aid,'' said adolfo calero, a leader of the rebel political directorate, who met with wright and other congressional leaders on the aid package
the first american troops to return from a training mission in honduras to counter a nicaraguan advance earlier this month parachuted into their home base monday amid cheers of relatives and friends
an estimated 800 soldiers dropped into the sicily drop zone at fort bragg, home of the 82nd airborne division, about 5 p.m. they were met by a military band and commanding generals from the base
earlier in the day, the troops from the 82nd airborne whistled as they boarded seven c-141 transports for the united states
israel has handed over classified documents to independent counsel lawrence walsh for his iran-contra investigation under a cooperation agreement reached after year-long negotiations, an israeli official said monday
in return, walsh apparently agreed to revoke the subpoenas he issued to four israelis who arranged the 1985 and 1986 shipment of u.s.-made anti-tank and anti-aircraft missiles to iran, the official and a u.s. lawyer indicated
he will get what he wants without us having to give up what we wanted,'' said the israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity
supporters of slain indian activist julian pierce said monday they would seek to change state law that would automatically make his judicial primary opponent the winner of the election
backers of pierce, a lawyer who was shot to death over the weekend at his rural home in what authorities called an assassination, decided to seek a special legislative session to allow a substitute candidate in the may 3 primary for superior court judge in racially divided robeson county
state law says if a candidate dies 30 days or more after the filing period closes in that election, the opposing candidate is declared the winner
an angry gov. evan mecham complained from the stand at his impeachment trial monday that he was ``insulted'' by a prosecutor's comparing his actions to embezzlement
i have to make a statement,'' mecham declared, ignoring orders from arizona supreme court justice frank gordon to refrain from comments beyond answering questions asked
i resent so highly the word embezzlement in my presence,'' mecham said. ``i'm insulted by it.''
president reagan said monday the american public won't accept trade restrictions and retaliation against foreign manufacturers
reagan, promoting his free-trade stance even in the face of mounting u.s. trade imbalances, warned that a trade bill under consideration in congress could weaken international trading systems and ``require the president to start trade wars.''
i'll veto if i must,'' reagan told reynolds metals co. workers on the eve of a crucial house-senate conference committee meeting on the bill
a rare first edition of edgar allan poe's first book, a collection of poetry written when he was 14, is to be auctioned by sotheby's, which calls it ``the most exciting book discovery in many years.''
in the 161 years since its publication, only 11 other copies of ``tamerlane and other poems'' have been found. published in 1827 by an obscure boston printer when the poet, short story writer and critic was 18, it could bring as much as $300,000 at auction on june 7
this 12th copy of the book was discovered in a bin of early 20th-century pamphlets on fertilizers and farming machines by a massachusetts book collector while he browsed at an antique barn in new hampshire. the price was $15
on feb. 15, 1986, the amsterdam news printed a front-page editorial calling upon mayor edward i. koch to resign
koch ignored it
he also ignored the next week's editorial, and the one after that. he has now ignored 110 consecutive editorials on the front page of new york's oldest black newspaper, each broadside demanding that he leave office
although saddled with drug problems of their own, a number of asian countries are extending effective help to americans trying to stem the flow of narcotics into the united states, senior u.s. officials say
the united states regards afghanistan, iran, laos and syria as patently uncooperative, but the officials say such countries as thailand, malaysia, burma, pakistan and china, along with hong kong, work closely with americans in cutting asian opium production and tracking drug shipments and dealers
in march, for example, asian-american teamwork led to the arrest in new york city of an alleged drug baron the u.s. drug enforcement administration (dea) says may have smuggled up to $1 billion worth of heroin into the united states
the trail of kon yu-leung, a high-living chinese carrying the passports of at least six countries, reportedly had snaked down from the opium fields of the ``golden triangle'' of thailand, burma and laos through hong kong and on to the united states. the heroin was hidden in shipments of innocent-looking vases, ice buckets and t-shirts
exchanging intelligence and tracking kon and his syndicate for four years were a special thai anti-narcotics unit, the royal hong kong police and some of the 80 dea agents based in asia
in this part of the world countries have acknowledged that they too have an internal drug problem,'' dea head john c. lawn said in an interview during a conference in kuala lumpur. ``they are overt in cooperating so that something can be done not only about the international problem but their domestic one.''
opium-smoking has long been a problem in asia because of the proximity of the drug. but asian nations in recent years have cracked down hard. malaysia, for example, has the death penalty for narcotics offenses
while the greater u.s. anti-narcotics focus is currently on latin america and the carribean, the dea has sharply revised its estimate of southeast asian heroin consumed by american addicts from 18 percent to 30 percent. an additional 37 percent is said to originate from the so-called ``golden crescent'' _ iran, afghanistan and pakistan _ and the rest comes largely from mexico
also requiring shifts of tactics and possibly manpower is dea's assertion that asian syndicates are replacing the mafia as wholesalers of heroin to american addicts, estimated to number about 500,000. according to the dea, about 70 percent of heroin reaching new york city originates in southeast asia, up from 4 percent five years ago. latin america is the chief source of cocaine
the war against drugs in asia works both ways. the united states, for example, helped set up a network of drug rehabilitation centers in thailand that treat some 30,000 addicts a year. the thais in turn have forged a dedicated group of anti-drug lawmen who each year arrest more traffickers and greater quantities of drugs, much of them bound for the united states
we couldn't really operate without the americans,'' said col. viraj jutimitta, widely regarded as one of thailand's best anti-narcotics officers. the united states supplies one of his elite units, ``the dirty dozen,'' with radios, vehicles, travel allowances and even copying paper
the united states also is providing aircraft and herbicides to spray opium fields in burma and pakistan and has helped thailand's largely successful effort to get hill tribes people to substitute coffee, vegetables and other crops for their traditional opium
the u.s. state department spends about a third of its $100 million anti-narcotics budget in asia, maintaining drug coordinators in every embassy and 24 officers at special narcotics units in in thailand, burma and pakistan. somewhat less than a third of dea's current $525 million budget is allocated to asia
cooperation, however, stops at the frontiers of war-torn afghanistan and politically hostile iran and syria. opium and heroin production in communist laos is reported soaring with the connivance of high-level authorities, but u.s. officials say there is reluctance to impose sanctions for fear the laotian government will refuse to cooperate on the accounting of americans missing in action from the indochina war in laos
in contrast, china has moved to forge links with the international anti-narcotics community which has detected new trafficking routes across its vast expanses from the golden triangle
most recently, authorities in china, hong kong and the united states got together to nab a ring attempting to smuggle heroin stuffed inside dead ornamental fish. when the drug-laden gold carp were discovered in shanghai, chinese police contacted american counterparts. the fish were flown to their san francisco destination, along with a senior shanghai police officer, and subsequent arrests were made at both ends of the connection
lawn said thai-u.s. teamwork, which he rated as excellent, was essential since thailand was the main funnel for heroin pouring out the golden triangle, which is formed by the rugged borderlands of burma, laos and thailand
american agents regularly tip off the thais about suspected drug carriers entering their country while thai police officers have followed traffickers to the united states to facilitate investigations and arrests. under a treaty now being considered, the united states would channel a share of assets seized from traffickers to thailand's anti-narcotics program in cases where thai lawmen provided assistance
when u.s. sailors by the hundreds descend on thailand's anything-goes beach resort of pattaya for shore leave, the two sides activate operation ``stable boy.'' a dea agent mingles with the americans while thai undercover police shadow local drug pushers
the leeway american agents have to operate varies among asian countries and there is invariably no power to arrest. but a number of countries give dea the green light to track traffickers and joint operations are mounted. in 1986, a dea agent on the malaysian island of penang posed as a drug dealer to entrap a local trafficker. when sufficient evidence was obtained, malaysian police moved in to make the arrest
in thailand and the united states authorities are now after traffickers behind what the thais say is the world's greatest drug haul: 1.4 tons of top grade heroin seized in february in bangkok, thailand's capital
the drugs, concealed in bales of smoked rubber sheets, were destined for new york city, where their street value, when cut and diluted, would have been more than $2 billion
when the sun goes down and the evening breeze comes up, luanda comes alive to an afro-latin beat called batuque, nightclub doors swing open and angola's 13-year civil war fades away _ until tomorrow
the night, in this capital of 960,000 people south of the equator, is for restaurants, discos, movie theaters, recreation centers and pop concerts _ or even just watching ``love boat'' at home on tv
but tomorrow always comes and one of the world's longest-running ``regional conflicts'' will be back in view again in the steaming daylight _ the pro-soviet, pro-cuban and marxist slogans on the billboards and walls ... the troops back in battle again in the southern countryside against the u.s. and south african-supported union for the total independence of angola (unita) rebels
but the night is for none of that in luanda
at the kizombo recreation and cultural center in the golf neighborhood, a ``sparkling'' tropical night show goes on to the accompaniment of a group called the kiezos
tables are available only by advance reservation and they are for couples only
at the mae negra (black mother) recreational center, a private club in the cuca neighborhood, four women and a man go through a gymnastic dance routine to the throbbing beata of the batuque
after the performance, elegantly dressed couples fill the floor of the cavernous pink, purple, red and blue center to dance to african, caribbean, british and american tunes
between dances, patrons fill their plates at a buffet, which comes with the $8.30 admission, of fish stew, salads, baked beans and tifufuntila, peanut butter mixed with manioc meal and sugar
cold local beer, colas and orange sodas go with it, but champagne can be had if ordered a week or two in advance, the locals say
at discos like the caixote (little box), flamingo and adao, bouncer-doormen size up prospective patrons, letting in the subdued, the well-dressed and the well-known for free
the t-shirt crowd and the unknown usually end up back on the street wondering where to go before the midnight-to-6 a.m. curfew
a recent pop concert at the neves bendinha movie theater sold out before showtime with a seat going for the same $8.30 it cost for an evening at mae negra
on the bill one recent night was an all-star angolan roster including os anjos (the angels), singers minguito, cananito alexandre and ze do pau and the closing act of ``bruxo e a bruxa'' (the male and female witch)
the fare at luanda's 12 movie theaters reflects a diversity that contrasts with the government's public austerity program and ranges from the expected cuban, czechoslovak, soviet and yugoslav films to jessica lange's ``frances'' and ``lonewolf mcquade,'' a chuck norris action movie featuring the texas rangers
for those who stay home, tpa, the state-run television, offers ``love boat'' in english with portuguese subtitles at prime time on sunday night
angola was a portuguese colony for 400 years until 1975 when it gained independence, and the portuguese language is still widely used
even in the southern provinces, close to the war zone, the atmosphere changes when the sun goes down
across the street from the hostal america in kuito, capital of central bie province, some of the 40,000 cuban support troops in angola as well as cuban civilian doctors, teachers and nurses were seen by visiting foreign reporters whooping it up at the local recreaction center
swisttal-heimerzheim, west germany (ap) _ bored with her office job, michaela busemann went off to learn how to shoot a machine gun and become part of an elite group of women breaking into an all-male domain _ the west german border police
the police are responsible for guarding the country's borders, including those separating west germany from the communist east
they also provide security at federal facilities and airports, run patrol boats along the coast in the north and baltic seas, arrest drug smugglers, and are deployed to help state police control unruly demonstrators
since the federal border police force was founded in 1951, only men were permitted to join. but last year the government permitted enlistment of women
on oct. 1, 1987, 31 women chosen from a group of 1,000 applicants began 30 months of training at swisttal-heimerzheim, 12 miles west of bonn
i was working in an office and it was boring,'' ms. busemann said in an interview, ``so i joined the border police because this is much more interesting.''
ms. busemann, who is 20 years old, has her sights set on completing the tough 30-month course, which includes handgun and machine gun target practice
the recruits also regularly train in the martial art of jujitsu, scramble through obstacle courses, and do required conditioning sports such as swimming and long-distance running
in addition they have a full classroom schedule, including law courses and other police-related subjects
asked how she and the other women were accepted by the men, ms. busemann said: ``at first there were a few funny remarks, but that ended quickly.''
ms. busemann is one of 29 women remaining from the 31 that began the training
two of them dropped out because they kept getting homesick,'' said spokesman hartmut ortlepp of border police command group west in bonn
he added that when the border police opened up for women applicants in 1987, ``there were 1,000 applicants for the initial 30 slots offered.''
we culled that down and finally started with 31 last october,'' ortlepp said
west germany's constitution bans women from the regular military services. ortlepp said authorities at first had some reservations about women becoming part of the 20,000-member border police forces
but when the women joined there was a very quick change. the tone of the men has become more respectful, more courteous; it's a change for the better,'' said ortlepp
the average age of the women is between 20 and 21 and they are more mature than the male recruits who average between 18 to 19.''
ortlepp added that political opinion would play a role in what assignments the women receive, but those completing the course would be considered qualified to apply for any border police assignment or advanced training
that could include, he said, joining the gsg-9 anti-terrorist commando squad, the most elite branch of the border police _ ``but that's a political question.''
in october 1977, gsg-9 commandos stormed a lufthansa airliner hijacked by arab terrorists to mogadishu, somalia. the action rescued 86 hostages aboard and resulted in the capture of one hijacker and the death of two others
whatever assignment they get, the women are still enthusiastic about the prospects
it's fun, and there are a lot of new things to do and learn,'' said 20-year-old heike hartmann
a short distance down the forest road, where ms. hartmann and the others were taking part in a field exercise, 21-year-old sybille jakoby from the saarland gave another reason for joining the border police
i always wanted to do police work, but i couldn't join the saarland state police because their minimum height for a woman is 1.68 meters (5 feet 6).''
but the federal border police minimum is 1.65 meters (5 feet 5) and that's exactly what i am.''
thousands of monuments and temples from india's ancient past are neglected and forlorn, slowly crumbling under the onslaught of time, weather and vandals
even the taj mahal, the 17th-century ``monument to love'' that perhaps is the best-known symbol of india's past, is in trouble, its marble yellowing and cracking under the assault of fumes from a nearby oil refinery
decay and disregard also blight such famed monuments as the domed, 12th-century temple to the hindu lord krishna here in puri and the erotic temple sculptures of khajuraho
lesser known but historically no less important monuments suffer even more
hundreds of poor people make their homes or even keep their cattle in mogul tombs. others cart away chunks of monuments to build makeshift houses. marble is scratched with uncaring visitors' names, and peepul or fig trees sprout from cracks in ancient walls
critics attribute the disrepair to a lack of regard for history by most indians, a large majority of whom are concerned with day-to-day survival, and a lack of will on the part of the government
despite protests from environmentalist, the oil refinery still operates near the taj mahal in agra, the magnificent tomb built by the mogul emperor shah jahan for his favorite queen, mumtaz mahal
but even at that, the taj, which attracts 1.4 million visitors a year, is the best preserved of india's monuments, with pollution levels at least monitored and treatment applied to stained marble
the famous erotic temples at khajuraho in central india are one of india's main tourist attractions. but large parts of the temples are covered with moss and algae, and hundreds of smaller statues, awaiting transport to museums, lie exposed to the sun and rain
of the 85 temples built in the years 950 to 1050, only 22 survive. those are protected from vandals and treasure hunters only by a single barbed wire fence
in india, the archaeological survey, a 125-year-old government body, looks after 3,524 monuments of ``national importance,'' and state governments are responsible for 1,500 other historic buildings. but that still leaves thousands of sites, either ancient or notable for artistic beauty, with no protection
we try to maintain what we have in the best possible condition,'' said j.p. joshi, the archaeological survey's director general
we have helped them survive. ninety percent of india's ancient history is our contribution. we have worked hard and quietly.''
but conservation enthusiasts, such as abhishek singhvi, vice president of the delhi conservation society, contend that the archaeological survey and the states simply do not have the money or qualified personnel to look after all the majestic remains
this is not a priority area and funding is a perpetual problem,'' singhvi said
the survey received about $12 million for monument protection in 1985-86, or an average of $284 a month for the maintenance, repair and protection of each of the 3,524 monuments on the list
the conservationists maintain the nation as a whole has become complacent about its history
at puri, one of the four major hindu pilgrimage centers, major leaks appeared in 1966 in the dome of the temple to lord krishna, but 21 years passed before restoration started
the work was blocked by the temple's own priests, who went to court claiming that repair would anger the gods and cause the temple to collapse
local kings had covered the temple with thick plaster to save it from the salty sea breeze about 300 years ago. in time, the plaster began to absorb water, adding enormous weight to the dome, causing cracks and making it vulnerable, said guru prashad mohanty, the temple's chief executive officer
the court rejected the priests' claims last year, and hundreds of archaelogical survey workers now are chiseling away the old plaster, exposing hidden statues and strengthening the temple
not all efforts at restoration have such happy endings
in new delhi, which is a composite of seven cities built by different rulers dating to the 8th century, some monuments simply disappear as modern neighborhoods overwhelm smaller tombs and courtyards
singhvi said a 1913 survey listed about 1,400 monuments in new delhi. of these, 400 have vanished without a trace, most likely torn down overnight by people putting up houses, he added
new delhi, which is a federal territory and not part of any state, has no law empowering it to take over monuments, and it must depend on the archaeological survey for conservation
singhvi and other conservation enthusiasts say one way to raise money to save india's past is to raise admission prices at monuments, maybe as much as five times current levels. he said foreign tourists could easily pay 70 cents instead of the present 15 cents to see the taj mahal
hardly a week goes by without reports in the newspapers of outbreaks of diseases among nigeria's 100 million people _ yellow fever, measles, meningitis, tetanus, cholera, polio, guinea worm and others
hundreds of thousands die each year as a result of infectious disease, malnutrition, poor sanitation and the lack of medical care
the majority of our people do not have access to health care,'' said dr. olikoye ransome-kuti, the minister in charge of health for africa's most populous nation
her task is to improve the health of nigeria at a time when the once-wealthy oil giant has been forced to drastically cut spending
ransome-kuti's approach to an array of problems is nothing short of a complete reform of the health care system and his program has won praise from the world health organization in geneva
our priority is to establish a basic primary health care system,'' he said in an interview. ``if we can put that in place, at least 50 to 60 percent of our health problems will be solved.''
previous administrations spent millions of dollars on large modern hospitals for the major urban areas, but most never were completed because of financial mismanagement and the country's falling oil revenues, ransome-kuti said
nigeria has joined a growing number of developing countries that are switching from large hospitals to a decentralized network of small health centers in rural and urban areas. the centers focus on preventative measures to control diseases before they require expensive hospitalization or reach epidemic proportions
the new program stresses mass immunization campaigns, oral rehydration therapy for diarrhea, africa's largest child-killer, and nutrition, hygiene and family planning education. it also seeks to provide cleaner water and human waste disposal systems
nigeria's predominantly rural population is highly susceptible to outbreaks of measles, typhoid, cholera, and other diseases largely caused by a lack of clean drinking water and poor hygiene. many villagers are suspicious of modern medicine, preferring to visit traditional healers whose treatments often aggravate health problems
the world health organization in geneva once assailed nigeria's health policies but now applauds them
nigeria has a headstart,'' said the organization's representative here, samuel brew-graves. ``it has the leadership and the know-how and is applying it.''
about a third of the nation's local government areas have been given 500,000 naira ($100,000) each to set up community health centers. ultimately all 304 local areas will be included in the program
both rural and urban areas suffer from a high infant mortality rate _ 150 per 1,000 live births in rural areas. three in 10 children die before age 5 in the urban areas, said a 1987 health ministry report
as many as 2,000 nigerian children die daily due to malnutrition, chronic undernourishment and related health problems
urban hospitals are rundown and underequipped to deal with the cities' burgeoning populations. basic drugs are in short supply, and the country's lack of hard currency has made it difficult to buy spare parts for medical equipment
another major problem is the low morale of doctors in the civil service. many doctors in urban areas moonlight illegally to supplement their meager salaries. others remain unemployed rather than work in the rural areas, most of which lack even rudimentary health facilities or basic amenities for doctors' families
ransome-kuti said last year he might be forced to import doctors from cuba and still is keeping that idea alive, despite protests from the nigerian medical association
my aim is to get health services to the people. if nigerian doctors show unwillingness to serve, i'm willing to use health personnel from any country,'' he said
ransome-kuti's younger brother, beko, also a doctor, is vice president of the medical association. he said there should be no need to import doctors
if the amount of money spent on foreign doctors was offered to nigerians they wouldn't be short of people applying,'' he said
the government seems to think patriotism and nationalism are enough to get people to the rural areas. incentives need to be given to attract doctors there.''
but the health minister said it is in his plans to do that, explaining that comfortable housing, electricity, running water and adequate schooling for doctors' children will be provided in rural posts
once these services are delivered, the doctors will find their place in the rural areas,'' he said
today is easter sunday, april 3, the 94th day of 1988. there are 272 days left in the year
today's highlight in history:
on april 3, 1860, the legendary pony express began service between st. joseph, mo., and sacramento, calif. the service would last for only 1{ years before giving way to the transcontinental telegraph
on this date:
in 1776, george washington received an honorary doctor of laws degree from harvard college
in 1783, washington irving, author of ``rip van winkle'' and ``the legend of sleepy hollow,'' was born in new york city
in 1865, union forces occupied the confederate capital of richmond, va., during the civil war
in 1882, the notorious outlaw jesse james was shot to death in st. joseph, mo., by robert ford, a member of his own gang
in 1936, bruno hauptmann was electrocuted in trenton, n.j., for the kidnap-murder of the lindbergh infant
in 1946, lt. gen. masaharu homma, the japanese officer responsible for the bataan death march during world war ii, was executed
in 1948, president harry s. truman signed the marshall plan, which allocated more than $5 billion in aid to 16 european countries
in 1964, the united states and panama agreed to resume recently severed diplomatic relations and seek prompt settlement of the canal dispute
in 1968, north vietnam agreed to meet with u.s. representatives to set up preliminary peace talks
in 1982, britain dispatched a large naval task force to the south atlantic to reclaim the disputed falkland islands, which had been seized by argentina
ten years ago: ``annie hall'' was named best picture at the academy awards ceremony in los angeles. the movie's co-star, diane keaton, was named best actress, and woody allen was named best director. richard dreyfuss won best actor for ``the goodbye girl.''
five years ago: final preparations were being made for the maiden launch of the space shuttle challenger, which was to take four astronauts into orbit
one year ago: stock prices rocketed on wall street as the dow jones industrial average soared 69.89 points, ending the day at a record 2,390.34
today's birthdays: actor marlon brando is 64. actress-singer doris day is 64. actress miyoshi umeki is 59. sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., is 58. actress marsha mason is 46. singer wayne newton is 46. singer tony orlando is 44. former football player lyle alzado is 39. comedian-actor eddie murphy is 27
thought for today: ``time is a circus always packing up and moving away.'' _ben hecht, american screenwriter (1893-1964)
today is monday, april 4, the 95th day of 1988. there are 271 days left in the year
today's highlight in history:
twenty years ago, on april 4, 1968, civil rights leader martin luther king jr. was shot to death in memphis, tenn., where he had gone to support a strike by city sanitation workers. a student of the life of mahatma gandhi and a winner of the nobel peace prize, king advocated non-violent civil disobedience as a way of combating racism. he was 39 years old
on this date:
in 1818, congress decided the flag of the united states should consist of 13 red and white stripes and 20 stars, with a new star to be added for every new state of the union
in 1841, one month after his inaugural, president william henry harrison succumbed to pneumonia, becoming the first u.s. chief executive to die while in office
in 1850, the city of los angeles was incorporated
in 1887, susanna medora salter became the first woman to be elected mayor of an american community when she took office in argonia, kan
in 1902, british financier cecil rhodes left $10 million in his will to provide scholarships for americans at oxford university
in 1949, the north atlantic treaty organization was founded
in 1969, a surgical team in houston led by dr. denton cooley implanted a temporary artificial heart in a 47-year-old patient while awaiting a human donor heart. the patient, haskell karp, died april 8, one day after receiving a human heart
in 1974, hank aaron of the atlanta braves tied babe ruth's home-run record by hitting his 714th round-tripper in cincinnati
in 1975, more than 130 people, most of them children, were killed when a u.s. air force transport plane evacuating vietnamese orphans crashed shortly after takeoff from saigon
in 1977, 72 people were killed when a southern airways dc-9 crashed in new hope, ga
ten years ago: some 2,000 people marched through memphis, tenn., to mark the 10th anniversary of the assassination of civil rights leader martin luther king jr
five years ago: the space shuttle challenger roared into orbit on its maiden voyage. the u.s. government granted political asylum to chinese tennis champion hu na. actress gloria swanson died in new york at age 84
one year ago: during a visit to chile, pope john paul ii denounced torture and pleaded for reconciliation, telling tens of thousands of people in the city of punta arenas, ``you must find concrete means of creating a true culture of peace and harmony.''
today's birthdays: former dance teacher arthur murray is 93. broadcaster john cameron swayze is 82. composer elmer bernstein is 66. author-poet maya angelou is 60. sen. richard lugar, r-ind., is 56. baseball's national league president, a. bartlett giamatti, is 50. actress catherine spaak is 43. actress nancy mckeon is 22
thought for today: ``like anybody, i would like to live a long life. longevity has its place. but i'm not concerned about that now, i just want to do god's will. and he's allowed me to go up to the mountain, and i've looked over and i've seen the promised land.'' _ martin luther king jr. (1929-1968)
