a drug that could save your life may be hiding right now in a bit of ordinary seaweed
so could chemicals that could produce better crops, kill dangerous pests or clean toxic wastes. they just haven't been discovered yet
we're essentially land creatures. that's why we've focused on land plants. but the sea, chemically, is a very different environment, and you will find many new and different things there,'' said kenneth terry, vice president of ocean genetics inc
the young company 60 miles south of san francisco wants to be the first to find, develop and perhaps market some of the potentially valuable products that may be lurking in seaweed and other forms of marine algae
in hundreds of glass dishes and flasks in its laboratories or huge bubbling tanks in seaside greenhouses, ocean genetics is growing, studying and testing more than 300 species of the simple plants
algae, which range from one-celled organisms to large, familiar seaweeds, already are used to make many things, including stabilizers, thickeners and texturizers important in the food and cosmetic industries and gels essential to science and medicine
two of those gels are agar _ the familiar culture medium in petri dishes _ and its purer, electrically neutral form, agarose, which is criticial for many research procedures
there are no substitutes for either, producers are few, and demand keeps growing. that means a profitable opportunity for ocean genetics, which plans later this year to market agar and agarose it's now producing and testing
agar and agarose provide us with the steppingstone i felt was necessary for ocean genetics to find and develop other product lines,'' said company president and founder wayne harvey
those yet-undiscovered products are the primary, though long-term, goal of the company, the company officials said in recent interviews
the highest potential is for pharmaceutical and animal health care products. but i think the potential of agrichemicals, in particular natural pesticides ... and plant-growth regulators also are signficant,'' harvey said
bay venture group, which provided ocean genetics $200,000 in seed capital when it was formed in 1981 and other financing since, is pleased with the privately-held company's progress and is optimistic about the future
it has all the characteristics of a successful business,'' said bvg general partner bill chandler, also a director of ocean genetics. ``i think the company is going to be a major pioneer
and of course, there's a saying that while pioneers get shot in the back, they also get to claim the new land.''
once it identifies new chemicals, ocean genetics will be able to grow the algae they come from very quickly, harvey said
that's primarily because the company combines engineering knowledge with plant physiology and biochemistry and will avoid ``the vagaries of nature'' by raising large monoculture crops of proven plants in indoor tanks, he said
but the process begins in a santa cruz laboratory filled with hundreds of petri dishes and seething carboys filled with large pieces of brown, red and green algae
the specimens, collected all over the world, are cleaned and small pieces are put in the petri dishes, where they grow for several months. then they are transferred to the carboy containers, where for another six to nine months they are kept in purified, nutrient-rich salt water
some of them are just incredibly beautiful. look at the lace of the leaf of this plant,'' said harvey, displaying a specimen whose delicate russet network was revealed by the strong light behind its container
once we have found an organism that produces a product, we do extensive studies ... to find out how we can control its environment to maximize the production and the quality of what we're interested in,'' harvey said
controlling reproduction, screening cells for mutations and cloning are some of the methods the company can use to increase and improve desirable qualities, he added
ocean genetics' first research product, phychobiliproteins, already are being produced and tested. the naturally flourescent chemicals found in certain seaweeds can be used in medicine to tag some types of cells. someday they may replace radioactive tracers now used to study and treat diseases like cancer and aids, harvey said
these little puppies are worth $10,000 to $15,000 a gram ... wholesale,'' he said, holding a test tube of glowing purple liquid
after growing in the carboys, some plants are freeze-dried and sent to one of several pharmaceutical, chemical or biotech companies, which test the samples for possibly valuable substances
but other promising varieties are ``grown up'' and studied further in several stages in computer-controlled tanks inside greenhouses on land the company leases from the university of california-santa cruz, terry said
reaching into one tank, terry pulls out a handful of material that looks like reddish-brown steel wool _ a plant whose origin or possible future use he and harvey good-naturedly refuse to reveal
this is a unique opportunity,'' terry said. ``it's about as if we were able to start over on land. the sea is a whole fresh resource.''
jerry mcdowell makes a whole lot of cents
mcdowell heads the plant where most of the nation's pennies are produced, though the u.s. mint finishes the job by stamping shiny blanks with their slogans and abraham lincoln's profile
mcdowell knows just about all there is to know about the nation's 1-cent piece. he's learned most of it since 1981, when the u.s. treasury department gave up penny production and assigned the task to ball corp.'s zinc products division in greeneville
pennies used to be made almost entirely of copper, but skyrocketing prices for the metal sent the federal government in search of cheaper materials and lower operating costs in the private sector
mcdowell and other ball officials convinced the mint they could do the job in greeneville, and the nation's copper-plated penny over a zinc base was born
they very quietly introduced this thing and nobody much knew there was a change,'' mcdowell said. ``there was one helluva a lot of testing before they switched over.''
the old pennies were 95 percent copper and 5 percent zinc. the new pennies are 97.5 percent zinc and 2.5 percent copper, he said
the mint first wanted to go to all-aluminum, but aluminum was very light and trouble was anticipated with vending machines. federal officials then thought about an all-zinc penny, but zinc is silvery like other coins and tarnishes quickly, mcdowell said
ball came up with the idea to plate zinc with copper,'' he said
the phase-in from old penny to new took a year, he said, with the 42-acre plant shipping new pennies in 1982 for the first time
about 70 percent of the nation's pennies are made in greeneville, or about 8.5 billion blanks under the government's $18.2 million contract with ball for 1988. a much smaller operation in la salle, ill., also makes penny blanks under a small business set-aside program with the government
ball corp. reported net income in 1987 of $66.3 million on sales of just over $1 billion, said tom jenkins, an accountant in ball's muncie, ind. headquarters. that compared with income of $58.9 million on a similar sales total in 1986
the government ships zinc and copper to greeneville and the zinc is melted down, cast at a rate of 35,000 pounds an hour and rolled into thin sheets, coiled 13,000 pounds at a time, then pressed into penny shapes and rimmed before copper is added during a series of electroplate and cleansing rinses
the process takes about two hours, and the longest time spent is electroplating, mcdowell said. each blank penny weighs about 2.5 grams, and 181 pennies weigh a pound as opposed to 145 pennies a pound of the old, mostly copper cents
zinc is less dense than copper,'' mcdowell said
the pennies are turned from a sleek silver to a shiny copper color during their electroplating baths. after they're dried and an anti-tarnish material is added, the blanks are checked for quality before they're shipped to mints in 3,300-pound wooden crates lined with plastic
when they're new, they want them to look new,'' mcdowell said
a federal law prohibits the government from spending any more on making a coin than the face value of the coin, which means pennies must be made with all costs included for less than a cent each
when copper prices went as high as $1 a pound in the early 1970s, the government was spending a full cent per penny to manufacture the coins itself. in the late 1970s, copper cost as much as $1.45 per pound. ball is now making pennies, and they're finished off by the mint, at a total cost of sixth-tenths of a cent, mcdowell said
the mint coins the pennies in philadelphia and denver after they're shipped from greeneville by rail and truck
ball cranked out about 12 billion penny blanks in 1982, the first year of full production, because the government feared there would be a penny shortage when the word got out copper was no longer going to be the primary material
the government ordered so many pennies that year and in 1983 because officials were jittery after people took silver coins out of circulation in droves around 1965, when the mint stopped using silver for dimes, quarters and half-dollars
no similar penny shortage occurred, however, and the government later cut back production in greeneville so the inventory that had built up could be depleted, mcdowell said. penny production has been steady since 1987
the greeneville plant employs about 300 people, with the facility also manufacturing casings for batteries and other zinc-based products
the mint still makes all other coins itself and likely will continue to do so, mcdowell said
security is not extraordinary at the ball plant since the pennies are shipped as blanks, he said. besides, vending machines don't take pennies anyway so criminals aren't much interested, mcdowell said
how are you gonna peddle them?'' he said. ``they're blank.''
the stock market was lower in moderate trading early today, holding steady despite a residue of nervousness left by friday's 45-point drop in the dow jones average of 30 industrials
the closely watched blue chip average was down 9.45 points at 1,969.50 at 11 a.m. est. declining issues outpaced advances by around 10-to-3 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,038 issues falling, only 280 gaining and 370 unchanged
volume on the big board was about 51.1 million shares
traders had been looking anxiously toward today's opening on wall street after friday's tumble, which closed out the worst trading week so far this year
the bearish sentiment deepened overseas earlier today when the dollar came under pressure and stock traders in london ignored a turnaround on the tokyo stock exchange. the financial times-stock exchange index of 100 selected stocks was down 15.1 points, or 0.9 percent, at 1,752.8 at midday. during the morning, it was down 19.5 points
the early decline on wall street is ``sort of a hangover from last week,'' said hugh johnson, a senior vice president of first albany corp. in albany, n.y. ``we've been almost rudely reminded that the market is still on very, very thin ice.''
