live cattle were .03 cent to .28 cent higher with april at 75.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .35 cent higher with march at 82.80 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .57 cent lower with april at 45.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .27 cent to .72 cent lower with may at 56.65 cents a pound
livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on friday
american stores co. today launched its $1.74 billion tender offer for lucky stores inc., a $45-a-share bid that would create the nation's largest grocery store chain if successful
that is correct,'' said american stores vice president michael holt, confirming that the offer to lucky stockholders began this morning. he refused to comment further
lucky, the country's sixth-largest supermarket chain, boasts annual sales of about $7 billion, with 480 stores in the west, midwest and southwest, mostly in california and arizona. american stores, with annual sales of $15 billion, has about 1,700 retail outlets in 40 states, making it the nation's third-largest grocery retailer
lucky officials at the company's dublin, calif., headquarters referred calls to new york spokeswoman lissa perlman. she confirmed the tender offer had begun, saying lucky officials have been reviewing the offer with financial and legal advisers
lucky strongly advises its stockholders not to take any action with respect to the american stores offer'' until the lucky board of directors has a chance to further study the bid and make its recommendation, ms. perlman said
no deadline for a recommendation was given
wall street reacted to news of the bid by sending lucky store's stock up 87{ cents per share to $48.62{ per share at midday on the new york stock exchange. american stores down $1.87{ per share, at $54.75 per share
american stores chairman l.s. skaggs notified lucky stores chairman john m. lillie of the then impending tender offer in a march 21 letter. skaggs said if the offer was successful, he planned to combine american store's alpha beta stores with lucky's operation under the lucky name
the letter praised lucky's management and marketing strategies and invited lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed. lucky's headquarters would remain in dublin, skaggs said
the bid for lucky comes 16 months after a takeover specialist asher edleman dropped his hostile effort to acquire the company. in return, lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills
lucky kept edleman at bay partially by selling off non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures
after the text of the letter was released last week, lucky officials had no comment on the american stores' tender offer except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
american stores last made financial headlines in 1984 when it spent $1.1 billion to take over jewel companies inc., a chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store chain
that acquisition expanded american stores' operations from just over 1,000 retail outlets to its present 1,700. the company has three divisions _ skaggs, which operates supermarkets in the western united states; american superstores, which runs outlets in the midwest and east, and osco drug stores, which has stores nationwide
the company operates stores under the names acme, jewel, star, buttrey, skaggs, skaggs alpha beta, and osco drug
