the supreme court today refused to hear an appeal by companies seeking refunds of new jersey taxes they paid to help clean up hazardous waste
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that could limit the amount of the refunds
the new jersey supreme court ruled in december that the businesses are entitled to only a partial refund if the state legislature does not appropriate enough money to reimburse them fully
the case stems from a dispute over new jersey's so-called spill fund and whether it was preempted by the federal superfund law
the u.s. supreme court ruled in 1986, in an earlier review of the new jersey case, that the superfund preempted _ at least partially _ state efforts to deal with hazardous waste pollution through taxation
the high court said states only may tax the same companies subject to the superfund law for purposes not covered by the federal act
congress then removed the preemption feature from the superfund law to eliminate the potential obstacle to state clean-up programs
at issue in the case acted on today is the size of the refund the companies are entitled to recover for the period before the preemption feature was eliminated
the new jersey supreme court interpreted the 1986 u.s. supreme court rulig to allow the state to retain part of the taxes the companies paid for clean-up costs
the state court said that if the new jersey legislature failed by june to reimburse the spill fund for the full amount of preempted expenditures, the businesses are entitled only to a partial refund
the spill fund was created in 1977, supported by tax revenues that average about $10 million a year
the $1.6 billion federal superfund was created in 1980 and renewed in 1986
seeking the refunds are exxon corp., b.f. goodrich, union carbide, monsanto and tenneco
they said the new jersey court ruling would permit the state illegally to retain millions of dollars in tax revenue
the case is in re exxon corp., 87-1296
there are few disputes more vociferous than those on how uncle sam, along with his nieces and nephews in smaller governmental entities, earn their income and spend their money
every taxpayer has an opinion. every business, too. tax reform and watchdog groups exist in most municipalities. presidential candidates can't steer clear of the subject. congress tinkers with it every year
academics write books about taxing and spending. institutions exist for the specific purpose of studying every detail of every proposal. pressure groups and lobbyists are in a constant uproar about their favorite projects
here's a sampling:
the poor are being nickeled and dimed to death by state sales taxes, says citizens for tax justice. sales taxes are regressive, says the public interest organization's director, robert s. mcintyre
as a share of income, he states, sales and excise taxes take five times as much from poor families _ and three times more out of middle-income families _ as they take from the rich
taxing the poor heavily is both curel and inefficient,'' he says. ``it doesn't produce much in the way of revenues, because the poor don't make very much money.''
progressive taxes, based on the ability to pay, are the answer, he says. he suggests a sales-tax rebate plan to mitigate some of the regressivity of such taxes, which some states impose even on food, gasoline and utilities
the center for the study of economics in columbia, md., pushes what it calls incentive taxes as a way to generate revenue, while simultaneously improving the economic base of a municipality
it's not a new idea, having been proposed many years ago by economist henry george. in fact, some municipalities have accepted the notion, but not enough of them according to the center, which proselytizes with missionary zeal
one of its tenets is that the value of land was created by society and government. nevertheless, taxes on undeveloped land are almost always far below land on which an investor has placed a building
in short, downtown parking lots pay low taxes and contribue minimally to the area's economy in terms of jobs, payrolls and products. but lots with structures on them and job-producing businesses in them are taxed more heavily
they ask if the opposite policy wouldn't be more productive? shouldn't that parking lot be forced to develop itself into a more economically productive role? how better to do it than by taxing it into compliance?
no discussion of spending and taxing could be so boisterous as to drown out j. peter grace, who headed the president's private sector survey on cost control, said by the white house to have saved $40.5 billion in fiscal 1988
now head of citizens against government waste, grace is currently circulating his notions of how uncle sam can reduce the budget deficit by $60 billion a year
he claims, for instance, that $6 billion could be saved in three years by establishing a bipartisan commission to recommend an extensive program of military base closings
an additional $1 billion could be saved over three years, he says, by imposing user fees for non-emergency coast guard services, such as getting a tow if your outboard runs out of fuel
earlier this month, the president's management report said recommendations by the private sector survey led to savings of $30.6 billion in fiscal 1986 and $38.9 billion in fiscal '87, for a three-year total of $110 billion
they still haven't gone far enough,'' said grace in handing congress his new proposals
never at a loss for money-saving ideas is the heritage foundation. this year, as in years before, it is suggesting that big savings are possible by ``privatization'' _ turning various functions over to the private sector
this can be accomplished, it says, by selling off assets such as the federal loan portfolio and the naval petroleum reserve; by contracting out services that it now tries to handle by itself; and by further deregulation
if heritage had its way, public housing would be privatized, a private air traffic control system would be developed, and amtrak, the passenger rail service, would be sold to private operators
american farmers won't get all the new business if japan opens its market to more agricultural imports, japanese commentators said on the eve of a visit to washington by the japanese agriculture minister
if japan can import freely, there is always australian beef, and fruit from other countries,'' which cost less than u.s. products, said mitsuru uchida, professor of political science at tokyo's waseda university
the united states will suffer. people will buy from cheaper places,'' said hirotatsu fujiwara, a political commentator and author
takashi sato, the minister of agriculture, is scheduled to travel to washington on tuesday to seek an easing of u.s. demands for an end to japan's barriers against beef and orange imports
the current four-year agreement on beef and oranges expires thursday. the united states has refused to open negotiations on a new one until tokyo draws up a timetable for a complete end to the quotas. it also has threatened to take the matter to the general agreement on tariffs and trade, an international forum that oversees the trade rules agreed upon by its member nations
in separate interviews, fujiwara and uchida said japan should open its market to imported food. but both expressed doubts over whether ending japan's limits on beef and citrus fruit imports would help reduce the united states' huge deficit in its trade with japan, which reached a record $59.8 billion last year
japan in recent years has bought almost 20 percent of all u.s. farm exports, or nearly $6 billion worth in 1986, according to japanese government estimates. japanese officials say the united states ignores the fact that japan is the world's largest importer of farm products
but over the years, beef and oranges have become a symbolic issue in what the united states sees as japanese foot-dragging in efforts to solve the trade imbalance
japan's politically influential farm groups say their members' livelihood would be threatened by an end to the import barriers. government officials want market-opening steps taken gradually, although opinion within the government and ruling liberal democratic party on how quickly to move still is divided
talks on monday failed to iron out differences
u.s. officials say the barriers mean japanese consumers pay two to four times what their american counterparts pay for beef and citrus fruit
the quasi-governmental livestock industry promotion corp. says american square-cut chuck beef had a wholesale price here of 831 yen a kilogram (about $3 a pound) last month, while a similar cut from australia had a wholesale price of 757 yen a kilogram ($2.74 a pound). retail prices are substantially higher
australia has made plain that it will seek to ensure that any japan-u.s. agreements on beef are not made at australia's expense
under the expiring agreement, japan raised its annual quota for high-grade beef imports from the united states from 31,000 tons in 1983 to 58,400 tons in 1987, while raising its quota on orange imports by 1,100 tons a year
meanwhile, it raised its overall quota for beef imports from 141,000 tons in 1984 to 177,000 tons in 1987
in fiscal 1986, which ended last march, japan imported 188,000 tons of beef _ including 63,000 tons from the united states and 113,000 tons from australia. of its orange imports, 99 percent came from the united states
international business machines corp. leads forbes magazine's list of the nation's most valuable companies for a fourth consecutive year, the magazine said monday
ibm's stock market value at the end of 1987 was $69.0 billion, a decline of 5.2 percent from a year earlier. that was still enough to surpass exxon corp., whose stock market value rose 4.5 percent to $52.6 billion
ibm, the world's largest computer company, has led the forbes list since 1984, when american telephone &amp; telegraph co. fell off the top of the heap because of the breakup of the bell system
among the big movers in the top 10, merck &amp; co. inc., the rahway, n.j.-based pharmaceutical company, climbed to sixth from ninth. ford motor co. ascended to ninth from 15th, while general motors corp. fell to eighth from fifth
stock market value is determined by multiplying the price of a company's stock by the number of its shares
here are the top 10 companies in forbes' market value list, which will appear in the ``forbes 500s'' issue of april 25
1. international business machines corp., $69.0 billion, down 5.2 percent
2. exxon corp., $52.6 billion, up 4.5 percent
3. general electric co., $39.8 billion, up 1.6 percent
4. american telephone &amp; telegraph co., $29.0 billion, up 8.2 percent
5. du pont co., $20.9 billion, up 3.5 percent
6. merck &amp; co. inc., $20.8 billion, up 23.2 percent
7. philip morris cos. inc., $20.2 billion, up 18.2 percent
8. general motors corp., $19.1 billion, down 9.0 percent
9. ford motor co., $18.6 billion, up 26.6 percent
10. amoco corp., $17.8 billion, up 6.5 percent
