a flood of travel scams has pushed two florida legislators to propose a law that would require bonding for travel agents, a plan that gained the support monday of state attorney general bob butterworth
travel agents would be required to register with the state and post bond ranging from $10,000 to $25,000, unless they already are bonded by airline recording corp., under the proposed measure
butterworth endorsed the bill at a news conference at the coconut creek government center
when bogus holidays are offered by deceptive telephone promotions, the reputation of florida as an ideal vacation destiny is damaged,'' he said
his office launched a major investigation of travel scams last june with raids on eight offices. complaints naming more than 200 other travel companies are under investigation
fraudulent travel providers who fast talk customers in telephone promotions are being brought to justice,'' butterworth said
although the bill would add regulation, it has picked up industry support
the professional is concerned to make sure the traveling public does not get bilked, and i think the professional also is concerned he doesn't want the reputation of the industry impugned by scam operators,'' harold berns, a member of the board of directors of the american society of travel agents, said monday
the professional travel agent is more than happy to see this happen,'' said berns, owner of air and sea travel in fort lauderdale. ``we've heard too many horror stories. not only here, but all over the country.''
tobin and weinstein charged tour operators who take money from unsuspecting consumers for trips they will never deliver are a growing problem
a 1985 state law made the fraudulent sale of travel a misdemeanor. but victims have no way of recovering their money without bonding, weinstein said
opposing the bill would ``be like being against apple pie,'' said berns
most of florida's 2,200 legitimate travel agents already meet the bill's requirements by registering with airline recording corp., which requires bonds of up to $50,000 bond
virtually all travel agents who sell airline tickets must register with the corporation, berns said
agents already associated with such a recording association would not be required to register under the bill, weinstein said. but agents already bonded may voluntarily register with the state
failure to obtaing a bond would be a misdemeanor, and the state division of consumer services would have the power to shut down unbonded agencies
new england fishermen returned to port last year with 12 million fewer pounds of fish and shellfish than in 1986 but the value of the catch soared 14 percent to $512.6 million, according to figures compiled by a federal agency
massachusetts led the five states in the region with fishing industries both in total harvest and value, followed by maine and rhode island. new hampshire led connecticut in terms of harvest weight, but connecticut's catch was worth more
gloucester fishermen caught the most fish and shellfish but the value of the catch was substantially below that of new bedford fishermen, whose lucrative harvest of pricey sea scallops made that port first in the nation in terms of catch value for the second consecutive year
the region's 1987 lobster harvest was virtually identical to the previous year, 19.8 million pounds compared to 19.7 million pounds in 1986, but the value of that harvest jumped from $46.2 million to $54.6 million
the preliminary harvest figures were compiled by the northeast fisheries center, a division of the commerce department's national marine fisheries service. the center compiles the data for an annual report on the fishing industry nationwide that the commerce department is expected to release in april
commercial fishermen throughout the region caught 543.7 million pounds of fish and shellfish in 1987, down from the 1986 total of 555.7 million pounds. but because of increased overall fish prices, the catch value increased from $448.9 million to $512.6 million
massachusetts fisherman harvested 256.8 pounds of fish and shellfish in 1987, down from 271.3 million pounds a year earlier. but the value of the bay state catch jumped 14.4 percent from $243.6 million in 1986 to $278.9 million last year
the maine catch of 169 million pounds was up slightly from 168.2 million pounds in 1986, but the value of the harvest increased 22 percent from $108.4 million to $132.4 million
rhode island's catch also remained relatively stable, 100 million pounds in 1987 compared to 101.6 million pounds in 1986, with the value of that state's catch increasing 3 percent from $75.1 million to $77.5 million
new hampshire fishermen caught 9.3 million pounds of fish and shellfish last year, up from 7.9 million pounds in 1986. the value of the harvest increased nearly 26 percent, from $6.2 million to $7.8 million
connecticut had the smallest regional harvest in terms of weight, 8.6 million pounds, but it was worth $16 million, an increase of 2.5 percent from $15.6 million in 1986, when that state's total catch was 6.7 million pounds
in terms of weight, gloucester led the region's major fishing ports with a catch of 92.6 million pounds, followed by new bedford, point judith in narragansett, r.i., portland, me., rockland, me., boston and newport, r.i
new bedford fishermen harvested about half of the 18.2 million pounds of sea scallops caught in new england in 1987, according to fisheries center spokesman ron l. schultz
the average price of $4.42 a pound paid to fishermen for sea scallops was by far the highest of the 14 major species of fish and shellfish harvested in new england waters. the average price paid to fishermen for lobster was $2.91 a pound
the price paid to gloucester fishermen falls far below that paid to their new bedford counterparts because two of the major species harvested by gloucester fishermen, pollock and atlantic herring, net per-pound prices among the lowest of the 14 species
control data corp. will buy a 20 percent stake in silicon graphics inc. for $68.9 million in a step intended to cement their business relationship, the computer companies said monday
minneapolis-based control data said it intended to buy $150 million worth of computer workstations from silicon graphics over the next three years, continuing an arrangement with the mountain view, calif.-based company that dates back to late 1986. the companies will cooperate on developing new workstations
control data will buy newly issued shares of common stock in silicon graphics at a price of $22.50 a share that will represent 20 percent of the company's stock
