the board of directors of federated department stores inc. will move wednesday to end the bidding war for the retailer by acting on the final competing purchase offers of r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. and campeau corp., federated said monday
a committee of federated's outside directors met monday to determine bidding procedures and would inform macy and campeau of those guidelines, federated said in a statement
the board's wednesday meeting was to be held at an undisclosed location in new york. federated has said edward finkelstein and robert campeau, the chairmen respectively of macy and campeau, would be allowed to address the directors
macy and campeau have each offered more than $6 billion to buy federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer. macy's bid has the approval of federated management
in a letter to both suitors, federated said, ``it is anticipated that the board will consider and act on the parties' final bids at a board meeting on wednesday, march 30. federated's advisers will continue to be available to you to discuss all matters.''
federated said last week its board would meet this week to consider campeau's $6.53 billion offer and a $6.3 billion bid from macy
robert campeau, whose toronto-based company has been trying since jan. 25 to buy federated, will address federated's board if invited, ms. frank said
i'm sure he will go. nothing's been firmed up, at this point,'' she said
macy, based in new york, had no comment, said spokesman james fingeroth
federated disclosed last week it was negotiating with macy about an improved macy offer, but said there was no guarantee negotiations would be successful
campeau last week raised its two-step, all-cash offer to approximately $73 a share from $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. campeau offered to pay $82 each for 70.5 million federated shares and $37 for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares in a subsequent merger. campeau also extended its deadline until midnight edt april 4, when macy's offer is to expire
campeau, a development company that bought allied stores corp. in december 1986, also proposed an alternate friendly merger under which it would pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares in a tender offer and $73 for the remaining shares after the merger
macy has offered $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy would exchange shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares
federated and macy have signed a merger agreement under which macy would take over federated in a newly formed, joint company
federated's divisions include bloomingdale's, abraham and straus, burdine's, filene's, foley's, lazarus and rich's department stores; ralphs supermarkets; gold circle discount stores; and main street and children's place specialty stores
federated has also delayed putting into effect, until at least wednesday, a ``poison pill'' amendment to its shareholder rights plan. that would allow shareholders to buy new shares at a steep discount and make an unwanted takeover more expensive. division</head>
the federal trade commission on monday approved furr's inc.'s purchase of safeway's 59-store el paso division
however, furr's must hold the stores separately pending the final sale of 12 safeways in new mexico and texas to jaynes group inc., according to the ftc
the jaynes group is a newly formed corporation organized by former safeway employees. both it and lubbock-based furr's are privately held and did not disclose the amount of the transactions
kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co. of new york acquired safeway in 1986 in a $4.3 billion leveraged buyout to fend off a hostile takeover by the dart group of maryland. it has been selling off whole divisions to pay off its debt
during the four-month ftc review period, furr's operated the 59 stores as an autonomous division
furr's now operates 154 retail grocery stores in texas and new mexico. it also operates two distribution centers and several support offices
the ftc's only objection to furr's purchase of safeway's el paso division was that it would have a monopoly in 12 new mexico and texas cities
furr's reached an agreement with the jayne's group to buy the stores, which are in the texas cities of pecos and fort stockton and the new mexico cities of alamogordo, artesia, clovis, espanola, hobbs, las vegas, lovington, portales, roswell and silver city
stock prices declined broadly today, dampened by new declines in the dollar and lingering anxiety about wall street's own strength
five minutes before the close, the dow jones average of 30 industrials was down 0.50 point at 1,978.45. the broader market posted more substantial losses
stock prices declined broadly today, dampened by new declines in the dollar and lingering anxiety about wall street's own strength
many investors had their new-found confidence shaken late last week, when stocks fell sharply on thursday and friday. the dow jones average of 30 industrials tumbled around 45 points on friday after falling nearly 44 points in the previous session _ sparking fears that today's session could turn into another ``black monday'' akin to oct. 19
but today's decline was tempered by some ``bargain-hunting'' buying at the lower price levels, traders said. they noted, though, that many foreign investors and financial institutions remained on the sidelines
although today's losses were more moderate, analysts said they reflected a bearish sentiment that continues to hang over the market
it will take a while before this blows over,'' said richard schmidt, an analyst for advest inc. in hartford, conn. ``we're testing some lows here.''
the anxiety was deepened today by fresh declines in the battered dollar on world currency markets
we're again hooked to the dollar,'' said monte gordon, director of research for dreyfus corp. ``the market continues to wallow in confusion and uncertainty.''
the u.s. currency was quoted at about 123.83 japanese yen in late afternoon, down from 125.30 yen late friday in new york. the dollar had also retreated to around 1.6563 west german marks from 1.6760 marks
the dollar's slump brought the federal reserve into the market to buy dollars in a bid to support the currency after it fell to around 124.00 yen, traders reported
the financial markets have been ``reminded that stabilizing the dollar is not going to be easy,'' said hugh johnson, a senior vice president of first albany corp. in albany, n.y
traders are anxiously looking toward tuesday's scheduled report on the leading economic indicators for february for a signal on the economy's direction. key unemployment data for march is set to be published on friday, but stock markets will be closed that day in observance of the good friday holiday
irving bank corp., which is resisting a $1.08 billion takeover offer from another banking company, said monday it took additional steps to discourage hostile bidders from acquiring its stock
irving said its board of directors approved an amendment to its share purchase rights plan that would deal with the possibility of a ``street sweep'' under which a bidder who terminates a tender offer then begins buying the target company's begins on the open market or in privately negotiated deals
irving said the provision was adopted to assure that a street sweep would not jeopardize irving's efforts to explore alternatives that would maximize values for its shareholders
bank of new york co. launched a $60-a-share offer of cash and securities last week for each of irving's 18.1 million common shares outstanding
irving has called the offer inadequate, and indicated last week that it was seeking a friendly bidder and exploring other alternatives to thwart the hostile offer
the scrap has attracted an unusual level of attention because hostile takeover efforts are rare in the banking business
a spokesman for bank of new york, owen brady, said his company thought the latest provision adopted by the irving board was illegal and said it was investigating what to do about it
separately, bank of new york disclosed that its chairman, j. carter bacot, asked joseph rice, irving's chairman, in a letter to make sure that bank of new york gets a chance to look at any of the confidential financial information that irving has been sharing with other potential friendly bidders
under the new move by irving, the company's previously adopted share purchase rights plan would be activated if a party who made a tender or exchange offer subsequently bought enough non-tendered irving stock to push its total irving stake to 5 percent or more
if that occurred, each right would entitle its holder to purchase irving stock with a market value double the right's exercise price
bank of new york's tender offer currently is scheduled to expire april 15
steel production rose to 1.996 million tons in the week ended march 26, an increase of 0.3 percent from the previous week's 1.991 million tons, the american iron and steel institute reported monday
the industry's production amounted to 93.0 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 92.7 percent in the previous week
estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 23.725 million net tons, an increase of 33.2 percent from the 17.805 million net tons in the previous year. the steel operations of usx corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a strike during the first month of 1987
production so far this year used 89.9 percent of capacity, compared with 68.0 percent a year earlier
net tonnage by district for the week ended march 26: northeast coast, 291,000; pittsburgh, 204,000; youngstown, 124,000; lake erie, 163,000; detroit, 174,000; chicago, 535,000; midwest, 177,000; southern, 225,000; and western, 103,000
the dow jones average of 30 industrials edged up 0.82 point to 1,979.77
declines outpaced advances by about 2-to-1 on the new york stock exchange
big board volume totaled 142.82 million shares, down from 163.17 million in friday's session
the nyse's composite index was down 0.47 at 146.11
at the american stock exchange, the market value index fell 2.64 to 292.00
u.s. sen. john heinz monday said he will introduce legislation to thwart a hostile takeover of koppers co. by british business magnate brian beazer and the wall street investment bank shearson lehman hutton inc
the pennsylvania republican charged again at a news conference that if a $1.7 billion tender offer from bns inc. succeeded, beazer will gain a monopoly in the various local markets for aggregates, road building materials that include the sand and pebbles added to concrete to make cement
one of the reasons it's attractive to have a stranglehold on the existing aggregates business is that environmental laws are such at the state and local level that you cannot easily open ... a new source of aggregate,'' he said. ``so in effect it is a sellers' market for a very very long time.''
u.s. sen. arlen specter, r-pa., said monday he asked attorney general edwin meese to personally review the koppers case and to respond to the request by thursday
heinz withheld details of the proposed legislation
to reveal our stragegy might very well be to jeopardize its success,'' he said
the proposal will be offered this week or after the easter break in congress as an amendment to pending legislation, heinz said. the proposed law is unlike an amendment sponsored by u.s. rep. john bryant, d-texas, to require foreign investors to disclose details of takeover attempts
i'm not in the business of making hollow promises, and i do not make idle threats,'' heinz said. ``i have drafted and am prepared to introduce and press legislation to make the takeover of koppers extremely unpalatable to beazer-shearson and similar consortiums in the future
the corporate raiders will be and should be as surprised by this legislation as koppers was by this raid.''
we are not corporate raiders,'' beazer declared in a full-page advertisement monday in pittsburgh's newspapers. ``our goal is not to make a quick buck. rather, we are in the process of creating a vital, dynamic worldwide organization.''
beazer's ad appealed to koppers' worried employees and to the city to investigate the fate of the atlanta homebuilder cohn communities and the dallas construction materials company gifford-hill after he acquired them in 1985 and 1986 respectively
each of those companies has grown and prospered under our ownership,'' he said
koppers has rejected each of the offers, $45, $56 and $60 per share, that bns has made since launching its cash tender offer march 3. the latest expires april 7, although a federal court in california has blocked the acquisition over anti-trust concerns
koppers management says it may sell all or part of the company or pay cash to shareholders to keep the company out of beazer's hands
heinz said taxpayers would spend more for public roads if the takeover succeeds. the combination would heighten beazer's concentration in markets where his holdings and koppers compete
the two of them combined in what are essentially local market areas would, if the sale went through, amount to a de facto local monopoly on very costly road building materials,'' he said
the senator, allegheny county commission chairman thomas foerster and others at the news conference warned that the takeover jeopardizes the approximately 1,100 pittsburgh-area jobs in koppers' chemicals businesses
beazer has said he would sell chemicals and related businesses, although it is not clear that all those jobs would be eliminated
opponents also worry about the $232 million that koppers contributes to the area economy
heinz joined city, county and state officials who have lambasted shearson for going a step beyond traditional takeover financing and becoming an equity partner in the takeover company, bns
i am appalled by the involvement of shearson,'' he said. ``shearson stands to gain tens of millions of dollars in fees simply for shuffling some paper around.''
shearson officials have said their ownership in bns is merely a temporary method of helping finance the takeover
the federal fund that insures deposits in commercial banks could suffer a loss in 1988 for the first time in its 54-year history, federal deposit insurance corp. chairman l. william seidman said monday
seidman said a loss to the insurance fund, if any, would depend on how much the fdic spends to resolve the problems of first republicbank of dallas, which earlier this month received a $1 billion infusion of government aid
the deterioration of texas banks, hard hit by losses on real estate and energy loans, has raised concern about the health of the insurance fund, which backs deposits of up to $100,000 in 13,700 commercial banks
speaking at a luncheon meeting with reporters, seidman said it is too soon to say with certainty what the cost of restoring first republicbank to health will be. but, he said the $5 billion to $6 billion estimates of some are ``far higher than anything that is likely to be required.''
he said the $1.7 billion cost of the 1984 bailout of continental illinois bank &amp; trust co., which was about the same size as first republicbank, ``is the best guide we have.''
the fdic's initial outlay on first republicbank could be higher than the ultimate cost, just as it was in the case of continental when the agency spent $4.5 billion, seidman said
however, he said the fdic now usually tries to structure bank rescues so that the initial cash cost is close to the ultimate cost
if the first republicbank cost is in the $1.7 billion range and if banks fail this year at about the same rate as last year, then ``it is possible we will have a loss in 1988,'' he said
last year, a post-depression record of 184 banks failed. forty-four have failed so far this year and seidman said he expected the 1988 total to be roughly the same as 1987
as failures have increased, the steady growth of the fdic fund _ from $4.6 billion in 1970, $11.6 billion in 1980 to $17.9 billion in 1985 _ has slowed. the fund finished 1986 with $18.2 billion and 1987 with $18.3 billion
seidman said the 1988 loss, if it occurs, would be ``something under 5 percent ... certainly under ... $1 billion.'' he said he did not see any prospect for what he termed a substantial loss, one approaching 20 percent, or about $3.5 billion
he contrasted the relatively healthy condition of the fdic fund with that of the federal savings and loan insurance corp., which insures deposits in 3,170 savings institutions. fslic was insolvent until last fall when money began flowing from congressionally-authorized bond sales. it has had to keep bankrupt s&amp;ls open because it lacked the money to pay off depositors
the dollar plunged again monday, piercing key levels as central bank intervention failed to pull it out of the doldrums
gold prices rose. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $455.10 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from friday's late bid of $452.75 an ounce
in a wave that swept westward, the dollar fell in tokyo before closing lower in very light european trading. in new york, the dollar dipped below the 124-yen barrier to finish at its lowest point since early january in active trading
dealers said the federal reserve entered the market to buy dollars, but the move only served to smooth out the currency's latest decline, which began last week
the fed was not very useful in what you'd call turning (the dollar) around,'' said ron sapiro, head trader at continental illinois national bank &amp; trust co. in chicago
but because the dollar's decline was essentially orderly, ``there was no reason for the fed to come in en masse,'' he added
traders in europe were surprised that central banks did not aggressively step in to support the dollar. ``it's gotten away with (the decline) because it's been so gradual,'' said a london trader, who speculated that the central banks would have intervened to stave off a hastier retreat
traders said the dollar's slide was fueled more by investors' attraction to other major currencies than by any worries about u.s. economic factors. ``everybody's in love with the yen,'' rather than spurning the dollar, sapiro said
but the yen is not the only currency on the rise. ``all the high-yielding (major) currencies are benefitting'' from the market's recent strength, said james mcgroarty, a vice president at discount corp
instead of simply selling dollars, traders are jockeying their deals among several currencies. ``there has been a lot of cross-playing,'' sapiro said, albeit at the dollar's expense
with most currency markets scheduled to close friday for the easter holiday, traders may already be beginning to square off their positions, analysts said
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar fell for a third consecutive trading day, dropping 1.31 yen to a closing 124.43 yen. later in london, the dollar was quoted lower at 124.20 yen
in new york, the dollar closed still lower at 123.84 yen, down sharply from 125.30 yen on friday
the bank of japan intervened shortly after the start of tokyo trading to prop up the dollar at about 124.40 yen, traders said. one of the central bank's currency dealers, taeko kobayashi, said the bank bought $100 million to $200 million
the british pound rose in london to $1.8590 from $1.8360. in new york, it cost $1.8705 to buy one pound, more expensive than friday's $1.84175
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late friday, included: 1.65615 west german marks, down from 1.6760; 1.3652 swiss francs, down from 1.3865; 5.6130 french francs, down from 5.68625; 1.23715 canadian dollars, down from 1.24205; and 1,226.00 italian lire, down from 1,238.50
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late friday, included: 1.6605 west german marks, down from 1.6760; 1.3705 swiss francs, down from 1.3865; 5.6275 french francs, down from 5.6860; 1.8685 dutch guilders, down from 1.8820; 1,231.00 italian lire, down from 1,241.00; and 1.2377 canadian dollars, down from 1.2433
gold prices jumped higher. on new york's commodity exchange, gold closed at $455.80 a troy ounce, up from $453.20 on friday. in london, gold rose to a late bid price of $454 a troy ounce, compared with late friday's $451.70
in zurich, gold also moved higher, closing at a bid $453.50, compared with $451.50 late friday. earlier in hong kong, gold fell 59 cents from saturday's close to a bid $454.67
silver closed unchanged at $6.665 a troy ounce on new york's comex. in london the metal traded at a bid of $6.63 a troy ounce, down 1 cent from late friday. concerns</head>
the possibility of severe drought damage to brazilian soybean crops helped propel u.s. soybean futures prices above $6.50 a bushel monday to their highest levels since mid-1984
grain futures retreated in other trading on the chicago board of trade
on other exchanges, copper futures fell sharply while precious metals were mixed; energy futures advanced; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced
news that a month-long dry spell in the brazilian soybean-growing region of rio grande du sul had prompted the government there to declare a state of emergency on friday gave u.s. soybean futures a healthy boost, analysts said
but traders were divided over the extent of damage to the nearly ripe brazilian crop, especially after light weekend rains were reported in the rio grande du sul area
nevertheless, most soybean contracts closed at new lifetime high prices on a combination of fundamental and technical factors with most players feeling bullish ahead of thursday's agriculture department reports on spring planting intentions and grain stocks, analysts said
right now, everything seems to be go in this market,'' said ted mao, grain specialist with shearson lehman hutton inc. in new york
wheat posted significant losses due to rainy weather in the midwest, which was seen as helping out the new crop, said jerry gidel, an analyst in chicago with g.h. miller &amp; co
wheat settled 4 cents to 5{ cents lower with the contract for delivery in may at $2.99{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to } cent higher with may at $2.10{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with may at $1.66} a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 9} cents higher with may at $6.55} a bushel
copper futures plummeted on new york's commodity exchange in reaction to a rise in inventories of the metal at the warehouses of the world's two largest copper exchanges
the comex reported an increase in warehouse copper stocks of 1,425 short tons to 11,170 short tons. the london metal exchange reported an increase of 425 metric tons to 56,725 metric tons
the closely watched march contract was the big loser, tumbling 6.15 cents to $1.076 a pound. some of that activity was also due to traders selling out of the march contract before it goes off the board on tuesday, said bette raptopoulos, metals analyst in new york with prudential-bache securities inc
also on the comex, gold futures advanced slightly and silver was nearly unchanged in quiet trading
gold settled $2.60 to $2.80 lower with april at $455.90 a troy ounce; silver was unchanged to 0.5 cent lower with march at $6.665 a troy ounce
energy futures advanced in slow, featureless trading on the new york mercantile exchange
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 7 cents higher with may at $17.10 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent to .47 cent higher with april at 48.17 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .08 cent to .10 cent higher with april at 48.02 cents a gallon
the contracts for april and june delivery of live cattle posted new highs on the chicago mercantile exchange. feeder cattle also advanced while pork futures retreated
higher cash markets underpinned the rise in cattle futures, said tom morgan, president of sterling research corp. in arlington heights, ill
pork-complex prices fell on expectations that the usda's quarterly hogs and pigs report will show an increase in the nation's hog herd of 4 percent to 8 percent from a year ago, morgan said
live cattle settled .30 cent to .55 cent higher with april at 75.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .73 cent higher with march at 82.95 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .33 cent lower with april at 46.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .92 cent lower with may at 56.45 cents a pound
stock-index futures advanced on the chicago merc, where the contract for june delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 2.15 points higher at 259.90. the underlying spot index finished .45 point lower at 258.06
representatives of international paper co. and its striking unions met monday in an attempt to defuse the hostility that has permeated negotiations during a yearlong contract dispute and hindered chances of a settlement
both sides declined to release information on what was discussed or how long they met
we've agreed that any releases would be joint statements and only where there's something to report,'' said william meserve, president of local 14 of the united paperworkers international union in jay, maine
he did say the two sides would meet again tuesday, and the talks are expected to last for weeks. ip has paper mills throughout the country
company spokesman william greener echoed meserve's statement, saying from the company's purchase, n.y., headquarters that neither side intended to release details of the meetings
ip and its unions, the upiu and the international brotherhood of firemen and oilers, have been at odds for more than a year over contracts that have come up for renewal. the disagreements focus on whether local contracts should restore premium pay for sunday and holidays
premium pay had been eliminated with labor's approval from past contracts, but since the industry's fortunes have improved in the last year, the unions have campaigned to revive the benefit
about 3,500 workers in four locations are embroiled in contract fights. in mobile, ala., 1,200 workers have been locked out of their jobs by the company. an additional 2,300 have struck plants in jay, lock haven, pa., and depere, wis
contracts are also open in pine bluff and camden, ark., and natchez, miss
ip has continued to operate its mills with replacement workers. the company claims the strike-breakers are now permanent employees and has offered assistance to strikers who want to re-enter the job market, including positions at other ip mills. the unions have rejected such offers
international paper co. claimed earnings of $305 million in 1986 and said it expected to post earnings of $407 million when final figures are released. however, the company said its profitablity was below the industry average in both 1986 and 1987, when measured in terms of its net worth
a fresh decline in the dollar and lingering anxiety about wall street's own strength pushed stock prices mostly lower monday, but the market avoided the sharp falls of the preceding two sessions
the dow jones average of 30 industrials closed a scant 0.82 higher at 1,979.77, after posting moderate declines through much of the trading session
but the broader market moved downward. declining issues outpaced advances by more than 2-to-1 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,059 issues falling, 468 gaining and 420 unchanged
volume on the big board totaled 142.82 million shares, down from 163.17 million in friday's session
many investors had their new-found confidence shaken late last week when stocks fell sharply on thursday and friday. the closely watched dow jones average tumbled around 45 points on friday after falling nearly 44 points in the previous session _ sparking widespread fears that monday's session could turn into another ``black monday'' akin to the collapse on oct. 19
we've been almost rudely reminded that the market is still on very, very thin ice,'' said hugh johnson, a senior vice president of first albany corp. in albany, n.y. ``it's still volatile and vulnerable.''
but monday's decline was tempered by some ``bargain-hunting'' buying at the lower price levels, traders said. they noted, though, that many foreign investors and financial institutions remained on the sidelines
although the latest losses were more moderate, analysts said they reflected a bearish sentiment that continued to pervade the market. and the anxiety was deepened by fresh declines in the battered dollar on world currency markets
we're again hooked to the dollar,'' said monte gordon, director of research for dreyfus corp. ``the market continues to wallow in confusion and uncertainty.''
the u.s. currency was quoted at below 124 japanese yen in late trading in new york, down sharply from more than 125 yen late friday. the dollar also retreated to around 1.66 west german marks from 1.68 marks
earlier in the day, the dollar's slump brought the federal reserve into the market to buy dollars in a bid to support the currency after it fell to around 124 yen, traders reported
the financial markets have been ``reminded that stabilizing the dollar is not going to be easy,'' first albany's johnson said
