a state court judge reserved a decision monday on a request that he prohibit six former top executives of lord, geller, federico, einstein inc. from soliciting business or employees from lord geller for their new ad agency
justice herman cahn asked attorneys for lord geller, which had made the request for a preliminary injunction, and for the defecting lord geller executives to work out a plan for introducing evidence in the case
the six executives, led by lord geller founding partners richard lord and arthur einstein jr., walked off the job march 18, saying they felt unduly constrained under the ownership of the british firm, wpp group plc
wpp group, which is headed by martin sorrell, had aquired lord geller last summer when he bought its parent, jwt group inc., for $566 million in the biggest ad agency acquisition ever. in addition to lord geller, jwt group owned the much larger advertising agency, j. walter thompson co
since the six top partners left lord geller to form a new agency called lord, einstein, o'neill &amp; partners, about 30 other lord geller employees have quit, some of them signing on with the new agency
two lord geller clients, wnbc-tv and new yorker magazine, have indicated they plan to take their business to the new agency
but most of the ad world's attention is focused international business machines corp., the computer giant which reportedly accounts for about half of lord geller's $245 million in annual billings
four companies seeking to build a state-of-the-art transportation system in florida's congested corridors conjured images monday of a bullet train that would whisk passengers at speeds of 150-250 mph along a tampa-miami route
company representatives envisioned sleek, high-technology trains that resembled airplanes in appearance, planned suburbs and cities springing up along the routes and quiet and comfortable trips between tampa and miami that took only 90 minutes, regardless of the weather
state officials attending the presentations were urged to think about the tourism boom, the business opportunities and environmental advantage of having a clean and efficient way of moving as many as 6 million people along routes between miami, orlando and tampa every year
legislative leaders seemed to like what they were hearing
florida was the first state to have a settlement in the new world, it was the site of the first moon launch and now it will be the site of the first truly modern rail system in the world,'' said house speaker jon mills. ``i think it's symbolic of what florida can become.''
mills, d-gainesville, attended the crowded presentation ceremony in florida's old capitol along with gov. bob martinez, senate president john vogt, d-merritt island, and officials of the rail commission
the florida high speed rail transportation commission was not expected to award a franchise until september 1991 to allow time to study the project and its costs, which could run as high as $5 billion. the train linking tampa, orlando and miami is expected to be running by 1995
state guidelines mandate that the project must link the three cities, but the applicants will determine precise routes, financing agreements and the technology they will use
the company that wins the franchise will be allowed to develop property adjacent to the route for rail stations and connecting attractions. the idea is that those developmental rights will help the company recoup the startup costs of building the rail system
one of the four applicants was tgv of florida inc., backed by the french company alsthom, which supplies tgv trains to the french national railways, and bombardier inc., a canadian manufacturing consortium
tgv's proposal for an electrified system would include trains that could run up to 185 mph and the cost several billion dollars
tgv's big advantage is that the system in france has been very successful
all american magneplane inc. argued that its technology was newer, faster and cleaner environmentally. the magnetic-levitation trains, called ``mag-lev'' for short, would glide along a magnetic field along an elevated track. because a magnetic force controls the movement of the train instead of electricity or diesel-powered engines, company officials said their system eliminates the dependence on oil
that system also is expensive, in the neighborhood of $3 billion
two other companies, the florida high speed rail corp. and stone and webster engineering corp., have proposed plans for systems that run a little slower, in the neighborhood of 150 mph, and cost less because they use existing transportation corridors
stone and webster have submitted the lowest general estimate of cost, recommending that the system could be built for about $1 billion
after judging the proposals on the basis of environmental effects, financial arrangements, growth patterns and technologies, the rail commiission can recommend one, or none, of the applicants to the governor and cabinet
the world bank, which borrows on world markets for re-lending to poor countries, announced on monday that it is asking 14 u.s. companies outside new york and three in toronto to be agents for the sale of its longer-term bonds
its object is to get a bigger variety of investors, the announcement said
the 17 companies will be in addition to the five in the united states which are now primary agents for what the bank calls its continuously offered longer-term securities (colts). these are bonds with maturities of three to more than 30 years
it has $1.4 billion in such bonds outstanding
a former stock analyst who pleaded guilty to a criminal charge in the ``yuppie five'' insider trading scandal, settled a civil action with the securities and exchange commission monday
andrew solomon, formerly a researcher at the marcus schloss &amp; co. brokerage, settled civil charges by admitting his participation in a scheme to trade on inside information of corporate activities
insider trading is the wrongful use of confidential information to profit in securities transactions
the settlement is subject to a judge's approval
solomon, 28, of manhattan, pleaded guilty june 5, 1986, to one count of conspiracy. he was sentenced nov. 26, 1986, to one year's probation, 250 hours of community service and a $10,000 fine
he could have been sentenced to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine
solomon was part of a ring that included four wall street professionals and one of their clients, all known as the ``yuppie five.'' they traded in securities involved in six proposed or anticipated corporate takeovers using non-public information
in settling the sec civil charges, solomon admitted passing on inside information about gaf corp.'s tender offer for union carbide corp., dominion textile's tender offer for avondale mills as well as a takeover bid of american brands by bat industries, all before they were made public
in february, marcus schloss &amp; co. agreed to pay $410,700 _ without admitting or denying guilt _ to settle civil insider trading charges with the sec
general motors corp.'s chevrolet division is extending rebates ranging from $400 to $1,200 on several cars and trucks, the company said monday
the incentives, which were to expire april 30, will run through may 11
they include rebates of $1,200 to import owners buying the subcompact chevrolet nova, built at a toyota-run joint-venture factory in fremont, calif. non-import owners receive a $600 rebate on nova
other rebates include: $400 on chevrolet cavalier, $500 on beretta, spectrum, s-10 pickup and blazer, full-size pickup and cab-and-chassis and chevy van and sportvan; $750 on camaro and celebrity and $1,000 on spectrum turbo and camaro in hawaii and california
the rebate can be taken as cash or used for a down payment. buyers must take delivery by the campaign's expiration
usg corp. urged its stockholders monday to reject a slate of board candidates recommended by desert partners lp and repeated its opposition to the texas group's $1.9 billion hostile takeover attempt
in a letter accompanying its proxy statement for the may 11 annual meeting, usg asked its stockholders to elect the slate of candidates nominated by the usg board to fill six spots on the 15-member panel
desert partners, meanwhile, announced it had extended until april 8 its $42-a-share cash tender offer for up to 21.5 million shares of usg stock. the offer was set to expire monday at 11:59 p.m. est
desert partners, a limited partnership led by texas oilmen jack e. brown and cyril wagner jr., had also offered to buy the remainder of usg's outstanding shares with securities valued at $42 a share
chicago-based usg, a leading producer of gypsum wallboard and other building materials, told its stockholders that desert partners had reserved the right to cancel its tender offer unless all of the many conditions set forth in securities and exchange commission regulations were met
if desert partners were to win the proxy fight, then drop its tender offer, ``desert partners would have obtained control of 40 percent of usg's board without paying anything to usg stockholders or committing to do so in the future,'' wrote robert j. day, usg's chairman and chief executive officer
day stated that brown and wagner had proposed takeovers of at least three other public companies in the past but had not yet acquired any of them
day's letter said desert partners' proxy materials did not disclose whether its board candidates had any experience in overseeing a large public company ``and did not disclose what the desert candidates would do if elected other than support the desert partners takeover campaign.''
desert partners announced the extension of its cash tender offer in a statement. the texas group also said it was negotiating for additional financing in hopes of increasing the number of shares in the cash tender offer from 21.5 million to 39 million
desert partners owned a 9.9 percent stake in usg when it launched the tender offer, and said a ``nominal number'' of shares had been tendered through the end of last week. bid for icl, no pickup.</note>
corning glass works and smithkline beckman corp. each raised their bids monday for international clinical laboratories, a chain of clinical-testing laboratories that is based in tennessee
corning moved first, increasing its tender offer to about $360 million, or $35 a share for icl's 10 million-plus outstanding shares and common stock equivalents
but smithkline, based in philadelphia, soon followed by raising its offer to $37 a share, which it said would amount to about $400 million. it had previously offered $32 a share
on wall street, ici's stock rose $1.75 per share to $36.75 in nationwide over-the-counter trading
corning had started the bidding on march 8 at $260 million
under terms of its merger agreement, corning would have an option to buy 3 million unissued icl shares as well as ``all the shares owned by certain directors and officers'' for $26 each
henry wendt, smithkline chairman and chief executive officer, said the merger with the nashville, tenn.-based icl would fit with the pharmaceutical giant's acquistion of bio-science laboratories
this increased offer reaffirms the strategic commitment to invest in our key businesses,'' wendt said. ``since the merger with bio-science laboratories in 1985, our clinical laboratories have made a substantial and growing contribution to the corporation
this investment will enhance that record of achievement,'' wendt said
the smithkline offer expires at midnight april 20, the company said
corning's latest offer, which is subject to federal approval and is contingent on buying a majority of shares, expires at midnight april 8
in raising its offer, corning chairman james houghton said his company would not back off from its campaign
expansion of our medical-laboratory business is an important strategic goal, and this acquisition continues to be a very attractive one for corning, even at this increased price. we are determined to complete our agreed-upon merger,'' he said
icl operates 13 major laboratories, mainly in the south and west, and earned $4.8 million on sales of $205 million last fiscal year
the company would be merged with corning's own laboratory subsidiary, metpath inc., which is based in tetersboro, n.j., and has a dozen other testing labs in the united states
besides laboratory services, corning makes consumer housewares, optical fibers and other telecommunications equipment and speciality glass and ceramics. last year, corning had sales of $2.08 billion
smithkline bio-science laboratories, the company's clinical laboratory segment headquartered in king of prussia, pa., operates 22 regional laboratories. it reported sales of $431 million last year. share and clarifies references to size of companies. picks up 11th graf pvs ``the letter praised...''</note>
american stores co. said monday it was prepared to up its bid for lucky stores inc. to more than $1.9 billion in an effort to create the nation's largest grocery store chain
in a letter to the board of the dublin, calif.-based company, american stores chairman l.s. skaggs said his company was ready to offer $50 per share if a ``mutually acceptable agreement'' could be worked out with lucky stores
earlier monday, american launched a cash tender offer for lucky at $45 per share, or a total of $1.74 billion. that offer expires at midnight april 22
we made clear our willingness to negotiate concerning all aspects of our offer, including the price,'' said skaggs in his letter to lucky
skaggs noted that lucky stores' representatives had so far declined the invitation to negotiate
the combination of american, the nation's third largest grocery retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion, and lucky, the sixth largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion, could produce the biggest grocery retailer in the country, analysts say
lucky stores officials were not immediately available for comment on the latest developments, which were announced by press release after the close of stock trading
lucky shares advanced 87{ cents to close at $48.62{, while american shares lost $1.75 to finish at $54.87{ on the new york stock exchange
before american revealed the contents of its letter to the lucky stores board, lucky spokeswoman lissa perlman said company officials had been reviewing the offer with financial and legal advisers since last week
lucky strongly advises its stockholders not to take any action with respect to the american stores offer'' until the lucky board of directors has a chance to further study the bid and make its recommendation, perlman said
no deadline for a recommendation was given
in a march 21 letter, skaggs notified lucky stores chairman john m. lillie of the then impending tender offer. skaggs said if the offer was successful, he planned to combine american store's alpha beta stores with lucky's operation under the lucky name
the letter praised lucky's management and marketing strategies and invited lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed. lucky's headquarters would remain in dublin, skaggs said
the bid for lucky came 16 months after takeover specialist asher edelman dropped his hostile effort to acquire the company. in return, lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills
lucky kept edelman at bay partially by selling off its non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures
after the text of the letter was released last week, lucky officials had no comment on the american stores' tender offer except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
american stores last made financial headlines in 1984 when it spent $1.1 billion to take over jewel companies inc., a chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store chain
that acquisition expanded american stores' operations from just over 1,000 retail outlets to its present 1,700. the company has three divisions _ skaggs, which operates supermarkets in the western united states; american superstores, which runs outlets in the midwest and east, and osco drug stores, which has stores nationwide
the company operates stores under the names acme, jewel, star, buttrey, skaggs, skaggs alpha beta, and osco drug. billion,'' with reno court developments, picks up 5th graf original, ``the kansas ... regulatory approval.''</note>
a proxy solicitation by batus inc., which is making a hostile bid for insurer farmers group inc., may be illegal and may have to be halted, the kansas insurance department has said
the ruling was disclosed monday by los angeles-based farmers, which has been resisting takeover overtures by batus since january. it was later confirmed by batus, the american subsidiary of london-based bat industries inc. plc
at issue is whether a proposal by batus for which proxies are being sought would, if successful, constitute a change in control of the company
the proposal seeks to make farmers' directors reconsider their previous refusal to negotiate on batus' takeover offer of $63 per share, or $4.5 billion
meanwhile, farmers filed suit monday in nevada, where the company is incorporated, challenging batus's proxy solicitation. farmers claims batus did not disclose enough information in the solicitation. an april 13 hearing on the dispute was scheduled in u.s. district court in reno
judge howard mckibben also said he would decide by wednesday whether to declare unconstitutional the nevada takeover act, which prevents stockholders from taking advantage of tender offers after the deal is 60 days old
the nevada attorney general's office contends the law is meant to protect investors from being strung along for months during a takeover bid
but batus' attorneys argue the nevada law conflicts with the federal williams act, which gives shareholders the right to participate in tender offers at will
the kansas insurance company holding act says no one can take control of an insurer without first obtaining regulatory approval
control shall be presumed to exist if any person ... holds proxies representing 10 percent or more of the voting securities,'' the law says
if the issue isn't resolved or the proxy solicitation isn't ``stopped immediately,'' the regulators said, the department will be ``required to initiate the applicable administrative or legal action.''
the kansas insurance department outlined its concerns in a letter to batus dated last thursday
batus said monday that it is responding and ``strongly believes that it will be able to satisfy the concerns raised.''
batus is basing its argument on the contention that its proposal, even if successful, couldn't directly constitute a change in control of farmers
in fact, a change in control cannot result from a vote on our proxy,'' batus spokesman wilson wyatt said
kansas is one of nine states in which farmers owns insurers. regulatory approval must be obtained in each of those
besides kansas, where farmers group operates farmers insurance co., and california, where farmers group is based, the other states are arizona, idaho, illinois, ohio, oregon, texas and washington
farmers, in its release monday, noted that insurance regulators in texas, illinois and idaho have rejected or found deficient certain required filings by batus on grounds that they contained inadequate information
bat is a tobacco, retailing and paper-goods conglomerate that for some time has been seeking a foothold in the u.s. financial services market. its american subsidiary, batus, is based in louisville, ky
farmers, with about $11 billion in assets, is the nation's third largest home and auto insurer, and the seventh largest property and casualty insurer
an executive vice president of allied signal inc. has been chosen the company's president and chief operating officer, officials of the advanced techonolgy firm announced monday
alan belzer, who has also been president of the company's $2.8 billion engineered materials sector, will assume his new posts april 1, said edward l. hennessy, chairman and chief executive officer of allied signal
hennessy said the materials sector under belzer, 55, has been the most consistently profitable of allied signal's three operating units
in his new position, alan will oversee the day-to-day operations of the company's successful core businesses in aerospace, engineered materials and automotive products,'' hennessy said
belzer, 55, joined allied signal in 1955
